name: Carbon River Ranger Station
description: Located in the northwest corner of the park, the ranger station is staffed by rangers or volunteers. Building hours may vary so call ahead for hours 360-829-9639. When open, rangers and volunteers provide park information, wilderness camping, and climbing permits. Wilderness camping permits available by self-registration when closed.
audioDescription: The Carbon River Ranger Station is housed in a remodeled farmhouse with an angled roof and a covered porch. There is angled parking along the main road on either side of the ranger station driveway, which curves down a short hill to reach the building. The interior of the building consists of one large room, with a long wooden desk directly across from the front door. A fire place is on the right side wall, flanked by two iPad kiosks, which play videos and interactive exhibits about the natural and cultural history of the Carbon River area. Various informational signs are attached to the walls in between large windows. A small table in front of one of the windows to the right of the door holds books, maps and other merchandise.

name: Carl Hayden Visitor Center
description: Main visitor center for Glen Canyon National Recreation Area and Rainbow Bridge National Monument. Exhibits about recreation and historic water use. Tours of Glen Canyon Dam are closed.
audioDescription: Just north of Glen Canyon Bridge on U.S. Highway 89, Carl Hayden Visitor Center is located at the edge of the canyon. The parking area is difficult to navigate because of the proximity of the canyon walls, and security measures in place for Glen Canyon Dam. It is a mid century modern style building with beige gravel concrete walls. There are barriers between the parking lot and building that are easy to walk or maneuver a wheelchair through. A low memorial fountain is in front of the building. A large circular section of the building juts over the cliff above Glen Canyon Dam. The entrance faces the front parking lot. Upon entering, the restrooms are on the left. Certain areas are closed to the public due to security reasons. Interactive exhibits and picture windows are in the rotunda. There are no stairs in the public areas of the visitor center. Wheelchairs are available by request. When you walk straight into the rotunda, you will encounter the information and tour desks. Tours of Glen Canyon are on a seasonal schedule. There are two elevator rides, but no stairs along the tour route. Movies in the auditorium are open captioned. Audio description of the movies is available by request. The back deck of the building is accessible through the back door, or by walking around the building from the parking lot. Views of Glen Canyon Dam, Lake Powell, Glen Canyon Bridge, and the Colorado River. When the building is closed, sections of the parking lot are also closed.

name: Carriage Barn Visitor Center
description: Built on the foundation of an earlier stable in 1895 to house the Billings' horses and carriages, this building is currently used as the headquarters and visitor center for Marsh-Billings-Rockefeller National Historical Park. Explore the exhibit, "A Place in the Land", visit the AMP bookstore, or sign up for ranger programs (advanced reservations preferred). Junior Ranger books and passport stamps are available at this location. Open daily from 10am to 5pm, Memorial Day weekend (late May) to Oct 31.
audioDescription: The Carriage Barn Visitor center sits at the top of a short, steep hill with a gravel path leading from Elm St and the Billings Farm and Museum. The building is three stores and the basement/first floor is partially underground. A sign next to the front door reads "Marsh-Billings-Rockefeller National Historical Park Carriage Barn, Stewardship Programs, and Visitor Center". The building is remodeled with the foundation of an 1895 carriage house. A weathervane sits on a small turret on the top of the building pointing in the four cardinal directions.

name: Casa Grande Ruins National Monument
description: Construction began in 1932 to create the current adobe visitor center. Funding was provided for only half of the open square building, final completion was delayed until 1956. Exhibits, restrooms, bookstore, and orientation movie are available in the current building. All park visitors enter the historic area by passing through the visitor center.
passportStampLocationDescription: Casa Grande Ruins National Monument Casa Grande Ruins Visitor Center There are several cancellation stamps at this location including Casa Grande Ruins National Monument, Juan Bautista de Anza National Historic Trail and Great House picture stamp.
directionsInfo: Transportation is by private vehicle. The park is in Coolidge, Arizona, about an hour-long drive from either Phoenix or Tucson. From Interstate 10 take the Coolidge exits and follow the signs to the park entrance. The entrance road ends at the park visitor center and parking area.

name: Castolon Visitor Center
description: Located in the Castolon Historic District, the Castolon Visitor Center is open daily during the winter months. River use permits are issued during normal business hours, and entrance fees can be paid at the Castolon Visitor Center. The Castolon Visitor Center has a Big Bend Natural History Association bookstore and nearby restrooms. The visitor center is located in the historic Garlick House, immediately behind the Magdalena House Exhibits. Stop by to meet a ranger and plan your adventure.
audioDescription: The Castolon Visitor Center is located within the historic Garlick House in Castolon. This small adobe building is located on the edge of a bluff with expansive views of the Rio Grande floodplain, and 1,500 feet high cliffs of the Sierra Ponce extending into Mexico. The nearby Magdalena House exhibit building offers exhibits highlighting the lives of early bi-cultural, bi-national settlers who worked together to live in this remote area. The visitor center contains an information desk and some sales items. Historic images are on display that highlight the rich border culture and history of the Castolon area.

name: Cedar Breaks Visitor Contact Station
description: Coming Soon! The National Park Service and Zion Forever Project are working with partners and supporters to enhance the view at Cedar Breaks National Monument and bring a new home for visitors at the park. The facility will serve the needs of the visitors in an efficient and sustainable way through modest design limiting the impact on the park’s dramatic landscape. Construction began in 2021, for visitor services please visit https://www.nps.gov/places/cedar-breaks-information-center.htm.

name: Cedar Grove Visitor Center
description: This visitor center is next to the South Fork of the Kings River in mixed conifer forest at an elevation of 4,600 feet (1,400 m). Learn about the natural and cultural history of the Cedar Grove area. Nearby services include accessible restrooms and a pay phone.
audioDescription: A small building is surrounded by incense-cedar and small, young sequoia trees. Needles from the trees cover the ground, forming a reddish carpet. The building is rustic, made in the style of a log cabin. The logs are painted brown. In the center of a building is a single doorway with two paned windows on either side. To the right of the door when facing the front door, there's a sign kiosk with maps and a bulletin case. Next to the kiosk is a pay phone. To the left of the building is a restroom, painted in the same color of brown.

name: Chalmette Battlefield and Chalmette National Cemetery
description: Site of the Battle of New Orleans in 1815, Chalmette Battlefield contains a reconstructed American rampart, an 1830s house, 100-foot-high Chalmette Monument, and outdoor exhibits for self-guided tours. Visitor center films and exhibits share the battle and the site's later history. Ranger talks offered daily. Chalmette National Cemetery was established during the Civil War and holds more than 14,000 graves of Americans from the War of 1812 to the Vietnam War; audio tour available. Free.
audioDescription: Traveling from New Orleans 6 miles west on St. Bernard Hwy. (LA 46) turn right on Battlefield Rd. and drive through the main gates. Welcome to Chalmette Battlefield and National Cemetery of Jean Lafitte National Historical Park and Preserve. The Chalmette Visitor Center is located less than a mile ahead as you travel south toward the Mississippi River. Observe the 20 mph speed and directional signs as you pass the National Monument to the visitor center parking lot. Restroom facilities are located nearby in the smaller of the two buildings. The Visitor Center is on opposite side of the parking lot and both buildings are less than 100 feet apart. The visitor center is a light beige with green trim, metal roofed, rectangular shaped approximately 200' x 100' building. Two green automatic entrance doors face the center of both the south and north entrances of the visitor center. Climbing a couple of handrail steps a push button is on the right column for auto operation of the entrance doors or they can be manually pulled opened. Walkways are handicap accessible and make elevated 90 degree turns to the entrance doors of the visitor center. Once inside the visitor center, you are greeted at the ranger desk, and just beyond is a museum with exhibits and films for your enjoyment.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Chalmette Cancellation Stamp is your personal record of visit to the Chalmette Battlefield and National Cemetery which offers living history programs, ranger talks, and visitor center exhibits and films. It is the site of the 1815 Battle of New Orleans. The stamp is available at the ranger desk in the visitor center.

name: Chamizal National Memorial Cultural Center
description: The Chamizal National Memorial Cultural Center includes the theater, exhibit areas, park store and visitor information desk. It also provides visitor access to the Franklin G. Smith Gallery located next door in the Administrative Office Building.
audioDescription: The single story visitor center is in the middle of the park grounds facing south toward Mexico. Its smooth, stucco walls are painted a sandy tan color. It overlooks a wide plaza paved in triangle patterns that combine to form hexagons. The hexagonal shape is also seen in the architecture of the theater's high roof projecting up from the rest of the building. At the entrance, outer walls slant inward toward a recessed front of reflective glass panes about forty feet long combined. Two sets of double doors on either end of the glass front open outward by pulling handles or pressing an automatic opener mounted on the stucco wall near each door. Three cement benches are lined up along the glass front between the two sets of doors. Letters along the roof line spell, "Chamizal National Memorial Cultural Center," and logo decals for the National Park Service and Chamizal National Memorial adhere to the glass below. To either side of the doors, low rock walls encase raised beds planted with trees and other vegetation. Flat pavers on top of the rock walls also serve as a place to sit down. Two plaques are located on the wall near the left door as you face the entrance. One plaque is about Stephen T. Mather, and the other is about the park in commemoration of the bicentennial of the US Constitution. An animal resistant trash can and recycling receptacle is located along the raised bed wall on the left side of the entrance. Cigarette disposal receptacles are located to either side of the entrance. A bike rack is located along the raised bed wall to the right of the entrance.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Chamizal National Memorial and Camino Real de Tierra Adentro National Historic Trail standard cancellation stamps are both available at the visitor information desk when the Cultural Center is open: during regular hours and evening events. More stamps are available from staff by request during regular hours: custom stamp from National Parks Travelers Club, custom US/Mexico eagle logo, and Chamizal National Memorial Junior Ranger badge.

name: Chancellorsville Battlefield Visitor Center
description: The Chancellorsville Battlefield Visitor Center contains exhibits about the battles at Chancellorsville, Wilderness, and Spotsylvania Court House and a 22-minute film that plays every 30-minutes. Pick up park maps and talk to park staff about the battles and your visit.
audioDescription: Approach the Chancellorsville Battlefield Visitor Center from a sidewalk connecting the parking area to the one-story Mission 66 style visitor center building. A flagpole, a metal interpretive compass with directions to nearby battles, and a 4 foot by 8 foot painting of the Battle of Chancellorsville are outside the visitor center. Double doors lead into the lobby area with an orientation desk 10 feet beyond the second double doors. Behind the orientation desk is a park store. To the left is the museum exhibit space.

name: Channel Islands National Park Visitor Center
description: The Robert J. Lagomarsino Visitor Center at Channel Islands National Park features a bookstore, a display of marine aquatic life, and exhibits featuring the unique character of each park island. Visitors also will enjoy the 25-minute park movie, “A Treasure in the Sea,” shown throughout the day in the auditorium (closed-caption film available upon request). The fully accessible visitor center is open 8:30 am until 5 pm daily. The visitor center is closed on Thanksgiving and December 25th.
audioDescription: The Channel Islands National Park Visitor Center Building description: The Robert J. Lagomarsino Visitor Center sits at the tip of the Ventura Harbor. Surrounded by water, this striking two-story gray building has open air exhibits spaces, balconies, an outdoor amphitheater area and viewing tower. A live tidal pool with daily talks and exhibits encompass the unique character of each park island. The four-story viewing tower is embellished with artistically cut metalwork in a green patina of kelp, fish and a pelican. The tower interior offers exhibits and views of Ventura Harbor, the Channel Islands, and the Ventura coastline. The Center’s interior exhibits have several marine and Channel Islands related educational displays including a rocky tidepool, elephant seal exhibit and pygmy mammoth exhibit. There is also a theatre, and Information Center.

name: Charles Pinckney National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: A historic Lowcountry cottage house serves as the park's visitor center. Visitors can enjoy museum exhibits, film options, Jr. Ranger program, and obtain park and local area information and orientation. Property owner William Mathews constructed the house ca. 1828 on the foundations of the Pinckney house. The house retained its characteristics through subsequent owners until Thomas Ewing bought Snee Farm in 1936. Thomas and Anna Ewing added two one-story rear (north) wings in 1936.
audioDescription: The Charles Pinckney National Historic Site Visitor Center is located in the 1820s coastal cottage. From the parking lot, walk through the covered area with a cement square pad to your left and the brown wooden restroom building with a green metal roof and green accents to your right. There are several brown and black plastic benches and a picnic table on the pad. There is a bottle fill and water fountain station in the center of the restroom building. Follow the oyster shell and cement path beyond this area which leads you to the entrance to the historic house/visitor center. The house is a white, wooden house with brown wood shingles on the roof and four chimneys. There are three dormers located on the second level. It is rectangular in shape with the entrance centered on the long side. Two rectangular wings were added to both the left and right sides; the wings come out from the house on this side to create a horseshoe shape. There are 10 glass windows with green shutters, the main door is wooden with a glass storm door and is centered on the house; this is the entrance into the house. Historically, this was the back side of the house. There is a porch with white wooden railings and a dark wooden floor which extends across the main door and two of the windows. A brick staircase with four steps centered on the house, is wide on the bottom and narrows as you go up onto the porch. To the right of this is a small white lift for accessible access for the house. Once on the porch, on either end are two wooden white doors which are used by staff only. The opposite side is the historic entrance and the way most leave the house today. This side is like the backside in that there are three dormers, the chimneys are visible on the roof line. The wings are visible, but they are situated further back. The porch on this side extends the length of the front of the house. The railings are wooden and painted white and the floor is dark wood. There are several rocking chairs situated on this side of the house for public use. The brick staircase with is centered on the porch, but it is the same width all the way up. There is a thin metal handrail on one side of the staircase. Eight windows are visible with green shutters and a white wooden door with a glass storm door is centered along this side to provide access. Along the two sides there are windows with shutters for both upstairs and downstairs. On one side of the house is an addiional wooden door for staff access. There are gutters and downspouts along all sides of the roof. The house foundation is comprised of brick columns with white wooden slats. There are several crepe myrtle trees draped with Spanish moss around the house; beyond this there are a couple of bushes.

name: Charlestown Navy Yard Visitor Center
description: Located in Building 5 of the Charlestown Navy Yard, this Visitor Center features exhibits and a short film about the work and workers of the Navy Yard who supported the United States Navy from 1800 to 1974. Please note that access to this building is through a security checkpoint.

name: Chatham Manor
description: Atop Stafford Heights, 250 years of history blend with the present at Chatham Manor. Chatham witnessed the horrors of slavery, the establishment of the United States, conflict surrounding the institution of slavery and Civil War, Reconstruction, and Colonial Revivalism. The Chatham gate is open 9 am to 5 pm every day.
audioDescription: Chatham Manor is a large, two-story brick plantation house, with single story wings on either side. The entryway to Chatham goes down a single lane dirt road leading to a parking lot. Once parked, the pathways towards the house lead through the gardens. Their are three primary pathways to the house, one straight through the center of the gardens, and two on either side. The parking lot is cattycorner to the house. On the other side of the house is n extensive terraced yard with a view to the city of Fredericksburg.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Chatham passport stamp is located here.
directionsInfo: Chatham is located across from Fredericksburg in Stafford County. From the Fredericksburg Battlefield Visitor Center, turn Left on Lafayette Blvd until the street dead ends at Sofia St. Turn left on Sofia Street and drive for 0.4 mi. Turn right onto Chatham Bridge/Kings Hwy/William St. Across the bridge, turn left at the first light to Chatham Heights Rd. In 0.1 mi turn left onto Chatham Ln.

name: Chickamauga Battlefield Visitor Center
description: The Chickamauga Battlefield Visitor Center is located at the north end of Chickamauga Battlefield. Inside are museum exhibits on the Battle of Chickamauga and Campaign for Chattanooga, as well as the Fuller Gun Collection. There is a bookstore administered by America's National Parks and an orientation film is shown every half hour. The Chickamauga Battlefield Visitor Center is open daily from 8:30 am to 5 pm but is closed on Christmas Day and New Years Day.
audioDescription: From the parking lot, visitors walk up the sidewalk, flanked on each side by Civil War cannon, before entering the building. Once entering the building, visitors will find a large map in the room's center, with restroom entrances to the left. In the rear, center of the room, is the information desk, staffed by NPS employees. The America's National Park's Bookstore is located to the right of the information desk. Also, to the right of the information desk is a hallway leading to the museum's major exhibits on the Battle of Chickamauga and the Fuller Gun Collection. To the left of the information desk is a hallway leading to the timeline room/theater (which seats 150 guests).
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is located in America's National Park's bookstore, inside the visitor center building.

name: Chiricahua National Monument Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is open from 8:30 am to 4:30 pm Mountain Standard Time. Exhibits about the geology, natural history, archaeology and cultural history are housed in the visitor center, build by CCC stone masons in the late 1930s. A short video about the park is available as well. A bookstore offers a wide range of titles on topics ranging from Apache history to children's books about the regional flora and fauna.

name: Chisos Basin Visitor Center
description: The Chisos Basin Visitor Center includes interactive exhibits on plants, animals, and birds found in the Chisos Mountains. Backcountry and river use permits are issued during normal business hours, and entrance fees can be paid at the visitor center. A Big Bend Natural History Association bookstore and restrooms are located at the visitor center. A water faucet is available on the east side of the building for filling personal water containers
audioDescription: The Chisos Basin Visitor Center is located in the Chisos Basin developed area, where the road into the mountains ends. It sits in a bowl or basin, completely surrounded by high mountains. A low "V" at the western side of the basin is the low point through which water exists the basin, and provides a stunning view to the desert below. Located near the visitor center are the hotel rooms, gift shop, restaurant, and campstore that are part of the Chisos Mountains Lodge complex. The inside of the visitor center includes a small bookstore, exhibits that talk about the wildlife and plantlife of the Chisos Mountains, and an information desk. Restrooms and a water bottle filling station are located out in front of the visitor center.

name: Christiansted National Historic Site Bookstore and Welcome Center
description: The bookstore is located at the historic Scale House, at the water's edge.
audioDescription: Walk west down Hospital Street towards Christiansted Harbor. At the intersection of Hospital and King Street is the two-story Scale House. The bookstore and visitor contact post is located through the large arched doorway to the left; the historic scale is located through the large arched doorway to the right.

directionsInfo: To Christiansted National Historic Site from Henry E. Rohlsen Airport: Drive east on Route 64 to Melvin Edwards Highway (Route 66). name: Christiansted National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: Fort Christiansvaern at Christiansted National Historic Site serves as the point of information for all three national park units on St. Croix, including Buck Island Reef National Monument and Salt River Bay National Historical Park and Ecological Preserve. Visit the fee booth at the fort for brochures, pamphlets, and guides.
audioDescription: From the parking lot walk north towards the water. Turn left at the concrete walkway and follow the walkway as it passes the gated stable yard. Turn right where it intersects the main concrete walkway. The entrance to the fort is straight ahead. Once inside the ravelin yard turn to the first door to the right; this is the fee booth. Pay entrance fees at the desk.

name: City of Rocks Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center for City of Rocks National Reserve and Castle Rocks State Park is located just outside the National Reserve in the community of Almo. Stop in to chat with a Ranger or pick up maps, guide booklets, and other informative resources. We also offer souvenirs such as books, mugs, apparel, postcards, and stickers.
audioDescription: Exterior: Overview: The visitor center is located in sagebrush rangeland surrounded by mountains in the near distance. At this location is a parking lot, the main visitor center building with free wifi, vault toilet, water spigot, short interpretive trail, xeric garden, lawn, and picnic tables. Highway 77 spur runs north/south along the west side of the Visitor Center complex. Surrounding the area are views of rangeland, mountains, and rock formations. The paved parking consists of 9 demarcated parking spots, including one handicap accessible spot, and a large open area for vehicle turnaround/extra parking. A concrete sidewalk borders the south side of the parking lot and runs along the north side of the Visitor Center building, connecting the Visitor Center entrance to the west and the vault toilet to the east. Centrally located along the sidewalk is a general information board and a weatherproof box containing maps and brochures. On the east side of the parking area is a 0.2 mile long loop trail. The trail is 4 ft wide compacted gravel with a mostly level surface. Along the trail are two replica prairie schooner wagons, three information exhibit signs, a weather station, and an area with shade trees, picnic table, and fire ring. On the southeast corner of the parking lot is an ADA compliant vault toilet. Just to the west of the toilet are a few garbage/recycling bins and a drinking water spigot. The Visitor Center building is a 2 story former ranch house from the early 1900s with red brick walls and white accents similar to other historic houses in the town of Almo built in the same era. The entrance to the Visitor Center is on the northwest corner of the building. West of the building is an open lawn with a few picnic tables and large shade trees. On the southwest of the building is a covered porch with a picnic table underneath on a concrete pad. Interior: Overview: Stop in to chat with a Ranger or pick up maps, guide booklets, and other informative resources. There are souvenirs for sale such as books, mugs, apparel, postcards, and stickers. Inside the visitor center is the main room/front desk area, the gift shop room, the theater room, and employee offices. The floors are flat carpet, except the entryway, which is stone. Main Room: The front door enters into the main room of the Visitor Center. Directly in front of the entrance, about 4 feet inside is the front desk and cash register which spans the right wall (west). Past the desk to the south is a large doorway which leads to the theater room. On the east wall is a rotating exhibit. To the left of the exhibit is a hallway that leads to employee offices and an employee restroom, available to visitors upon request. The north wall, next to the entryway, contains an entrance to the gift shop in the center, with a wall of free brochures next to the door. Gift Shop: The gift shop contains a rotating selection of merchandise available to purchase such as books, mugs, apparel, postcards, and stickers. On the west wall is shelving, cabinets, a countertop, and a large picture window. The north wall contains hanging merchandise items and a small window. The east wall is mostly covered by a large bookshelf with two columns of 5-6 shelves of varying sizes. Directly next to the bookshelf is a small nook with more merchandise. Theater Room: The theater room is on the south end of the building. This room has 2 display cases in the northwest and southwest corners with rotating exhibits, as well as 2 rows of chairs set up toward a tv screen on the east wall. Ask a ranger for assistance to play an 8 minute video about the park. The video has subtitles, and can also be played with audio description. The video is also available on the website. To the left of the TV on the east wall is an entrance to the employee kitchen, back door, and a staircase leading to employee offices.

description: Enjoy sweeping views of the Smokies, weather permitting, and get your park questions answered. Peruse a small bookstore and shop. Public restrooms are available.
audioDescription: This stone building was constructed in the 1930s and served originally as a restroom. Today it houses a park bookstore and souvenir shop. Knowledgeable volunteers provide information and a small assortment of exhibits convey information about air quality.

name: Colter Bay Visitor Center
description: A surviving Mission 66 visitor center, the Colter Bay Visitor Center provides great views of Jackson Lake. Inside, view 35 artifacts from the David T. Vernon Indian Arts Collection. The auditorium hosts ranger-led programs and shows a variety of park-related videos throughout the day. Visit this facility for trip planning information, backcountry, or boating permits. Shop at the Grand Teton Association bookstore, attend a ranger-led program, or visit nearby shops and restaurants.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is a low, long building. Its vertical board-and-batten siding is painted a dark brown. The entrance is located close to the center of the building and may be accessed by a ramp or up a set of three steps just to the left of the ramp. There are benches to the left of the steps. Restrooms are located in a breezeway at the far left end of the building. A ramp leads up to the breezeway. The entrance leads into a large, airy lobby with walls and ceiling of natural-finished pine. An information counter is on the right wall and the entrance to an auditorium is on the left. To your immediate right as you enter is a wide doorway leading to the bookstore and gift shop and a small exhibit area which features American Indian objects from the David T. Vernon Collection including touchable exhibits. At the far right, past the counter is an area which hosts American Indian guest artists during the summer months. The far wall of the entrance lobby is glass and has an exit onto a large deck in the rear of the building. From here the land slopes down to the bay with views of Mount Moran beyond. The deck is surfaced with rough planking with wide, one-inch spacing between the planks and is edged with a wooden railing. Several benches are located long the railing. At the far left end stairs provide access to the waterfront.
directionsInfo: Heading north on US 26/89/191, turn left (north) at Moran Junction and continue 10.5 miles on US 89/191/287 to the Colter Bay Village sign, turn left (west) and continue about one mile to the visitor center. Heading south on US 89/191/287 from Yellowstone National Park, continue 18.5 miles to the Colter Bay Village sign, turn right (west) and continue about one mile to the visitor center

name: Corinth Civil War Interpretive Center
description: Located near the site of Battery Robinett, the Corinth Civil War Interpretive Center, is open from 8:00 am to 5:00 pm every day except Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day. Center exhibits include interactive displays and multimedia presentations on the Battle of Shiloh and the Siege and Battle of Corinth. The Corinth Civil War Interpretive Center is located at 501 West Linden Street in Corinth, Mississippi.
audioDescription: The Corinth Civil War Interpretive Center is a modern structure containing both historical artifacts from the battle and interactive learning activities that tell the story of the Siege and Battle of Corinth and the Union occupation of the town and war's impact on local civilians. Once you arrive in the parking area at 501 West Linden Street, walk east to the head of the sidewalk and follow it to the main building entrance. As you walk you will see the "detritus of war" on both sides of the walkway leading to the Center. This represents the wreckage and debris left behind in wartime Corinth. Once you reach the main entrance a large bronze bas relief on your left represents soldiers on the march. Enter the building and an information desk will be to your front, staffed by NPS rangers and volunteers. It's here where visitors will find more information about the Center and the surrounding area. To your right, you will find the restrooms and main movie theater. To your left will be the bookstore and the entrance to exhibit areas. Just to the left of the information desk you will see two glass doors that lead out into a courtyard and the Fountain of American History. This water feature tells the story of the founding of our nation up to the end of the Civil War. Please, take a moment to reflect on this story and how it still affects us today. Once you enter the exhibit area, you will se artifacts from the Siege, Battle, and Occupation of Corinth, and learn about the war's impact on the town and people. Visitors will discover two short films that are continually shown throughout the day; one examining the Battle of Shiloh and the other about Corinth during the war. On the north side of the Center two glass door lead outside into an area built to replicate a Civil War fortification, one of many that defended Corinth and its garrison during the war. A short walk behind the Center will lead you to the former site of Battery Robinett and several monuments.

name: Coronado National Memorial Visitor Center
description: The visitor center includes in-depth exhibits on the Coronado Expedition of 1540-1542, as well as thorough information about the natural history of the park. There are hands-on displays of 16th century clothing and armor for visitors to try on, and interactive exhibits in English and Spanish. A 14-foot picture window provides visitors with a wonderful opportunity to view and photograph the flora and fauna in a relaxed atmosphere.

name: Cottonwood Visitor Center
description: Near the South Entrance to Joshua Tree National Park. Exhibits, bookstore, water, and flush toilets onsite. Picnic area nearby.
audioDescription: The Cottonwood Visitor Center sits on a high desert plateau in the transition zone between the Mojave and Colorado deserts. To the northeast, Eagle Mountain stands lofty as a rugged backdrop. Weather can be extreme. Summers are blistering, with bright sunny weather and temperatures exceeding 100 degrees daily. Winters are cool to cold, with strong winds and sub-freezing nights. Snow is possible. The occasional rainstorm poses the threat of flash flooding. There is abundant flora and fauna nearby. Desert wilderness surrounds the visitor center. Around the building we find short desert plants. There are cacti and various flora with thorns and sharp points. Cat’s-claw acacia and many of the shrubs can be unforgiving if brushed up against. There are also plants native to the Mojave, such as yucca, juniper, and sage. In spring, red berries appear on the purple bush. Prince’s Plume are adorned with yellow flowers. The ironwood trees near the Bajada Nature Trail sprout pink and purple flowers. After a rain, the Ocotillo grow red flowers and green leaves. The Prince's Plume, ironwood trees, and Ocotillo are native to the Colorado desert. Gambel’s Quail call out throughout the day, often scurrying around the parking lot. Mule deer, coyotes, and even bighorn sheep frequent the nearby landscape. Throughout the day ravens and turkey vultures soar overheard. Black-tailed jackrabbits nervously hop along, as a red-tail hawk eyes it’s next prey from the sky. In the warmer months, rattlesnakes and desert tortoise roam the nearby sandy trails. There are three one-story buildings that comprise the visitor center facilities: The visitor center, a restroom, and a staff office. From the parking area, the visitor center is located to the left. The restroom is situated to the right of the visitor center and 30 feet across from the parking lot. The men’s restroom is located on the left side of this building, and the women’s restroom is located on the right side. There are picnic tables and bulletin boards between the restrooms and the office to the right. The visitor center also serves as a gift shop and fee-entrance station. The door is located on the south side of the building. As you enter, there is a brochure table 6 feet from the inside of the door. On the right side of the building you will see interpretive panels with information about the geology, history, and geography of Joshua Tree National Park. On the walls on the south and east side of the building are panels with quotes about the park. This side also has displays with merchandise sold by the Joshua Tree National Park Association. The front counter is 25 feet from the door where you can buy park passes and merchandise. A window on the west side of the building that has been modified to receive payments for entrance fees, directly to the left of the front counter. Plexiglass hangs around the front counter for the protection of staff and visitors. The building has standard lighting and when the blinds are up, the outside sun provides ample illumination. To the right of the front counter there are more displays for merchandise. On the east wall, there is a window with a majestic view of Eagle Mountain, Mastodon Peak, and the surrounding desert. South of this window there is a bookcase with various publications on Joshua Tree National Park. In the center of the visitor center there is a life-sized mold of a desert tortoise enclosed in glass. On the west side, to the left of the brochure table, there is a window. Next to this window there is a fold-out sign that says “Encuentra Tu Parque” (“Find your Park” in Spanish). There are more store displays as you make your way closer to the front counter. There is a small, slightly shaded courtyard in-between the visitor center and the offices. There are creosote bush and beavertail cactus in the middle. A small bench is located about 10 feet to the north of the offices. There is also a bulletin with park information, maps, and trail guides. All facilities are accessible through paved and level walkways. Outside of the visitor center, there are sidewalks between the parking lot and the buildings. The parking lot has 2 handicapped spaces, with accessible ramps and paved paths to the visitor center, restroom, and office. The office is restricted to park staff and those with authorization to enter. To the right of this building is a flagpole and a sign showing air quality and fire danger. There is also a sign that displays fees to enter the park. There is a short tenth of a mile dirt nature trail that is immediately east of the visitor center. The trail is a loop that starts a few feet from the paved path that leads to the main entrance. It ends on the east side of the parking lot. There are signs along the way identifying various plants and shrubs that can be found in the area. Park rangers here every day to answer questions and provide guidance into Joshua Tree National Park.

name: Cowpens National Battlefield
description: Museum contains a reproduction 3-pounder cannon, other weapons and artifacts of the Revolutionary War period, and exhibits. "Cowpens: A Battle Remembered" is an 18-minute video shown hourly in the museum. American Battlefield Trust film on the American Revolution shown in the map room (18 minutes) Sales Outlet operated by America's National Parks offers books, postcards, and theme-related souvenirs.
audioDescription: From the Visitor Center Parking Lot, a sloping concrete patio/walkway leads to the 1932 US Monument and visitor center. Black granite squares with names and dates of Southern Campaign of the American Revolution battles are inset into the walk way. At the top of the slope, to the left is a small wayside exhibit and a 32 foot grey granite obelisk with bronze markers on 2 sides. This is the US Monument. The interpretive battlefield trail begins behind the monument. The visitor center restrooms are to the right of the monument, and the visitor center is behind it. The restrooms are in a square brick building that is attached to the brick visitor center by a covered breezeway. To the right of the visitor center is a flagpole.
passportStampLocationDescription: If you are not able to visit Cowpens National Battlefield this year, you can still get a virtual passport stamp. The stamps are a classic NPS Passport Cancellation Stamp consisting of a circle, park name and date.

name: Craggy Gardens Visitor Center
description: The small, historic visitor center and America's National Parks store is nestled in the gap between the rocky, Craggy Mountains. At over 5,000 feet elevation, harsh weather often invades these exposed ridges, resulting in the gnarled forests of beech, birch, and buckeye. These summits have been home to some of the most spectacular rhododendron displays along the Parkway corridor. For generations, visitors have headed up to the Craggies in mid to late June to view the pink and purple blooms.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps are located in the America's National Parks store in the visitor center.

directionsInfo: Craggy Gardens is located 20 miles north of our Blue Ridge Parkway Visitor Center (MP 384) and 18 miles north of the Folk Art Center (MP 382), with the drive taking about a half hour. If you take Ox Creek Rd (MP 375) up from Weaverville it takes about 15 minutes on the Parkway.Craggy Gardens is about a half hour drive south of Mount Mitchell, the tallest mountain in eastern North America. Mount Mitchell's access road (NC-128) turns off the Parkway at MP 355.

name: Craig Thomas Discovery & Visitor Center
description: The grand expanse of the Teton Range rises above the visitor center. Inside, interwoven themes of place, people, preservation, mountaineering, and American Indians encourage visitors to contemplate the past, present, and future of this place. Visit this facility for trip planning information, backcountry or boating permits. Shop at the Grand Teton Association bookstore, enjoy the variety of exhibits and artwork, attend a ranger program or watch a movie about the park.
audioDescription: The Craig Thomas Discovery and Visitor Center is reached by a wide paved pathway that curves around from the parking lot on the north side of the building. From the parking lot, you can see the side of the building, its grey metal roof slanting up to your right. The building has horizontal wood siding with a natural finish, but the west end, to your right, is glass from floor to ceiling. The sidewalk approaches the building from the east, where it forms a "U" shape around a central courtyard. The sidewalk splits to lead to a veranda on either side of the courtyard. At the split is a life-size sculpture of a bull moose. The paved courtyard is sunken, with 4 shallow steps leading down from the veranda on all sides. Two large boulders sit near the middle. Viewed from the front, the roof forms a jagged line, echoing the mountain peaks beyond. The veranda roof is supported by large wooded posts spaced 12 feet apart. To reach the entrance, proceed down the veranda along the right side of the courtyard to the far corner. Turn left and the doors will be 15 feet beyond on your right. Audio descriptions of the interior will be automatically triggered by bluetooth transmitters located throughout the space. To hear the first of these, move about 25 feet to your right along the wall after you enter the building.

name: Cruz Bay Visitor Center
description: Virgin Islands National Park and Virgin Islands Coral Reef National Monument Visitor Center is located in Cruz Bay.
audioDescription: The Cruz Bay Visitors Center is in the town of Cruz Bay adjacent to the National Park’s Finger Pier and the Cruz Bay public baseball field. The driveway to the Visitors Center is at the beginning of the North Shore Road, Route 20. There are numerous spots for visitors to park outside the building. Also located in the area near the parking lot are the men’s and women’s rest room. You can enter the building by using a ramp, or two staircases located on either side of the ramp. The building was deigned to look like an old Danish West Indian warehouse with large shuttered windows designed to replicate the carriage doors of tan old warehouses. It is light yellow in color. The shutters are dark green. There are several interpretive exhibits in the building. The first is titled Changing Paradise and brings attention to the constant changes that happen on the island--both natural changes and changes by the movement of different groups of people throughout the Caribbean. Across from the first panel is the entrance to the gift shop managed by the Friends of Virgin Islands National Park. You can find park souvenirs like t-shirts, patches, stickers, books, post cards and magnets in the gift shop. As you continue to the second panel titled Marine Ecology you will find information on the life below the surface in the waters that surround the park. There is also a display case with examples of coral and a diorama of a coral reef . The next panel called The Shoreline has photographs of the plants and animals that live in-between the land and the sea. There are photographs of crabs, shore birds, nesting sea turtles and coastal vegetation. Separated by a replica of a tall Kapok tree the next panel titled The Land has photographs of different terrestrial habitats and the creatures that can be found there. You will see photographs of bats, frogs and lizards. In between The Land panel and the next panel titled The First People there is a glass display case with some replicas of artifacts from the early inhabitants of the Virgin Islands, the Taino’s. Ceramics and stone axes can be seen inside the case. Across from this panel in the middle of the room there is a topographical model of the island of St John. It shows the boundary of the park as well as the roads, beaches and park trails. The large shuttered windows separate the First People panel with the next exhibit panel titled Colonial St. John. This panel focuses on the plantation system and the layers of change that occurred on St. John. There are sketches of windmills, great houses and enslaved Africans working in the sugar cane fields. Another display case separates the Colonial St. John panel from the Africans panel. This case has replicas from the plantation days like cane knifes and ceramic plates. The Africans panel tells the story of the horrible conditions of the human cargo aboard slave ships and the rising up, the slave revolt, that took place in 1733. There are sketches of enslaved Africans working in the cane fields and there is a Conch Shell hanging over the panel which is a symbol for Freedom in the Caribbean. There is another display case with crafts that were made by Virgin Islanders after emancipation. Skilled craftsmen and women made items like fish traps and baskets, necessary to survival. The last exhibit panel titled Our Environmental Heritage pays tribute to the people who remained on the island after the plantation economy came to an end. There are photographs of former cultural demonstrators who shared their skills with park visitors over the years. Where the displays end you will find yourself across from the front desk of the Visitors Center where you can talk with staff, pick up brochures and make purchases from the gift shop. At the end of the desk there is a water filling station.

name: Cumberland Gap National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The Cumberland Gap National Historical Park Visitor Center is located on U.S. Highway 25E just south of Middlesboro, Kentucky.
audioDescription: Cumberland Gap National Historical Park’s visitor center is located south of Middlesboro, KY and is accessed from Hwy 25E exit ramps. Address for use with a GPS is 91 Bartlett Park Road, Middlesboro, KY 40965. GPS coordinates: Lat: 36.602758 Long: -83.695322. The visitor center is open daily from 9 am to 4 pm. The visitor center is closed on Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day. The American flag and park signage alert that you have arrived at the accessible visitor center complex. As you step from your vehicle, immediately immerse yourself in the park’s rich chapters of history. A hewn log cabin in front of the visitor center evokes images of the early settlers from all walks of life who traveled through America’s first doorway to the west. A banner on front of the visitor center parades images of letters from settlers revealing their hardships, fears, and dreams of entering into a new land which lay beyond the Appalachian Mountains. A M1841 6 pounder field gun on the visitor center front patio stands as a silent sentinel of the numerous Civil War fortifications which were perched on high places ringing Cumberland Gap. Union and Confederate regiments spent months at a time at the Gap, watching and waiting for the enemy’s next move. Here, a war of nerves pivoted more on available supplies and flanking movements than on bombardments or bloody assaults. Enter the visitor center and find yourself in the Southern Appalachian forest! Six-foot wide diameter trees, representative of the old growth forest that once dominated the area, tower in the visitor center lobby. Exhibits in the visitor center museum chronicle the many stories of the Gap. Two high-definition films, “Daniel Boone and the Westward Movement” and “The Cumberland Gap” further orient you to the park. Become a Junior Ranger! An America’s National Parks store in the visitor center provides sales items to help you delve deeper into the park’s cultural and natural history. Get stamped with seven passport cancellations which are only available at the visitor center. Restrooms, located at the end of the building closest to the parking area, are open 24 hours a day.
passportStampLocationDescription: Cumberland Gap National Historical Park has seven passport stamps that are a circle with Cumberland Gap NHP printed along the top border, the date in the center, and the location printed along the bottom border. The main stamp location is Middlesboro, KY. Additional locations are Wilderness Road Trail, Hensley Settlement, Iron Furnace 1819, Gap Cave, Tri-state Marker, and Pinnacle Overlook.

name: Cumberland Visitor Center
description: The Cumberland Visitor Center is located at mile 184.5 along the C&O Canal towpath in Allegany County, MD. Located in the Western Maryland Railway station, the visitor center features a spacious exhibit area full of interactive displays about the history of the C&O Canal and Cumberland. Pass through a model of the Paw Paw Tunnel and step back into the hey day of the canal. Awaiting you is a life size section of a canal boat. View exhibits on the canal's construction, cargo, mules, locks, and crew.
audioDescription: [98 Words] The Cumberland Visitor’s Center is a 3 story red and white brick building. The second floor is a train station, which is about 20 feet above the ground floor. In front of the building is a large public space all lain with red brick, a statue of a mule with their caretaker, and a water fountain. The end of the GAP trail and well as the beginning of the C&O Towpath starts in front of the building. To the right of the building is a large mural of the history of Cumberland, Maryland stretching about 100 feet long.

name: César E. Chávez National Monument Visitor Center
description: Explore the history of Cesar Chavez and the farmworker movement. Originally built in 1914, the visitor center was entirely rebuilt in 2003. Inside, watch films about Cesar’s life, contemplate his office, and view exhibits that tell the story of the boycotts and marches that began the farmworker movement, and of the people who united to work for human rights. The visitor center has an auditorium that has hosted naturalization ceremonies, and a store that offers books and souvenirs. There is no entrance fee.
audioDescription: A concrete pathway turns left and then ends at the entrance of a handsome wooden building. The wood siding is painted white and windows along the front are divided into many panes. Trees and shrubs provide shade all around the building. A small flag features a portrait of Cesar Chavez and reads, "Sí, Se Puede." An arrowhead-shaped wooden sign, the logo for the National Park Service, is mounted on the building next to the flag. Wooden double doors lead into the building. A receptacle for trash and cigarettes is just to the right of the doors. Inside, a sign points toward restrooms on the right side of the entrance. A drinking fountain is in the restroom corridor.

name: Dante Fascell Visitor Center
description: The Dante Fascell Visitor Center is located at Convoy Point, 9 miles East of the city of Homestead, Florida. A beautiful museum offers a virtual journey through the park's four ecosystems using dioramas, audio and video. Several films are available to help you learn about the park, including the 20-minute feature presentation: Connections. The Gallery highlights the works of local artists who find inspiration in the park.
audioDescription: The visitor center is located on the east side of the parking lot. It is a two story, grey clapboard building with a weathered metal peaked roof. A large wrap around porch with rocking chairs is on the second floor facing east with a view of the boat harbor, mangrove shoreline, and Biscayne Bay in the distance. Located on the first floor are a classroom, restrooms, and a water fountain/bottle filling station. On the second floor is the museum with natural history displays and the auditorium where the park film is shown. Separate from the museum, the bookshop is also located on the second floor. Check in here for boat tours with the Biscayne National Park Institute. A second water fountain/bottle filling station is also located here. Access to the floors is via the elevator, ramp or stairs.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are located in the Dante Fascell Visitor Center. The Virtual Visit passport stamp is available online.

name: Darrah Hall
description: Darrah Hall is the oldest building on the campus of the Penn Center, and is the park's base of operations for the Penn Center National Historic Landmark District.
audioDescription: Darrah Hall is the oldest building on the campus of the Penn Center. Over the years it has been used as a classroom, community center, basketball court, temperance hall, and today is the hub of the park's operations on the Penn Center campus. The building is made of wood and painted white, with a red-shingle roof. Most of the paint is a little older and flaking in some places. It is a one story building, but there are steps up to a front porch. On the right side of the building is a long ramp to a side entrance. The building is situated in a field, and there are a few picnic tables scattered in the yard. To the right of the building are two small white structures - a storage shed and a restroom. Inside Darrah Hall there are wooden floors, with high ceilings supported by visible wooden ceilings. The walls are wood panels with large open windows, most illuminating the space with natural light. At the front of the building is a small elevated stage with a red curtain pulled closed. Around the walls are a series of printed banners that show historic photos of the building over the years.

name: David Wills House
description: The home of Gettysburg attorney David Wills was the center of the immense clean-up process after the Battle of Gettysburg and where President Lincoln put the finishing touches on his Gettysburg Address. The museum features six galleries, including two rooms that have been restored to their 1863 appearance: Wills' office, where he planned for a Soldiers' National Cemetery after the battle; and the bedroom where Lincoln stayed and prepared the Gettysburg Address. Admission to the the Wills House is free.

name: De Soto National Memorial Visitor Center
description: The De Soto National Visitor Center shows the park's movie Hernando de Soto in America throughout the day. Visitors can receive information such as program and tour times and signups, trail maps, brochures, and the parks Junior Ranger Activity Book.
audioDescription: De Soto National Memorial's Visitor Center is located just east of the parking lot. To get to the Visitor Center take the side walk on the northern end of the parking lot through the palisade entrance. Continue to follow the sidewalk and take a right turn to face east towards the entrance of the Visitor Center.

name: Denali Bus Depot
description: This summer facility is operated by our concessionaire rather than by the National Park Service. It is the primary place to buy bus tickets, arrange for stays in park campgrounds, or to check in for an existing reservation. Coffee and grab-and-go food is also available for purchase. Only credit cards are accepted here.

name: Denali Visitor Center
description: Open in summer only, this is the main visitor center near the park entrance. During the summer, you can explore exhibits, watch the park film, pay the park entrance fee, and talk with a ranger. In fall, winter and spring, the Murie Science and Learning Center (MSLC) acts as the park's Winter Visitor Center.

name: Devils Postpile Ranger Station
description: The Devils Postpile Ranger Station is open daily from 9 am - 5 pm during the operating season which is typically mid-June to mid-October. Rangers can help you plan your adventure at Devils Postpile. The ranger station is listed on the National Register of Historic Places for its association with changes in national park planning and development from the late 1930s to the start of World War II in 1941. The simple two-room cabin was constructed in 1941 from lumber salvaged from the demolished Sentinel Hotel.

directionsInfo: Shuttle Bus: Most visitors must park at the Mammoth Mountain Ski Area and use the mandatory shuttle. The shuttle bus operates from mid-June through the Wednesday after Labor Day. By car: From U.S. Highway 395, drive 10 miles west on S.R. 203 to Minaret Vista and then another 8 miles on a paved, steep mountain road. Please note that this road is single lane for approximately 3 miles. By plane: The closest commercial airport is the Mammoth Lakes/Yosemite Airport (MMH), located on U.S. Highway 395.

name: Devils Tower National Monument Visitor Center
description: The Devils Tower National Monument Visitor Center currently contains the Devils Tower Natural History Association Bookstore. The visitor center was built in the 1930s by the Civilian Conservation Corps and is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp has the name and location of the national monument and today's date. The cancellation stamp is located just outside of the Visitor Center, 24 hours a day.

name: Dickey Ridge Visitor Center
description: Dickey Ridge Visitor Center (mile 4.6) is located near Front Royal, Virginia, in the northern part of the Park. It's the ideal place for visitors entering through the Front Royal Entrance Station to find restrooms, information, a bookstore, publications, and maps. Right across Skyline Drive from the visitor center you will find the popular Fox Hollow Trail trailhead.
audioDescription: Dickey Ridge Visitor Center is a long single story, rectangular, brown wooden building. The parking lot is to the south of the building. Restrooms are found next to the parking area. A tall antenna is next to the building by the southern end. There is a semi-circular paved stone terrace directly in front of the building with two large planter boxes located by the main glass double doors. A sign that says "Entrance" hangs from the roof by the main doors. There roof extends out from the building to create a veranda alongside the length of the building. It is supported by many wooden pillars. The building also has many large floor to ceiling windows. You enter the building into a large central room where you will find the ranger information desk directly ahead as well as other bulletin boards with information. Turning right and heading through a doorway will take you to Shenandoah National Park Association's gift shop. Turning left from the central room and heading through a doorway will take you to the interpretive exhibit, including a large bas relief map of Shenandoah National Park lying flat on a table. Continuing further through another doorway in this direction will take you to the auditorium where movies and Ranger talks are presented. Exiting the building will bring you back to the terrace and a great view looking westward.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are located at the information desk inside of the visitor center.

Take the exit onto Route 340 South and follow signs for Shenandoah National Park and Skyline Drive, which will lead you to the Front Royal Entrance Station . Once on Skyline Drive, make your way south to mile marker 4.6; you will find Dickey Ridge Visitor Center on your right.

name: Dock Ranger Station
description: The ranger station at the Alcatraz Island Dock is staffed at all times. Staff here can help you with directions, information, Special Ranger and Junior Ranger programs, emergency assistance, and more. In accordance with CDC, state, and local public health guidance related to COVID-19, these hours may vary.

name: Dog Canyon Ranger Station
description: Visitors can pick up brochures and maps from the Dog Canyon Ranger Station when staff or volunteers are available. The Dog Canyon Ranger Station is open intermittently depending on staff availability. If staff and volunteers are present they may be patrolling trails or the campground and not necessarily inside the station.

directionsInfo: Coming from Texas: Traveling north on Highway 62/180 you will cross the state line into New Mexico. About 27 miles after crossing the state line, you will come up on the junction of Dark Canyon Rd-408. Turning in to Dark Canyon Rd-408 N follow the road for 22 miles to the junction of NM-137 N. At the junction, turn into NM-137 N and follow for 35 miles to the entrance of Dog Canyon.

name: E. E. Fogelson Visitor Center
description: Begin at the Visitor Center, where you can watch an introductory film or view an excellent museum that covers the region's history and archeology. Before your walk, you'll receive a narrative brochure. You may also purchase an interpretive guide that you take on the Ancestral Sites Trail with you. Be sure to wear sunscreen and bring a water bottle, which you can fill up with chilled water in the Visitor Center.
passportStampLocationDescription: The stamps are just inside the visitor center's front doors right next to the information desk. We have 6 different stamps to add to your collection!

name: Eagle Visitor Center
description: Located along the mighty Yukon River in Eagle, Alaska, this visitor center is the welcome center for those ready to explore Yukon-Charley Rivers National Preserve. Speak with a ranger, receive a backcountry orientation, and finalize the details of your trip in the preserve.

name: Eastern Front Visitor Center
description: The Eastern Front Visitor Center is the park's main visitor center, including museum, gift shop, and 18 minute video. The Visitor Center is open every day. Hours: 9:00 am - 5:00 pm. Visitor Center is closed Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Years Day.
passportStampLocationDescription: Rubber Stamp includes "Petersburg National Battlefield" and the date of visit. Stamps for Junior Rangers and other units with in the park.

name: Education Center
description: Begin your visit at the Education Center, located in Cantons historic City National Bank. At the Education Center visitors can explore our small museum of rotating exhibits, watch a film, earn Junior Ranger badges, and get their official passport cancellation.
audioDescription: The Education Center is a six story building of sandstone. The exterior of the building says City National Bank on the first level and has a façade of alternating arched and squared windows. There are two sets of stairs leading in and out of the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is located in the education center.

name: El Malpais Visitor Center
description: Located on exit 85 off I-40 in Grants, NM, the El Malpais Visitor Center is staffed by park rangers from the National Park Service. Stop in for maps, information, orientation, cave permits, a Western National Parks Association bookstore, museum exhibits, and park movies.
audioDescription: The El Malpais National Monument Visitor Center is a southwestern inspired building with beige and red stucco. The front entrance is landscaped with black lava rocks, and a cement walkway leads to a picnic area and a balcony that overlooks a panorama of black basalt landscape dotted with desert flora.
passportStampLocationDescription: The El Malpais Visitor Center has an El Malpais stamp and a Continental Divide Trail stamp.

directionsInfo: Take Exit 85 off I-40 in Grants, NM. If coming from the east, turn left at the stop sign, and proceed across the freeway overpass. If coming from the west, turn right at the stop sign. Turn left at the entrance sign to the El Malpais Visitor Center. Continue 300 yards to the parking area.

name: El Morro Visitor Center
description: Your visit to El Morro National Monument begins here. Park rangers and volunteers are available to answer your questions and orient you to the facilities and self-guided trails. Both of the park trails begin at the visitor center.
audioDescription: The El Morro Visitor Center stands before tall sandstone cliffs that rise 200 feet above the valley floor. The visitor center is a one-story structure that exhibits architecture from the 1960s. The building incorporates tall glass windows, rock columns, and paneled wood sidings.
passportStampLocationDescription: Two passport stamps are available at the Visitor Center. The standard cancellation stamp can be found here, as well as a US Camel Corps stamp.

name: Ellis Island Information Desk
description: The Ellis Island Information Desk provides general information, including the schedule of ranger-guided tours, special program, and film times. A ranger or volunteer is available to answer questions and provide information about the Ellis Island Museum of Immigration and make recommendations for your visit. The park brochure, Passport To Your National Parks (R) cancellation stamp, and the ferry departure schedule are also located at the information desk.
audioDescription: The Ellis Island Information Desk is located inside the main building on Ellis Island. This brick and limestone building is three stories high with ornate windows and cupolas. Upon entering the building, the desk is on the left below informational signs that highlight the movie times and tour times that are being offered that day. On the desk are located boat times as well as maps for the museum. The height of the desk as approximately three (3) feet while the length is about thirty (30) feet. The sides are a gray concrete while the top of the desk is a smooth, dark gray stone.
passportStampLocationDescription: The circular stamp reads Ellis Island Immigration Museum, New York, NY with the date in the middle.

name: Ellwood
description: Ellwood is located on the Wilderness Battlefield. Ellwood was a slave plantation, a Civil War headquarters and hospital, and its small family cemetery contains Confederate general Thomas "Stonewall" Jackson's arm. The gate is open during the hours the house is open, but the grounds of Ellwood are open sunrise to sunset. When the gate is closed visitors may park next to, but not blocking, the gate and walk the grounds.
audioDescription: Taking a left turn from Constitution Highway to a gravel single lane road will lead to the Ellwood gate. If the gate is closed, park to the side, and walk a quarter mile up the dirt road to Ellwood Manor. If the gate is open, drive up until you reach the parking area to the right of the long driveway. The grounds of Ellwood are surrounded by agricultural fields. The lawn from the parking area to the house is flat, but there is no set pathway through the grass. The manor house is a 2 and a half story red farm house. The front of the house, with stairs leading to double doors, is facing away from the parking area. There is an accessible ramp in the rear of the house, facing the parking area.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Ellwood passport stamp is available here. This stamp is also available at the Chancellorsville Battlefield Visitor Center for times when Ellwood is closed.
amenities: ['Accessible Rooms', 'Baby Changing Station', 'Gifts/Souvenirs/Books', 'Historical/Interpretive Information/Exhibits', 'Information', 'Parking - Auto', 'Parking - Bus/RV', 'Restroom', 'Restroom - Accessible', 'Water - Bottle-Filling Station']
directionsInfo: Ellwood is located on the Wilderness Battlefield off of Rt. 20 (Constitution Hwy), approximately 5 miles west of the Chancellorsville Battlefield Visitor Center. To reach Ellwood, turn into the gravel driveway at the brown "Ellwood" sign on Rt. 20, 0.6 miles southwest of Rt. 20's intersection with Rt. 3. The Ellwood driveway-entrance is on your left when headed west on Rt. 20, towards Orange, and on your right when headed east on Rt. 20, towards Rt. 3.

description: The Entrance Station is your first stop at Valles Caldera National Preserve. Rangers and volunteers are available to answer questions, provide park information, and sell park souvenirs and merchandise. Two accessible, unisex, vault-toilet restrooms are available across the parking lot.
audioDescription: Driving down the main entrance dirt road, the Entrance Station is visible from a distance. The tan-colored cabin has a large dirt parking lot on the right as you approach. A ramp on the parking lot side makes the building accessible for people with mobility issues. A separate cement building directly across the parking lot from the contact station provides two accessible, unisex, vault-toilet restrooms.

Visitors arriving outside station hours may pay their fee directly through www.recreation.gov. Park brochures can be found at the signboard on the right.
audioDescription: Approximately 1/2 mile from the entrance to the park, visitors will pass through the 2 lanes of entrance station kiosks where they will pay entrance fees, purchase park passes and request information. name: Ernest F. Coe Visitor Center
description: The Ernest F. Coe Visitor Center is the visitor center closest to Homestead for Everglades National Park. It is open 365 days a year and offers educational displays, orientation films, and informational brochures. Park Rangers are available to help plan your trip. There is a giftshop that sells souvenirs and snacks. In the summer time it is open 9AM - 5PM and in the winter it is open 8AM - 5PM.
audioDescription: There are four rows for parking in the parking lot. In the middle of the lot, there is a grassy median that has an interpretive sign, sitting benches and garbage and recycling bins. There is a crosswalk on the east side, allowing for safe crossing to the visitor center building. As you approach the visitor center there will be accessible restrooms, a water fountain and a water bottle filling station on the north side. On the south side, you will see an open Everglades interpretive area, with a large park map and information on places you can check out. There are also garbage and recycling bins. There is a boardwalk that takes you to the visitor center and there are a few interpretive signs along the boardwalk’s railing. About 60 yards (55 meters) down the boardwalk you will reach the front doors to the visitor center. There is a silver button with a blue accessibility symbol on the south side. After you go through the front doors, you will enter the foyer. In the foyer, there is a silver button with a blue accessibility symbol on the right-hand side. In the visitor center, there is a bookstore on your left-hand side. The bookstore sells clothing, books, gifts and other items. Across the bookstore, on the right, there is a large Everglades map mounted on the wall. The map describes points of interest and places to visit while in the park. To the right of the bookstore, there is a large green and brown desk staffed by Park Rangers and volunteers. Park maps, Junior Ranger booklets and other information are available there. There is a television above the information desk and to the right. The screen shows weather information, a schedule of ranger programs and other pertinent information that varies seasonally. Across from the information desk, is a large and detailed exhibit called “Winter Refuge in a Gator Hole”. This circular exhibit allows the visitor to feel things such as an alligator tail and alligator tracks. The exhibit is replicating an alligator hole in the winter. There is a large alligator replica in the center, with bird replicas hanging from the ceiling, and more birds and vegetation surrounding the alligator and along the edge of the exhibit. As you follow the circular exhibit, there are screens on the exhibit panel that show alligator behavior and at the far end of the circular exhibit is a replica mother alligator with her young. Across from the circular exhibit and back towards the front doors is a movie theater that plays the park’s orientation film on request. Between the doors of the movie theater is an exhibit on the Nike Missile Site housed in a glass case and illuminated by a single lamp. The case contains newspaper clippings and other artifacts from the Cuban Missile Crisis. Across from the Nike Missile Site and to the right of the far end of the circular exhibit is an exhibit about birds. The exhibit is a small, dark booth with two spotting scopes. Birds can be seen flying in a video through the spotting scopes. Across from the exhibit with the spotting scopes, is an exhibit called ‘The Great Water Debate’ that explains water issues in South Florida. Different telephone receivers can be picked up and one could listen to the opinions and concerns of various stakeholders about water in the Everglades. To the right of ‘The Great Water Debate’ is a wall mural called ‘The Big Picture’ and it shows how human activity has disturbed the Everglades ecosystem endangering the environment and life within it. On the exhibit panel are lighted buttons that can be pressed to show different aspects of the Everglades. To the left of ‘The Great Water Debate’ exhibit, is a mosaic tile design of South Florida on the floor. There are large windows showing the patio area and to the left is an exhibit on invasive species. The invasive species exhibit is a brown kiosk with a small television screen that shows a video playing on a loop. On the other side of the mosaic tile design of South Florida is an exhibit on the past and present-day indigenous Seminole and Miccosukee peoples and their lands. To the left of the Seminole and Miccosukee exhibit, are double doors that lead to the visitor center patio. There is a silver button with a blue accessibility symbol on the right-hand side on the wall. The patio has rocking chairs, benches and interpretive signs. The deck in the patio overlooks a large freshwater borrow pit lined with tall and green vegetation.

name: Escalante Interagency Visitor Center
description: This center is jointly run by Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument (Bureau of Land Management), Glen Canyon National Recreation Area (National Park Service), and Dixie National Forest (National Forest Service). It features outdoor exhibits focusing on trip planning and interior exhibits on the scientific research surrounding the Escalante region. Permits for hikes into Glen Canyon Wilderness must be obtained here in person. Call ahead for permit status and road conditions. 435-826-5499.
audioDescription: Cylindrical and rectangular building made from local rocks and set ion a Hill at 755 W Main St, Escalante UT. Parking lot is gravel and partially covered. There is an area in front to drop off passengers. Stairs immediately in front of building, with long ramp along the side for an accessible entry. Outdoor shade structure and patio with picnic tables and potable water along the south side of building. A large metal sculpture of a whiptail lizard and a few informational panels are out front. Restrooms are outside of the visitor center on the patio.
passportStampLocationDescription: Escalante Interagency Visitor Center holds the stamps for Glen Canyon National Recreation Area (Escalante, UT), Old Spanish National Historic Trail (Escalante, UT), and Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument (Escalante, UT). These stamps are only accessible when the visitor center is open.

name: Eugene O'Neill National Historic Site
description: The visitor center is part of the Eugene O'Neill NHS. Due to the location and nature of the park, the visitor center is accessible as part of a reservations only tour. There is a small bookstore on site.
passportStampLocationDescription: Here is your "Virtual Visit" Passport stamp for 2020. You may copy or print this passport image for your virtual visit to our site.

amenities: ['Restroom']
directionsInfo: Due to the nature of Eugene O'Neill NHS, visitors are not able to drive directly to the park site. Instead, reservations are required and we offer a free shuttle that will pick up the visitor in downtown Danville, CA. The shuttle meets at 205 Railroad Avenue in downtown Danville, just outside the Museum of the San Ramon Valley. Parking is available next to the museum. More information will be given once you call and make a reservation with the park staff.

name: Exit Glacier Nature Center
description: The Exit Glacier Nature Center is open daily during the summer season. It is closed during the winter. The nature center is the trailhead for all that the Exit Glacier area has to offer, including the Harding Icefield trail. The building includes exhibits about the Exit Glacier area, an Alaska Geographic bookstore, and park rangers to help answer questions about the area.

name: Fairbanks Alaska Public Lands Information Center
description: The Fairbanks Alaska Public Lands Information Center (FAPLIC) supports the appropriate use and enjoyment of Alaska's public lands and resources through "one-stop shopping" for public lands information, trip-planning assistance, and resource education. The interagency partnership encourages visitors and residents to seek meaningful, safe and enjoyable experiences on public lands and inspires to conserve and sustain the natural, cultural and historic resources of Alaska.

name: Faneuil Hall Visitor Center
description: Located in the heart of downtown on the market floor of the historic 1742 building, the Faneuil Hall Visitor Center is the main visitor center for Boston National Historical Park and Boston African American National Historic Site. Maps and information for the Freedom Trail® and Black Heritage Trail® are available here. Tours begin here seasonally.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport Stamps are located at the Visitor Center desk in the Faneuil Hall Marketplace.

name: Fire Island Lighthouse
description: The Fire Island Lighthouse is on the western part of Fire Island National Seashore, adjacent to Robert Moses State Park. The Fire Island Lighthouse area offers exhibits, a nature trail, interpretive programs and curriculum-based fourth grade education programs (school groups by reservation only). There is walking access to the Lighthouse Beach (no lifeguards).
