directionsInfo: Take Robert Moses Causeway south to its end. Circle the Robert Moses State Park water tower, then proceed east to Parking Field #5. There is a parking fee at certain times of the year. On busy summer weekends, you should expect a delay getting to the park due to the high volume of traffic. Park on the east end of the parking lot and follow the boardwalk to the lighthouse (¾-mile walk).

name: Fishing Bridge Visitor Center and Trailside Museum
description: The distinctive stone-and-log architecture of this old building—known as "parkitecture"—was one of several prototypes for park buildings around the country. Today, the visitor center and museum highlight the ecology of Yellowstone Lake, focusing on birds. Also stop by to visit with a ranger and find out when ranger programs are scheduled, buy a fishing permit (payable by debit or credit card), pick up a souvenir, or take in some truly stunning views of Yellowstone Lake and the surrounding mountains.
audioDescription: Fishing Bridge Visitor Center and Trailside Museum 243 words A gravel path lined by stones leads to the one-story wood and stone structure with rectangular windows and three sets of double doors on the building facade. A gable roof supported by large round timbers overhangs the cement patio spanning the front of the building. Just below the roofline, the ends, or cross-sections, of several other timbers jut out slightly over the patio. On the left and middle entrance, an uneven stone step leads to the concrete patio with seams resembling the shape of stones. The right entrance does not have a step but is uneven with protruding stones where the stone step is is filled in with asphalt to make an uneven ramp to the patio. This leads to a concrete ramp with rails and a lip at the threshold into the building. An accessible button is at the left of the left of the door entrance. Indoor features include an information desk staffed by park rangers, exhibits, and an educational bookstore. A ramp is available on request to access the bookstore or Lake Biology exhibit rooms. There are two signs indicating the location of the restrooms. One sign accompanied by a long white arrow pointing left reads: “Restrooms by Parking Area.” The second sign reads “Restrooms” and includes an arrow pointing toward a wooded path that leads to the public restroom. There are evergreen trees dotting the grounds surrounding the center, where the Yellowstone River can be viewed behind the building. END OF MESSAGE

name: Flagg Ranch Information Station
description: The Flagg Ranch Information Station is located in the John D. Rockefeller, Jr. Memorial Parkway—the heart of the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem. For visitors traveling south from Yellowstone National Park, Flagg Ranch is the first stop for trip planning information. This small wooden cabin is staffed daily during the peak summer season and includes a visitor information area, small sales area, exhibits depicting the Rockefeller legacy and restrooms.
audioDescription: The Flagg Visitor Information Station is a one-room log cabin. A plank sidewalk leads to the building from the paved parking area. A peaked roof supported by wooden posts covers the porch area where there is a brochure dispenser, a log bench and a pay telephone. The door is on the right side of the front. Inside the information counter is along the left wall. Restrooms are located straight ahead long the rear wall. There is seating along the right wall and a low table in the middle of the room.

description: Visit the desk and talk with a ranger to learn more about the memorial. The visitor center features a permanent exhibit that focuses on the Flight 93 story within the context of September 11, 2001. Visitors are welcome to a self guided tour through inter-active exhibits. *Taking photographs and/or video recordings of the images and displays within the Visitor Center is prohibited.*

name: Florida Keys Eco-Discovery Center
description: Temporarily closed due to Covid-19. Enter Florida Keys Eco-Discovery Center and take a journey into the world of the native plants and animals of the Keys, both on land and underwater. Leave with an increased awareness and appreciation of the need to protect and conserve ecosystems of South Florida. The Center features over 6,000 square feet of interactive and dynamic exhibits including a mock-up of Aquarius, the world's only underwater ocean laboratory.
audioDescription: The Eco-Discovery center is 6,400 square foot interagency visitor center located on the Nancy Foster Environmental Complex. The property overlooks the North West Channel, has three government docks and accessible outdoor seating for visitors. The two-story building directly behind the center is the administrative headquarters for Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary. The paved parking lot has spaces for roughly twenty-five vehicles and disability parking spaces. On the exterior of the building one begins their journey through the marine environment of North Americas only living barrier reef. Large aluminum replicas of fish, dolphins, rays & corals cascade down and around the center towards benthic critters living on the seafloor, which rests on a flat concreate path >36” wide towards the main entrance doors. These doors are equipped with a silver button and accessibility symbol. Inside, the main foyer contains information in multiple different languages regarding the center and the sounds you hear are that of nature in each habitat. An information desk is positioned just to the left of the main foyer. From the main foyer one can go straight, left, right or to the outdoor patio also located on your right. The interior floor plan would look similar to an S w/right angles. On your immediate right-hand side, there is a gift store that sells books, clothing, gifts. The main exhibit rooms start on your left and feature three interconnected rooms that contain storyboards, interactive displays, replicas, dioramas and videos. The first room is on land, the second begins underwater and the third is a 74-seat theater. These rooms begin at the highest elevation, the hardwood hammocks. A large map of South Florida with buttons illuminates interactive features such as currents, shipwrecks, coral reefs and 42 bridges connecting the Keys to mainland Florida. Also featured is a diorama of the hardwood hammocks, black and red mangroves and the shoreline transition with native species of birds, spiders, and crabs. Directly behind the terrestrial diorama is an exhibit for Dry Tortugas National Park. On the wall a massive image of historic Fort Jefferson is featured, video displays and magnificent frigate birds roosting in their mangrove home on Long Key extend to life. The terrestrial and underwater rooms are connected by a passageway with a 3d film on your left and painting of a shallow seagrass flat on the right. Hold your breath, from here we begin our journey underwater. The second room is circular beginning in the shallow seagrass meadows, ending with the deep shelf and in the middle featuring succession of coral reefs as though one were leaving the shoreline headed towards deep blue water and pelagic species. Overhead life size replicas of Loggerhead Turtles and an Eagle Ray swim above with their large heads or tails longer than some vehicles. A replica of the undersea laboratory Aquarius, found roughly 6 miles off Key Largo, rest in the center of the room. The Aquarius replica has interactive displays and videos of aquanauts conducting saturation diving missions. Prior to entering the third room and movie theater a large coral sample is displayed on the wall. This coral sample provides centuries of history and significant human events outlined in the life span of the core sample. Directly to the left of the coral sample is a sign and the entrance to the Eco-Discovery Theater. The theater features a 20-minute film starting every ½ hour. A digital timer is located above the entrance indicating the next start time. The film, Reflections of Florida Keys is closed captioned. From the main foyer going straight we encounter the living reef exhibit. The living reef exhibit features one 2,500-gallon aquarium and 4 smaller tanks. The larger tank is home to grunts, snappers, spanish hogfish and other iconic keys reef species. The first smaller tank has living stony coral which make up the geology of the keys. The second tank displays soft corals, anemones, sea-snails and other colorful reef fish. The last two smaller tanks have native conchs and exotic, invasive lionfish. An 8-minute closed captioned video is shown in the living reef exhibit overviewing their work to grow corals in labs and replant them on reefs. Images and timelines of our reefs declining and their work to restore them through science and innovation are found throughout the Mote living reef exhibit. Taking a right outside the living reef exhibit brings visitors to our restrooms. Each of these restrooms have accessible stalls and baby changing stations. Water fountains are adjacent to the restrooms and vending machines located on your left. Down the short hallway from vending machines is a conference room. The areas between the main entrance and vending machines are cemented where food and drinks are permissible. The carpeted areas of the Eco-Discovery Center contain interactive displays and electronics, here food and drinks are prohibited.

name: Florissant Fossil Beds Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is where you should start your visit to Florissant Fossil Beds. At the Visitor Center you can show your pass, if you have one, and/or get passes. There is also a museum full of fossil exhibits, a theater to see the park film, and a bookstore. The Visitor Center also bathrooms and a water fountain and bottle filling station.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center at Florissant Fossil Beds is accessed by taking the main entrance road off of Teller County Road 1. After parking, you can access the visitor center by walking down the central sidewalk of the parking lot. To the north, you will have a great view of the Florissant valley which is a grassy flat valley surrounded by low, pine covered hills. The follow the sidewalk and/or parking lot to either the stairs leading to the front entrance. There is also an accessible ramp going up to the front doors. There is a set of double doors when entering. As soon as you enter, the restrooms are to the left down a short hallway. The water fountain is also located here. Through a second doorway you will enter the main lobby. To the left will be the visitor center desk where you can pay your fee and receive orientation information. The Rocky Mountain Conservancy is also located to the left after you enter the main lobby. To your right is the entrance to the exhibit area which has a variety of dioramas, hands on exhibits, and a large display of mostly insect and leaf fossils. The park theater where the film is show is just a little to the right of center in the lobby. By walking through the lobby you will access the back doors of the visitor center which will lead you to the back patio, outdoor exhibits of petrified redwood trees, and the self guided trails.

name: Foothills Visitor Center
description: This visitor center is one mile past the Ash Mountain entrance station along the Generals Highway. Stop here for information, maps, books, gifts, and restrooms. Browse exhibits about the ecology and human history of the foothills, and join a free ranger-led program.
audioDescription: The Foothills Visitor Center building is a Mid-Century Modern design. It is a one story, rectangular building with masonry, glass, and yellow-paneled walls. On one side is an extension in light yellow stucco. The main building has a low pitched gabled roof with wide overhanging eaves that shade the concrete walkway to the entrance doors. A masonry wall across from the main entrance creates a hallway to the restrooms. On front of the building from left to right: The National Park Service Emblem, in the shape of a brown arrowhead, pointed downward. Inside the arrowhead are the words in white lettering, “National Park Service” with a green sequoia tree shape to its left. Near the bottom of the arrowhead is a white buffalo silhouette set against a green meadow, with a white lake and snowcapped mountain behind it. A tall, narrow window with a yellow panel runs from the ground to the roof’s peak. Next to it is the Foothills Visitor Center Sign, with the words, “Foothills Visitor Center” and a colorful illustration of the head and shoulders of a quail, shown in profile. Its head is brown with a small pointed beak. The crown of the quail’s head has a curved black top knot that curls forward. A black and white streak curves behind the eye and along the black neck. The neck has rows of blue and black crescent shaped “feathers”. The shoulders are brown, and the breast is blue and brown. Behind the quail is the faint outline of a light green silhouette of yucca plant, with a spiky ball of leaves at the base, and a single tall spire of flowers, rising like a plume above it.

name: Fordyce Bathhouse Visitor Center and Museum
description: The Fordyce Bathhouse Visitor Center and Museum is open daily. Park rangers are available at the front desk from 9 am - 5 pm to assist with any questions and offer information.
audioDescription: The Fordyce Bathhouse is a three story tan, brick building with a front porch and a green awning held up by chains. The porch features rocking chairs and a table to get passport stamps. There are many windows decorated with carved stone around the perimeter, and the tan bricks are placed to from a pattern of diamonds around the walls.
passportStampLocationDescription: Located on the front porch of the Fordyce Visitor Center and Museum is a table set up with passport stamps.

name: Fort Barrancas Visitor Center
description: The Fort Barrancas Visitor Center tells the long history of European settlers attempts to secure the vital Pensacola Bay beginning in the late 1700s and through its deactivation in the mid-1900s.
audioDescription: Fort Barrancas Visitor Center. The visitor center is a one-story building with a brick and concrete façade with a concrete patio in front. The glass entrance is near the center of the building. To the left of the entrance a breezeway leads to the rear of the building where the walk to the fort is located. On the left side of the breezeway are the restrooms. On the rear of the building on the right is a water fountain and water bottle refill station. Five benches are located around the patio in front. In the middle of the patio is a nine-foot-long cannon resting on concrete mounts. Between the patio and the entrance drive is a grassy area with a flag pole and two more cannon. The parking area lies to the left of the patio. At the right a sidewalk borders the entrance drive. Along the walk is an artillery exhibit with additional cannon and two mortars. There are several graphic panels in this area, mounted on the wall near the entrance, in the breezeway, in a kiosk near the parking area and next to the artillery exhibit.

directionsInfo: The Fort Barrancas Area is on Taylor Road approximately a half mile east from the Museum of Naval Aviation. The area includes the historic Water Battery, Fort Barrancas, trails, visitor center, picnic areas, and the Advanced Redoubt. Visitors may access the Fort Barrancas via the main gate entrance to the Pensacola Naval Air Station.

name: Fort Bowie National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is best accessed via the Fort Bowie Trail. The story of Apache Pass and the events that led to the establishment of Fort Bowie are best understood via a 3-mile roundtrip hike from the trailhead on Apache Pass Road to the visitor center and Second Fort Ruins. For those who cannot hike the trail visit our Directions page for more info: http://www.nps.gov/fobo/planyourvisit/directions.htm
passportStampLocationDescription: The cancelation passport stamp is available on the front porch of the visitor center.

directionsInfo: From Willcox, AZ / points west on I-10: drive 23 miles east of Willcox on Interstate 10 to the the town of Bowie. Exit at the first Bowie exit and drive through the town. Follow the signs for Fort Bowie National Historic Site and turn south on Apache Pass Road. Drive 13 miles to the Fort Bowie Trailhead (the last mile of the road is unpaved). Be prepared to walk the three miles round trip to the ruins and back to your car.

name: Fort Clatsop Visitor Center
description: The Fort Clatsop Visitor Center is the first stopping spot for your visit to Fort Clatsop. The rangers inside are able to provide brochures and hiking trail maps of our site and the local area as well as take entrance fees or park passes. An exhibit hall detailing the Corps of Discoveries journey and the local Indigenous people can be found inside alongside a movie theater. The LCNHPA's Bookstore is found inside, offering a wide selection of historical books and gifts.
audioDescription: Approximately 60 feet from the road of the parking lot you will be walking across a brick pathway to the double doors of the visitor center, a one story rectangular building with large windows and slanted roofs. On the way you will be passing by the american flag flying besides a native plant rain garden filled with shrubs. As you enter into the double doors you enter a large wood entryway. At the end of this entryway to the right is the restrooms and water drinking fountain and bottle filling station. Directly to your left lies the front desk where a park ranger can check and issue a inter agency pass, national park pass, or you can pay the entrance fee to the park. You are also able to acquire maps, brochures in multiple languages, and a park brochure and map in braille. Beyond the front desk is the park bookstore, a small room that you are able to loop around a middle island. A book store associate is available to answer questions or assist you in finding books, gifts, historic reproductions, and more. Turning around from the book store a set of double doors leads to the 100 yard winding trail through a coastal rain forest down to the gates of the second recreation of Fort Clatsop while to the left you can walk another 20 feet to reach an entryway for the the exhibit hall. This exhibit hall features a dimly lit loop with information about the Lewis and Clark expedition and the indigenous people that live in this area. After entering the exhibit hall right and in fifteen feet you will come to an open doorway, entering this brings you into a hallway where twenty feet down a gentle grade ramp brings you to the Netul River Room, a room for meetings and tour groups, while heading right brings you through a wooden double door into the movie theater. Assisted listening devices for either room can be requested at the front desk.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps available not only account for the site here at Fort Clatsop, but also our satellite sites both on the Washington and Oregon coast. A sixth passport cancellation stamp for Fort Columbia, WA is available at this visitor center as well.

name: Fort Donelson Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is located at the main park entrance, just off Highway 79. Museum exhibits, a gift shop, handicapped accessible restroom, and information are available for visitors. The park audiovisual films are available at our website under the link: https://www.nps.gov/fodo/planyourvisit/things2do.htm We encourage you to begin your visit at this location. GPS: 120 Fort Donelson Park Road, Dover, TN 37058
audioDescription: Visitors will exit Hwy. 79 and follow the park road making an immediate right turn into the parking area. This parking area has 30 parking spaces to include two handicap accessible parking spaces. In this immediate area there is a flagpole, cannons, earthworks, mature trees, and trash receptacles. This is also the location of the park visitor center that is currently under renovation. Follow the sidewalk to the visitor orientation area at the park pavilion and park Visitor Center. Be aware this concrete sidewalk is aged and uneven with concrete curbing. This changes to a brick walkway to guide you between two native plants gardens as you walk into the pavilion. When you walk to the visitor center, you will be walking on a gravel path. Be careful with footing as this may be slippery when icy or wet. The open-air pavilion has brochures and information materials as you step inside the west side of building. It is open daily. Contact the Ranger staff by intercom to request to enter the Visitor Center. Exit to the north side of the pavilion. The plastic mat will take you back to the sidewalk or follow this into the Visitor Center. Once you've picked up materials or completed the tour of the Visitor Center, return to your vehicle to begin the self-guided auto tour.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is the classic NPS Passport Cancellation Stamp consisting of a circle, park name and date. GPS: 120 Fort Donelson Park Road, Dover, TN 37058 36° 28' 56.6666" N 87° 51' 45.3260" W

name: Fort Frederica Visitor Center
description: Start your tour of Ft. Frederica National Monument in the visitor center. Pick up orientation information at the desk, get your passport stamped, view the park film in the theater, look at the museum exhibits, try on colonial clothes, play colonial games, inquire about junior ranger programs, and shop in the Fort Frederica Association bookstore. Newly remodeled restrooms are located across the breezeway, and down the hallway, from the entrance to the visitor center
audioDescription: The visitor center is a L shaped brick building with tabby accents. The roof is made from artificial wood shingles. There are several low azalea bushes that line the front of the building. The building itself is nestled under the canopy of several large oak trees. The sidewalk from the parking lot leads to a set of 5 stairs that lead to a breezeway. The breezeway is square, with a tall vaulted ceiling. At the top of the stairs you are entering the breezeway. Directly to the left at the top of the stairs is a cigarette disposal vessel and on the post directly above this is the button for the automatic door leading into the visitor center. The entrance to the visitor center is directly left of the stairs and ahead about 10 feet. Continuing around the breezeway, to the right from the visitor center entrance is a bench followed by a water fountain station. There are two fountains, one tall and one shorter. The taller station has an automatic bottle filling station. To the right of the water fountain is a small dog water station. There is a button on top of the dispenser that fills the bowl for the dogs. The water fountain is followed by another two benches, perpendicular to each other. To the right of the last bench are the stairs that lead to the park grounds. Back at the main entrance to the breezeway, To the right at the top of the stairs is a bench. Perpendicular to the bench along the side wall is a door leading to ranger offices. To the left of the ranger office is another bench. To the left of the bench is a soda machine. To the left of the soda machine is a hallway where the restrooms can be found. The restrooms are described below. To the left of the hallway entrance are several trash and recycling bins. The first is an animal proof trash can. The lid is about 3.5 feet off the ground and pulls forward to provide access to the receptacle. Next is a series of three recycling bins. First is a small circular opening for cans, next a slot for paper and lastly a larger circular hole for plastic. Perpendicular to these bins in another bench. To the left of the bench are the series of 7 stairs with a handrail in the middle that leads to the park grounds. The restrooms are found down a hallway to the left of the soda machine in the breeze way. The doors to the restrooms are on the left. The women’s is first, followed by the men’s 10 feet beyond. The door opens outward and the handle does not turn. When entering the restroom, there are two sinks located to the right. Automatic soap dispensers are located to the back right of each sink and an automatic hand towel dispenser is located on the half wall to the left of the sinks. Beyond the half wall are a bank of toilet stalls. The doors open inward into the stall. The furthest stall is an ADA stall that contains its own sink. The men’s restroom is a mirror image of the women’s. After the sinks, there are a bank of 3 urinals followed by two stalls, with the furthest one being an ADA stall with its own sink. The entrance to the visitor center is through a pair of large double doors. Once inside, you will pass through the Fort Frederica Association Bookstore. On the left, there are various books, colonial toys and souvenirs. To the right upon entering is the visitor information desk. Here you can speak with a park ranger, get a map of the park and check out for the bookstore. Beyond the bookstore and ranger desk the room opens up into an exhibit hall. There are various exhibits about the colonial history of the park. Soon after entering the exhibit hall, there is a hallway on the left that leads a short way to a theater. The floor begins to slope downward as you enter the theater and the seats will be on your right. There are 15 rows of theater seats. The front of the theater contains a small stage area and a lectern. There is a screen mounted to the wall that shows films. The emergency exit is to the right of the stage area. On the other side of the seats, another walkway leads up to the level of the visitor center and back into the exhibit area.

name: Fort Laramie National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: Start your tour at the Visitor Center. Located in the restored 1884 Commissary Storehouse, you can view an 18-minute orientation film, tour our museum, and browse our award-winning bookstore.
audioDescription: The Fort Laramie National Historic Site Visitor Center is located in the 1884 Commissary Building. This lime grout (cement) structure was used as a storehouse by the Commissary Department during the last five years of the fort's operation as a military post. Following the decommissioning of Fort Laramie in 1890, it was used as a stable and store by the Wilde family - local homesteaders - until it was transferred to the state of Wyoming in 1937 and then the National Park Service. It was converted into a temporary visitor center in the 1950s. To reach the visitor center from the parking lot, take the paved path from the obelisk downhill toward the Laramie River.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available at the Visitor Center. In addition to the park stamp, visitors can also get stamps for the Oregon, California, Mormon Pioneer, and Pony Express National Historic Trails. A bonus stamp is also often available.

directionsInfo: The park is located in southeast Wyoming approximately 100 miles north of Cheyenne and 55 miles west of Scottsbluff. From Interstate-25, take exit 92 to US Highway 26, proceed east to the town of Fort Laramie; turn right on State Route 160 and travel 3 miles to the park entrance. From US Highways 26/85, go west from the town of Lingle on US 26 to the town of Fort Laramie; turn left on State Route 160 and travel 3 miles to the entrance gate. The visitor center is downhill from the parking lot.

name: Fort Larned Visitor Center
description: Located in one of the two historic barracks buildings, the park's Visitor Center features a bookstore with a wide variety of books on Army life, the Plains Indians and the Santa Fe Trail. Exhibits in the museum tell the stories of the westward expansion of the United States government, international commerce, and conflicts affecting the American Indians, traders, soldiers, and Indian agents in and around Fort Larned.
audioDescription: Visitor Center 467 words The Visitor Center is in the first of the two barracks buildings on the left as you face the north side of the Parade Ground. It is a one-story sandstone block building facing the Parade Ground. The building is 150 feet long with an 11 foot deep wood porch running the length of the building. The porch roof is an extension of the building roof and is supported by 16 white, square wood columns, nine feet apart. The porch is six inches above the ground. Wheelchairs can access the porch from the west end where an 11 foot wide asphalt path, parallel to the main parade ground path, slopes up to the porch. The path extends out 30 feet from the west end of the porch. The building has a gable roof covered with brown wood shingles. Four brick chimneys are spaced approximately 45 feet apart across the ridge line at the top of the roof with the first and last chimney two feet from their respective ends of the roof. The building has 10 windows and two doors, with both the window frames and the doors painted white. From the left as you face the building are: three windows, a double doorway, four windows, a double doorway, and three windows. The windows are six feet tall by four feet wide and the doorways are eight and a half feet tall by four and a half feet wide. The doors are four feet wide by six and a half feet tall and recessed one foot from the front of the exterior wall. There is a row of five glass panes, one foot high by eight inches wide, above both sets of doors. The glass panes are recessed one foot from the front of the doors. The windows and doors are spaced approximately six feet apart across the front of the building with the first and last window six feet from their respective ends of the building. The building entrance is the left double doorway. The words "Caution Automatic Door" are painted horizontally across the middle of each door, with "Pull to Open" written just above the doorknob located on the right side of the left door. The word "Welcome" is written vertically on the right edge of the left door centered between the doorknob and the top of the door. All the words are painted in black 19th century script. The porch is level with the doorway allowing for wheelchair access into the building. The button to open the doors automatically is located on the porch column opposite the door. The door on the right is not an entryway into the building; it is solid and has no doorknob Inside is a bookstore/giftshop area with some interpretive exhibits, and a museum area with the main interpretive exhibits. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are three passport stamps available at Fort Larned - one for the fort, one for the Santa Fe National Historic Trail, and one for the bicentennial of the Santa Fe Trail. The stamp station is located in the book store near the window on the north wall.

name: Fort McHenry National Monument and Historic Shrine
description: The trail has many points of entry and exploration along its auto route and water route. The visitor center at Fort McHenry serves as the trail's headquarters and visitor center. A short 10-minute orientation film is shown two times per hour. Restrooms, exhibits and a gift shop are also located in the building.
audioDescription: The trail has many points of entry and exploration along its auto route and water route. The visitor center at Fort McHenry serves as the trail's premier visitor and orientation center. A short 10-minute orientation film is shown two times per hour: on the hour and half-past the hour throughout the day. Restrooms, exhibits and a gift shop are also located in the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport Stamp for the Star-Spangled Banner Trail is located in the lobby of the Fort's Visitor Center. To see other locations of Trail passport stamps, visit: https://www.nps.gov/thingstodo/stsp-passport-stamps.htm

name: Fort McHenry National Monument and Historic Shrine Visitor Center
description: The Fort McHenry Visitor Center is open daily from 9:00 am - 4:45 pm. Inside the visitor center is an introductory museum, a movie (plays every 30 minutes), the park bookstore, restrooms, and water bottle filling station. The visitor center and museum are free to visit. Visitors interested in purchasing entrance passes to the Star Fort Historic Zone or an America the Beautiful pass can do so here.
audioDescription: The Fort McHenry Visitor Center is open daily from 9:00 am - 4:45 pm. Inside the visitor center is an introductory museum, a movie (plays every 30 minutes), the park bookstore, restrooms, and water bottle filling station. The visitor center and museum are free to visit. Visitors interested in purchasing entrance passes to the Star Fort Historic Zone or an America the Beautiful pass can do so here.
passportStampLocationDescription: Fort McHenry's visitor center features five stamps for your NPS passport. They include the Fort McHenry stamp, Star-Spangled Banner NHT stamp, Chesapeake Bay Gateway Network Stamp, Baltimore National Heritage Area Stamp, and the Junior Ranger stamp. If the visitor center is closed during your visit, you can contact the park to have a stamp mailed to you.

name: Fort Monroe Visitor and Education Center
description: Great start to any Fort Monroe visit. Accessible visitor center provides orientation, exhibits, park store, brochures, passport stamps, junior ranger and B.A.R.K. ranger programs, restrooms, water filling station, schedule a Casemate Museum timed reservation. Admission is free. Parking in the rear. For information or schedule guided tours email visit https://fortmonroe.org or call 757-690-8181. All children (under the age of 18) must be accompanied by an adult. Address: 30 Ingalls Rd Fort Monroe, VA 23651
audioDescription: Great start to any Fort Monroe visit. Accessible visitor center provides orientation, exhibits, park store, brochures, passport stamps, junior ranger and B.A.R.K. ranger programs, restrooms, water filling station, schedule a Casemate Museum timed reservation. All children (under the age of 18) must be accompanied by an adult. Address: 30 Ingalls Rd Fort Monroe, VA 23651

name: Fort Moultrie Visitor Center
description: The Fort Moultrie Visitor Center is located at 1214 Middle Street, Sullivan's Island, SC. Inside are museum exhibits, a 22-minute orientation film and a museum store. The visitor center and fort are open daily from 9:00 am-4:30 pm. The park is closed Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day and New Year's Day. There is a park entrance fee.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is located at the entrance to the parking lot. You will park and then walk back on a cement sidewalk to the building. While the Visitor Center is as tall as a two-story building, the interior is only one-story with a very high ceiling. The shape of the building is a rectangle with different angles along the sides and corners. There is landscaping surrounding it on three sides consisting of oak trees, palmetto trees, small trees shrubs and ornamental grasses including sweet grass. The sidewalk will curve and start ramping up towards the Visitor Center. The walkway/ramp turns to brick at the corner of the Visitor Center which is on your right. At that junction, if you move to the right staying on the cement sidewalk, you will come to an opening on your left which leads to a staircase which goes up to the roof for a view of the surrounding area. Continuing up the brick ramp, there is a metal handrail running along the building on the right side and a low brick wall on your left. Where the handrail ends, you are now at the top of the ramp, and there is another opening to the right in the Visitor Center wall which is a small rectangular alcove with entrances to the women’s restroom on the right and the men’s to the left. While standing at the top of the ramp, you are at a corner of a rectangular brick patio area to your right is the Visitor Center wall. and to you left is a short brick area topped with grey recycled lumber which serves as long bench with no arm or back rests. Halfway down the bench is a small, brown metal sign about Major General Moultrie. The picture of Moultrie and writing is etched in gold and reads “Down the walk on your left is the grave of General William Moultrie. A citizen of Charleston, who on June 28, 1776 led American troops in the defense of the city. From the walls of the unfinished palmetto log fort on Sullivan’s Island he won a remarkable victory over a great British invasion fleet. His achievement gave meaning to the words of the Declaration of Independence, which was adopted within days after the battle, and a grateful people of South Carolina paid him a singular honor in forever linking his name with the fort.” Near the upper left corner of the brick patio is a brown metal flagpole with a US flag. Continuing from the restroom alcove down the right wall is a bottle fill and water fountain station on the right. Continuing beyond this is a locked wooden door which serves as the staff entrance only. The wall turns to the left. Along this wall a set of double doors provide access to the Visitor Center which is surrounded on each side and above by large tinted windows. There is a 3 ½-feet high square pole centered in front of the doors with a button to press to activate the automatic door opener. The doors swing out towards you. Above the glass doors and windows, is a large cement, cream colored, rectangular space with the words “Fort Moultrie Visitor Center” done in black metal lettering. To the left of the words is a large NPS arrowhead. Continuing to the left of the Visitor Center entrance, the wall angles left. There is trashcan with recycling on the right and trash on the left. There is a set of stairs to the left of this taking you down to a cement sidewalk. For the stairs, there are four steps and a landing and then five more steps down. There are metal handrails on either side and two more in the center which divide the stairs into three sections. If you follow the sidewalk to the left, you will return to the parking area; taking it to the right will take you around the Visitor Center to the main road. Crossing the street will take you to the fort itself. On the road side of the Visitor Center, there is a wide, brick ramp going extending from the cement sidewalk to the Visitor Center. To the right of you will be the Visitor Center wall which slopes upwards towards the roof the Visitor Center. On your left is a short brick wall. Where the ramp flattens out, this short, brick wall will become a long bench which is topped with grey recycled planks with no arm or back rests. Beyond the bench area is a landscaped grass lawn with the Fort Moultrie sign angled toward the road. The sign itself rectangular with the long side paralleling the ground. The top of the sign has a dark brown band at the top with “National Park Service. U.S. Department of the Interior” Below this the remainder of the sign is light brown with “Fort Moultrie Visitor Center. Fort Sumter National Monument.”. All writing is in white. The sign itself is flanked on each side by a brick column. A National Park Service arrowhead is on the left side column. The tall brick wall of the Visitor Center on the right side of the ramp angles across with tinted glass windows and another set of double doors with access into the Visitor Center. There is a 3 ½-feet high square pole centered in front of the doors with a button to press to activate the automatic door opener. The doors swing out towards you.

name: Fort Necessity/National Road Interpretive and Education Center
description: The exhibits an programs at The Fort Necessity/National Road Interpretive and Education Center immerse visitors and students in the diverse cultures and customs of mid-eighteenth century Pennsylvania. The bookstore gift-shop provides a selection of theme related souvenirs and in-depth material for those who want to learn more after visiting the park. Exhibits also cover the National Road, the first federally funded highway, that linked the east and west of the young United States.

name: Fort Pulaski Visitor Center
description: The Fort Pulaski Visitor Center is located next to the main visitor parking area and historic Fort Pulaski. Here you can watch the park film, check out a variety of exhibits about Fort Pulaski, and get park and program information for a wonderful visit to the national monument.
audioDescription: Standing in the Fort Pulaski National Monument main parking area and looking south, you can see the rebricked masonry walls of Fort Pulaski toward the left of the scene and the masonry walls of the park visitor center toward the right. To the left of the visitor center, the park restrooms are located in a separate comfort station. When Fort Pulaski National Monument was opened for visitors in the late 1930s it did not have a place to greet visitors outside of the fort. Construction of the visitor center began in late 1962, and the building was completed and opened to the public in October of 1964. The one-story brick structure was designed by the National Park Service Eastern Office of Design and Construction and takes much inspiration from Eero Saarinen’s Kresge Chapel at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in Boston. Both buildings have a similar circular plan, base arches, rusticated brick, and surrounding gravel moats. One main difference, however, is the height of the new building. It was kept low to prevent it from intruding on the historic fort. There are accessible ramps on the east and west sides of the visitor center. Once you enter the building your are confined by the round structure. There is a large area in the center of the building surrounded by exhibits, a small theatre, and the visitor contact desk. The north side of the visitor center has the long visitor contact desk. You'll find park staff willing and able to answer questions and orient your park visit. The desk also has a number of printer materials to take. The north side of the visitor center has the theatre and exhibits. Behind the desk there are doors that lead to office space in the building. The theatre holds approximately 30 people and shows the park film at the top and bottom of the hour. The film is around 20 minutes. There are a number of exhibits that highlight the cultural history of Fort Pulaski. There are cases with a number of artifacts to view. In the center of the space there is an historic 3D cutaway model of the fort made in the 1930's. There is also a large black mortar tube that acts as a donation box for the park. At the east landing exit, there is a water fountain and water bottle refilling station.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are several cancellation stamps at this location including Fort Pulaski National Monument, Underground Railroad Freedom Network, and Gullah-Geechee National Heritage Corridor. The park also features the United States Lighthouse Society Passport Stamp for the Cockspur island Lighthouse.

name: Fort Spokane Visitor Center and Museum
description: Located in the former guardhouse, located in the middle of historic Fort Spokane, the visitor center and museum are open seasonally, from Memorial Day to Labor Day of each year. During the summer of 2023, the Fort Spokane Visitor Center and Museum will be open Friday through Sunday, 11am to 3pm. These hours begin May 26 and end September 3. For an audio description of the park brochure, visit the Publications or Accessibility page of our website: nps.gov/laro
audioDescription: The Fort Spokane Visitor Center and museum is house in the 1892 brick guardhouse near the parade grounds. A crushed gravel walkway leads to the visitor center covered porch and continues around the parade grounds. Interpretive signs are found along the parade grounds walkway sharing information about the various buildings that once stood on the site. Inside the visitor centers, you can learn about the three eras of Fort Spokane: military fort, American Indian boarding school, and tuberculosis sanitarium.
passportStampLocationDescription: Located inside the Visitor Center; only available when the visitor center is open. Next closest location for Lake Roosevelt NRA Cancellation Stamp and Ice Age Floods National Geologic Trail Cancellation Stamp is Grand Coulee Dam Visitor Center, operated by the Bureau of Reclamation, in Coulee Dam, WA.

name: Fort Sumter Visitor Center
description: The primary departure point for Fort Sumter is the Fort Sumter Visitor Center at Liberty Square, located at 340 Concord Street, in downtown Charleston. Visitors can find parking in a City of Charleston parking garage (fees apply) at 24 Calhoun Street, just steps away from the entrance to Liberty Square. There is no fee for entrance into the visitor center. Boats also depart from Patriots Point, 40 Patriots Point Boulevard, Mount Pleasant. There is a fee for riding the concession-operated ferry.
audioDescription: The Fort Sumter Visitor Center is located on the waterfront of the Liberty Square Park. When entering the park, there are two walkways made of bluestone. To the right of the park entrance is the cement sign with metallic lettering. In the middle is black, metal gate. Centered on the gate are the words Liberty Square with a National Park Service arrowhead. On the left, is an entrance sign for the South Carolina Aquarium. Follow either bluestone walkway down to the Septima Clark water fountain. Along the way is a large open green space to your left and two shade shelters made of brick on the right. There are banners featuring iconic scenes and people associated with Fort Sumter hanging on the brick pillars of the shade shelters. The park is landscaped near the shade shelters and buildings with a variety of trees like magnolias and live oaks, as well as ornamental bushes and grasses. There are numerous metal trashcans and benches scattered throughout the park. At the end of the bluestone walkway there is a tall metal flagpole. The base of the flagpole is surrounded by a half-circle fountain with water which cascaded down from the top of the fountain into the pool of water below. No one is allowed to go into the fountain. On the opposite side of the fountain are three bronze signs on Septima Poinsette Clark, a Civil Rights leader, to whom the water fountain is dedicated. Beyond the fountain, the South Carolina Aquarium, a four-story, building with lots of windows is to your left. On the right is the Liberty Square Visitor Center. The building is constructed with red brick, approximately 50-feet high at its tallest, and in the shape of a long rectangle with the short sides facing the park and the water of Charleston Harbor. A long, cement staircase with metal handrails on each side and one in the middle lead up to the landing and entrance to the Visitor Center. On the wall above the stairs and landing is a National Park Service arrowhead with the words “Fort Sumter Visitor Center” to the right in gold metallic lettering. On the landing, there is an elevator to your right. In the center is a glass turnstile door to the left and a single glass door to the right. A button to the right of the single door activates the automatic door opener. On left side beyond the turnstile door, is a glass window which opens for purchasing tickets for the concession-ferry to Fort Sumter. A large video screen to the left of the ticket window displays information about the ferry boats. Back on the ground level, the building is open underneath with brick columns and archways to mimic the cannon casemates at Fort Sumter. On the end closest to the park and under the stairs is an entry point for the elevator. In the center space under the building on the left side are wooden benches with no arm or back rests and cement legs. The benches are positioned to face a brick wall with a video monitor mounted to run a variety of short videos about the park. To the right of this and still under the building are black stations connected with nylon ropes to create queuing lines for the ferry boat. There is another entry way from the right side of the building to this area nearby. Outside of the left wall is a long ramp which zigzags up to the Visitor Center level of the building. A staircase at the end of the building on the Charleston Harbor side merges into the ramps. A large rectangular square area is available outside of the backdoors into to the building for waiting for the ferry or looking at the sites around Charleston Harbor. The backdoors have a turnstile door on the right and a single glass door on the left. The single door is activated by a button on the left of the door. To the right of the doors, is a bottle fill and water fountain station. There are several interpretive signs about the nearby attractions as well as several benches.

name: Fort Union National Monument Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is currently open 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. Handicapped parking spaces for standard sized vehicles are available in the Visitor Center parking area. Several "oversized" parking spaces in the parking lot can accommodate campers, buses, and large RV's. Brochures are available outside the visitor center doors from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.
audioDescription: The Monument visitor center is situated close to the parking lot, which is a cul-de-sac. Most parking spaces are 50-75 yards from the visitor center. The parking lot and visitor center sit on the short-grass prairie. There is a reproduction Civil War-era cannon in front of the visitor center. There are several picnic tables outside the front of the visitor center. Three of the picnic tables are under a shelter. The other tables are partially shaded. Restrooms are accessible from the outside of the visitor center on the parking lot side of the building. The visitor center is a small, one-story building. The historic fort is behind the visitor center. A walk of about 75 yards is required to reach the fort buildings from the visitor center. The inside of the visitor center includes an information desk, park store, a theatre and museum exhibits. The theatre has seating for 20 people. The store encompasses about 500 square feet, and the museum exhibits occupy about 750 square feet.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are three passport stamps: 1) an undated line drawing of one of the fort buildings; 2) a dated stamp for the Monument; and 3) a dated stamp for the Santa Fe National Historic Trail at Fort Union.

New Mexico: From Albuquerque (156 miles), Santa Fe (94 miles) or Las Vegas, NM (28 miles) take I-25 north, exit 366 at Watrous, 8 miles on NM 161. Colorado: From Denver (313 miles), Colorado Springs (243 miles) or Raton (95 miles) take I-25 south, exit 366 at Watrous, 8 miles on NM 161.

name: Fort Vancouver Visitor Center
description: Begin your visit by learning about all the park's venues through new exhibits and activities. Watch a short film about the site's history, peruse the park's bookstore, and enjoy a display of artwork by American Indian artists.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is a light green building with a large overhang covering a plaza in front of it. It is adjacent to a parking lot; in front of the building is a loading and unloading area. There are steps leading down to the front of the building. From the parking area to the east of the building, there is a ramp leading to the front of the building. An American flag flies on a flagpole in front of the building. There are two doors at the main entrance. Inside the building, the orientation desk is to the right. Also to the right is the entrance to the Visitor Center theater. To the left is the bookstore. Straight ahead of the entrance is a large art installation called Spirit Pole.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available for Fort Vancouver National Historic Site, Lewis & Clark National Historic Trail and the Oregon National Historic Trail. Additional stamps for junior rangers, the Northwest Explorer Program, and a stamp with an image of Fort Vancouver's bastion are available.

name: Fort Washington Park Visitor Center
description: Built in the 1820s, this bright yellow building was once the home of Fort Washington's commander. Today, it serves as the Visitor Center for Fort Washington Park. Inside you will find the park bookstore, a small museum, and two restrooms. The Visitor Center is staffed with Rangers ready to answer your questions.
audioDescription: A two story brick building painted bright yellow with dark green trim. A small porch on the front leads to the main door. The interior is laid out with a wide hallway in the center, two rooms on the left, one room and two restrooms on the right. The front left room is the bookstore. The back left room contains benches and an audiovisual system. To the immediate right of the door is a staircase going up. The upstairs is not open to the public. Just past the staircase is a small hallway containing a water refill station and two restrooms. There is also a staircase leading down with a swinging door. This area is not open to visitors. The back right room contains a small museum exhibit. Opposite the front door is a door which leads to a balcony on the rear of the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: A Passport Stamp station is set up just inside the Visitor Center. It contains the cancellation stamps for Fort Washington Park, as well as for the nearby Piscataway Park, Fort Foote Park, and Harmony Hall. The station also offers stamps for the Star-Spangled Banner National Historic Trail, the Potomac Heritage Trail, the Civil War Defenses of Washington and the Captain John Smith National Historic Trail.

name: Fossil Butte Visitor Center
description: Over 2000 fossils are on exhibit. Video programs feature what scientists have learned from the fossils and the rocks they're found in, and how fossils are excavated and prepared. Visitor Center hours vary by the season.
audioDescription: From the visitor center parking lot, a cement walkway slopes down to the visitor center on the left. On the left, by the parking lot, is a diorama showing what fossil quarrying looks like. On the right railing, curving around the visitor center, is a geologic timeline from the creation of the Earth to current time. Behind the visitor center is Fossil Butte. As you enter the visitor center, an exhibit case is directly in front of you. Around the case to the right is the front desk. The restrooms are to the left as you enter, down a 5 to 10-foot hallway between a rock wall and an exhibit of a virtual aquarium. As you enter the visitor center, you enter the main room, there is another room if you walk straight from the front door and around an exhibit case. To the right of the front door is the bookstore, to the left of which is the front desk. If you continue down the hallway between the front desk and the bookstore, there is the movie room on your left through a curtain. If you instead continue straight, you will exit two sets of double doors to the back porch where there is a view of Fossil Butte. There are thousands of fossils on display in the visitor center, including an exhibit in the restrooms. An audio description phone app of some of the specimens is available. There is an audio-described film available. Please ask at the front desk for more information.

name: Frederick Douglass NHS Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center of the Frederick Douglass NHS is located at the bottom of the hill near the parking lot. Inside of the Visitor Center you will find staff who can facilitate your visit, a bookstore run by America's National Parks, handicap accessible restrooms, a water fountain, exhibits and historic objects, as well as a theater with seating, where a 20 minute closed-captioned film on the life of Frederick Douglass is played.

name: Fredericksburg Battlefield Visitor Center
description: Inside the Fredericksburg Battlefield Visitor Center are three rooms with exhibits about the Battle of Fredericksburg and its impact on the nation, a 22-minute park film, and an information desk where our staff can provide guidance on getting around as well as insight into the history of the battle.
audioDescription: A two-story brick building with a wrap-around driveway leading to a parking lot in the rear. There is an entry way on the road-facing side of the building, with an accessible ramp, and an entry way on the parking lot side of the building, with a stairway. Upon entering the building from the parking lot side there are additional stairs that go up, to a lobby, or down, to the lower level. The entryway from the road side leads directly to the lobby. In the lobby there is an information desk, flanked by rooms with exhibits on either side. In the lower level there is a room with exhibits, a restroom, and an auditorium.

name: French Quarter Visitor Center
description: Visitor center exhibits and a film share the history and traditions of the lower Mississippi River delta and of New Orleans, home to one of America's most distinctive cultural mixes and rich in food, music, architecture, and more. Free admission.
audioDescription: Welcome to the French Quarter Visitor Center. In this building we also house our museum that tells of the cultural histories you'll find at all six of our sites. A large tan sign hanging from the balcony above, marks our Visitor Center. With your back turned to the street, you're facing our visitor center's two entrances. On the left, a set of green doors are propped open leading up a slight ramp to our visitor center and museum. As you make your way in through this entrance, follow the wall on your right to reach the Information Desk and talk with a Park Ranger. To find the bathrooms, continue past the Information Desk and out the doors on the next wall. Immediately to your left is the women's bathroom. For the men's bathroom walk about 10 feet and it will be on your left. At the entrance on the right, a large cast iron gate is swung open to reveal a long, enclosed carriageway. This passage has a brick flooring and is lined with decorative gas lamps that hang from the ceiling. At the end of the carriageway you'll find our courtyard, filled with trees and native plants. A fountains sits on the right, a couple yards away from the edge of the carriageway. If you follow the left wall along the carriageway and around a turn, you'll come across a set of doors along that same wall that lead into the visitor center and museum. As soon as you enter, the Information desk will be on your right. To find the bathroom, follow the left side of the carriageway and around the turn. On the wall directly in front of you, will be the women's bathroom on the left, and the men's bathroom on the right. Along the right wall of the carriageway you will find two benches you can sit and relax on. Continuing up the right wall you will reach the fountain which is surrounded by benches you can rest on.
passportStampLocationDescription: Mark your NPS passport with our official passport cancellation stamp, and take us with you wherever you go! Our French Quarter Visitor Center stamp is done in the classic NPS style.

name: Furnace Creek Visitor Center
description: Furnace Creek Visitor Center is the central hub for all things Death Valley. Here you can pay the park entrance fee, speak with a ranger about trip plans or questions, participate in the Junior Ranger program, watch the 20-minute park film, explore museum displays, and browse the park bookstore.
audioDescription: Large single-story building with covered walkway leading to entrance. Entrance is through two sets of double swinging glass doors. Directly ahead is a recessed wooden information desk, staffed by rangers, where visitors can pay fees and receive information. To the right is a museum with display topics including wildlife, human history, dark skies, climate/weather, and geology. To the left is a large table topographic map of the Death Valley area. Beyond the map are shelves and tables with merchandise (clothing, books, and educational souvenirs), sold by the non-profit park bookstore, Death Valley Natural History Association. Large double doors lead from the bookstore to an auditorium with seating, a stage, and a projector screen.

name: Gallatin House
description: The Gallatin House was the home of Albert Gallatin. The house contains contains exhibits on Gallatin's family life and public career.
passportStampLocationDescription: The standard Passport Cancellation date stamp for Friendship Hill National Historic Site - New Geneva, PA is available at the visitor center desk from 9:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. daily. This is the only cancellation stamp for Friendship Hill. On weekdays from October through April, the stamp is available at the Fort Necessity visitor center for people who have visited Friendship Hill.

name: Garden Key Visitor Center
description: Garden Key Visitor Center is located inside Fort Jefferson. At the visitor center you will find artifacts, an informational movie, the bookstore, and souvenirs.
audioDescription: The Garden Key Visitor center is located inside of the huge red brick Fort Jefferson. Enter the fort through the stony sally port walkway into the large grassy interior of the fort. You will notice several large sea grade trees with their wide, light green leaves. Turning to the right after entering the fort, a Small brown/orange National Park Service Arrowhead sign indicates the Visitor Center Entrance. Stepping up into the visitor center, visitors enter a small museum room and will notice several artifacts encased in glass museum displays. Ceramic pots, plates, irons and other household items are displayed and catalogued. The museum room also features 2 small restored cannons resting against the front entry walls. They are black and shiny, sitting in reconstructed wooden carriages. Opposite the cannons is another glass display case, which show older unrestored cannon, shot and shot materials as well as a large cement barrel. All of these artifacts look old, rusted and weathered after decades of being submerged underwater. In the corner of the white bricked room, there is a short doorway leading to the bookstore. A sign indicating ‘low height’ warns visitors against hitting their head as they enter the bookstore. Inside the bookstore is a large light brown desk which is topped with colorful souvenirs, magnets and keychains. Brightly colored clothing hands on the wall along with several posters, maps and books available for purchase. Leaving the bookstore and heading back into the museum room, several interpretive displays about fort construction and bird migration cover the white painted brick walls. Immediately to the right, pass through the arched brick doorway into a small theater room which has several book cases and a small seating area. The light blue walls of this room feature a clear bulletin board display case with park information, as well as a large screen for showing the park film. In the far left corner of the theater room, two large brown bookcases contain dozens of animal skulls, bones and numerous large seashells. Sea turtle skulls and shells are featured prominently, and their beaks are propped open to greet the visitor. Numerous white and pale pink conch and whelk shells are available for closer examination. The far walls of the theater room are covered with brightly colored interpretive boards, with information about seagrasses and island formation. A small wooden door through an arched doorway leads to a ramp descending onto the first tier of the fort for more exploration

name: Gateway Arch Visitor Center
description: The Gateway Arch Visitor Center, located directly under the Gateway Arch, is the central location for the journey to the top, the Arch Museum, the film Monument to the Dream, the Arch Store and the Arch cafe. Enter the Visitor Center from Smith Square to the west of the Arch directly across from the Old Courthouse. The North and South legs of the Gateway Arch are exit only from the visitor center and museum.
audioDescription: The Gateway Arch Visitor Center is a semicircular wall of glass and steel built into the berm directly below the soaring Gateway Arch. The glass catches the light and gleams. The entrance curves around a round pool that shows the reflection of the entrance and the Arch. Passing through the glass door to either side of the curve, the bright, white entrance area has the ticket center on the left, an information desk in the middle and the security area on the right. Once you pass through security, you descend an escalator into a large area with a soaring white ceiling passing by a mezzanine that has a terrazzo floor with an embedded map showing the path of many trails to the west from St. Louis. Descending further on the escalator you see large screens with movies of natural scenes and reenactments of explorers and pioneers. Passing through the middle of these large screens you enter the museum which features many touchable exhibits for guests with low vision.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport stamp is a circle with the name Gateway Arch National Park along the top, the date in the middle and St. Louis, MO along the bottom.

directionsInfo: Gateway Arch National Park is located in the heart of downtown St. Louis on the Mississippi River. Interstate Routes 44, 55, 64 and 70 converge near the park. The Gateway Arch is easily accessible from St. Louis' MetroLink Lightrail. Board at any station and exit at 8th and Pine or Lacledes Landing and follow the signs to the Memorial (a 10 min. walk) Please note: Visitors now enter the Arch through the west entrance, which faces Fourth Street and the Old Courthouse. The Gateway Arch legs are now exit only.

name: General Grant National Memorial Visitor Center and Overlook Pavilion
description: Located west from the main mausoleum, across the southbound lanes of Riverside Drive, the Visitor Center provides a bookstore, gift shop, information desk, public restrooms, exhibits and a park film, and a viewing pavilion of the surrounding Riverside Park and Hudson River. The structure was originally a comfort station built in 1901 and was renovated to become the Visitor Center in 2011.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Visitor Center Information Desk have a self-service stamp and ink pad. Contact us via email or phone with a preferred date if you would like a stamp mailed to you.

directionsInfo: From the front of the Mausoleum, walk west toward the Hudson River, and use the crosswalk on Riverside Drive. Make a right turn on the opposite side of the street until you see the columns of the Pavilion. Take the stairs down to the level below the overlook to find the main entrance to the visitor center. (An ADA accessible ramp is available to the north of the stairs). The MEN and WOMEN signs above the visitor center doors are relics of the original purpose of the building. Everyone is welcome.

name: General Grant's Headquarters at City Point
description: Station is located in the former plantation home of the Eppes Family. When open, visitors can view a 15 minute video and tour the first floor of the home including a room with interpretive exhibits and two rooms with original 18th and 19th century furniture that belonged to the Eppes Family. Exhibits focus on the Union Army's occupation of City Point, as well as the lives of the free and enslaved people who lived on the plantation before the war. See closures listed.
passportStampLocationDescription: Rubber date stamp with the text "City Point" and "Petersburg National Battlefield". When the visitor contact station is closed the passport stamp for Grant's Headquarters can be found in the Eastern Front Visitor Center.

directionsInfo: From I-95 & 295: Take Rt. 10 east towards Hopewell. Cross over the Appomattox River and at the second traffic light past the bridge take a left onto Main Street/Appomattox Street. Follow until it meets Cedar Lane and take a left. As you come up to the plantation house the parking lot is on the left. From Williamsburg: Take Rt. 5 north and turn left to cross the Benjamin Harrison Bridge (Rt. 156). After crossing over the James River turn right onto Rt. 10 and follow into Hopewell. Turn right onto Main Street

name: George Rogers Clark National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The George Rogers Clark National Historical Park Visitor Center is a great place to start your visit. The visitor center contains a small exhibit area. There is a 30-minute introductory movie called "Long Knives" which shares the back story of George Rogers Clark and his military campaign. Before going to the Clark Memorial, check with the ranger at the visitor center.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a red and white brick building down a short path approximately 250 feet from the parking lot. It has a ramp which starts on the right hand side of the accessible on the path from the parking lot. There are two steps next to the ramp for visitors to use. Inside the Visitor Center there is a small exhibit space, bookstore, restrooms, and auditorium where the park movie is shown.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are three stamps available at the visitor center.

directionsInfo: The George Rogers Clark National Historical Park is located within the city of Vincennes, Indiana. Evansville is approximately 50 miles to the south and Terre Haute is approximately 50 miles to the north. Highway 41 provides good roads from the north or south. Highway 50 provides access from the east and west. From Hwy 50 east and west or from Hwy 41 from the north use the 6th Street exit. On Hwy 41 from the South use the Willow Street exit. From there follow the blue directional signs for the park.

name: George Washington Carver National Monument
description: 1/6/23 When COVID Community Level is "high" according to the CDC, masks are required inside buildings at George Washington Carver NM. The visitor center is a multilevel facility that houses a museum, theater, park store, interactive exhibits areas, classrooms, additional restrooms, library, museum collection facility, offices space, and a large multipurpose area that also serves as a tornado shelter. It is open daily, 9am to 5pm, except Thanksgiving Day, December 25, and January 1.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 435 words. The visitor center, which is approximately 95 feet from the sidewalk, is a two-story multi-colored brick and dark brown siding building with landscaped grass below 4 paned windows that are 3 across with checkered paneling between the windows. To the left of the windows there is a covered walkway that leads to some seating for a shady place to sit and is used by school groups when we have a scheduled education program as another entrance. To the right of the main entrance there is text, which reads George Washington Carver National Monument, and a National Park arrowhead with two black benches with slots in them below the text and arrowhead. From the sidewalk directly in front of the visitor center walk approximately 82 feet to reach an automatic door button that is located about waste high on the right wooden post walk an additional 12 feet to get to the double glass entrance doors the automatic doors remain open for about 10 minutes. Through the glass doors walk about 8 feet turn right toward the north entrance there is a ramp that leads to our restrooms. As you walk down the ramp on the right is a wall with a bulletin board about 4 feet high walk about 30 feet turn left walk about 5 feet end up on a tile floor to the right is the men’s bathroom to the left women’s bathroom straight ahead about 5 feet there is a locked door to the left of the locked door there is a water fountain which is close to the women’s restroom door at the back of the water fountain there is a sensor that enables you to refill a water bottle. Turn around about 270 degrees facing east then turn right and walk 30 feet to return to the main lobby. To the right is a curved Information Desk about 15 feet ahead leads to a gift shop. Turn right walk about 30 feet to the left there is an opening to the museum straight through the museum is the entrance to our theater. From the entrance about 80 feet straight ahead there is a staircase 7 stairs up leads to our discovery area 16 stairs down leads to our lower level. The elevator is located to the left of the staircase that heads to the lower level. On the lower level turn left walk about 22 feet through a doorway first door on the left men’s restroom continue about 50 feet 2nd doorway on left women’s restroom. End of description.

name: Georges Island Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center on Georges Island occupies a 1906 historic brick building that originally stored and serviced mines for the minefield located in Boston Harbor. The Visitor Center has a ranger-staffed desk, island and harbor information, a short informative movie about Fort Warren, an exhibit on the island's history, and restrooms. All are available during operating hours.
audioDescription: Long, rectangular two story brick building. Visitors face the main entrance after they disembark the ferry and walk off the pier. The main entrance is one of the shorter sides of the rectangular building. While all brick, the brick on the ground floor of the facade is arranged in defined horizontal rows. Two sets of dark green double-doors are separated by two sets of paned windows outlined in white trim. The doors are paneled on the bottom half, with paned windows on the top half. Above the doors and windows on the first level are vertically arched rows of bricks in an art deco style. A white ledge separates the first and second floors. Above the ledge is are the words "Visitor Center" in black. A series of two larger glass-paned windows flank both the left and right sides, with two smaller paned windows in the middle. All windows have white trim and art deco empire-style molding on top of them in concrete. There is a pediment on top of the second story outlined by a cornice. At the center is a small glass circular window.

name: Giant Forest Museum
description: The museum is housed in a historic market in the Giant Forest sequoia grove at 6,500 feet (1,980 m) elevation. Explore exhibits about sequoias and learn why this landscape grows the biggest of big trees. Stop here before you explore the grove. During wilderness permit non-quota season, permits can be picked up at a self-issue station outside the museum.
audioDescription: You are on a plaza just outside of The Giant Forest Museum building. It is a long single story wooden building with a peaked roof. The structure is built with tongue and groove wooden posts and beams visible on the exterior of the building. Each end has a forward facing peaked roof and over the center of the building facing the plaza is a gabled roof with six windows. An engraved wooden sign hangs from the gabled roof. It reads, “Giant Forest Museum”. The building has brown planked wood siding. There are six wooden double doors spread along the length of the building. Above them are a row of small paned transom windows. Between each set of doors are larger multi-paned windows, with mullions and frames painted light green. On the ground outside, below each large window, is a crescent shaped stone ledge at curb height. The entrance is through the first set of double doors as you cross the road from the parking area and enter the plaza. There is a post with a handicap press pad on the stone ledge to the right of the entrance doors. The doors open outward. Above the door frame, the hours are posted.

NM Hwy 15 from Silver City is only for passenger vehicles and motorcycles. Typical driving time is 1.5-2 hours. For RVs and trucks with trailers: take NM Hwy 152 from Santa Clara to NM Hwy 35. NM Hwy 35 connects with Hwy 15 to the park. Typical driving time is 2-2.5 hours.

name: Gilbert Grosvenor Visitor Center
description: Begin your exploration of the park in the visitor center. Pick up a park brochure for more information about the cave shelter and hiking trails. Watch a 7 minute film about the early inhabitants of Russell Cave and view the artifacts that were excavated from the cave shelter. Check out the Eastern National bookstore that has an assortment of books and souvenirs for adults and children.
audioDescription: Upon arriving at the parking lot at Russell Cave exit your car and follow the sidewalk in front of the parking lot to the visitor center. Across the road from the parking area is a picnic space with several tables. There is a sign before getting to the visitor center labeled Gilbert Grosvenor Visitor Center. Check out some of the flowers as you pass our native flower garden. Past a small rock wall that encloses the garden you will find the front door to the visitor center. Inside you can pick up park brochures, shop the park store, and learn more about the park. The bookstore has books about the prehistoric people, Indian tribes, all things nature, and several souvenirs such as magnets, hiking stick medallions, and lapel pins for purchase. By walking around the museum, you will discover a small sampling of artifacts that were excavated from the cave shelter in the 1950s and 1960s. When walking around the exhibits you will find reproductions of the different weapons the prehistoric people used to hunt, some animal bones from the different animals they hunted and ate, different types of containers they used to gather items in, several spearpoints and arrowheads, gaming pieces, pottery sherds, bone needles, knives, and a pump drill. Throughout the exhibits you will find several Prehistoric Puzzles and History’s Mysteries. In the middle of the room is an exhibit labeled How Long is a Long Time Ago? Below this is a diorama from the back of the cave looking out of the shelter with small prehistoric figures representing the daily lives thousands of years ago. Walking on around this exhibit is a timeline of events happening around the world as people inhabited Russell Cave. After looking at the artifacts there is a theatre around the corner where the 7-minute film about the people who lived at Russell Cave is shown. When exiting the theatre there are restrooms on the right and straight forward is the back door that leads you to Russell Cave.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Russell Cave stamp, the Trail of Tears of Alabama stamp, and the Russell Cave Junior Ranger stamp are all available upon request at the front desk.

name: Glacier Bay National Park Visitor Center
description: Located on the second floor of Glacier Bay Lodge in Bartlett Cove, 10 miles from Gustavus. Staffed daily in summer with park rangers. Stop by for exhibits, park information, trip planning, bookstore, reading area, hydrophone kiosk, interpretive programs, park films, brochures, and much more.
