name: Glen Canyon Conservancy Flagship
description: An official visitor center for the state of Arizona, and acting as Glen Canyon's supplementary visitor center in Page AZ, the Flagship office and retail store is a great place to start your Glen Canyon adventure. Our partners Glen Canyon Conservancy offer the historic big relief map that originally anchored the Carl Hayden Visitor Center. Let the knowledgeable staff help you plan your trip, browse the retail store for books, maps, and gear that you'll need during your visit.
audioDescription: Glen Canyon Conservancy's Flagship location is a storefront at 12 North Lake Powell Boulevard, Page AZ 86040. There is a small parking lot on the side. A low ramp leads to the building entrance. No stairs. The large relief map is on the left, surrounded by a metal railing. Large wooden posts are present in various parts of the room. The rest of the floorspace is a retail store for books and gear related to the area. Shelves are spaced for ease to maneuver.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps that had been living at Carl Hayden Visitor Center are now also at the Flagship. When CHVC is closed, the stamps are available here. There are stamps for Glen Canyon National Recreation Area, Rainbow Bridge National Monument, and Old Spanish Trail National Historic Trail.

name: Golden Gate Bridge Welcome Center
description: The plaza is the starting point for all your bridge-related adventures. From here, you can learn about the history of the bridge and its impact on the Bay Area with the help of interactive installations and models, including a cross-section of the bridge's main suspension cable. There is limited paid parking at the plaza, and we highly recommend that you take public transit.

name: Golden Spike National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is the first place to stop for any visitors coming out to the park. The center features the WNPA Park Store, exhibits, a theater, picnic areas, and a welcoming staff that will help visitors get the most out of their visit. Spring-Summer: The visitor center is open daily, 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM MDT. Fall-Winter: Mid-October to mid-April the visitor center is open Thursday-Monday 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM MST (excluding Thanksgiving, Christmas Eve, Christmas, and New Year's).
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is the first place to stop for any visitors coming out to the park. The center features the WNPA Park Store, exhibits, a theater, picnic areas & a welcoming staff that will help visitors get the most out of their visit. Spring-Summer: The visitor center is open daily, 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM MDT Fall-Winter: Mid-October to mid-April the visitor center is open Thursday-Monday 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM MST (excluding Thanksgiving, Christmas Eve, Christmas, and New Year's).
passportStampLocationDescription: Golden Spike National Historical Park participates in the NPS Passport program. The passport stamp is located inside the Visitor Center, unless noted otherwise on the park's Current Conditions page.

directionsInfo: Golden Spike National Historical Park is 32 miles west of Brigham City, Utah. Travelers on I-15: use exit 365 and drive west on Utah 13 and 83 through Corinne (follow brown directional signs) to Golden Spike Drive. Turn left and follow signs to the visitor center (8 miles). Southbound travelers on I-84: use exit 26 and drive south on Utah 83 (follow brown directional signs) to Golden Spike Drive. Turn right and follow signs to the visitor center (8 miles). Lat/Long 41.617410,-112.550986

name: Golden West Visitor Center
description: Visitor Center located short walk from the passenger ferry landing at Stehekin Landing inside what was the historic Golden West Lodge. Exhibits: Relief map and natural and cultural history of the area. Arts & Humanities of Stehekin operates the Golden West Gallery, featuring local art and crafts. Facilities: Information desk, bookstore. Audiovisual program. Summer ranger programs offered.

name: Gran Quivira
description: The Gran Quivira Visitor Center includes restrooms, museum, and a bookstore. During the summer (May 1-October 31), trails and restrooms are open daily from 9am-5pm; the visitor center is open Thursday-Monday from 9am-5pm. During the winter (November 1-February 28th), trails and restrooms are open daily from 9am-4pm, and the visitor center is closed. From March 1st through April 30th, the visitor center is open Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays 9am-4pm and the trials and restrooms are open daily 9am-4pm.
audioDescription: As you drive up the paved Quivera Flats Road, the parking area is paved. Follow the asphalt trail a short distance to a covered walkway. The restrooms are on the right (women's on the left; men's on the right) and the visitor center is in a separate building to the left. Inside the Gran Quivira Visitor Center is a bookstore and a museum.
passportStampLocationDescription: Each of our three sites and Headquarters have a stamp that will say Salinas Pueblo Missions NM, the date, and the name of the site. The Gran Quivira Visitor Center has the Gran Quivira stamp.

name: Grand Canyon Visitor Center (South Rim)
description: This fall, the Visitor Center is open daily from 10 am to 4 pm. Trip planning and hiking information is available through exhibit kiosks and sidewalk signs outside of the building. Park in one of four large parking lots and get your first look at Grand Canyon by walking to nearby Mather Point. With your vehicle parked at the Visitor Center, you can also board free shuttle buses and be transported around the village and out to scenic overlooks.
audioDescription: Four large parking lots surround a several hundred-square foot (approximately 200 m square) concrete Grand Canyon Visitor Center Plaza. The visitor center itself sits on the north side of the plaza. Inside the long, glass-faced building are displays about the canyon, trip planning tools, and a park ranger-staffed information desk. At the east end, you can enter a theater, which shows the accessible park film “Grand Canyon: A Journey of Wonder.” A large 3-D relief map with videos features a variety of canyon locations and experiences. Adjacent to the visitor center building, to the west, are restrooms and a water filling station. Additional restrooms and a second water filling station are located to the east a short distance along the path toward the landmark Tribal Medallion and Mather Point. To the southeast of the plaza is the Grand Canyon Visitor Center shuttle bus terminal, with shuttle buses to all areas of the park. A bike rental shop and café serving grab and go food is situated at the western end of the plaza, and a large Grand Canyon Conservancy Park Store sits on the south side of the plaza, directly opposite the visitor center. There is a water fountain located to the left inside the store, and there are several benches out front. The Park Store features a wide variety of books, maps and gifts to help you plan your trip to Grand Canyon, learn more about its geology, ecology and human history. Park Store purchases help fund new exhibits, scientific research, trail restoration, wildlife monitoring, ecological restoration, support for the arts, Junior Ranger and education programs, and historic building preservation.
passportStampLocationDescription: Grand Canyon Visitor Center has its own, official, dated passport cancellation stamp which reads "Grand Canyon, AZ" at the bottom. It is identical to the dated passport cancellation stamp available at Park Headquarters. However, this stamp is slightly different from the dated passport cancellation stamp available at the nearby Grand Canyon Conservancy Park Store, which reads "Visitor Center Plaza" at the bottom.

directionsInfo: Once you get past the South Entrance Station, continue following the road you are on for 5 miles, and it will lead you to the Visitor Center. Just before the parking areas, the road curves to the left. You can park your car in one of four parking areas, then get your first view of Grand Canyon by taking a short walk to nearby Mather Point. From the Visitor Center, it is also possible to Park-and-Ride. Leave your car at the Visitor Center, then board free shuttle buses and ride around the South Rim.

name: Grand Sable Visitor Center
description: Nestled at the foot of the Grand Sable Dunes, the Grand Sable Visitor Center is located near the eastern gateway to the park and along the North Country National Scenic Trail. The lovely, wooded Sable Creek Trail also begins here. The building is open summer only (as staffing allows) from 9 am to 5 pm through the end of September. Closed the rest of the year. Flush indoor restrooms available when open. A vault toilet located across the parking lot is open year-round.
audioDescription: From the parking lot, follow the concrete pathway which will angle to your right up to the front door of a two-story farmhouse nestled at the base of the Grand Sable Dunes and surrounded by trees. The front door to the farmhouse takes you into the Grand Sable Visitor Center. The front door swings outwards and is the only entrance to the visitor center. Inside, the visitor center information desk is slightly to the right and is seven feet away in front of you. To the left as you enter, a large map of the park is located on the wall. To the left of the information desk, and going further into the building, is the cooperating association retail store. Beyond the store merchandise, there is a hallway along the left side that takes you to the restrooms. The first door on the right in the hallway is the women’s restroom. The second door on the right is the men’s restroom. The doors open into the restrooms and are not automatic. A drinking fountain is in the hall between the doors. There are accessible stalls in each restroom, as well as sinks for handwashing.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Grand Sable Visitor Center has one passport stamp available. When the VC is closed, take a photo of the stamp posted on the outside information board. You can resize and print it on paper later, fill in the date, and then cut and paste it into your NPS passport book.

name: Grant Visitor Center
description: Fire plays an important, natural role in the ecosystems found in Yellowstone National Park and the surrounding region. Learn more about this and the fires of 1988 in the exhibit hall, gather park information and trip ideas, shop for souvenirs at the park store, join a ranger program, buy a fishing, boating, or backcountry camping permit (fees are payable by debit or credit card), or use the restrooms.
audioDescription: Grant Visitor Center 228 words A cement sidewalk leads to this one-story brown structure with a wide gable roof shading its entrance. Affixed to a horizontal board forming the base of an open triangle just below this roofline is the arrow-shaped National Parks Service emblem. Four wide steps with wooden handrails at left and right lead to a covered porch area also extending left and right. The double-door entrance to the Center is approximately six feet forward from the top of the stairs. You will encounter a rubber mat in front of the doors. A small sign with a wheelchair logo hangs on a pillar to the left of the top stair, indicating the wheelchair ramp with shallow curb that slopes upward approximately 20 feet from the left side of the building. Doors to the restrooms are located on the porch to the right of the entrance. The women’s room is approximately 10 feet from the entrance, with the men’s room another 25 feet beyond the women’s room. A covered deck overlooking the West Thumb of Yellowstone Lake is located at the rear of the center. This deck, which offers numerous benches for viewing the lake, can be reached by stepping through a second set of double doors in the building’s interior. Other indoor features include an information desk staffed by park rangers, exhibits, educational bookstore, theater, and backcountry office. END OF MESSAGE
passportStampLocationDescription: The "Grant Visitor Center" passport stamp is located in the Yellowstone Forever bookstore within the Grant Visitor Center.

name: Great Basin Visitor Center
description: Phone: (775) 234-7520 Located just north of the town of Baker on the west side of NV Highway 487. The Visitor Center contains an information desk staffed by park rangers, exhibits about the ecology and history of the park, a theater with the park film, and brochures.
audioDescription: Located at the bottom of a valley. 13,000 foot mountains cover the background with colors changing from a sage green at the base to a treeless brown on the top of the peaks. The Visitor Center is tan with a sage green roof. There are two buildings with outdoor seating between them. Inside the Visitor Center, to the left is the park store, directly in font in the information desk, and to the right is the exhibit hall. Within the exhibit hall are numerous exhibits, starting on the left and moving in a clockwise motion. The exhibits cover the geology of the Great Basin, the night sky, bristle cone pine trees, life zones, and cultures of the Great Basin.
passportStampLocationDescription: Use the virtual stamp below to mark your visit to Great Basin National Park. Just fill in the month, day, and year on your own. In person stamps are available at the Great Basin Visitor Center during operating hours.

name: Great Falls Tavern Visitor Center
description: The Great Falls Tavern Visitor Center is located at mile 14.3 along the C&O Canal towpath in Montgomery County, MD. The Great Falls of the Potomac have drawn people to the river's shore for centuries. To American Indians, a gathering place; to George Washington, an impediment to navigation; to thousands of visitors every year, an awe-inspiring site. Throughout the generations Great Falls Tavern continues a long tradition of hospitality.

name: Great Island Cabin Office
description: Located at Great Island on South Core Banks, this area is only reached by either the park ferry or your personal boat. The vehicle ferry coming from Davis, NC lands here, dropping off 4-wheel drive vehicles and passengers. The Office is open seasonally from 8:00 AM - 3:00 PM daily. Available facilities: First Aid, park passport stamp, free Jr Ranger booklet, beach wheelchair (free rental), recreation permits
audioDescription: Located on South Core Banks, the Great Island Cabin Office serves not only as the office area for the operation of the rustic cabins located here, but also as a visitor center for this ferry arrival point on the island. Ferries carrying 4x4 vehicles and walk-on passengers come from the town of Davis on the mainland across the about 3 miles of water to the barrier island. This location is about mid-way on the 20 mile long island and is about 10 miles north of the Cape Lookout Lighthouse. Once off the ferry, follow the sand road east towards the ocean, the cabin office is the 2nd cabin on the right. Stop in here to ask questions, find out the time of the next tide, and get your beach driving permit decal for your vehicle . The Cabin Office is also the place to check in to your reserved cabin, purchase ice or emergency gas, and use the air compressor to re-inflate your tires after driving on the beach.

name: Great Sand Dunes Visitor Center
description: The visitor center offers restrooms, a water fill station, interactive exhibits, and a 20-minute video about the park. Park rangers are available to answer questions and help you plan your time.
audioDescription: The visitor center offers restrooms, a water fill station, interactive exhibits, and a 20-minute video about the park. Park rangers are available to answer questions and help you plan your time.

directionsInfo: From CO Highway 160: Between the towns of Alamosa, CO, and Blanca, CO, there will be large brown signs marking the turn off to the park. Turn north on CO State Highway 150. Drive straight (north) for 15 miles to the entrance of the park. From CO Highway 17: Near the town of Mosca, CO, turn onto County Road Lane 6N. At the end of the road, turn left (north) onto CO State Highway 150. This highway will take you into the national park.

name: Gulf Coast Visitor Center
description: The Gulf Coast Visitor Center temporary building is open daily from 9:00 am to 5:00 pm. The canoe/kayak launch and parking lot are open, however services are limited. There is currently no drinking water available. For more information, call the visitor center at 239-232-0057. The Gulf Coast Visitor area serves as the gateway for exploring the Ten Thousand Islands, a maze of mangrove islands and waterways that extends to Flamingo and Florida Bay accessible only by boat in this region.
audioDescription: The Gulf Coast Visitor Center was in a beige triple-wide trailer. The trailer has four long windows that face west. The entrance to the trailer is by white double doors. There is a silver, metal, accessible ramp that leads to the front doors of the trailer. The ramp is decorated by exhibits in the shape of mangrove trees. The exhibits are brown at the bottom and green at the top. Attached to the ramp is a brown sign with white letters that reads Everglades National Park Gulf Coast Visitor Center. There is also a National Park Service arrowhead attached to the ramp in front of the double doors. At the beginning of the wooden boardwalk that leads to the trailer is a gray box labeled “Camping Permits” on a wooden stand. North of the camping permit box are trash and recycling bins. North of the visitor center is a wooden boardwalk that leads to the restroom trailer. The restroom trailer is white and has five stalls one of which is accessible. Along the wooden boardwalk are trees, mostly mahogany with Spanish moss hanging from their branches. The visitor center parking lot has two rows of parking that are separated by a grassy median. West of the parking lot is Chokoloskee Bay, a ½-mile wide body of water. Across the bay is a continuous line of mangrove trees. All around the parking lot are trees, mainly palm trees. West of the parking lot is a flagpole which flies the American flag. Inside the visitor center and just to the right when you first walk in is a framed poster that reads “Ranger Natural Service.” Just to the left of that is a gray donation box with a glass front. The glass has the National Park Service arrowhead on it. Just to the left of the donation box is a closed door with no public access. To the left of that is a black, tall table. The table has various maps of the 10,000 Islands. Above the table hanging on the wall is a framed poster that reads “Heroes of the Everglades.” To the left of the black table and framed poster is an encased skin of a Burmese python. The skin extends from the floor of the visitor center to the ceiling. Left of the skin is a framed picture from 2018 of Park Rangers and volunteers holding a 13-foot long Burmese python. Below the picture is a bumper sticker that reads “Report invasive species” and “www.ivegot1.org.” Below that is a small informational card that reads “Seen something exotic? Report your sighting!” To the left of the bumper sticker, framed picture and informational card are two more doors with no public access to them. Attached to a false gray wall is a large poster that reads “Cities of Shell” informing you on the archaeology of the 10,000 Islands. Above the poster and to the right is a replica of a white ibis hanging from the ceiling. Below the poster on the floor is a long folding table with a black tablecloth over it. To the left of the “Cities of Shell” poster is another slightly smaller poster whose title is “Gentle Giant” and it informs on the manatee. The poster is varying shades of blue and has several pictures of the West Indian Manatee on it. To the left of that is a letter-sized, laminated sheet of paper that reads “Sawfish Hotline” and gives you a number to call if you see a sawfish. To the left of that is another large horizontal poster whose title is “Vanishing Relic” and it informs on the Smalltooth Sawfish, an endangered species. The poster is varying shades of gray, light blue and white, and there are several pictures of sawfish and fishermen with sawfish. To the left of the “Vanishing Relic” poster is a wooden case with a replica sawfish inside and behind a glass window. Below the sawfish exhibit is a plastic, life-sized sea turtle. To the left of the exhibit is the information desk. The desk is long and black with a banner hanging from it that reads “Everglades National Park,” The banner is black with a small arrowhead symbol on the bottom right corner. Behind the information desk are three whiteboards. One reads “Sites at Capacity” and the other two are for seasonally variable information. Behind the information desk is also a large map of Everglades National Park. To the right of the large Everglades National Park map are two plastic wall hangers that contain several binders and books. To the left and above the Everglades National Park map is a clock. Left of the information desk is a tall desk with two desktop computers and a printer. To the left of the desk with the computers is a smaller, brown desk. Left of the brown table are two refrigerators. To the left of the refrigerators are two tall, black desks belonging to the park concession. Left of the black desk is the defibrillator. To the left of the defibrillator is the exit which is the same as the entrance to the visitor center trailer.

name: Guy Bradley Visitor Center (at Flamingo)
description: The Guy Bradley Visitor Center is open year-round and features educational displays, informational brochures, a bookstore and more. Campground facilities, a public boat ramp, marina store, a fish cleaning station, and hiking and canoeing trails are located near the visitor center.

Turn right at the first traffic light onto Palm Dr. (SR 9336/SW 344th St.) and follow the signs to the park. name: Hale Ho'okipa Visitor Center
description: Stop by to receive a park orientation at Hale Ho'okipa, the Park's Visitor Center and location of the Hawaii Pacific Parks Association Bookstore.
audioDescription: The park visitor center is single building located in a lava flow off the main Highway that leads into Kailua-Kona. It has basic services, bathrooms and an accessible walkway from the main parking lot.

directionsInfo: Kaloko-Honokohau National Historical Park is located on the west coast of the island of Hawai'i, approximately 3 miles south of the Keahole International Airport (Kailua-Kona Airport) and 3 miles north of the town of Kailua-Kona, on the ocean side of Highway 19. The visitor center, Hale Ho'okipa, is located half a mile north of the entrance to Honokohau Harbor. The Kaloko road gate is located across the highway from the Kaloko New Industrial Park (across from the big yellow "Kona Trade Center" building).

name: Haleakalā Visitor Center
description: About a 30 minute drive from the Headquarters Visitor Center, the Haleakalā Visitor Center is perched on the edge of the impressive volcanic valley. Inside, park staff can answer questions at the information desk. Visitors can learn about the history of the mountain through various displays. There is also a Hawaiʻi Pacific Parks Association bookstore with souvenirs available for purchase. Restrooms are located nearby in a separate building and are open 24/7. Please check the alerts page for any closures.
audioDescription: A four-step stairwell and paved path lead from the parking lot up to a small rock visitor center perched on the edge of the Haleakalā crater. A metal railing extends on one side with uneven gravel and rocky viewing area. A separate building with restrooms is along the paved pathway to the left out of the parking lot. The single story rock structure can be accessed by an entrance near the bathroom building or an entrance at the top of the stairway and paved path. Inside is a small bookstore with racks of clothing, books, and souvenirs in one area. There is an information desk and checkout area. Expansive glass windows provide views into the crater valley of the dozen cinder cones and valley floor several thousand feet below. Flat panel exhibits adorn the walls, and a large 3D topographic model map of the mountain and crater valley stands in the middle of the room. There is a small office with closing door in the rear of the one-room visitor center space.

name: Hangar Visitor Center
description: The Hangar Visitor Center is closed as the park prepares for a major rehabilitation of the Texas White House and the Hangar. Visitors are welcome to walk the grounds, and portable toilets are available. Drinking water and flush toilets are available at the Reconstructed Birthplace.
audioDescription: Airplane Hangar Visitor Center. 187 words The hangar is a low, wide building with a gently sloping roof peaking in the middle. The siding is corrugated metal painted a light Army green. The front of the building, originally open, is now enclosed by a glass-walled extension with a shed-type roof sloping down to the front. Double glass doors at the left end form the entrance, leading through a small foyer into the visitor center itself. The information desk is about 15 feet straight ahead from the doors. There are a number of graphic displays inside and entry to the rest rooms is located along the back wall. A sign just to the left of the entrance reads, “Airplane Hangar Visitor, Texas White House Tours, Lyndon B. Johnson National Historical Park.” Just in front of the building at the right front corner are historic gas pumps with Gulf oil logos. Farther to the right is a grassy area where a map of Texas has been outlined on the ground with rocks and gravel and blue glass for the Gulf of Mexico. A flag pole stands in the middle. End of description.

directionsInfo: The Hangar Visitor Center is located on the LBJ Ranch. First, obtain a driving permit at the Lyndon B. Johnson State Park and Historic Site located on Highway 290 between Johnson City and Fredericksburg. Cross the Pedernales River to enter the LBJ Ranch. The ranch entrance gate is open 7 days/week, 9:00 am -4:30 pm. Following the LBJ Ranch Driving Tour route will lead you to the Hangar Visitor Center located in the Texas White House Complex. Plan on approximately 30 minutes drive time from the State Park.

name: Hans Flat Ranger Station
description: The remote Hans Flat (Maze) Ranger Station is normally open daily year-round. While physically located in Glen Canyon NRA, it is operated by the rangers of Canyonlands National Park. This ranger contact station has a picnic table and vault toilet, and a small selection of books and maps for sale. There are no services, food, gas, trash collection, electricity for visitor use, nor potable water. The nearest communities with amenities are Hanksville (68 miles) and Green River (86 miles).
audioDescription: This ranger station is a modular-style building with a set of wooden steps and a long wooden ramp leading up to it. The interior of the building is wheelchair accessible, and offers trip planning, maps, and souvenir purchasing. The parking area is flat. The road to approach the ranger station is not paved and impassible in bad weather. RVs and large low-clearance vehicles are not recommended.

directionsInfo: Getting to the Orange Cliffs requires four-wheel-drive and a lot of time. To reach Hans Flat Ranger Station, from I-70 take UT 24 south for 24 miles. A left turn just beyond the turnoff to Goblin Valley State Park will take you along an unpaved, two-wheel-drive dirt road, 46 miles to the ranger station. Blowing sand dunes or precipitation can degrade the road condition at any time. Roads beyond the ranger station require high clearance and four-wheel drive year-round.

name: Hans Flat Ranger Station
description: The remote Hans Flat (Maze) Ranger Station is normally open daily year-round. This ranger contact station has a picnic table and vault toilet, and a small selection of books and maps for sale. There are no services, food, gas, trash collection, electricity for visitor use, nor potable water in The Maze. The nearest communities with amenities are Hanksville (68 miles) and Green River (86 miles).
audioDescription: Hans Flat Ranger Station, which serves as the Maze District’s visitor center, sits at 6,500 feet on a broad mesa top with canyons dropping to the south, east, and further north. The surrounding landscape is dominated by pinyon pine and Utah juniper trees, and desert shrubs. The building is situated on the south side of a Y-junction on a remote and infrequently trafficked dirt road. In the front of the building is a small parking area, which is indicated by a line of large stacked rocks. There is a gap in the line of rocks to create a walking path to the building’s entrance. Where the walking path and right-side parking boundary meet is a flagpole. Immediately left of the building is a gravel driveway which gives more immediate wheelchair access to the building. From the parking area, facing south, the building is a rectangular single-story modular with pale yellow wood-textured paneling, white corrugated skirting, and an angled white corrugated roof. There are four sets of side sliding windows which are bordered by brown panels. The windows furthest to the right and left of the building are slightly obstructed by large pinyon pines. Left of center of the building is a wooden porch which may be accessed by using steps immediately ahead or by a ramp that curves around the left side of the building. The portion of the porch above the doorway is sheltered by a protruding A-frame roof. At the point of the porch roof is a light brown rectangular wooden sign with white lettering reading, “Hans Flat Ranger Station. National Park Service.” To the left of the sign is the National Park Service arrowhead logo. The building entrance is through a screen door and hinged entry door. Just south of the parking area boundary and west of the station is a picnic table with a shade structure. From the picnic table, looking beyond the station and to the right, the Henry Mountains can be seen in the distance. A unisex vault toilet sits on the northwest side of the Y-junction, or nearly directly across the road from the picnic table. The interior of the building has vinyl flooring and wood paneled walls which are decorated with historical pictures and posters relevant to Canyonlands National Park. The visitor area is small, containing an information desk, informational displays, and some items for purchase.

name: Harkers Island Visitor Center
description: Available Facilities: Restrooms, first aid, ferry ticket booth, picnic area, and a kayak launch site. Programs and Amenities: Exhibits on island history and ecology including the Shackleford Banks horses; interactive map of the park; Discovery Room with sounds of the seashore game, a touch table and other kid friendly activities; the park film is shown upon request; book store; Ranger programs and free Junior Ranger and Junior Ranger Adventures activity guides
audioDescription: The Harkers Island Visitor Center sits at the end of Harkers Island next to the water. From this point, visitors can look across the 3 miles of water to the Cape Lookout Lighthouse. The parking lot in front of the visitor center serves not only the visitor center, but also the passenger ferry out to the islands. There is no charge for parking and overflow parking areas are available. On the northern side of the parking lot there is one set of restrooms – male, female and family – available in a separate building. On the eastern edge of the parking lot is the passenger ferry waiting area. Sidewalks lead the way to the Visitor Center entry doors (two sets of double doors which open out, the set of doors to the left have an ADA door assist control on a support post), the ferry ticket window (on the outside of the main visitor center building to the left) and also meander through the grass and along the edge of the water around the building and back to the beginning of the Nature Trail. The Visitor Center has a staffed information desk, an exhibit area, a park store and a theater showing the park’s movie. The movie is open captioned and assistive listening devices are available by request at the information desk with the movie being audio described or having the movie’s narration amplified – a single ear clip speaker or a neck loop is available for each unit. Restrooms (male, female) are also found inside the building. Baby changing tables are found in each restroom.

description: The Visitor Center is located at the main entrance of the park at 171 Shoreline Drive, Harpers Ferry, WV 25425. Visitors may ask questions, pick up park maps and brochures, and more. audioDescription: A one-story rectangular brick building. A central double-glass door with two slim rectangular windows on either side, topped by an arched three-panel window, is framed by symmetrical large 9-paned arched windows. The central pane of both windows has painted text: Harpers Ferry National Historical Park. The metal roof peaks above the central double-glass door and arched three-panel window. A sign hung below the peak reads, Visitor Center. The National Park Service arrowhead is hung on either side of the central door. There is a small rectangular cupola composed of three horizontal windows on each side.

name: Harriet Tubman Underground Railroad Visitor Center
description: Operated in partnership with the Maryland Park Service, this visitor center considers the life and legacy of Harriet Tubman, born a slave here in Dorchester County, Maryland. Tubman escaped her condition of slavery and returned to Maryland to bring more than 70 relatives and friends to freedom using the Underground Railroad network. Experience the landscape that colored Tubman's early life, and explore exhibits and a film to learn more about her compelling story.
audioDescription: Once inside the park and from the curb near the park Visitor center you will want to walk approximately 60 feet staying straight and slightly to the right. To your right is the Accessible door panel that opens the doors to the visitor center. Walk through the doors and the front desk will be 15 feet to your left.

name: Harry F. Byrd, Sr. Visitor Center
description: Byrd Visitor Center (mile 51) is located across from Big Meadows in the center of Shenandoah National Park. Available facilities include: restrooms, information desk, ranger programs, bookstore, publications, maps, and first aid. Within close proximity to countless activities and hikes, it's a great place to start your next trip!
audioDescription: Byrd Visitor Center is a building off mile 51 of Skyline Drive. The visitor center is across from Big Meadows on the northwest side of the road. In front of the visitor center is a large parking lot. Facing the visitor center from the parking lot there is open space outside the entrance of the visitor center with an American flag, a statue of a man in the Civilian Conservation Corps, and to the left a large sign. The sign has a stone foundation with a brown metal frame coming out of the stone. On top of the frame are two brown, metal rectangles with the text, "Harry F. Byrd, Sr. Visitor Center." To the right there is an expanded patio area with bushes and shrubs planted inside a rectangular stone planter that is raised and also provides benches. Beyond the planter to the right are bathrooms. The patio is bordered at the front and to the right by rectangular columns that lead to a covered area between the patio and the visitor center walls. There are benches in between the columns near the planter. Facing the entrance of the visitor center, there is a brown, wooden sign on a column to the left indicating whether the visitor center is open and the hours. There is a bulletin board with current information on the right and the National Park Service arrowhead logo on the left. Entering the visitor center through two double glass doors, there is a vestibule inside. A sharp left leads to the Shenandoah National Park Association's gift shop. To the right of the gift shop and on the left of the wide open area is a long desk. Rangers and volunteers at the desk can answer questions about trip planning and the resources at the Park. On the right begins an interpretive exhibit about the history of Shenandoah National Park and the people who lived here before the establishment of the Park. The exhibit begins through a hallway on the right and makes a loop, leading visitors around until they exit back to the open area. Between the exhibit entrance and exit is the entrance to the theater when the park film plays. On the side of the building opposing the entrance is a large window that looks out to the meadow across the street. There are many seats near the windows where visitors can sit and relax.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are located at the information desk inside of the visitor center.

Follow Old Bluff Road for 4.5 miles to the park entrance sign, which will be on the right. Proceed one mile to the Harry Hampton Visitor Center. Parking lots will be on the right. Short brick paths lead up to the Visitor Center. Inside you find an America's National Parks bookstore.

name: Hartwell Tavern
description: Hartwell Tavern is closed for winter. The building will re-open in spring 2024.
audioDescription: Hartwell Tavern is a two story, unpainted wooden structure set within a partially cleared landscape beside the Battle Road Trail bordered by low stone walls. The walk from the parking area to the tavern is approximately 200 yards. When you arrive at the tavern proceed to the right of the stone wall in front, then across the front lawn to the front door.

description: The visitor center offers orientation information, a bookstore to shop for gifts, and a great views of the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse.
audioDescription: From the main parking lot at the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, follow the walkway up the ramp on to the boardwalk. There are two buildings at the top of the boardwalk. The restrooms are the building on the right. The visitor center is the building to the left of the restrooms.

name: Hatteras Island Weather Bureau Station
description: The Hatteras Weather Bureau Station was built in 1901 as one of the many stations along the east coast that would forecast weather for boats and the surrounding communities. Today the building is used as a information center.
audioDescription: From the main parking lot at the U.S. Weather Bureau Station on Hatteras Island, follow the sidewalk up to the front door of the weather bureau. Inside, on the first room on the left you will find various brochures, newspapers, and other publications that provide information on the local area. The other rooms inside feature displays that explore the history of the U.S. Weather Bureau and weather forecasting on Hatteras Island. There are no restrooms located on site

name: Headquarters Visitor Center
description: During the summer season (May 1 through October 31), the Headquarters Visitor Center in Mountainair is open daily 9:00 a.m. - 5:00 p.m. During the winter season (Nov 1 through April 30), the Main Visitor Center in Mountainair is open Thursday-Monday from 9:00 a.m. - 4:00 p.m. A 14-minute park movie is shown, on demand, at the headquarters. The visitor center includes a museum, restrooms, and gift store. All park sites closed Thanksgiving, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day.
audioDescription: When you walk into the visitor center, the Ranger desk will be directly in front of you. The restrooms are accessed by following the hallway to the left of the Ranger desk (Continue straight down the hallway until it ends and turn left. The women's restroom is on your right; continue down the hallway to the end and the men's restroom will be on the right). The water fountain is between the two restrooms. From the main entrance, turn left to walk into the museum. The Park Movie will be shown in a room to the right. The movie is on demand, with the buttons underneath the TV; the lefthand button is English, and the righthand button is Spanish.
passportStampLocationDescription: Each of our three sites and Headquarters have a stamp that will say Salinas Pueblo Missions NM, the date, and the name of the site. Our Main Visitor Center (Headquarters) in Mountainair, NM has its own stamp and a stamp for each of the three sites.

name: Headquarters Visitor Center
description: The Headquarters Visitor Center is 1 mile (1.6 km) past the Summit District entrance gate. Inside, park staff can answer questions at the information desk. A small exhibit hall features displays on the park's natural and cultural history. Restrooms are accessible from the outside and open 24/7. Please check park alerts for information on closures.
audioDescription: A one-story, tan building situated next to the park road. The outside of the building displays a National Park Service Arrowhead and the words "Visitor Center." A garden of native trees and shrubs is planted along the sidewalk to the front doors. A lobby with glass windows has a bench and leads into a small exhibit hall. The exhibits feature Native Hawaiian cultural practices. There are accessibility options for the exhibits available at the front desk. To the right of the exhibits is the front desk, where park rangers supply maps and brochures. Copies of the main park brochure in Braille are available at the front desk to borrow. Behind the rangers at the desk is a large painting of the park's incredible biodiversity. Next to the information desk is the cash register for the partnering bookstore, Hawai'i Pacific Parks Association. The bookstore offers hiking and birding guides, books on Native Hawaiian history and culture, and educational children's books. Postcards, magnets, t-shirts, and a small selection of snacks are also available. By the windows looking out to the road is the Headquarters Visitor Center stamp on a small table. The stamp says "Haleakalā National Park, Headquarters" and shows the current date and a small engraving of a nēnē. There is green ink and sheets of paper available next to the stamp on the table. All throughout the visitor center are realistic models of some of Hawai'i's native birds perched on branches by the ceiling. The models feature the i'iwi, which is a bright red bird with a long, curved, red beak. There is also the 'apapane, which is red and white, and the 'alauahio and the 'amakihi, which are both yellow birds.
passportStampLocationDescription: The round stamp reads "Haleakalā National Park" on the top and "Headquarters" on the bottom. The center shows the current date and a small engraving of a nēnē, Hawaiʻi's state bird.

name: Henry A. Wallace Visitor Center
description: Named in honor of the man who served as Secretary of Agriculture (1933-1940) and Vice-President during Franklin Roosevelt's third term, the Henry A. Wallace Center offers an array of services designed to enhance your visit to Hyde Park. The visitor center provides information on tours, exhibits, gardens, trails, activities, special events, and the film "Rendezvous with History." Our experienced staff can help you plan an itinerary for your visit.

name: Henry Hill Visitor Center
description: Begin your visit to the Park at the Henry Hill Visitor Center. Here, you can pick up a park brochure, trail guide, or learn about the daily schedule of interpretive programs. A museum features artifacts related to the First and Second Battles of Manassas as well as a 6-minute electronic map showing the troop movements during the first battle. Walking tours of the fighting on Henry Hill during the First Battle of Manassas begin here daily at 11:00am and 2:00pm.

name: Henry M Jackson Memorial Visitor Center
description: Located at Paradise, on the south side of Mount Rainier, the Jackson Visitor Center is open throughout the summer and with limited days and hours in the winter. Inside the visitor center are accessible restrooms, an information desk staffed by a ranger or volunteer, food services, gift shop, park movie, and exhibits about the plants, animals, and the volcano.
audioDescription: The visitor center building is two stories tall. The sides of the exterior are carved blocks of mottled gray and white granite speckled with black and planks of wood. Floor to ceiling multi-paned windows, trimmed in light green, fill most of the north and south sides. The smooth, gray metal roof has a steep slope to the north and south from its center peak. To reach the visitor center, approach from the parking area. There are multiple-door entrances on either side of the building, allowing you inside. The first floor is an open space, like a Great Hall, open to the steeply pitched ceiling above the second floor. Throughout the building, its triangular wood roof trusses, which mirror the roof’s slope toward the north and south, as well as many upright, rectangular wooden columns, are exposed. The wood is a warm golden tan color. Steel beams and metal trim, both black, accent the wood. The frames of the multi-paned windows are the same warm golden tan wood. On the first floor, restrooms, drinking fountains, and telephones are located outside the main entrance. An information desk sits in the middle of the building with rangers eager to answer questions. Behind the information desk is the entrance to a theatre, which shows the video, “A Restless Giant: The Ever-Changing Nature of Mount Rainier,” theater and in the back building sits the cafeteria. Near the staircase to the second floor is a three-dimensional map of Mount Rainier National Park and the nearby panels of information about planning your visit. After going up the stairs you arrive in the main exhibit area on the second floor. An audio description tour of the exhibits is available for check out at the information desk.

name: Heritage Center
description: This National Park site houses the National Homesteading Museum. State-of-the-art exhibits present homesteading in an interactive setting. Such topics as the Act's influence on immigration, agriculture, industrialization, native tribes, the tallgrass prairie ecosystem and Federal land policies are presented in an educational and thought-provoking manner. The hours listed below generally include the Homestead Education Center, Freeman School, and Palmer-Epard Cabin.
audioDescription: As you walk up the sidewalk to the Heritage Center you see cutouts of the 30 homestead states. Each has a square inside that represents the amount of land that was settled under the homestead act in each state. The heritage center itself has a curved roof that comes to a point resembling a plow. As you enter the building, you first arrive in the bookstore which includes an informational desk. As you move further into the lobby and bookstore you approach a railing that has a view of the split-levels allowing you to see the national homesteading museum in the basement of the buildings. The stairs leading down have large print posters of advertisements that were used during the Homestead Era.
passportStampLocationDescription: Homestead National Monument of America has cancellation stamps available in both the Heritage and Education Centers. Virtual Visit Stamps are found on our website.

name: Heritage Center
description: The Grand Portage National Monument Heritage Center opened on August 10, 2007 with a commitment to honor the area's history, people and culture. The building houses exhibit galleries about Anishinaabe (Ojibwe) culture and the fur trade, America's National Parks bookstore, multi-media programs. Ask questions, plan your visit, stamp your passport, borrow snowshoes (in winter), and more at the "Circle" (front desk). The upstairs of the Heritage Center serves as Park Headquarters.
audioDescription: The Grand Portage National Monument Heritage Center is a two story building, set atop a rocky hill. Upon entering the Heritage Center the front desk sits in the center of the room. Here, you can find information about park programming and resources. From the front desk you may enter into the exhibit hall to your left. To the right, three comfortable chairs face a fireplace. Heritage Center exhibits include artifacts, murals, a large birch bark canoe, photography, and historic Ojibwe lodges. You may experience multi media exhibits as well. Our classroom space to the right and down the hall from the information desk provides a comfortable seating area to enjoy films. Accessible restrooms are located within the Heritage Center, behind the information desk. The Eastern National Bookstore is also located within the Heritage Center to the left of the restrooms as you face away from the windows.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport Stamp is available at the Heritage Center front desk, and at the outdoor Heritage Center contact station when station is open.

name: Hiouchi Visitor Center
description: Northern-most park visitor center located 9-miles east of Crescent City on Hwy 199. Exhibits about Tolowa culture and art, redwood ecology, park information, junior ranger program, bookstore and retail sales.
audioDescription: This is a single story, low profile building painted brown. It has a large brown and yellow sign that reads "Hiouchi Visitor Center. Redwood National and State Parks". There is a driveway and parking area behind it, also with restrooms, picnic tables and some interpretive signs and information kiosks. A ramp goes from the parking area into the visitor center.

name: Historic Cant Ranch Museum
description: Enjoy the exhibits on the ground floor of the Historic Cant Ranch museum, featuring artifacts from some of the Native Americans who inhabited the region, and stories from homesteaders describing early ranch life. Learn about James and Elizabeth Cant's experience immigrating to John Day Basin from Scotland in the early 1900s, raising a family, and living off the land until their deaths in the early 1970s.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available during operating hours. During the off-season, the Cant Ranch passport stamp is available at the Thomas Condon Visitor Center.

name: Historic Jamestowne - Trail Headquarters
description: The trail shares a headquarters with Historic Jamestowne, an historic site and visitors center managed by Colonial National Historical Park. Visitors to this coastal Virginia island can explore the site where English colonists built their first successful settlement. Jamestown was the starting point of John Smith's voyages, which form the basis for the trail's route today. Take in the natural beauty of the James River, bike around the loop road, go on a guided tour, and more.

name: Hoh Rain Forest Visitor Center
description: Located in the Hoh Rain Forest. The visitor center is open daily during the summer and intermittently during the winter. Educational exhibits and informational brochures available.
audioDescription: Hoh Rainforest Visitor Center. 1 minute From the parking lot, a flat concrete sidewalk leads to a concrete patio around the visitor center. A brown wooden sign with white text along the sidewalk reads, Hoh Visitor Center, Elevation 573 feet. The one story rectangular gray wooden building with a flat roof faces the patio. The double door entrance to the center is on the right. A brown and white sign above the door reads, Hoh Rainforest Visitor Center. On the left are two all-gender accessible restrooms. In front of the visitor center on the left is a covered area with two benches and a water fountain. The exhibits inside the visitor center are audio described.

name: Homestead Education Center
description: Homestead National Monument of America uses the Education Center to provide today's visitors the opportunity to meet their quest for further knowledge about homesteading through Hands-on arts and crafts or living history demonstrations, real life science experiences, and distance learning. The Education Center also hosts many temporary exhibits and special programs. Talk to the Ranger in the Education Building [or at the Heritage Center] about these opportunities.
audioDescription: A brick, L-shaped building that stands nearby a woodland and has an open space patio to the rear.

name: Hopewell Furnace National Historic Site Visitor Center - 2 Mark Bird Lane, Elverson, PA 19520
description: Your first stop should be the Hopewell Furnace NHS Visitor Center where you will find staff eager to assist with your orientation to the park. Exhibits about furnace operations and the making of iron products including the original Mark Bird 1772 stove are on display. You can shop for Hopewell Furnace NHS related items by visiting the Eastern National store, a not-for-profit cooperating association; proceeds help fund park programming. Restrooms are available at the Visitor Center as well.
audioDescription: Your first stop should be the Hopewell Furnace NHS Visitor Center where you will find exhibits tracing the 112 years of furnace operations and the making of iron products. You will learn about Hopewell's community and the formidable skills and teamwork needed to make the iron products. The park's stove collection is also on display, including the original Mark Bird 1772 stove. You can still shop for Hopewell Furnace NHS related items by visiting the Eastern National Bookstore. Items include a variety of souvenirs, such as postcards, t-shirts, magnets, Junior Ranger items as well as Park Ranger-recommended books and films. Proceeds help fund programming at Hopewell Furnace National Historic Site. The Museum Store is managed by Eastern National, a not-for-profit cooperating association. In addition, park staff and volunteers are available to assist visitors with site orientation, directions and information. Public restrooms are located outside on the lower level of the Visitor Center. A water fountain with a bottle filling station and doggie drinking station is located just outside the restrooms. Dogs on leash are welcome to accompany their owners in the historic village. Only certified service dogs are permitted to enter historic structures with their owners. Since Hopewell Furnace is also a working farm, visitors are asked not to feed the farm animals and keep dogs away from the livestock.

name: Horseshoe Bend National Military Park Visitor Center
description: Visit our newly renovated museum to learn more about the Muscogee (Creek) people who made Alabama their home for thousands of years. See the 23-minute park film to learn about events leading to the Creek War and the consequences still reverberating today. Discover young Andrew Jackson as he builds his reputation as a tough-as-nails fighter. Participate in Junior Ranger activities, get your Passport stamp, or shop in our bookstore for educational items for all ages. Rangers are available to assist you.
audioDescription: Horseshoe Bend is 12 miles north of Dadeville, Alabama on US Highway 49. To reach the visitor center turn into the park entrance off of Highway 49. In about 100 feet, turn right into the parking area. Go about 200 feet and park on the right in on of the two accessible spaces. When you leave your vehicle, walk up the short accessible ramp that is between the two parking spaces. Two more steps leads to a knee-high brick wall. Face right and walk seven steps to the trash can and recycle bin. Navigate around it back to the wall, which angles 45 degrees left. Walk four more steps to the accessible down ramp with railings. Walk down the ramp. Take three steps and you will be next to a bench. If you need to use the restroom first, walk thirty steps straight out from the bench to the pavilion. You will be between two hip-height brick walls. Walk five steps straight from the wall opening. Turn right and walk six more steps. Make sure to stay centered as you will pass between two partition walls. You will be facing the utility closet between the restrooms. The women's restroom is to the right, and the male restroom to the left. To reach the visitor center from the restrooms, retrace your steps back to the pavilion opening with the hip-height walls. Walk forward 4-5 steps and turn right. Walk 24 steps. To go into the visitor center, you will turn right at this point and walk six steps to the front door of the visitor center. To see the cannon before going inside, instead of turning right, go straight for three more steps and you'll be at the cannon wheel. If you don't need the restroom, starting from the bench at the bottom of the ramp, turn left and walk 6-7 steps to the cannon. From this point it is eight steps forward to the visitor center.

directionsInfo: Horseshoe Bend National Military Park is located along Highway 49 in northeastern Tallapoosa County. From US-280 in Dadeville, travel 12 miles north along US-49. From US-280 in Alexander City, follow US-22 east for 19 miles. Turn right onto Horseshoe Bend Road/Highway 49, and travel 5 miles south to the park entrance. From Newnan, GA, follow GA-34 W and AL-22 W for about 60 miles, then make a left on County Road 79 in Daviston. Follow CR 79 for 8 miles, then left on US-49. Park entrance is 0.2 miles.

name: Houghton Visitor Center
description: The Houghton Visitor Center is located in Houghton, Michigan. It is the mainland headquarters for Isle Royale National Park. Trip planning assistance, Ranger III tickets and information, a park store, and viewing the park film are available.
audioDescription: The Houghton Visitor Center is located within the Isle Royale National Park Headquarters Complex. The entrance is located off of Lakeshore Drive. The headquarters complex is gated for transportation security, and visitors may only enter when the gate is open. When open, visitors are welcome on foot, bicycle, or in a vehicle. Follow the painted arrows past several maintenance buildings, along the pier where the RANGER III ferry docks, past the visitor center, to the parking lot. Several buildings are marked as administrative offices, and the signed visitor center is located in the center of the paved entryway and parking lot. The visitor center entrance is located by the flag pole. Obtain passes, permits, and information from park rangers. Shop the Isle Royale & Keweenaw Parks Association Store. Watch the park's 25 minute orientation film. During RANGER III passenger ferry operations, the front entrance gate is closed, and vehicle and pedestrian traffic are routed down a paved bike path to a different parking lot access point. When the visitor center is closed, the entrance gates are closed.

directionsInfo: The Visitor Center is located on the east end of Lakeshore Dr. in downtown Houghton, MI on the Keewenaw Waterway adjacent to the historic Dee Stadium. If traveling north on US41, turn right on Lakeshore Dr. just as you enter downtown Houghton on Shelden Avenue. The turn is adjacent to the Chamber of Commerce. If traveling north on M26, merge with US41 South. As you leave downtown use the left lane to briefly return to Shelden Ave and US41 North. Then take a right turn on Lakeshore Dr.

name: Hovenweep Visitor Center
description: The visitor center should be your starting place for any visit to Hovenweep. Rangers are available to answer questions and provide guidance on the best way to visit the monument. Restrooms, bookstore sales, and exhibits are available.

name: Hubbell Trading Post NHS Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is located east of the trading post. Interpretive exhibits on Hubbell family, the Long Walk, weaving, and a children's trading post are located inside. Ask for brochures and other informational leaflets. Guided tour tickets for the Hubbell Home are available. An interactive video, and viewing of 1-2 minutes snapshots of different videos that are for sell at the trading post are all available inside.
directionsInfo: From East: drive 1/2 mile west of junction Hwy 364-191, entrance is on left-hand side. From West: drive 5 miles east on Hwy 191, drive over bridge, turn immediately to right after the bridge. We share entrance road with the Mormon Church (landmark).

name: Hulls Cove Visitor Center
description: Located close to Bar Harbor off Route 3, the Hulls Cove Visitor Center is Acadia’s main visitor contact station and transportation hub from May into October. It is a popular, and often crowded, first stop for many visitors. It is adjacent to an entrance for the park's iconic 27-mile Park Loop Road and it serves as a key stop for several routes on the fare-free Island Explorer bus system. From a large parking lot, visitors must climb 52 steps to the main entrance. There is a separate accessible entrance.

name: Human History Museum
description: Indoor exhibits focus in the human history of Zion National Park. A 22-minute orientation film highlights the dramatic landscapes of the park and examines the history of the canyon. Rotating art exhibits feature regional artists. Visit the bookstore for maps, book, and gifts. There are dramatic views of the Towers of the Virgin and Bridge Mountain outside.
audioDescription: Located 1 mile from the South Entrance. Reserved parking spaces are available with a ramp leading to the building. The Human History Museum is temporarily closed due to the COVID-19 Pandemic.

name: Humpback Rocks Visitor Center
description: Travelers heading south from the northern end of the Parkway experience a scenic drive through an Appalachian hardwood forest with ridge top views of the Shenandoah Valley to the west and Rockfish Valley to the east. The rock outcroppings on the mountain and the relocated collection of 1890s farm buildings where settlers scratched out a living in the rocky soil makes Humpback Rocks perhaps the best representation of the varied combination of natural and cultural features anywhere along the Parkway corridor.

name: Illinois Valley Visitor Center
description: The center provides information about the area, including up to the moment cave tour information at the Oregon Caves National Monument. Same day tickets for cave tours are available at the center Memorial Day Weekend through Labor Day. Afternoon wait times can be long in the summer. Buying tickets before driving to the park can save a lot of time and hassle. (Reservations can be bought up to one day in advance of the day of visit on Recreation.gov.)

name: Independence Visitor Center
description: The Independence Visitor Center is located at 6th and Market Streets. Pick up a park map, plan your visit, and watch films in the Independence Visitor Center. Ask knowledgeable park rangers about programs, walking tours and special events. City concierge staff will gladly assist you with information about lodgings and restaurants.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is a two-story, narrow modern building that stretches north-south almost the length of a city block running along North 6th street, between Arch and Market Streets. The rest of the block on its east side is green lawn and trees, part of an open park that stretches two blocks between Arch and Chestnut Streets with the National Constitution Center on the north and Independence Hall on the south. The main entrance is on the south end of the building. In the center of the building there are two sets of double glass doors with two wide steps in front and a long ramp on the left. The peaked roof extends out over the entrance. There is a balcony on the second floor with metal lettering across the front that reads Independence Visitor Center. On the other side of the ramp is a one-story wing that extends out towards the street. On the front of the extension are tall, darkened, glass panels with words from the Declaration of Independence etched on them. Metal lettering across the front of the wing also reads Independence Visitor Center. As you enter the front doors you are facing a long hall with a polished floor sloping upward away from you. A gift shop is on the left and restrooms are to the right. At the top of the slope are two areas that show films. The park theater is tucked back to the left while an open area just off the hall shows a tourist information film. Just past the theaters on the left is a small exhibit area that includes tactile models of Independence Hall and the Liberty Bell and the park information desk. On the right is a Philadelphia tourist information desk. Another set of entrance doors is on the right just before the tourist information desk. At the far north end of the building on the right is a small café with a seating area and water bottle filling station. There are more double glass doors at the end of the building, forming the North Entrance. End of Description.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are many passport stamps for Independence National Historical Park. Most of the stamps are located at the park ranger information desk inside the Independence Visitor Center. Other stamps are located at the Independence Square Museum Shop inside Old City Hall.

name: Indiana Dunes Visitor Center (Dorothy Buell Memorial Visitor Center)
description: View lobby displays and pick up brochures about Porter County, Indiana, Dunes State Park, and Indiana Dunes National Park. Enjoy educational displays and watch two short orientation videos. Shop in the Eastern National bookstore. The visitor center is open everyday with the exception of Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day.
audioDescription: The main entrance to the Indiana Dunes Visitor Center is made from concrete, red brick, glass doors, and green metal. Walking through the first set of doors least to an entryway with some pamphlets about the local area. Continuing through a second set of doors leads to the main gallery. A welcome desk is on the left side of the room. In the rear center is the gift shop. Along the middle and right of the room are brochures about the park and local communities. The theater room is along the wall in the back right. The exhibit room and restrooms are down the hallway on the far right.
passportStampLocationDescription: The stamp is circular in shape. It is made of orange ink. The inside of the circle, at the top, are the words Indiana Dunes National Park. The bottom inside of the circle has the words Porter, IN. There is no date with this stamp.

name: Information Center
description: Find basic information about the memorial as well as information about the local area. Opens at 8:00 am daily (closed December 25th). Closes at 6:00 pm October 1 through November 5, 5:00 pm November 6 through late May, 10:00 pm June through mid-August, and 9:00 pm mid-August through September 30.
audioDescription: The Information Center is a concrete and granite building located near the parking facility. Outside a sign reads Welcome to Mount Rushmore and displays information about the day's activities. Inside the building is an information desk with park rangers available to answer questions, give directions and provide information about Mount Rushmore and the surrounding area. The Annual Pass - Military, Access Pass and Every Kid Outdoors Pass can be acquired here for eligible visitors. Wheelchairs are available to check out for free. Mount Rushmore brochures and newspapers are available here as well. A large map of the Black Hills on the wall behind the information desk helps visitors orient themselves and find nearby attractions. A large map of the Mount Rushmore grounds on an adjacent wall helps visitors find their way to the other buildings and trails on the property. This building also has a water fountain with a bottle fill station. A Mount Rushmore Bookstore offers educational materials, puzzles, games and post cards for purchase.
passportStampLocationDescription: Located in the middle of the information desk.

description: The Birmingham Civil Rights National Monument interim visitor center is located at the The Birmingham Civil Rights Institute (BCRI). audioDescription: Freedom Riders National Monument is a new national park unit located in Anniston, Alabama. It is a park in progress with limited services. The park's temporary visitor center is located inside the Calhoun County Area Chamber and Visitors Center. Park brochures, information and information on Anniston's Civil Rights Trail can be found here.

name: Island Ford Visitor Center
description: The Island Ford Visitor Center is located in the historic Hewlett Lodge. Here you will be able to purchase your Annual Park Pass as well as any of the passes in the America The Beautiful series. While there pick up maps, obtain the latest information on the park, or pick up a souvenir from the Eastern National store.
audioDescription: (This description is in progress.) The Hewlett Lodge was built in the 1930s in the Adirondack style of architecture. You enter the lodge through a 10' by 10' vestibule and into the lobby/visitor center. Directly in front of you is a large stone fireplace with a painting of the river with the quote "The river runs not past, but through us." by John Muir. The visitor center contains a number of interpretive exhibits. Turning to your left along the front wall are 4 windows with two exhibits below the windows, the first entitled "More than a Line on a Map" Introductory text: "Without a boat or a bridge, how can you cross the river? The wide, rocky Chattahoochee was hard to cross on foot or horseback. It formed a natural boundary line in Georgia history. Take a look:" 1813 map of Georgia with the following caption. "An 1813 map shows the "Chatta Uchee" River as the southwestern border of the state of Georgia. Creek and Cherokee Indian tribes hold all land between the Okmulgee (Ocmulgee) and the Chatta Uchee rivers. Notice that Fulton, DeKalb, Cobb, and Gwinnett counties do not yet exist." credit: Courtesy of Hargrett Library, University of Georgia 1831 map of Georgia with the following caption. "Can you find the Cherokee Nation on this 1831 map? Hint: Look north of the Chattahoochee River. Both Creeks and Cherokee were forced from their ancestral lands in Georgia as a result of the Indian Removal Act of 1830. The tribes' departure cleared the way for white settlers north of the river. The river still forms the boundaries for parts of Fulton, Cobb, and Gwinnett counties today." credit: Courtesy of Hargrett Library, University of Georgia The the second exhibit is entitled "How to Live along the River" Introductory text: "In modern life, it's easy to forget your river. You turn on a kitchen faucet, flip a light switch - and never think of the river flowing through these everyday acts. You paddle, fish, or swim for recreation, with the river as your escape. Old stone structures on the water tell us how generations of people before us lived and worked along this fast-flowing river. As you explore the park, try to imagine how earlier generations felt about the river." Photograph of the river mid stream with the following caption. "Fish weirs are stone or wooden walls built into a stream. The walls funnel the fish into a small area so they are easier to catch. Traces of ancient weirs tell us that people have fished this part of the Chattahoochee River for millennia" credit: Fishing Weir in the Chattahoochee River Courtesy of Alan Cressler Photograph of dam and building with the following caption. "Marietta Paper Company - Sope Creek Plant Back in in 1859, a trip to the river might have meant a trip to work. The Marietta Paper Company employed dozens of workers in a paper mill along Sope Creek, a half-mile upstream from the Chattahoochee River. Union troops burned the mill during the Civil War - because it is thought to have made paper for thousands of dollars of Confederate money. The Sope Creek mill was rebuilt in 1868 and operated until 1902. Today, only the stone walls remain.: credit: Courtesy of Georgia Archives, Vanishing Georgia Collection, Cob516 Sample of Confederate $20 bill Sketch of mill with the following caption. "Lebanon Flour Mill Turn the corner and on the wall is a large photograph of over 40 people on a wooden raft. In the lower right corner of the photograph is the following text. " Take a minute and listen. When you walk a trail along the Chattahoochee River, your footsteps echo the footfalls of countless travelers from long ago. Can you hear them? For centuries, well-worn trails across the hilly Georgia Piedmont have led down to this restless river. Even today, almost every major road in this area tells us something about our historical and ancient connections to the ceaseless Chattahoochee. Lift the panels to uncover stories from the past along your daily route to work or school." Below the photograph are four panels with a photograph on the cover. Lift the panel and read the description of the photo. Panel 1: Photograph of people on a wooden ferry. Description: "Ferries Until about 1880, a ferry was the only way to cross the Chattahoochee, and you still might get wet. Ferry fare ranged rom 25 cents for a one-horse, two-wheeled, open carriage to 62 cents for a fully loaded wagon. Each of these "ferry" roads tell its own unique story along river. • McGinnis Ferry Road • Nesbit Ferry Road • Johnson Ferry Road • Powers Ferry Road • Paces Ferry Road photo credit: Courtesy of Georgia Archives, Vanishing Georgia Collection, Cob603

name: Island in the Sky Visitor Center
description: Visitor center normally offers: exhibits, book & map sales, backcountry permits, general information, vault toilets, and park rangers on duty. You can get drinking water inside (during open hours) or outside (24 hours a day).
audioDescription: The Island in the Sky Visitor Center is a low-profile building in an amazing location. To its north, a flat grassland extends to low lying cliffs and a towering mound of sandstone dominates the horizon. Looking west from this sandstone butte, the mix of grassland and low lying cliffs extends for miles until reaching the San Rafael Swell, a range of sandstone abutments. Directly behind the visitor center to its west and south, a small hill dotted with short Utah juniper and pinyon pine trees buts against the building. Across from the visitor center, to the east, the landscape drops away dramatically into a canyon two thousand feet deep. The canyon is wide enough to fit towering buttes and ever deepening canyons, yet the river that carved it is not visible. Every rock within the canyon is a deep, earthy red. Beyond the canyon rim in the distance, the La Sal Mountains ascend to over twelve thousand feet above sea level, twice as high as you now are. The building is situated to the west of a north-south roadway with a large parking lot in between the two. Directly north of the building is a line of pit toilets next to a flag pole, and beyond that four picnic tables, covered by wooden shade structures, extend into the grassland. Extending directly from the building’s front doors is a red concrete pathway, to either side of this, a mass of blue-grey desert shrubbery blocks much of the view of the visitor center from the road. The front of the building is dominated by a covered patio. Benches line the walls below a couple of large windows. North of the front doors, the patio is bare, left open as a space for educational programs. To the south, a couple of billboards provide basic information about the park and the patio extends beyond and around the building to a water spigot and another set of covered picnic tables. Inside the visitor center, a scale model of the canyons outside and further into the park sits near the front doors, slightly to the right. Signs surrounding this model briefly describe the different districts of this large park. Beyond this, a gift shop takes up the northern half of the visitor center’s interior. Columnar shelves are scattered about the floor while the northmost wall is covered in bookshelves and shirts for sale. A small dividing wall with a glass representation of an arch extends into the gift shop’s space. Upon this small dividing wall if a water fountain. The wall opposite the front doors, the western wall, is lined by a row of desks covered in maps and information used by the rangers behind to help plan trips to the park. The southern half of the visitor center’s hall holds an informational exhibit space, detailing the geology, history and ecology of the park. A doorway on the western wall of this space leads into a theater, where rows of benches sit in front of a big screen tv that shows the park film. White walls and dark brown floors define the sides of this large but full space.

name: Islesford Historical Museum
description: The Islesford Historical Museum is expected to reopen in 2021 showcasing both the upgrades and a community-curated exhibit helping to tell the stories of the Cranberry Isles.
audioDescription: A one-story brick building in Colonial-Revival structure with brick walls, hipped slate roof, and three oversized brick chimneys. It is along the shoreline of Little Cranberry Island.

name: Jackson Death Site
description: Confederate General Thomas "Stonewall" Jackson died in the farm office building of the Fairfield Plantation. Today, that office building is all that remains of the former slave plantation situated near the critical transportation hub of Guinea Station. The Jackson Death Site grounds are open every day, sunrise to sunset but the building is open seasonally.
audioDescription: From the parking lot, there is a paved sidewalk leading to a white office building. The building is a one-and-a-half-story, square, frame structure clad in white weatherboard siding and with little ornamentation. A cobblestone path leads from the parking area to the porch.

name: Jacksonville State University Little River Canyon Center
description: The Jacksonville State University Little River Canyon Center is located adjacent to Little River Canyon National Preserve. National Park Service staff and Volunteers and Jacksonville State University staff will greet you and help you plan your visit. Amenities include: Information desk, restrooms, movie, gift shop, trails, and picnic tables. Hours are 10 AM - 4 PM Central Standard Time. Closed Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Years Day.
audioDescription: The Jacksonville State University Little River Canyon Center is a large building with rock facia surrounded by green lawns and a mixed forest of conifers and deciduous trees. The main room of the Little River Canyon Center features a high ceiling and large windows, with a predominantly red and blue tile floor with green, white, and orange decoratively arranged. The main room features couches and chairs in the center, the information desk immediately to the right, and the gift shop immediately to the left. There are doors on the sides and back of the room - the door on the left leads to a large room available for rent for events, the door on the right leads to the theater, and the doors at the back lead to the back deck, lawn, a large covered raised stage, and the trailheads for the Path to Learning and the Bridge Trail. There are also two hallways off the main room. The hallway on the right leads to the restrooms, water fountain, two rooms available for rent for events and meetings, classrooms, and Jacksonville State University staff offices. The hallway on the left leads to National Park Service staff offices (no services available).
passportStampLocationDescription: Visitors to Little River Canyon National Preserve can get their Little River Canyon National Preserve and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail NPS Passport cancellation stamps at the Jacksonville State University Little River Canyon Center.

GPS units and apps may not recognize the 4322 Little River Trail NE Ste 100 address - please try the 432 Little River Trail address in your GPS.
