name: Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge Visitor Center
description: The Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge Visitor Center is the gateway to this 900-acre preserve, home to salt marshes, uplands, open bay and beach areas, and two man-made ponds, all supporting hundreds of species of plant and wildlife. The one story, flat-roofed building contains a ranger desk, colorful exhibits on the eco-system of the surrounding area, a classroom, a bookstore, wheelchair accessible bathrooms, water fountains, and tactile, hands-on nature exhibits.
audioDescription: Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge Center 940 words; Length: 3:26 The Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge Visitor Center is the gateway to this 900-acre preserve, home to salt marshes, uplands, open bay and beach areas, and two man-made ponds, all supporting hundreds of species of plant and wildlife. The one story, flat-roofed building contains a ranger desk, colorful exhibits on the eco-system of the surrounding area, a classroom, a book store, wheelchair accessible bathrooms, water fountains, and tactile, hands-on nature exhibits. The building is L-shaped, with one wing extending twenty-four feet towards the parking lot on the south side of the building. At the back of the building there is a garden of native plants found in the preserve, as well as the trailhead for the West Pond trail.You approach the building from the west side of the parking lot using one of two eight-foot wide concrete walks. The walkways have two-foot high solar lights on the side. The building sits back on a square concrete apron, twenty-four feet wide by twenty-four feet deep. There is a slatted bench on the right side of the platform and a garbage can just beyond. On the opposite side of the platform, a glass encased, weathered wood housing holds a bulletin board with information on the area. Over the entry doors there is a weathered wood overhang at roof level with "Jamaica Bay Wildlife Refuge" in raised gold metal letters. Solar panels sit at a 45-degree angle on a raised roof extension on the north side of the building. There is a women's room just to the right of the main entrance. A gravel path on the right leads around the building with a split rail fence on the right protecting the natural vegetation area. A sign issuing a warning about deer ticks hangs from the fence. The men's room is on the left of the path at the rear of the building, as well as a raised wooden apron leading to the rear entrance to the main room of the building.The trail head for the West Pond Trail is found at the rear of the building on the right hand side of the gravel walkway. There is a long trail and a short trail. You reach the trail head for the long trail first. The trailhead for the short trail is just to the left. If you continue along the rear path, you come to a phenology garden on the left. This garden has samples of different types of plants that can be found in the wildlife refuge. All of the plants are identified with markers. You enter the Visitor Center through the glass double doors into a trapezoidal-shaped foyer, about twelve feet deep and twenty feet wide at the widest point. The foyer has brown brick walls on the north and south sides. The bricks are set vertically and the walls are hung with floor-to-ceiling photographs of flora and fauna in the preserve. On the left, there is a photograph of a salt marsh with green marsh grass and mud flats. Hanging beside it is a photograph of a tree in early autumn, with leaves just beginning to turn bright red. On the right hand wall, there is a photograph of a small duck* sitting on a narrow rock in the water. Beside it hangs a close up shot of leaves just beginning to turn from green to orange and brown tones.Another set of wide, glass double doors framed in light brown wood open into the main room of the Visitor Center. The flat-screened television behind the desk displays information about events at the Wildlife Refuge as well as still photographs of the wildlife and plants in the area. Displays hang on the wall giving the history of the Jamaica Bay area, ecological information, and information on the National Park Service and parks throughout the United States. The room is approximately forty feet deep by twenty-four feet wide with twelve-foot high ceilings. The ranger station, a semi-circular, light wood desk about fifteen feet in diameter, is on the left. The light yellow walls and polished light wood floors combined with the floor-to-ceiling windows at the back wall give an open feeling to the space. Towards the back of the main room, there is a three-foot high, square, glass-topped display case with a map of the area entitled "Jamaica Bay, Above, Below, and All Around". On the four sides of the six-foot by six-foot display case, there are informational displays of various aspects of Jamaica Bay: the ongoing dredging, a short historical perspective of the area, the watershed ecosystem, and the wildlife. At each corner of the case, there is a tactile exhibit of different fish, shell fish, and amphibians in the area. There are boxes below the window sills at the rear of the room containing shells of horseshoe crabs, turtles, and mollusks. There are also boxes with mushrooms, pinecones, and other botanical samples. You can pick these samples up and feel them.The bookstore is on the left at the rear of the room. It sells games, books, plush toys, and souvenirs. There are windows on three sides of the store, filling the it with light.

name: James A. Garfield National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: In 1893, Lucretia Garfield constructed a Carriage House and Horse Barn behind the Garfield Home. In 1998, the same building was opened as the Visitor Center at James A. Garfield National Historic Site. Inside visitors can find the site's 18-minute film as well exhibits in chronological order of the president's life. Check-in for tours of the Garfield home are at the Front Desk.
audioDescription: The first thing in the Visitor Center is the bookstore and front desk with a National Park Service Park Ranger. Inside the Visitor Center visitors will find exhibits and an 18-minute introductory film about President Garfield. There are 15-20 different exhibits to view ranging from James' family tree to school days to the Civil War to the Presidency and then his assassination and death. There is low lights to help preserve the collection. Four of the exhibits have audio as well as a written transcript of what is occurring.

name: Jenny Lake Ranger Station
description: In the 1930s, the Jenny Lake Ranger Station and Museum opened as the park’s first visitor facility. Today, climbing rangers provide backcountry safety information, climbing route conditions and perform mountain rescues. A small raised-relief map features the core backcountry area and other exhibits address backcountry risks. A safety video provides visitors with essential information. The ranger station issues backcountry permits to all backcountry users.
audioDescription: The ranger station is west of the Northeast parking lot. The path leading to it is paved, but there are rough spots and breaks in the asphalt. The building is a one-room log cabin, painted dark brown with dark green trim. A white-lettered sign that reads “Jenny Lake Ranger Station” hangs from the peak of the roof in front. There are three steps up to the narrow planked porch across the front of the building. The door is in the middle of the front wall, directly opposite the steps. To the left of the steps stands a small sign. It has an historic photograph of a man in park uniform hiking across a snowy stretch near a mountain summit. The caption reads, “Park Ranger Phil Smith on mountain patrol, 1930s.” The main text reads, “Mountain Rescue. In the 1930s, this rustic cabin served as the park’s first ranger station and museum. This park’s tradition of hiring skilled climbers to perform mountain rescues dates from the 1940s. Rangers still provide backcountry information here and, when necessary, rescue lost and injured hikers and climbers.” Looking away from the Ranger Station you can see the Jenny Lake Visitor Center (Crandall Studio) to the west of the General Store. A log cabin similar in construction to the Ranger Station, this building is not accessible during the 2016-2017 seasons due to construction here at Jenny Lake.
directionsInfo: Heading north from Jackson on US 26/89/191, turn left (west) at Moose Junction and continue eight miles north to South Jenny Lake Junction. Turn left (west) into the developed area. Heading south from Yellowstone on US 89/191/287, turn right (southwest) at Jackson Lake Junction and continue 12 miles south to South Jenny Lake Junction. Turn right (west) into the developed area.

name: Jenny Lake Visitor Center
description: Harrison Crandall built this cabin in 1921 near the Cathedral Group Turnout as his studio. Today, the visitor center highlights art in the park through Crandall and other artist's work. Shop the Grand Teton Association bookstore, attend a ranger program or begin your backcountry adventure. Rangers are available in the plaza and on trails for trip planning and information. The nearby Jenny Lake Ranger Station offers backcountry permits.

name: Jewel Cave National Monument - Visitor Center
description: The visitor center offers two rooms of interactive exhibits and engaging displays, featuring the surface and sub-surface resources. A large classroom area is also available for school field trips and special events, with large windows facing to the south toward Lithograph Canyon. A park store connects the classroom to the exhibits and is operated by the Black Hills Parks and Forests Association. Ask to view our award-winning film about the park. Restrooms are available at the visitor center.
audioDescription: An earth tone, brick building with dark brown, metal panels for the roof. The exterior area includes a large cement patio, with landscaped sections including wood mulch and various trees and shrubs. A sidewalk wraps around the south side of the visitor center to the trailhead for the one-quarter-mile Roof Trail. A separate building is located across the patio, which is the theater for the park film. The building displays multiple octagon-shaped rooms for exhibits, which are connected by large hallways. Upon entering the visitor center, a diorama of rock outcroppings shares interpretive panels related to the surface features of a ponderosa pine forest, open meadows, and fire-scarred landscape. An adjoining room displays dioramas of limestone rock, interspersed with crystal forms and calcite spar to represent the cave. Interpretive panels with a large map on the wall detail the geologic story of Jewel Cave and share the complexity of its mapped and surveyed passages. A long hallway extends from the exhibit rooms to the elevator lobby, where guests line up for ranger-guided cave tours. On the brick walls on each side of the hallway are six slender interpretive panels, describing other cave parks within the National Park Service. Another hallway extends from the elevator lobby to a classroom area, which provides a countertop and stools for visitor activities. A television monitor is mounted on one wall for viewing various productions or using with presentations during school field trips. And finally, the classroom connects to the park store, which displays various furnishings and shelving units. These areas offer different products for sale, such as reference books, ID guides, maps, DVDs, Junior Ranger materials, and plush animals.
passportStampLocationDescription: Jewel Cave National Monument offers multiple passport stamps for interested visitors. An official cancellation station is located inside the visitor center, with two available stamps. The first is the official cancellation stamp for passport books. The second shows a calcite crystal with the words Jewel Cave, which was hand-carved by pioneer caver Jan Conn. Additional stamps include a Junior Ranger cancellation stamp and virtual stamps found online through the monument's website.

name: Jockey Hollow Visitor Center
description: This one story brick and glass structure came to the park during the preparations for the Bicentennial. Inside, visitors will find an information desk, bookstore, a painted mural depicting Jockey Hollow during the 1779 encampment, and a full scale replica of the log huts Continental Soldiers lived in. Guided tours of the nearby Wick Farm House usually begin here. The restrooms can be accessed from the exterior doors, and remain open after the visitor center closes.
audioDescription: A low one-story structure made of brown and red vertical bricks with plate glass windows. One side of the building containing the restrooms and bookstore is arranged in a circle, while the other side slowly blends into the nearby hillside. A pathway between the parking lot and the nearby Wick Farm goes up to the doors of the visitor center, then arcs around toward the restrooms before continuing around the other side. A sign: "Jockey Hollow Visitor Center" is located above the door facing the parking lot, with the National Park Service Arrowhead logo next to it. A trail guide map is fastened to the wall outside of this doorway. Inside, the bookstore, information desk, and exhibits can be seen through the glass.

name: John K. and Ruth Hulston Civil War Research Library
description: The Research Library is housed in the Visitor Center and is non-circulating collection. The Research Library focuses on the Civil War with an emphasis on the Trans-Mississippi theater of war, Missouri, and the Battle of Wilson’s Creek. The collection includes approximately 15,000 books and other items, such as regimental histories for many Civil War units, as well as a list of casualties for the Battle of Wilson’s Creek. Staff members can perform limited research for patrons by mail, e-mail, or phone.

name: Johnstown Flood National Memorial Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center has two floors of displays that explain the history of the South Fork Dam, the South Fork Fishing & Hunting Club, and how and why the 1889 Johnstown Flood occurred. There is also a 35 minute film,"Black Friday," shown every :15 past the hour, with the first showing of the day at 9:15 and the last showing at 4:15.

name: Joshua Tree National Park Visitor Center
description: The Joshua Tree National Park Visitor Center is located in downtown Twentynine Palms and features educational exhibits, a bookstore and giftshop, and visitor information.
audioDescription: The Joshua Tree National Park Visitor Center is located south of highway 62, by about half a block on Freedom Way. The building is surrounded by parking spaces and walkways on all sides. The visitor center is in the middle of the town of Twentynine Palms. There are other buildings in sight as well as sparse desert vegetation. To the south the mountains in the north boundary of Joshua Tree National Park can be seen. The visitor center itself is a dark tan, single-story building. There is a flag pole and shade structure near the front of the building facing highway 62. The parking spaces on the northside of the building are the closest to the front door and there are a few handicap parking spaces. There is a sidewalk surrounding the building.

name: Joshua Tree Visitor Center
description: The first stop for park visitors headed towards the West Entrance. Located in the village of Joshua Tree on Park Blvd. just south of Hwy 62. Exhibits, bookstore, cafe, flush toilets onsite; public telephone and showers nearby.
audioDescription: Joshua Tree Visitor Center is located outside the park in the village of Joshua Tree, population 8,000. It is five miles north of the West Entrance on Park Boulevard close to where Park Boulevard and Highway 62 intersect. From the intersection, heading south on Park Boulevard, the visitor center is on the right. The gravel parking lot, just south of the visitor center, can comfortably fit 40 cars. There is a curved cinder block wall that divides the parking lot from the visitor center. From the parking lot, there is a cement sidewalk leading a short distance through a modest cactus garden and ends at a small cement courtyard in front of the visitor center on the east side of the building. In the garden stands a flagpole and a rusted metal sculpture. The exterior of the single-story visitor center has walls that resemble corrugated metal. From the courtyard, another short cement sidewalk leads through a large wooden gate into an outdoor patio between the cinder block wall and the south side of the building. The patio is enclosed on its south end by the previously mentioned cinder block wall. Inside the patio, the ground is dirt and slopes down from the cinder block wall towards the double glass doors that lead into the visitor center. Two tables are on the patio near the doors where rangers can help visitors with information. Once entering the building, there is a one-room exhibit area with panels depicting geology, ecology, and history of Joshua Tree National Park. There is a life-sized replica of a Joshua tree accompanied with panels about the Joshua tree. There is a guitar and a U2 record album on display that represents the creative aspects of Joshua Tree National Park. There is a television that plays a 2-minute video about the park’s geology. The exhibit opens into the one-room bookstore. On display are souvenirs—stickers, patches, t-shirts, hats, stuffed animals, mugs, postcards, and books. On the side of the bookstore closest to the exhibit is a counter with three cash registers. Opposite the counter, on the north side, are two doors that open directly into the men’s and women’s bathrooms. Exit through the bookstore's double glass doors back to the courtyard on the east side of the visitor center. The northernmost section of the building, with a single glass door that opens out into the courtyard, is a cafe.

name: Kabetogama Lake Visitor Center
description: The Kabetogama Lake Visitor Center is open during our summer season from late May to late September. Kabetogama Visitor Center will be closed annually over the winter season. Nestled along the south west shoreline of Kabetogama Lake, within the community of Kabetogama. The Kabetogama Lake Visitor Center is open during the warm, summer months only from late May through late September.
audioDescription: 3 parking spots and 1 handicap parking spot is located directly in front of the Kabetogama Visitor Center. There is a bulletin board outside on the right side that has a large map of the park as well as a brochure rack. Once inside the building there is a bookstore located on the left side. Right after the bookstore is the front desk where a ranger is located at. Across the from the front desk on the right side of the building is a large map that lights up the campsites and visitor destinations within the park. After the front desk the room opens up to an exhibit area.
passportStampLocationDescription: A passport stamp is located inside the visitor center. There is also a passport stamp located on the bulletin board in front of the visitor center that can be accessed at all hours.

name: Kalaloch Ranger Station
description: Kalaloch Ranger Station is open daily during the summer and closed the rest of the year. Educational exhibits, informational brochures, a small sales area, and restrooms are available.
audioDescription: Kalaloch Ranger Station. 2 minutes A brown and white wooden sign along the road reads, Kalaloch Ranger Station. The National Park Service arrowhead logo is attached to the sign. The single story rectangular gray wooden building with a gray metal roof faces the parking lot. A brown sign with white text is attached to the front of the building on the right and reads, Information. Beneath this is the National Park Service arrowhead logo. The recessed entryway is between the sign and arrowhead on the right and a large window on the left. The blue front door with a large window is at the right edge of the recessed section. To the left, a sign hangs on the wall with either the word Open or Closed, and below, a box on the wall holds park brochures and other information. In the left corner of the recessed entryway atop a round wooden pedestal is a white whale skull which you may touch. An interpretive panel behind the skull reads, A Whale of a Trip. In one of the longest known annual migrations of any mammal, gray whales travel over 10,000 miles roundtrip between their Baja winter breeding grounds and Arctic summer feeding grounds. A few hundred whales shorten this migration and summer in shallow coastal waters in the Pacific Northwest. March through may are prime times to view spouting gray whales off the Olympic coast. A whale can weigh 20 to 35 tons and reach 45 feet in length, bigger than a school bus. In a lifetime, a gray whale can swim farther than the distance to the moon and back. Inside the Ranger Station are restrooms, an information desk, and a small bookstore.
directionsInfo: Kalaloch Ranger Station is located 36 miles south of Forks off of Highway 101.

name: Keller Interpretive Center, Abingdon Muster Ground
description: The Keller Interpretive Center at the Abingdon Muster Ground features displays and exhibits about southwest Virginia during the American Revolution, including the 400 Virginia patriots who left this spot on September 24, 1780 to join with fellow patriots at Sycamore Shoals and begin their march to the Battle of Kings Mountain. Seasonally available information, gift store, and all-year hiking trail on the Wolf Creek Trail.

name: Kelso Depot Visitor Center
description: Originally opened in 1924 as a train station, Kelso Depot was renovated and reopened in 2005 a Visitor Center for Mojave National Preserve. Former dormitory rooms contain exhibits describing the cultural and natural history of the surrounding desert. The baggage room, ticket office and two dormitory rooms have been furnished to illustrate depot life during the first half of the twentieth century. A 20-minute orientation film is shown in the theater. Note: Kelso Depot is currently closed for repairs.
passportStampLocationDescription: Contact us to get this stamp sent to you, or stop by the Hole-In-The-Wall Visitor Center. Virtual stamps available online at https://www.nps.gov/moja/planyourvisit/mojave-passport-stamps.htm

name: Kenai Fjords National Park Visitor Center
description: The main park visitor center is located in the Seward small boat harbor and is open daily during the summer season. The visitor center is closed during the winter months. The visitor center provides opportunities to view the park film, an Alaska Geographic bookstore, and park rangers to help answer questions about the area.

name: Kennesaw Mountain National Battlefield Park Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center at Kennesaw Mountain is located at 900 Kennesaw Mountain Dr. and is open Monday - Sunday, 9:00 am - 5:00 pm except on major holidays (Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Years).
audioDescription: The Visitor Center at Kennesaw Mountain National Battlefield Park sits at the base of Big Kennesaw Mountain. On the north side of the Visitor Center is the park's largest memorial field, and one of the more scenic views of the building, with Kennesaw Mountain in the background. The main entrance to the building is on the western side, off of the main parking lot. The first thing that visitors are greeted with from the parking lot is the standard flag pole flying the American flag, which signifies that the building is open. After a short set of stairs, you come to the front patio. A large, bronze cannon, green with age and patina stands directly in the front of the main doors. While this cannon's origins are unknown, the age is confirmed to be of Civil War era. Immediately upon entering the building, you are in the front vestibule. In this area, you are able to access the restrooms, or grab a set of maps/brochures. Continuing through the vestibule you enter the main room of the visitor center. To the immediate left is a doorway leading out to the back patio, with a view of the large memorial field. At each corner of the patio are two cannons (one on each corner). The one on the left is a slim, black iron gun known as a 3" Ordinance Rifle. The one on the right is a green patina'd bronze cannon known as a 12lb Napolean. Going back into the visitor center from the patio, you see the semi-circular front desk. The front desk is where you can purchase a park pass, souvenir, or chat with a ranger or volunteer. Continuing past the front desk, you enter the bookstore section. This bookstore is managed by America's National Parks, and sells everything from souvenirs and historical books, to cold drinks and refreshments. If you take a right past the front desk and head past the bookstore (now on your left), you will come to the park's auditorium. This is where, during normal operations, the park's film plays, on a loop, once an hour from 9 am to 5 pm. If you were to go straight past the front desk (the bookstore now on your right), you will run into the park's museum. Immediately in front of the museum , on the wall, is a large timeline depicting major events in Civil War history, spanning from 1860 - 1861. Upon entering the museum, the exhibits and information chronologically start at the beginning of the Atlanta Campaign, in the summer of 1864. The museum is designed to take you through that pivotal year, with exhibits, artifacts, timelines, and informational diagrams. After winding your way clockwise through the museum, you will exit at the rear of the bookstore.
passportStampLocationDescription: Kennesaw Mountain NBP currently has 3 passport stamps. The standard one will have the current date on it, as well as the location and name of the park (Kennesaw Mountain NBP, Kennesaw, GA) Our graphic stamp is an inset picture of a cannon in the foreground with the silhouette of Big Kennesaw and Little Kennesaw Mountain in the background.. The final stamp is our Jr. Ranger Stamp. It is in the shape of a ranger badge with a large 'flat hat' graphic in the middle. The text at top reads 'Junior Ranger'

name: Kenneth C. Patrick Visitor Center
description: Located at beautiful Drakes Beach, the Kenneth C. Patrick Visitor Center contains exhibits that focus on maritime exploration in the 1500s, marine fossils, and marine environments. A minke whale skeleton is suspended from the ceiling. Allow 20–30 minutes to view exhibits. Park- and ocean-themed books, guides, and postcards, and maps, along with coffee and packaged snacks are for sale in the PRNSA bookstore adjacent to the Kenneth C. Patrick Visitor Center.
audioDescription: The Kenneth C. Patrick Visitor Center is located within the western arm of a large one-story, elevated building made of wood adjacent to Drakes Beach. A bookstore and restrooms are also part of this building. A large parking lot is located to the visitor center’s west. To both the east and west of the parking lot and visitor center complex, the land rises steeply to over 80 feet (25 meters) in height and then plateaus. Coastal grasslands and coastal scrub cover the land. To the south of the parking lot is a sandy beach, beyond which is Drakes Bay. Within the visitor center is an information desk and exhibits that focus on 1500s maritime exploration, marine fossils, and marine environments. A minke whale skeleton is suspended from the ceiling in the center of the exhibits.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Point Reyes National Seashore passport stamp is available at the Kenneth C. Patrick Visitor Center's information desk when the visitor center is open. If the visitor center is closed but the adjacent Point Reyes National Seashore Association's bookstore is open, the passport stamp is available inside the bookstore. If both are closed (i.e., you are visiting on a weekday), the passport stamp is also available at the Bear Valley Visitor Center. Check operating hours to know when to arrive.

directionsInfo: From the Bear Valley Visitor Center, head north 0.2 miles (0.3 km) to Bear Valley Rd. Turn left and follow Bear Valley Rd. 1.75 miles (2.8 km) northwest to Sir Francis Drake Blvd. Turn left and follow Sir Francis Drake Blvd. 13.4 miles (21.4 km) west to Drakes Beach Rd. Tip: Follow road signs for “Lighthouse” until you see a sign for Drakes Beach. Turn left and follow Drakes Beach Rd. 1.6 miles (2.6 km) south to the Drakes Beach parking lot. Allow 30 minutes for the drive from Bear Valley.

name: King Salmon Visitor Center
description: Located next door to the King Salmon Airport, the King Salmon Visitor Center provides information on the many federal public lands of Southwest Alaska, particularly those in the Bristol Bay area. A large collection of films is available for viewing and an Alaska Geographic bookstore sells maps, charts, videos, posters, clothing and more.

name: King Salmon Visitor Center
description: Located next door to the King Salmon Airport, the King Salmon Visitor Center provides information on the many federal public lands of Southwest Alaska, particularly those in the Bristol Bay area. A large collection of films is available for viewing and an Alaska Geographic bookstore sells maps, charts, videos, posters, clothing and more.

name: Kings Canyon Visitor Center
description: This visitor center is in Grant Grove Village at an elevation of 6,500 feet (1,980 m). Learn about three regions in Kings Canyon National Park: giant sequoia groves, Kings Canyon, and the High Sierra. Watch a 15-minute movie (English/Spanish). A park store sells books, maps, and educational materials.
audioDescription: Kings Canyon Visitor Center is a single story wooden building with a peaked roof, made of corrugated metal. The building has brown, planked wood siding with bulletin boards and windows. The roof extends over the entrance door, supported by thick wooden beams and posts. The lobby and double entrance doors are glass and open outward. On the wall, adjacent to the entrance, metal lettering mounted on the building reads, “Visitor Center”. Below it is the National Park Service logo, in the shape of an orange arrowhead, pointed downward. Inside the arrowhead are the words in white lettering, “National Park Service” with a green sequoia tree shape to its left. Near the bottom of the arrowhead is a white buffalo silhouette set against a green meadow, with a white lake and snowcapped mountain behind it. A tall flagpole is on the right side of the visitor center. Along the building, to the left of the entrance, is a walkway under the eaves, where the restrooms, water fountain, and bulletin boards are located. A square framed wooden planter in front of the restrooms provides low seating around the native shrubs planted inside.

name: Kings Mountain National Military Park
description: The visitor center has a movie, a bookstore operated by America's National Parks, and a museum. The museum has artifacts from the battle and audio exhibits inside walk-in trees that resemble the 1780 battlefield.
audioDescription: Kings Mountain National Military Park is a very wooded park with rolling hills. As you enter the parking lot, the visitor center can be seen sitting atop a slight rise surrounded by loblolly pine, eastern red cedar, yellow poplar (tulip), red maple, scarlet oak, dogwood, and sweetgum trees. One leaves the parking area and approaches the Kings Mountain NMP Visitor Center (VC) on an 8-foot-wide stone pathway. It passes by the flagpole which stands on a low 2-stepped pedestal, all bordered by a low stone wall. To the right of the pathway is a large open lawn lined with trees and several shaded benches. The pathway is slightly inclined toward the VC entrance which is located under a breezeway. The paving color varies from grays to browns. The VC is a large gable roofed structure of moderate pitch, with its ridgeline running from right to left, and gives one the impression of three distinct areas or sections. The left portion of the brown raised seam metal roofline also juts upwards noticeably with large clearstory windows on each end admitting light. This raised roofline portion covers a larger area of the building that extends to the front some distance giving the entire building an “L” shaped footprint. This forward projected area contains the movie theater. The VC’s outer walls are mostly stone, made of “Winnsboro” granite, a light blue gray granite mined locally in the state. Every stone is sized irregularly but all a rectangular or squarish shape. The mortar is a very light color. The middle section of the building’s walls are primarily floor-to-ceiling glass. The right end of the VC consists of a separate stone/wood walled structure that contains the restrooms. It’s under the same roofline but is separated from the main Visitor Center area by a breezeway which has ceiling fans and a wide slate bench opposite the restrooms. One can continue through the breezeway to a patio area behind the building. The pathway stonework is continuous through the breezeway and to the beginning of the Battlefield loop trail. Also, under the breezeway are the Main VC entrance doors. The middle section of the VC houses the gift shop, which is bathed in natural light, courtesy of the floor-to-ceiling windows. Small skylights add even more light to the room which is about 25 x 50 feet in size. As you enter the Visitor Center, sits a large “L” shaped interpretive counter to the right of the entrance doorway. Most eye-catching are the three colonial gentlemen to the left. First is a Militia man dressed in a linen flock coat, breeches, and a tricorn hat displaying a piece of paper in the hatband to show he is a patriot. He is holding a flintlock long rifle and the accouterments of a 1700’s patriot: leather pouch, wooden canteen, tomahawk, powder horn, and shot . The second is dressed quite differently but is also a patriot. In a wool coat made from an old blanket and wearing moccasins and leggings this gentleman represents one of the Overmountain men, some of whom had traveled from what is now Tennessee tracking Patrick Ferguson, the British officer who had threatened there leaders, homes and land. Finally, the third and final gentleman is dressed in the traditional red coat, and tricorn hat of a British Officer, carrying a cartridge box, fur backpack, tin canteen and a British musket and bayonet. The front half of the room being mostly open with built-in cushioned benches along the perimeter allow visitors a place to sit and relax. The room is floored with slate of a uniform dark grayish-blue color, each stone is square or rectangular and laid in a regular repeating pattern, all mortared into place. The far half of the room is the gift shop. Only the back wall of the gift shop area is glass. The far wall is of Winnsboro granite and has a doorway that leads into the museum. The wall to the left is finished with vertical wood boards that have a rustic textured surface. Along this wall are two entrance passages that lead into the 123-seat movie theater. Looking above, one sees a light-colored tongue-and-groove pine cathedral ceiling with large beams carrying the load and providing attaching points for all the necessities of modern life such as HVAC, alarms, fire suppression, etc. Over the VC doors are more clearstory windows. A series of suspended wooden frames hold track lighting. Hanging along the wood theater wall are three paintings. Two are portraits, one of Major Patrick Ferguson, the other of William Campbell, the leaders of the opposing forces in the battle. The large center painting is a depiction of the Battle of Kings Mountain. To help the visitor orient themselves, a large topographical map table, about 7 feet square, is in the center of the room. It gives a three-dimensional depiction of the local terrain. It also depicts waterways and both 18th century and modern roadways. name: Kings Mountain National Military Park Visitor Center
description: The visitor center has a movie (25 minutes), a bookstore operated by America's National Parks, and a museum. The museum has artifacts from the battle and audio exhibits inside walk-in trees that resemble the 1780 battlefield.
audioDescription: Kings Mountain National Military Park is a very wooded park with rolling hills. As you enter the parking lot, the visitor center can be seen sitting atop a slight rise surrounded by loblolly pine, eastern red cedar, yellow poplar (tulip), red maple, scarlet oak, dogwood, and sweetgum trees. One leaves the parking area and approaches the Kings Mountain NMP Visitor Center (VC) on an 8-foot-wide stone pathway. It passes by the flagpole which stands on a low 2-stepped pedestal, all bordered by a low stone wall. To the right of the pathway is a large open lawn lined with trees and several shaded benches. The pathway is slightly inclined toward the VC entrance which is located under a breezeway. The paving color varies from grays to browns. The VC is a large gable roofed structure of moderate pitch, with its ridgeline running from right to left, and gives one the impression of three distinct areas or sections. The left portion of the brown raised seam metal roofline also juts upwards noticeably with large clearstory windows on each end admitting light. This raised roofline portion covers a larger area of the building that extends to the front some distance giving the entire building an “L” shaped footprint. This forward projected area contains the movie theater. The VC’s outer walls are mostly stone, made of “Winnsboro” granite, a light blue gray granite mined locally in the state. Every stone is sized irregularly but all a rectangular or squarish shape. The mortar is a very light color. The middle section of the building’s walls are primarily floor-to-ceiling glass. The right end of the VC consists of a separate stone/wood walled structure that contains the restrooms. It’s under the same roofline but is separated from the main Visitor Center area by a breezeway which has ceiling fans and a wide slate bench opposite the restrooms. One can continue through the breezeway to a patio area behind the building. The pathway stonework is continuous through the breezeway and to the beginning of the Battlefield loop trail. Also, under the breezeway are the Main VC entrance doors.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is a classic NPS Passport Cancellation stamps consisting of a circle, park name and date.

name: Kingsley Plantation Visitor Contact Station
description: You can explore the grounds at Kingsley Plantation, which include the slave quarters, barn, waterfront, planter's house, kitchen house, and interpretive garden. The visitor contact station/bookstore is located in a 1920s building adjacent to the plantation buildings.
audioDescription: The visitor contact station at Kingsley Plantation is hosted in a small portion of a large two story white building, formerly a 1920s clubhouse. A small wooden ramp leads you the the simple white door with a glass 4 pane window. The visitor contact station is two small rooms, one featuring a small exhibit and a sign in book, the next room hold a bookstore and a desk where rangers and volunteers stand to answer questions.
passportStampLocationDescription: This site has several cancellation stamps including Timucuan Preserve-Kingsley Plantation and a Gullah-Geechee Heritage Corridor stamp.

directionsInfo: From I-95 north of Jacksonville: Traveling from the north via Interstate 95, exit at the I-295 East Beltway (Exit #362 A). Exit at Heckscher Drive, turn left. Continue on Heckscher 9 miles. After passing the St. Johns River Ferry landing on your right, turn left 1/2 mile later at the brown National Park Service sign onto Fort George Island. Follow the signs; the road leads directly to the Kingsley Plantation parking lot. You can also reach Kingsley Plantation by boat.

name: Kittatinny Point Visitor Center
description: This visitor center is currently closed.
directionsInfo: The Kittatinny Point Visitor Center is located in New Jersey, off of I-80, and is approximately 35 miles south of I-84. To get to the Kittatinny Point Visitor Center from I-80, take exit 1 in New Jersey and follow the signs to the visitor center, which is within a half mile from the exit. From I-84, it is possible to get to the visitor center via River Road and Old Mine Road. Located in Columbia, New Jersey; GPS: 40.970202, -75.128278

name: Klondike Gold Rush National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is located in the historic White Pass & Yukon Route depot. Talk to a ranger, learn about daily programs, watch park film "Gold Fever: Race to the Klondike," and more. Restrooms, water stations, and benches are available for visitors.
passportStampLocationDescription: During the summer months the passport stamp is located on the accessible end of the visitor center desk, closest to the theater. The self-serve station includes the official cancellation stamp, the Klondike Gold Rush National Historical Park logo stamp, and paper for those who do not have a National Park Passport.

name: Knife River Indian Villages National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is located off Highway 37 just north of the city of Stanton, ND. The Visitor Center’s entrance is in the shape of a giant eagle welcoming visitors. Once inside, visitors can view the movie, tour the exhibits or shop in our bookstore. Outside and behind the Visitor Center is a reconstructed earthlodge (furnished with replica artifacts in the summer) and the beginning of one of the three trails located at the park.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a one story building approximately 50 feet wide and 50 feet length. It has a light brown stucco exterior. To the right of the front entrance door, there is a large architectural feature resembling an eagle. Immediately to the right when entering the front entrance doors is a hallway containing bathrooms. Six feet further, you will enter into the lobby proper of the building. The lobby area has a circular shape and is loosely based on the interior of a historical earthlodge. These features include four structural posts and the center floor space has a circular feature of inlaid stonework representing a firepit. The south wall of the lobby has gift items and books for sale. The east wall has a reception desk staffed by uniformed personnel. To the left of the reception desk is a door entering into a small vestibule. Turning to the left of this are doors that exit the facility towards the earthlodge and trail system. The north wall of the lobby has a large set of windows with a seating area below them. The west wall has an entrance to the museum and theater. The museum area has numerous wall panels of text and small artifact cases. Three cases contain many Native American artifacts. The theater shows a thirteen minute film featuring the cultural history of the Hidatsa tribe through the perspective of a woman known as Buffalo Bird Woman. The theater seats up to thirty people and the film is shown upon visitor request.
passportStampLocationDescription: Two cancellation stamps are available. One specific to the park and one for the Lewis & Clark National Historic Trail

name: Knob Creek Tavern Visitor Center
description: During the months of April, May, September, and October, the Knob Creek Tavern Visitor Center is open on weekends only 10:00am to 4:00pm, eastern time. Beginning on Memorial Day until Labor Day, the visitor center is open Thursday - Monday 10:00am to 4:00pm, eastern time. Inside the visitor center are exhibits and a park store.
audioDescription: Upon arrival at 7120 Bardstown Road, Hodgenville, Kentucky 42748 exit your car and head to the visitor center which ins the large building facing the parking lot. Inside the Visitor Center you can pick up park brochures and maps, shop in the park store and learn more about the park.

name: Kohm Yah-mah-nee Visitor Center
description: This year-round visitor center is located one mile from the Southwest Entrance. The visitor center offers an information desk, exhibit hall, auditorium, amphitheater (summer), park store, dining area, patio (summer), and a gift shop and cafe (summer). Free Wi-Fi is available inside.
audioDescription: This one-story, wooden building is nestled on the edge of a mountain valley lined by conifer forests and jagged mountain peaks. Most visitors enter through a large triangular overhang at the front entrance, which opens into a small 24-hour vestibule. A family, mens', and womens' restroom are located to the left. Two sets of double doors continue straight into the main building. Rangers provide information at an information desk at the right and notify visitors of the start of the 20-minute park film in the auditorium accessed through the doors to the left of the desk. In the center of the main room is a 3-D relief map of the park with buttons that indicate the four types of volcanoes in the park. To the immediate left of the map is a small, L-shaped park store. On the far side of the map is a doorway that opens to the back patio. The remainder of the rectangular building extends to the left and right of the map. The left wing of the building includes a seating indoor, fireplace, gift shop, cafe, and an exit to a service parking area. The right wing of the building includes a circular exhibit hall and an emergency exit in the far corner. The exhibit area includes an inner circle with volcanology interactive exhibits and an outer circle with text-based natural and cultural history exhibits. Within the outer circle are two smaller free-standing, cylindrical displays featuring interactive exhibits designed for young visitors.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamp is located in the park store, to the left of the relief map.

name: Kolob Canyons Visitor Center
description: This is the entry point to the Kolob Canyons area of the park. It is located 45 miles north of Springdale and 17 miles south of Cedar City at Exit 40 on Interstate 15. Park rangers are available to answer questions. Exhibits explore the geology, vegetation, and wildlife of this unique landscape.
audioDescription: The Kolob Canyons Visitor Center is located 45 miles north of Springdale and 17 miles south of Cedar City at Exit 40 on Interstate 15. Reserved parking spaces are available with accessible walkways leading to the building. Accessible unisex restroom, sales displays, water fountain, and information desk.

name: Kris Eggle Visitor Center
description: The Kris Eggle Visitor Center is a great place to start your visit at Organ Pipe Cactus. Rangers there provide orientation to the monument, answer questions, and offer suggestions on how to best enjoy your experience during your time here. Inside is an information desk with maps and guides, an exhibit area where visitors may learn about the Sonoran Desert, and a bookstore. A short nature trail starting behind the visitor center features Quitobaquito pupfish and signs about the life found in the monument.
audioDescription: Coming from the parking lot, the Kris Eggle Visitor Center is a light gray, one story building in modernist/international style. To the left of the front visitor center door is a planter box with various small cacti and one large organ pipe cactus. To the right of the visitor center door are benches and another planter that wraps around the side of the building, filled with various native cacti and shrubs. On the right corner of the visitor center is a large organ pipe cactus and a memorial stone. On the stone is a plaque commemorating Kris Eggle, a NPS law enforcement officer killed in the line of duty in 2002. Bathroom units are attached to the northern side of the visitor center. When you enter the Visitor Center, there is a ranger desk and cash register to the right. On the left side is the Western National Parks Association Store with several standing shelves and shelves covering the walls. A large topography map of the park stands alone. Deeper into the visitor center is a large auditorium where rangers will play the park film, and the exhibit hall. The exhibit hall is divided by the seasons starting with dry summers, wet monsoon summers, fall, winter and spring. Each section has a visual and descriptive display, plus a tactile exhibit associated with that season. For instance, in the spring exhibit features the many wildflowers that bloom during this season and there is a 'smell exhibit' where visitors can smell different iconic scents of the desert. The winter section talks about the various activities that the native people, the Tohono O'odham, engage in during the winter. There are examples of baskets and a mortero and pestle (grinding stone and grinding 'bowl.'). The fall section talks about the ranching history of the park and includes examples of cattle brands used by some of the local ranchers. The monsoon/wet summer section has a light-up magnifying glass that gives visitors a closer look at a moth, scorpion, and wildlife scat, and describes the desert life and greenery that emerges following the monsoon storms. The dry summer exhibit describes some of the wildlife of Organ Pipe Cactus National Monument, particularly the Gila Monster. There are three tactile circles that allows you to "feel" the skin of a Gila monster, see what Gila monster eggs look like, and hear the sound of cicadas. In the corner of the exhibit hall is a diorama of a pack rat nest. In the center of the exhibit hall is a diorama of a desert community, with a saguaro as the centerpiece and wildlife surrounding it like a jackrabbit, quail and small mammals. The back door of the visitor leads out to a paved, uncovered patio area where rangers deliver patio talks to visitors sitting on rows of benches. The trail continues past a small pond that hosts endangered Quitobaquito pupfish (a small fish; the males turn a bright blue during mating season). Mesquite trees hover above and around the pond. The Visitor Center Nature Trail continues around the back of the visitor center and through the desert, with the view of the Ajo Mountains in the distance. The trail weaves through examples of different cacti, with several interpretive signs along the way. The trail ends at the southern end of the visitor center, near the monument for Kris Eggle.

name: Kīpahulu Visitor Center
description: Located at the coastal Kīpahulu District. Information desk, exhibits on natural and cultural history, and a Hawaiʻi Pacific Parks Association bookstore inside. Restrooms are open 24 hours per day, 7 days per week, except when the park is closed during severe weather events. Please check park alerts for information on closures.
audioDescription: A one-story, tan building sits in a grassy lawn with native hala, or screwpine, trees casting shade to the right of the building. The outside of the building displays a National Park Service Arrowhead and the words "Visitor Center." A painting of the demigod Maui snaring the sun is next to the National Park Service arrowhead. To the left of the building is a deck with bunches overlooking the blue sea. On clear days, the island of Hawaiʻi can be seen in the distance with it's four peaks rising out of the ocean. In front of the building is a flagpole with the United States Flag and Hawaiian State Flag. A pathway leading off to the left guides visitors towards park trails and there are interpretive waysides along the path. Inside the building there are exhibits on Native Hawaiian cultural practices and Native Hawaiian history. A traditionally carved waʻa, or canoe, is positioned in the center of the exhibit area. To the right of the exhibits is the front desk, where park rangers supply maps and brochures. Next to the information desk is the cash register for the partnering bookstore, Hawai'i Pacific Parks Association. The bookstore offers hiking and birding guides, books on Native Hawaiian history and culture, and educational children's books. Postcards, magnets, t-shirts, and a small selection of snacks are also available. To the left of the cash register is the park stamp which says "Haleakalā National Park, Kīpahulu, HI" and shows the current date and a small engraving of kalo, or taro plant. There is green ink and sheets of paper available next to the stamp on the table. Hanging from the ceiling is a realistic model of the ʻiwa, or frigate bird, with deep black coloration, a forked tail, and a seven-foot wingspan.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is round and says "Haleakalā National Park" on the top, "Kīpahulu, HI" on the bottom, and shows the current date and a small engraving of a kalo (taro) leaf.

name: Laboratory Complex Visitor Center
description: Thomas Edison Laboratory Complex & Glenmont Grounds will be open to the public Thursday, Friday, Saturday & Sunday 10:00 AM to 4:00 PM. All visitors must begin at the Laboratory Complex.
audioDescription: The visitor center is located at 211 Main St., West Orange, NJ. As you enter the site, you will pass thru a large iron gate. Next, you will walk under a brick archway. The visitor center is located to your left inside of building one. Building One houses the visitor center, theater, souvenir store, as well as restrooms. This is the place to begin your visit to Thomas Edison National Historical Park.
passportStampLocationDescription: Thomas Edison National Historical Park consists of two parts. The Edison Lab complex, and the Edison home, Glenmont, located inside of Llewellyn Park. The site has a separate passport stamp for each location and they can be found at the main visitor center/ visitor contact station.

name: Lake Mead Visitor Center
description: Before you start your adventure, stop by the Lake Mead Visitor Center. Whether you have one hour or one week, rangers and volunteers will help you plan an unforgettable trip. In addition to grabbing maps and brochures, you can get your National Park passport stamp or become a junior ranger. The Western National Parks Association operates the park store from within the center. It's stocked with books about the park and the region, Native American arts, jewelry and crafts, posters, outerwear and more.

name: Laurance S. Rockefeller Preserve Center
description: The Laurance S. Rockefeller Preserve Center allows visitors to learn about Mr. Rockefeller's vision and his legacy of conservation stewardship. Exhibits engage visual, tactile, and auditory senses through a poem by Terry Tempest Williams, audio recordings of Mr. Rockefeller, videos, photography, and a soundscape room. Visitors may relax in the resource room, attend a ranger program, or strike out on a hike to Phelps Lake. The center does not have a sales area or offer permits.
audioDescription: The Laurance S. Rockefeller Preserve Center is reached by a 4-foot wide dirt and gravel path that winds up a gentle slope from the parking area, passing through sagebrush meadows. As you climb the path you see a long building to your right. It has a dark grey metal roof and wood siding stained a reddish brown. The building is in the shape of an “L” with the short end of the “L” facing the mountains. Past the left end of the building, the path turns to the right and leads to the entrance in the inside corner of the “L.” Where the path turns a large boulder sits with a sign reading “Laurance S. Rockefeller Preserve” with a green pine sprig logo off to the left. Another path leads straight ahead through a stand of Black Hawthorne bushes. The far wing of the building has a covered porch with wood decking running its length. During the summer season, six Adirondack chairs invite visitors to sit. The area inside the “L” is filled with a grove of aspen trees. At the far end of the porch is an open gravel area with a 3 foot boulder it the middle. A trailhead leads off to the right. Straight ahead is a small building with composting toilets. There is a central opening at the restrooms with doors leading to the right for women and to the left for men. Audio descriptions of the interior are available through the NPS Audio Description App, available on the App Store.

name: Lava Beds Visitor Center
description: Lava Beds is home to one visitor center located at the south end of the park, near cave loop road. An entrance station is located at the north end of the park, but is only open in the summer. As you drive through the park you can find information kiosks with park maps at Petroglyph Point, and Gillem's Camp.
passportStampLocationDescription: We have the standard passport stamp and one with a bat available at the Visitor Center.

directionsInfo: Lava Beds is truly a remote park, in a corner of California most people never visit. Most roads into this area wind through mountains and along rivers, and travel may take longer than expected. Services are few and far between, and winter driving conditions can be encountered any time between fall and spring. Remember to Plan Ahead - There is no gas available at Lava Beds. We encourage you to top your tank off in one of the nearby communities of Klamath Falls, OR, Merrill, OR, Tulelake, CA, or Alturas, CA.

name: Lehman Caves Visitor Center
description: Phone: (775) 234-7510 Lehman Caves Visitor Center is located 5.5 miles up from the town of Baker, NV. At this visitor center visitors can plan their visit, purchase cave tour tickets, watch the park movie, and explore exhibits about the caves and the darkness of Great Basin National Park.
audioDescription: Nestled at the base of the 13,000-foot South Snake Range, the Lehman Caves Visitor Center has fruit trees and large poplar trees close by. This brown building with a flat roof has double door entering into the information area and exhibit hall. To the left is the information desk and park store, to the right is the exhibit hall. The exhibit hall has two sections: caves and night skies. The cave section is a model of Lehman Caves with formations like shields, turnips, stalactites, and stalagmites. The night sky section has a curved ceiling with a large picture of the night sky at great basin with a timeline of different astronomical and historical events.
passportStampLocationDescription: Use the virtual stamp below to mark your visit to Lehman Caves. Just fill in the month, day, and year on your own. In person stamps are available at the Lehman Caves Visitor Center during operating hours.

name: Liberty Island Information Center
description: A ranger or volunteer is available to answer questions and provide general information about the Statue of Liberty and make recommendations for your visit. The park brochure, Passport To Your National Parks (R) cancellation stamp, and the ferry departure schedule are also located in the Statue of Liberty Information Center.
audioDescription: As you make your way off the ferry dock, heading straight towards the flagpole, you will find the Information Center on the left-hand side across from the Refreshment Building. The Information Center is wheelchair accessible. To find the accessible ramp, continue past the Information Center entrance steps. On the left-hand side you will find a walkway leading to the ramp to the Information Center entrance as well as the ramp to the Statue of Liberty museum. The building is one story high and has a concrete facade. Inside the Information Center, the ranger sits at a desk on the right and a bench is set-up on the left to watch the movie.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport Stamp is located on the information desk in the museum.

name: Light Station Visitor Center
description: Available Facilities: Restrooms, first aid, shade shelter, water fountain. Purchase tickets for climbing the lighthouse at the ticket window. Also available: park passport stamp station, free Jr Ranger & Jr Ranger Activity guides, bookstore, beach wheelchair (free rental) Located on South Core Banks near the Cape Lookout Lighthouse, this visitor center is reached only by the park ferry or private boat. Open from mid-March through October, 9:30 AM - 4:30 PM daily.
audioDescription: Located on South Core Banks near the lighthouse, this visitor center can only be reached by taking the ferry or your own boat to the area. Once to the island, follow the boardwalk from the ferry dock until the boardwalk widens out into a large wooden plaza area. On the left is the single story visitor center, a single door in the middle of the building (door swings out) allows access to the interior where you can find a ranger or volunteer to answer questions and a sales area. The interior is also airconditioned if you need to cool down during the summer months.
passportStampLocationDescription: Round stamp with Cape Lookout National Seashore at the top and Cape Lookout Light Station, NC at the bottom. Across the center is the date the impression was made.

name: Lincoln Borglum Visitor Center
description: Park information, film, museum exhibits and a bookstore. Opens at 8:00 am daily (closed December 25th). Closes at 6:00 pm October 1 through November 5, 5:00 pm November 6 through late May, 10:00 pm June through mid-August, and 9:00 pm mid-August through September 30.
audioDescription: The Lincoln Borglum Visitor Center is a concrete and granite building that sits at the top of the amphitheater with large windows that face Mount Rushmore. The visitor center consists of a large lobby with an information desk, bookstore and exhibits about the plants and animals of the area, the Civilian Conservation Corps in the Black Hills and the preservation of the sculpture. The visitor center also contains an exhibit hall with sections about Gutzon Borglum, the workers, the carving process and some of the dedication ceremonies. Two theaters show the film "Mount Rushmore: The Shrine," a 14-minute movie about the origins of the idea and the carving process that uses historical film footage. The Lincoln Borglum Visitor Center is accessible by two elevators or by using stairs on either side of the Grand View Terrace.
passportStampLocationDescription: Located at information desk.

name: Lincoln Home Visitor Center
description: Open 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM. Closed Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Years Day. Visitors using the parking lot must pay $2.00 per hour. We ask visitors please pay with debit or credit card as we do not accept cash. Here you can get free tour tickets and site orientation. In the VC, Theater One shows a park film, and Theater Two serves as the meeting point for tours of the Lincoln Home. Tickets are required for tours of the Lincoln Home. Exhibits, information, souvenirs and bathrooms are located here.
audioDescription: Lincoln Home visitor center is located at the central western edge of the park, at the northeastern corner of 7th and Jackson streets. Note that Jackson street is closed to vehicular traffic within the park's 4 square block boundaries. The visitor center has a southern entrance connected to the visitor parking lot by a straight brick pathway leading with a short set of stairs leading down to the lot. A ramp can be used instead of the stairs, located west closer to the 7th street sidewalk. A western entrance to the visitor center is also accessible from the sidewalk along 7th street. Inside the visitor center, the information desk is located in the southwestern corner of the building. At this desk, tickets and site orientation is handled. Restrooms are located in the northern side of the visitor center. Two theaters which play park films are located on the southeast and eastern sides of the visitor center. The souvenir shop is located in the northeastern side of the visitor center.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport stamp is located in the Eastern National America's National Parks bookstore against the north wall. It is on a lit bookshelf adjacent to the bathrooms. Available Stamps: Lincoln Home NHS, Underground Railroad Freedom Network, and other additional stamps.

name: Lindsay Warren Visitor Center
description: The visitor center of Fort Raleigh National Historic Site, housing immersive exhibits on the Algonquian, the English, the Roanoke Island Freedmen's Colony, the Civil War Battle of Roanoke Island, and Reginald Fessenden. A 17-minute dramatic video on the interaction between the Algonquian and the English is displayed in the visitor center's theater.
audioDescription: From the main parking lot at Fort Raleigh National Historic Site, follow the sidewalk to the main outdoor plaza. The Lindsay Warren Visitor Center will be towards your right. Proceed up the path to the front doors, and inside you will find an information desk, park store, exhibit hall, and 17 minute dramatic video on the interaction between the Algonquian and English settlers. The exhibit hall features interactive exhibits that explore the Algonquian, the English, The Roanoke Island Freedman's Colony, the Civil War Battle of Roanoke Island, and Reginald Fessenden's experiments. Restrooms are located outside the visitor center across the plaza.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport Stamp is available inside the Lindsay Warren Visitor Center.

name: Linn Cove Viaduct Visitor Center
description: The rugged slopes of Grandfather Mountain proved a challenging task to engineers as they completed the last section of the Parkway here in 1987, 52 years after construction began. To protect the fragile and ecologically sensitive slopes of the mountain, Parkway planners designed the award-winning Linn Cove Viaduct, and the visitor center at MP 304 celebrates this achievement. The beautiful Tanawah Trail runs nearby. The visitor center is currently closed.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps are located in the America's National Parks store in the visitor center.

name: Linville Falls Visitor Center
description: The Linville River flows from its headwaters high on the steep slopes of Grandfather Mountain and cascades through two falls as it beings a nearly 2,000 foot descent through this rugged and spectacularly beautiful gorge, carved out by the tall Linville Falls. Towering hemlocks, dense stands of rhododendron, and native wildflowers grow along the trails that begin at the visitor center and encircle the falls.

name: Little Bighorn Battlefield Visitor Center
description: The Little Bighorn Battlefield Visitor Center details the Battle of the Little Bighorn as well as providing information on the Custer National Cemetery. There is a Museum and Bookstore in the building as well as a covered patio area where ranger talks are held daily in the summer. Visitors can access the Visitor Center from 8:00am to 6:00pm Memorial Day to Labor Day and 8:00am to 4:30pm the remainder of the year.

name: Little Rock Central High School National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The visitor center features a detailed exhibit with interviews, news footage, and audio/video recordings of those directly involved + a new interpretive film, accessible restrooms and a Jefferson National Parks Association (JNPA) bookstore.
audioDescription: The one-story, tan brick building is composed of five forty-foot-wide columns arranged in a linear fashion with the long side facing South Park Street. The building, located at the intersection of South Park Street and West Daisy L. Gatson Bates Drive, also incorporates large expanses of glass windows shaded by metal roof overhangs. The windows on the south end of the building provide a view of Central High School and the Magnolia Mobil Station and draw visitors into the exhibit space. The building also includes a raised four-sided clerestory above the central lobby area which provides additional natural light to the public space. The visitor center includes two main entrances to the building: the east entrance is located off the main parking lot close to accessible parking spaces and the flagpole; the west entrance is off a plaza equipped with benches and stairs adjacent to South Park Street. Both entrances have a square automatic door button on the right side of the double doors leading into and out of the visitor center. Inside the visitor center are accessible restrooms and water fountains off the main lobby; chairs are arranged against a wall between the restrooms and water fountains for guest seating. The main lobby of the visitor center contains an information desk staffed by park rangers or volunteers to provide informal interpretation, give directions, or answer any visitor questions. Adjacent to the information desk is the bookstore which offers gifts, souvenirs and other relevant media relevant to the stories of the Civil Rights Movement and the Central High crisis. The main lobby also contains a multipurpose room with seating for fifty and the park's interpretive film (shown upon request). The exhibits inside the visitor center and off the main lobby are arranged to enter from the left and proceed through the room in a clockwise direction. The exhibits tell the story of African American civil rights from America's inception to today through various devices: panels with historical narrative content; interviews, news footage, and audio/video recordings of those who were part of the Central High desegregation; tactile models of Central High and Dunbar High; a special display case with rotating content relevant to this story; the painting America Cares, a work by George Hunt which features the Little Rock Nine and was used by the US Postal Service in a 2005 series "To Form A More Perfect Union" that celebrated milestones in Civil Rights.

name: Little Sand Bay Visitor Center
description: This seasonal visitor center is brand new in 2020. Exhibits on the grounds tell the story of Little Sand Bay and the challenges and joys of living in the North Woods, including the restored Twilite fish tug. The center offers orientation and information, camping permits, kayak safety guidance, and the America's National Parks bookstore.

name: Lodgepole Visitor Center
description: Located in the conifer zone at an elevation of 6,700 feet (2,040 m), the visitor center provides opportunities to view exhibits, get trip planning advice, get a wilderness permit, watch several park films, or shop at the gift shop. New exhibits immerse visitors in the wilderness environments of the parks, from the foothills to the highest peaks and to underground caves, as well as exploring the human history of the southern Sierra Nevada with tactile exhibits and soundscapes from every park environment.
audioDescription: You are standing on a paved courtyard with low stone edging and wood benches, around the low grass and conifer trees that landscape Lodgepole Visitor Center. Adjacent to the entrance is a large granite rock with a plaque on a grassy area. Lodgepole Visitor Center is a single story wooden building with a high peaked roof, made of corrugated metal. The building has brown, planked wood siding with bulletin boards and windows. The double entrance doors open outward. There is an additional peaked roof over the entrance door, supported by large wooden posts and beams. Along the building, to both the left and right of the entrance, is a low stone border that creates a walkway under the eaves of the roof. Centered under the entrance roof is an embossed wood sign over the door. It reads, “Visitor Center”. Above it is the National Park Service logo, in the shape of a brown arrowhead, pointed downward. Inside the arrowhead are the words in white lettering, “National Park Service” with a green sequoia tree shape to its left. Near the bottom of the arrowhead is a white buffalo silhouette set against a green meadow, with a white lake and snowcapped mountain behind it. To reach the restrooms, follow the covered walkway to the right of the entrance doors. The restrooms are at the end of the building.

name: Logan Pass Visitor Center
description: The Logan Pass Visitor Center sits atop the Continental Divide at 6,646 feet. The visitor center houses exhibits on the plants and animals found in the sub-alpine region of the park. Numerous exhibits outside the visitor center tell the story of geology, climate change, and life in the harsh alpine world above treeline. Logan Pass is perhaps the most crowded location in the park with the parking lot filling to capacity early in the morning. Plan to arrive early or visit later in the afternoon.
audioDescription: The Logan Pass Visitor Center sits atop the Continental Divide at 6,646 feet. The visitor center houses exhibits on the plants and animals found in the sub-alpine region of the park. Numerous exhibits outside the visitor center tell the story of geology, climate change, and life in the harsh alpine world above treeline. Logan Pass is perhaps the most crowded location in the park with the parking lot filling to capacity early in the morning. Plan to arrive early or visit later in the afternoon.

name: Longmire Museum
description: Located on the south side of Mount Rainier at 2,700 feet above sea level, the museum makes up part of the historic Longmire district. Once a ranger office, the building now houses historic exhibits about the park's natural and geological history, and animals. A ranger or volunteer staffs the museum to assist with park information and book and map sales.
audioDescription: The Longmire Museum is a small wood building with an angled roof surrounded by tall evergreen trees. A paved walking path, bordered by large stones, leads to the entrance. In front of the building to the left of the path as you approach the door is a large cross section of a log, framed by a wood shelter. Small plaques attached to the log cutting label the historic dates of various tree rings in the log. The entrance of the museum is a small covered porch with a framed, glass-covered exhibit window to the right of the door. A trash can may be on the edge of the porch to the right of the exhibit window. When you enter the museum, there is a small entry way, lined with bookshelves with materials for sale. Enter, then continue forward to enter the main space of the museum. The information desk is immediately to the left. To the right, the single main room of the museum is broken up by old museum exhibits, including a large glass case with a taxidermy mountain lion. Interpretive panels cover the walls.

name: Longmire Wilderness Information Center
description: Open during the summer, the Longmire Wilderness Information Center (WIC) is located in the lobby of the historic Longmire Administration Building, a picturesque example of National Park Service rustic architecture in Longmire. The WIC features a 3D model map of Mount Rainier National Park and has an information desk staffed by wilderness rangers. Rangers at the WIC assist with wilderness permits, trip planning, and providing maps and trail condition updates.
audioDescription: The Longmire Administration Building is a two-story building near the main road as you travel through Longmire. The building is framed by tall evergreen trees and there is a small lawn with a flagpole in front. The bottom story of the building is built from large rounded boulders, while the top story is built of wood logs, with a wood shingled roof. Both stories have rows of windows with white trim. The entrance is shaded by a porch with large log beams supporting the wood-shingled porch roof. A yellow log sign reading “Mount Rainier National Park” hangs from underneath the porch roof. A gravel path leads to the entrance across the lawn. The lobby of the building, a single rustic room, is the location of the Longmire Wilderness Information Center. Directly across from the entrance doors is a fireplace built of large boulders. A wood-paneled information desk is on the right side of the room, while a large three-dimensional map of the park fills a table on the left side of the room.

name: Lookout Mountain Battlefield Visitor Center
description: Atop Lookout Mountain, discover details about the siege of Chattanooga and the battles for control of the city. View exhibits and the historic 13- by 30-foot James Walker painting,THE BATTLE OF LOOKOUT MOUNTAIN. Point Park has battery positions, monuments, exhibits, trails, and views.
audioDescription: Visitors parking in the NPS parking lot at Lookout Mountain Visitor Center will walk toward the building on a sidewalk, leading them passed the water fountain and restrooms on their right. After passing this entrance, the next door to the right is one of the two visitor center entrances, the other being around the building's front, on the right. When visitors enter from the initially described entrance, they will be in the visitor center lobby/America's National Park's bookstore. To the right is a television that provides short, self-starting overview of Chickamauga and Chattanooga National Military Park. Continuing in the lobby, visitors will encounter the information desk, staffed by NPS employees. Just to the right of the desk, is the museum entrance. When entering through the door, exhibit panels will line the room, to the left is the large, 13 foot by 30 foot painting of the Battle of Lookout Mountain, painted by artist James Walker, in 1874. Just opposite the Walker painting, on the opposite wall, is another television with a self-starting overview of the Battles for Chattanooga.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Lookout Mountain Battlefield passport stamp is located inside the visitor center, across from Point Park.

name: Loomis Museum
description: The historic museum is located one mile from the northwest entrance of the park near Manzanita Lake. The museum is only open during the summer months. Visit for information, to view exhibits and the park film, shop at the park store, or participate in a ranger-led program (offered primarily outside in the adjacent Loomis Plaza). From the museum you can pick up the trail around Manzanita Lake or cross the highway to access the self-guided, interpretive Lily Pond Nature Trail.
audioDescription: This single-story building is built of native volcanic rock and surrounded by a three-foot-high rock wall. A set of steps leads to the front entrance, which opens into a large exhibit hall. An information desk and is located in the corner to the right and a park store is located in a corner to the left. A set of glass exhibit cases sit in the center of the room creating a circular walkway through exhibits on both sides. A doorway at the back of the hall leads down a short hallway to an auditorium where the park film is shown. The hallway ends at a wheelchair accessible entrance that exits to a ramp that wraps around the building and back to the front entrance. The museum sits on the west edge of a plaza, which includes a small restroom building and a second single story building that serves as a ranger station.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is located to the left of the information desk inside the museum.

name: Los Alamos Visitor Center
description: At the Los Alamos Visitor Center you can speak with park rangers, tour exhibits about the Manhattan Project in Los Alamos, and learn more about where to go in town.
audioDescription: From the street, the wide sidewalk slopes gently up to the one-story, tan stucco building that houses the Visitor Center. On each end, a short wing extends out towards us. The entrance is located in the section to your left. The flat roof overhangs the corner with the entrance and then covers the sidewalk as it continues along the front of the building. The front of the left wing has large windows along the front. The single door has a lever-style handle and opens inward. The bottom half of the door has a map of the Los Alamos sites. The information desk lies straight ahead as you enter on the far side of the room. End of Description.
