name: Lower Town Information Center
description: The Lower Town Information Center is not currently staffed by rangers. However, maps and information are available at the "Place in Time" exhibit space.
audioDescription: A two-story rectangular brick building. The first floor has a white central door framed by inset small rectangular glass panes, with two symmetrical windows framed by dark green shutters on either side of the door. The second floor has five symmetrical windows framed by dark green shutters. A black iron fence encloses a small yeaard in front of the building. A set of steps flanked by black iron railing leads to the front door.

name: Lowndes Interpretive Center
description: The Lowndes Interpretive Center is located roughly halfway between Selma and Montgomery along the Trail on U.S. Highway 80 West near Whitehall, AL. The center has exhibits, including interactive exhibits, that tell the story of the history of the Voting Rights Movement, the 1965 Selma to Montgomery Voting Rights March, and the Tent City that housed 20 families over a two year period following the passage of the 1965 Voting Rights Act. Visitors may view the film "Never Lose Sight of Freedom" in the theater.
audioDescription: This visitor center is a large beige brick structure, the front of the building is designed to look like a church with double steeples. When you enter from the back parking lot through the foyer, the ceiling is arched like a bridge with skylights. Directly ahead is a standing map kiosk, restrooms on the right, and on the left is the front desk, theater, and exhibit area. As you enter this museum area, the front desk is directly to the left, the theater is directly to the right, and the exhibits are straight ahead, the exhibits flow in the counter-clockwise direction starting and ending at the front desk. As you enter the exhibits, there are several glass panels with silhouettes and quotes, followed by several exhibits with video clips that automatically play and displays of various scenes of Historic Lowndes County. Halfway through the exhibits there are five mannequins facing a wall of windows that looks out on a walking path and a small domed gazebo designed to represent the state capitol building. As you exit the mannequin display area, on the left there is another glass panel that plays a video clip. The second-to-last exhibit is a display of the interior of a tent, designed to represent "tent city", this includes furniture secured to the floor. The last exhibit includes a table, stools, and large box to submit comments, thoughts, and memories from and about the Selma to Montgomery march. Lastly, as you exit the exhibits through the bookstore you return to the front desk.

name: Lyndon B. Johnson State Park and Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The state park encompasses more than 700 acres. Staff at the visitor center provide information and answer questions about the state park and the Sauer-Beckmann Living History Farm. Maps and free permits are issued here for driving tours of the nearby LBJ Ranch. A 26-minute, historic film on President Johnson at his Ranch shows on demand. A gift shop offers local souvenirs. Exhibits and displays on Texas pioneer life, the Hill Country and President Johnson are located in the nearby Exhibit Hall.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 110 words. From the parking area, there are several structures for the state park visitor center complex. Each has a shingled roof, and all have either a stone wall or wooden plank walls. The first structure on the right is the restroom building. The next building on the right is the visitor center. It is connected to the administration building on the left by a covered breezeway. The visitor center entrance is a glass door. Upon entry, there is a small exhibit area to the right, entrance to a large theater forward, and the visitor center desk is to the left. Past the front desk to the right is the gift shop. End of Description

name: Mabry Mill Cultural Site
description: The sights and sounds of rural life in Appalachia resonate at Mabry Mill during the summer and fall. Ed Mabry built this mill, where he and his wife ground corn, sawed lumber, and operated a blacksmith shed for their neighbors for three decades. It was a community gathering place for the folks who called Meadows of Dan their home in the early twentieth century.

name: Madison Information Station and Trailside Museum
description: Located about halfway between Old Faithful and West Yellowstone, you can stop here for park information as visitors have been doing since 1930. The structure is an example of "parkitecture" or designing a building in a way that reflects the surrounding ecosystem. You can also shop for souvenirs in the park store, attend a ranger program, purchase a fishing permit (fees are payable by debit or credit card), or use the restrooms.
audioDescription: Madison Information Station 226 words The Madison Information Station and Trailside Museum is a one-story wood and stone structure with shingled roof set at the edge of a meadow at the junction where the Firehole and Gibbon Rivers join to form Madison River. A triangular gable roof supported by several heavy logs shades the building’s entrance, a single 12-pane glass door located toward the left end of the structure. This entrance is flanked by irregular stone pillars; tree profiles and diamond patterns have been sawn into the ends of the flat vertical boards hanging just above the door and the two large windows to its left. There is also an entrance door on the right side into the Yellowstone Association bookstore. The approach to the building from the gravel path in front of the building slopes slightly but is accessible with assistance. You will encounter a flat stone slab outside the entrance and a small mat placed just outside the door. There is also a small ramp on both the front and back doors; these entries are wheelchair accessible. A sign standing between two windows to the right of the entrance reads: “Yellowstone Association Park Store. Inspire. Educate. Preserve.” In the summer months between Memorial Day and Labor Day, there is also a sign hanging over the left side entrance--the National Park Service entrance--that reads “Junior Ranger Station.” END OF MESSAGE

name: Magnolia Plantation Store
description: Magnolia Plantation is closed to the public until further notice due to road repair work.
audioDescription: From your vehicle you will walk north approximately 100-250 feet to the store. Pass through a pedestrian gate in the fence line to an accessible ramp that leads to the front porch of the store. The store has two wings on either side of the main part of the store. The right wing has a foyer with site maps and a door into the men's restroom. The left wing foyer is where you will find maps, brochures, a water fountain and water bottle filling station and the women's restroom. The main part of the store is only open when park staff is on site.
passportStampLocationDescription: During the closure of Magnolia Plantation the three Magnolia passport stamps available at the Oakland Plantation Store, Cane River Creole National Historical Park, Cane River National Heritage Area, and the El Camino Real de los Tejas National Historic Trail.

name: Mainland Museum
description: Exhibits explore the cultural and natural history of the island from prehistoric American Indian lives, through British occupation during the war of 1812, the Plantation Era, the Gilded Age, and the island today.
audioDescription: The Cumberland Island National Seashore Museum is located in Historic Downtown Saint Marys. It is on Osborne St, two blocks away from the waterfront. Located on the west side of the road, the building is a tall, square two story building. It is tan colored with green and white striped awnings. Four large, false picture windows line the front of the building. Each window has an image from the Island. One shows a picture of the beach at sunrise, another of the main road, one of the Dungeness ruins and another of Plum Orchard Mansion. In the middle of the building and between the windows is the main door. Set back into an alcove, the double doors have green trim. There is a button for the automatic door located on the right side of the alcove. Upon entering, there is an information desk ahead and to the left. When open, a ranger of volunteer will staff the desk. Just to the right of the desk, or straight ahead when you enter, is a water fountain with a bottle filling station. To the right of the water fountain is the men’s restroom. Inside the rest room there will be a sink to your left followed by a urinal and one stall near the end of the room. The ladies restroom is to the left after you enter the museum, ahead 15 feet, then turn right down the hallway for 10 feet. The bathroom will be on the right side of the hall, in a small alcove and then to the left. Inside the ladies room you will find the sink on the right followed by two stalls. The museum exhibits begin to the right as you enter the building. The museum walks you through in a clockwise direction. The island history is presented in chronological order beginning with the American Indians then the colonial era, the plantation era, the reconstruction era and finally into the back room with the Carnegie Era. From the back room, the hall way leads back to the front of the building. At the end of the hallway, another room opens to the right. This room contains exhibits telling the story of the War of 1812 and the British invasion of Cumberland Island. There is a small TV that shows a film on repeat about the archeological investigation of the Point Peter battle site.
passportStampLocationDescription: Two stamps are available at the Museum in Saint Marys. Cumberland Island Stamp – The official stamp with the words “Cumberland Island National Seashore, St. Marys, GA,” and the date. Gullah-Geechee stamp – A stamp commemorating Cumberland Island’s role in the Gullah-Geechee Heritage Corridor. Reads “Gullah-Geechee Historic Corridor, Cumberland Island,” and the date.

name: Mainland Visitor Center
description: The Mainland Visitor Center is located at the waterfront in downtown St. Marys, GA. Visitors taking a ferry to the island should check in at this location 1 hour prior to departure. The visitor center offers exhibits, a bookstore with memorabilia, and information to help you plan your visit to the island. Rangers are available to answer questions, sell park passes, and issue camping permits for private boaters. Long term parking is located one block west on the north side of the street.
audioDescription: The Cumberland Island National Seashore visitor center is located along the waterfront in Historic downtown St Marys. Located next to the city boat ramp, the visitor center stands two stories tall. On the opposite side of the visitor center, there is a grass courtyard area with a small covered pavilion. There are a few exhibit panels and benches throughout the courtyard. The visitor center building has blue siding with a tin roof. A balcony provides a view over the St Marys River. The down stairs of the building is mostly an open-air breezeway with a large standup map of the island situated in the middle of the breezeway closer to the water. You can enter the breezeway from the street or along the sidewalk that follows the river. In the breezeway you will find restroom facilities, a water fountain, and the main entrance into the visitor center. Upon entering the breezeway from the street, the main doors are located to your right about 20 feet into the breezeway. There is an automatic door activated by a button to the right of the double doors. Once inside, an elevator is located directly to the right and ahead 10 feet. If you continue a few more feet around the corner, a staircase rises on the right. Once upstairs, the visitor information desk is located on the left about 20 feet past the stairs. A ranger or volunteer will be present during operating hours. During ferry check-in, a line will form around the room guided by stanchions. There is a two-step process to check-in for the ferry. The first stop is with the concessionaire who will issue boarding passes and sell day-of ferry tickets. The second step is with a park ranger who will collect entrance fees, check and issue park passes and check in campers. A bookstore is located across the room from the information desk. The bookstore is three sided with displays in the center of the room. Items are displayed around the room and on the wall. The checkout counter is on the left side of the store as you enter. Beyond the information desk and bookstore, the room opens up into an exhibit hall with information about the island’s history. Several exhibits tell the natural and cultural history of the island. They are located along the outer perimeter of the room. Bathroom facilities are located downstairs in the breezeway, to the right past the main doors when entering from the street. The women’s room is the first door you come to and there is a water fountain and bottle filling station to the right of the restroom door. Upon entering the restroom, there is a half wall providing more privacy in the restroom. You will have to walk to the right around this and then you will find several stalls on the right with several sinks on the left. The men’s rooms is laid out similarly, with two stall and then two urinals along the right side wall.
passportStampLocationDescription: Three stamps are available at the Visitor Center in Saint Marys, GA. Cumberland Island stamp – The official stamp with the words “Cumberland Island National Seashore, St. Marys, GA,” and the date. Gullah-Geechee stamp – A stamp commemorating Cumberland Island’s role in the Gullah-Geechee Heritage Corridor. Reads “Gullah-Geechee Historic Corridor, Cumberland Island,” and the date. Quarter Stamp- A stamp replica of the official Cumberland Island National Seashore quarter that was released in 2018.

name: Malaquite Visitor Center
description: The Malaquite Visitor Center includes an information desk, park store and an exhibit area with information about park history, plants, and animals. Ranger-led programs are available during the summer season. A shaded picnic area is available on the deck. Restrooms are available across the deck from the visitor center. Wheelchair users can borrow a special beach wheelchair from the visitor center at no charge. An accessible ramp goes from the deck down to Malaquite Beach.
audioDescription: A deck at second-story height situates the visitor center and accompanying buildings above the dunes and provides an excellent view of the beach and the Gulf of Mexico. A shade structure covers much of the deck and there are approximately twelve picnic tables in the shade. There are two observation decks which provide views of the gulf and the coastal prairie. When walking up the stairs from the parking lot, the bathrooms and showers are across the deck. To the right is the education center which is open occasionally for special events. To the left of the stairs is the visitor center and park store. When you enter the visitor center, the park store is on the right. In front is the information desk and register. To the left is the exhibit hall which has information about the park. When exiting the visitor center, directly across the deck is a ramp which provides access to the beach in front.
passportStampLocationDescription: There is the official park passport date stamp, junior ranger stamp, and sea turtle stamp available at the visitor center.

name: Mammoth Cave Visitor Center
description: The park visitor center is the central point for visitors to orient themselves to what lies both above and below the surface at Mammoth Cave. Situated just up the hill from the cave's Historic Entrance, the visitor center is the departure point for all cave tours, and offers exhibits to prepare you for discovery. You can also meet a ranger for a talk or a hike. Gifts, restrooms, permits and information are available, and visitor amenities are offered by the nearby Mammoth Cave Hotel across the footbridge.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a large stone building located up a hill from the main cave entrance and behind the lodge. In front of the visitor center is an outdoor open are shelter with cave tour information. Entering the front doors for the building, restrooms are located to the left of the entrance. Continuing around the main lobby clockwise is the cave tour ticket sales area, exit doors to the cave tour departure area, a gift sales area, and exit doors leading to the lodge. Directly in front of the main entrance doors and centrally located in the main visitor center lobby is a visitor information desk. Counterclockwise to the right of the main entrance doors is the park bookstore, followed by the entrance to the visitor center exhibit area. The exhibit area is a loop hallway, with interactive exhibits and audio visual presentations.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Mammoth Cave Passport Stamp is located in the America's National Parks bookstore. The passport stamp is the NPS Classic Passport Cancellation Stamp consisting of a circle, park name and date.

directionsInfo: From the North: Take Interstate 65 to Exit 53 (Cave City Exit). Turn right onto KY-70. Follow 70/255 as it becomes the Mammoth Cave Parkway in the park. Follow the Mammoth Cave Parkway to the Visitor Center. From the South: Take Interstate 65 to Exit 48 (Park City Exit). Turn left onto KY-255 and follow 255 as it becomes the Park City Road into the park. Follow Park City Road until it joins the Mammoth Cave Parkway; turn left. Follow the Mammoth Cave Parkway to the Visitor Center.

name: Manzanar Visitor Center
description: The Manzanar visitor center offers extensive exhibits, a 22-minute park film, a bookstore, a Junior Ranger program, and an information desk.
audioDescription: The visitor center is located some distance from the highway, frontage road, and parking lot. It is in the high desert and as you approach from the parking lot, the high Sierra stand behind the visitor center. The visitor entrance is on the left front of the building, up a ramp or stairs. The building is quite large and tall, but it is navigable on one floor. The building was once the Manzanar High School Auditorium. You are entering from the back of the historic building.
passportStampLocationDescription: The single passport stamp for Manzanar National Historic Site is located in the bookstore of the visitor center.

name: Marinus Willett Visitor Center
description: Main visitor center for Fort Stanwix National Monument. See videos about the American Revolution in the Mohawk Valley and learn about the park's archeological collection. A bookstore can be found with souvenirs and books available for different ages. Restrooms are available for your convenience.

name: Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is the place to stop for a brief orientation to the historic site, registration for a tour of Dr. King’s Birth Home , a tour of the featured exhibits “Courage to Lead”, and “Children of Courage”, viewing a short film and the nearest restrooms.
audioDescription: The facility a short walk from the visitors parking lot and is clearly visible during Fall and Winter when foliage from the trees that line the Promenade are bare. Visitors arriving by coach should have their driver off load them along Irwin Street at the walkway (Promenade) and park their coach in the bus parking lots on John Wesley Dobb Avenue, which adjacent to the visitor parking. The Visitor Center is clearly marked with the park's name appearing on front and rear sides of this brick facility sporting a light green canopy. Visitors should stop here for a brief orientation by a Park Ranger. There are three exhibition areas contained within this facility which include: the "Children of Courage" exhibit, which is geared towards our younger visitors; the main exhibition entitled "Courage To Lead", which follows the parallel paths of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., and the Civil Rights Movement; and a changing exhibition in the D.R.E.A.M. Gallery, home to special exhibits. Films are shown daily on a 30-minute schedule in the theatre which seats approximately 126 people. There are teaser exhibitions in the atrium of this facility, at certain times, that support a variety of topics ranging from civil rights to the preservation practices applied to the historic structures, such as historic Ebenezer Baptist Church, the Birth Home of Martin Luther King, Jr. and the homes on the same block, and Fire Station Number 6. Visitors can obtain their passport stamp at this location, along with a park brochure, and Junior Ranger activity booklet. Although our park is self-guided, the tour of the Birth Home is led by a Park Ranger. Visitors "MUST" register for the Birth Home tour in-person on the day of their visit and the tours are on a first-come, first-serve, basis.
passportStampLocationDescription: The park has three passport stamps. Visitors can get their National Parks Passport Book stamped at the information desks located in the Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historical Park Visitor Center, Historic Ebenezer Baptist Church, and Historic Fire Station No. 6.

name: Maryland District Ranger Contact Station & Campground Office
description: Offers campground information and registration, backcountry camping permits, hunting information, entrance passes and over-sand vehicle permits.
audioDescription: The Ranger Contact Station and Campground Office is located in the Maryland District of Assateague Island on the west side of Bayberry Drive and adjacent to the entrance booths on the west side. The GPS location is 6633 Bayberry Drive, Berlin, Maryland 21811. Parking for vehicles, RVs and trailers is available on the west side of the building. The Ranger Station faces north and is a rectangular, one story gray building with white trimmed windows and doors, a covered deck and has a National Park Service Arrowhead centered above the doors. There is a short set of steps that leads onto the covered deck, as well as a wheelchair accessible ramp to the east of the stairs. There are two doors, one facing east and one facing west that open to a glass vestibule which then has a door to the south that leads into the Ranger Station. Inside the Ranger Station is an open area with a desk that extends the length of the building. Behind the desk are park rangers, offices, computers, fee registers and informational brochures. There is an educational exhibit of a horse skeleton filled with human trash. In the northeast corner of the building is a touch table exhibit with bones and shells available to touch.

name: Melrose Visitor Center
description: Located in the former kitchen building for the estate, the Melrose Visitor Center is the visitor contact station at the site. Tickets for the mansion tour are available here. There is also a gift shop and an adjoining exhibit room.
audioDescription: The visitor center at Melrose is located in the former detached kitchen of the estate. A pebbledash walkway leads visitors from the parking lot, through a swinging white picket gate, up to the two-story red brick building. The former kitchen has a two-story porch with large square columns. One entrance will lead visitors into the gift shop/ticketing area, the other entrance will leads into an exhibit room where there are informative panels that detail the history of the estate.
passportStampLocationDescription: At the Melrose Visitor Center, one has access to six (6) passport stamps for the Natchez National Historical Park which include the following park sites: Melrose, Fort Rosalie, and the William Johnson House. Visitors may also receive a stamp for the Natchez Trace Parkway, the park's Junior Ranger stamp, and the National Park Service's centennial stamp.

name: Memorial Visitor Center
description: The Memorial Visitor Center is closed from 12:00 to 1:00 pm. The Memorial Visitor Center, completed in 1943, was designed with two memorial halls and a connecting cloister. The Memorial Court features five sculptured panels, the work or E.H. Daniels, marking significant periods in the life of Abraham Lincoln. Museum artifacts and exhibits portray the life of Abraham Lincoln. Learn about his family, boyhood, and frontier life in Indiana.
audioDescription: Memorial Visitor Center. 665 words. The Memorial Visitor Center is a 230-foot wide, one-story, white limestone block building with forest on both sides and back. The building consists of three equal sections. Seen from the front, the long walls of the left and right wings have five windows. Three tall, narrow windows are set side-by-side in the middle of the wall. Two small, narrow windows are near each end of the wall. The curved middle section of the building is shaped like a horseshoe and goes back 75 feet with a courtyard in front. On the walls of the curved, middle section of the building are five 15-foot by 20-foot stone sculptured panels depicting people, drawings of buildings, and text. Two glass doors and two large windows separate the panels. On the stone blocks at the top of the building, above the panels, windows, and doors reads block text carved into the limestone. A five-foot tall stone wall stands between the parking lot and the building. An opening in the wall in front of the curved middle section of the building contains four, eighty-foot long stone steps. To the right of the steps, in front of the wall, a wooden sign reads, “Memorial Visitor Center, Lincoln Boyhood National Memorial, This memorial building is Indiana’s tribute to Abraham Lincoln and his family.” From the parking lot, two parallel stone walkways, with a patch of grass in between, lead to the stone steps and the courtyard. The courtyard contains eight benches, patches of bright green mowed grass, bushes, small trees and ground cover in beds next to the building. In the courtyard, stone paths branch off to four doorways. The middle path branches into two and leads to two double glass doors. Five steps with iron handrails lead from the courtyard to the doors. The main entrance to the visitor center is through the door to the right. The door to the left is locked. The left and right branches leads to three stone steps, and heavy, light oak, wooden, double doors. There is a narrow window on each side of the wooden doors. A concrete path leads from the courtyard, across the front to the left of the building and merges with a concrete path that starts from the accessible spaces in the parking lot. The path leads to a door on the side and a door on the back of the building. The main entrance glass door from the courtyard leads to the middle of a curved hallway with a brick floor, a sandstone wall on one side, and cherry paneled wall on the other. The Information Desk is directly across from the entrance door. The bookstore is on both sides of the hallway. To the right of the Information Desk and down the curved hallway 30 feet are restrooms. The Abraham Lincoln Hall is located at the end of the hall in the right wing. Beside the Information Desk to the left is the Auditorium. To the left and down the hall 50 feet is the Lincoln In Indiana Museum. The Nancy Hanks Lincoln Hall and restroom facilities are located at the end of the hall in the left wing. Alternate entrance doors: The heavy wooden entrance door on the left of the courtyard leads to the Nancy Hanks Lincoln Hall and restrooms. The heavy wooden entrance door on the right of the courtyard leads to the Abraham Lincoln Hall. The heavy wooden door on the left side of the building leads to restrooms and the Nancy Hanks Lincoln Hall. The rear entrance has a push button on the right of the path eight feet before the glass door. This door leads to the curved hallway. To the right and down three steps is the Nancy Hanks Lincoln Hall. To the left and down the curved hallway is the museum, auditorium, information desk, bookstore and restrooms. At the end of the hallway and down three steps is the Abraham Lincoln Hall. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: Both passport stamps are located in the Memorial Visitor Center near the front door as you enter the building. There are two stamps available, one is the location stamp which reads Lincoln City, IN, and the other reads, Living Historical Farm. The date used in the image is February 19. On February 19, 1962, President John F. Kennedy signed legislation creating Lincoln Boyhood National Memorial.

name: Meriwether Lewis Visitor Information Center Milepost 385.9
description: The Meriwether Lewis Visitor Information Center is open seasonally. It is located at milepost 385.9. At this visitor center you can browse exhibits on the last days of Meriwether Lewis and purchase items from the Eastern National sales outlet. Volunteers and rangers are on hand to help you plan your visit and discuss the final hours of one of the United States' most famous explorers!
audioDescription: This visitor information center is housed in a log cabin built in the 1930s. As you walk up the ramp to the entrance the door on the left takes you to the Visitor Center side where a Park Ranger or volunteer will be able to answer your questions and hand out information. This is also where bookstore is located. If you enter through the door on the right you will enter the small exhibit space that tells the story of Meriwether Lewis and how he came to the Natchez Trace and Grinder's Stand. This is also where passport stamps are located.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available when the Meriwether Lewis Visitor Information Center is open. When the Visitor Information Center is closed you can get passport stamps at the Parkway Visitor Center at milepost 266 near Tupelo, Mississippi.

name: Mesa Verde Museum
description: Located at milepost 20, the Mesa Verde Mesa Museum offers exhibits and cultural objects that provide insight into the Ancestral Pueblo lifeways. An orientation film is shown on the hour and half-hour, providing an excellent overview of the history at Mesa Verde. A museum store, water, restrooms, café, gift shop, and post office are all located nearby. Just behind the museum is a stunning view of Spruce Tree House, the third largest and best-preserved cliff dwelling in the park.
audioDescription: The Mesa Verde Museum is one of the oldest in the National Park Service. It was constructed between 1922 and 1925 of locally quarried sandstone – the same rock that the Ancestral Pueblo people used to construct their dwellings. Its Modified Pueblo Revival Architecture reflects the architecture of descendant communities and is well integrated into the natural landscape. It is surrounded by a mature pinyon and juniper woodland community located at the edge of Spruce Canyon. Just beyond the Museum is a deep canyon with the third largest cliff dwelling site, Spruce Tree House.

name: Mesa Verde Visitor and Research Center
description: Located at the park entrance, off Highway 160, this facility serves as the park’s primary facility for orienting visitors to opportunities within the park and surrounding area. Exhibits offer glimpses into the richness of Ancestral Pueblo culture and daily life.
audioDescription: The Visitor & Research Center is a modern building built in a Pueblo style with locally quarried sandstone, large glass windows, and a shaded patio that wraps around the building to the east. A large sculpture of an Ancestral Pueblo climber welcomes visitors into the space where visitors can learn about the tribal communities that have shared and have close affiliation with this land. A long concrete walkway leads into the visitor center, which offers a bookstore, exhibits, and staffed information desk. Inside the Center, visitors can view the park’s state of the art research and curatorial facility for the park’s archives and museum collection of over three million objects.

name: Mill Springs Battlefield Visitor Center and Museum
description: The National Park Service operates the Visitor Center and Museum in Nancy, KY. A free 20-minute film about the Battle of Mill Springs is available for viewing in the Visitor Center. There are restrooms and a research library. The museum features the Combat on the Cumberland exhibit with Civil War artifacts and replicas.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center has ample parking. Visitors enter on the side of the building facing the main highway and grassy expanse. Mill Springs National Cemetery sits alongside, its headstones a silent testimony to the battle here long ago. Once inside, restrooms are immediately to the right. The front desk is to the left. The Museum is beyond the front desk, with exhibits about the leaders on both sides of the battle, along with a portrait wall from the soldiers. A recreated cabin represents the encampment, along with a display of homelife and medical treatment. A separate room has a showcase of era weapons and items from the Civil War.

name: Mineral King Ranger Station
description: Located in a mixed-conifer forest at 7,600 feet (2,320 m), the Mineral King Ranger Station houses some exhibits on Mineral King's human and natural history. Books, maps, and educational items for sale. Food storage canisters are available. Obtain wilderness permits here. Planning to park overnight? Marmots may attempt to get in your car's undercarriage or damage wiring. Make sure that you wrap the underside of your vehicle in a tarp.
audioDescription: When you reach Mineral King Ranger Station there are two parking areas, the first is in front of the ranger station. It has an orientation kiosk, directions to the Campfire circle and restrooms. The second parking area is across the road. It has a smaller wood framed building with a Bear Safety exhibit. There are two metal bear storage lockers. There is a creek running by this lot. Picnic tables are next to the creek so it is a shady place to stop and rest. In front of the Ranger Station is a stone border, behind it, six stairs lead up to the deck of the Ranger Station. On the deck is a wayside exhibit about local trails, and a flagpole, flying the U.S. flag. The Station itself is a single-story cabin-style wooden building with a peaked roof. It has reddish brown planked wood siding. Large wooden joists support the roof. The entrance door is covered by a smaller overhanging roof, supported by rustic wooden posts and beams, with an embossed wooden sign over the door that reads, “Mineral King Ranger Station Elevation: 7,580 Ft.”. Posted beside the entrance door are a variety of notices. There are windows on either side of the door. High on the wall, is the National Park Service logo, in the shape of a brown arrowhead, pointed downward. Inside the arrowhead are the words in white lettering, “National Park Service” with a green sequoia tree shape to its left. Near the bottom of the arrowhead is a white buffalo silhouette set against a green meadow, with a white lake and snowcapped mountain behind it.

name: Minidoka Visitor Center
description: Located at 1428 Hunt Road. Start here for visitor information, the passport stamp, the park film, museum exhibits, and the park bookstore. The visitor center is open Fridays through Sundays, from Memorial Day weekend to Labor Day weekend. If the visitor center is not open during your visit, please check the After Hours box for brochures and the passport stamp. The historic site grounds are open year-round for self-guided walking tours.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a rectangular building refurbished from a historic maintenance warehouse building left from the original camp. The exterior is wooden frame and black tarpaper, with high windows. A breezeway separates the visitor center from the restrooms.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamp is available in the Visitor Center during operating hours and at the After Hours box when closed.

name: Minute Man Visitor Center
description: Minute Man Visitor Center is CLOSED for Winter and will reopen in May 2024. Restrooms are closed for winter. "The Road to Revolution" multimedia presentation is closed for winter but will reopen in May 2024. The show runs every 30 minutes starting at 9:00 a.m. The last show runs at 4:30 p.m. Reservations are not accepted. The show runs 27 minutes in duration.
audioDescription: The building is a one story, unpainted wooden structure with a large NPS Arrowhead on the front, just to the right of the front doors. The front, center of the building features a large window. In the center of the window is a set of double glass doors.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport Stamps at Minute Man Visitor Center are only available during operating hours throughout the regular season. Minute Man Visitor Center runs from the beginning of April- October 31. The stamps are located at the Ranger Information Table Stamps include: Minute Man Visitor Center Stamp Underground Railroad Network to Freedom Stamp Freedom's Way National Heritage Area Junior Ranger Stamp

name: Minuteman Missile NHS Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is the best place to begin your visit to the park. Exhibits, films, and a bookstore allow visitors to explore the story of the Minuteman Intercontinental Ballistic Missile System and its role in the larger context of the Cold War. ***Please Be Aware*** Please plan accordingly. The park changes days of operation between the winters and the summers. Summer season: mid-May through mid-October, open Wed-Sun, 8am-4pm Winter season: mid-October through mid-May, open Tues-Sat, 8am-4pm
audioDescription: An approximately 12,000 square foot brown and white building with south facing glass windows lies afixed to a moderately sized parking lot. The parking lot accommodates between two and three dozen vehicles. The building is approximately the size of two school buses on top of one another, with an ornamental and narrow white triangular feature at the entrance.
passportStampLocationDescription: All our available stamps are located in the visitor center lobby. Minuteman Missile National Historic Site is also featured in the 2018 Passport To Your National Parks® Stamp Set. Special Note About The Sputnik Anniversary Stamp: This passport stamp is located in the Visitor Center lobby during normal operating hours only from October 4 through January 4 annually to mark the historic 1957-58 operation of the world's first satellite, and inspired the Minuteman Missile one year later.

name: Mississippi River Visitor Center
description: Located in downtown St. Paul, in the lobby of the Science Museum of Minnesota, the Mississippi River Visitor Center serves as a gateway to adventure along the mighty Mississippi. Find interactive exhibits and get advice from park rangers as to things to do and places to go. Admission is free.

name: Missouri National Recreational River Headquarters
description: The Missouri National Recreational River has a visitor contact station located inside their headquarters building in Yankton, South Dakota. Information about the park including junior ranger booklets, passport stamps, park maps, and an 18-minute video are available 8:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday through Friday. The building is closed on all federal holidays including Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's days. For more information, please call 605-665-0209.
audioDescription: Word Count: 566 The park headquarters is a brown-tan colored, one-story building 123 feet long wrapped from ground up to four feet with brown terracotta colored stones. The roof is flat. The south facing side of the building has five office windows; three windows are equally spaced across the building from east to west until it reaches the front or visitor entrance door. From the visitor entrance door to the west are two office windows. On the west side of the building is a large garage door measuring 12 feet wide by 12 feet tall and faces to the south; it's connected to a concrete driveway reaching 72 feet to Second Street. The visitor entrance door is connected to a concrete sidewalk that leads from the doorway to the east 100 feet to a public parking lot. A 9-foot wide entrance sign that reads "Missouri National Recreational River" in white lettering against a brown background sits off the sidewalk 14 feet in a front lawn of grass. A 40-foot aluminum flagpole sits 15 feet outside the visitor entrance doorway with an American Flag waving at full staff. Five feet before entering the building on the west is a 6 foot tall and 5 foot wide green information board covered in clear plexiglass containing park information and a park map fastened to the inside bulletin board. The entry door is glass framed in metal and measures 7 feet tall and 4 feet wide and sweeps open to the right. The door does not have an automatic door opener. Three feet inside the visitor entrance door, a blue door mat measuring 6 feet wide by 4 feet is on the floor. A large brown National Park Service Arrowhead logo is on the matt including the words in white lettering Missouri National Recreational River is located below the Arrowhead. 10 feet from the door mat is a free-standing curved wall standing 8 feet tall and 8 feet wide and centered in the room space. The wall is curved inward toward toward the visitor entrance. In the center of the inside curved area about 4 feet up from the floor is a three-foot wide black screened television monitor. To the left at about 10 feet is a wall map measuring 8 feet by 5 feet showing the Missouri River and highways, roads, and place features. The green-colored map is framed in brown wood. On both sides of the map stands a brochure rack. Below the map and centered on the wall between the two brochure racks is a rectangle table with a chair. The table has passport ink stampers and a visitor sign-in log book. From the visitor entrance doorway on the right is a rectangle table on four legs standing 3 feet above the floor. On the table sits a model of a river steamboat in a glass case. Located on the wall directly above the steamboat case, in six-inch black plastic lettering, are the words Missouri National Recreational River. From the right side of the curved wall about 10 feet to the north are restrooms for men and women. The men's restroom entrance is to the left. The woman's entrance is to the right. There is a water fountain that sticks out from the north wall 12 feet to the west from the restroom entrances. There are not exhibits in the room except for the glass-cased steamboat model. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: Cancellation stamp reads Missouri National Recreational River with SD and NE. Lewis and Clark National Historic Trail cancellation stamp also available. Missouri National Recreational River 40th stamp showcases a paddler on the river. Outdoor passport stamp station available 24/7.

name: Montgomery Interpretive Center
description: The Montgomery Interpretive Center is located on the campus of Alabama State University in Montgomery, AL. Inside the center, exhibits tell the history of the last leg of the 1965 Selma to Montgomery Voting Rights March, the student involvement in the Voting Rights Movement, and the rally that occurred at the City of St. Jude campus the fourth night of the march. A 20-minute film about student protests in Montgomery during March 1965 is available for viewing.
audioDescription: The Montgomery Interpretive Center is located on the busy Alabama State University Campus in Montgomery, Alabama. The center is surrounded by large buildings, busy streets, and has the backdrop of a large football stadium. The center is a stone structure with a mural of the March from Selma to Montgomery on the side facing the street. The mural is made of thousands of small circular divots that show foot soldiers marching holding an American Flag. The mural is best viewed from the parking lot. The mural also has a quote that states “ Let us march on till victory is won” from Lift Every Voice and Sing - James Weldon Johnson. From the parking lot you will cross the street to the center and just below the mural is a ramp for easy access that can be accessed on the right side of the building. If you do not wish to take the ramp you can access the center via the seven steps on the left most part of the building. Whether you take the ramp or the stairs you end up at the only entrance to the center. The entrance is simple overhang covered in thin wooden planks that provide shade and protection from the weather. From this space you can enter the center through two sets of doors. The first must be pulled toward you and the second set of doors open automatically. Upon entering the center on the right there is a large grey stone etched with a photograph of several marchers walking with linked arms. This stone wall also has water that streams down. On the left of the entrance is a large white wall with a quote that states “I got freedom on my mind”. Continuing on the left of the wall is a hallway leading to exhibits. Right past this hallway is the welcome desk where you can find park employee and passport stamps. Just past the desk you will encounter exhibits, artifacts, and photographs of organizations, people and events that occurred during the Civil Rights Movement.

name: Moses Cone Manor House
description: This visitor center information desk and America's National Parks store share a grand, historic estate with a craft shop operated by the Southern Highland Craft Guild. The visitor information desk and bookstore are open from May through October, while the craft shop is open from early April through November. The estate grounds have 25 miles of carriage roads for strolling, small lakes and other historic structures.

name: Mound City Group Visitor Center
description: The only visitor center among all open sites of Hopewell Culture National Historical Park is at Mound City Group. Except for Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day and New Year's Day, the visitor center maintains regular Hours of Operation on a daily basis. Mound City Group visitor center is located on the north side of Chillicothe, on State Route 104, just north of the intersection with U.S. 35.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 365 words. The visitor center is a tan wood and stone-sided, one-story structure approximately 40 feet wide at the front entrance with text letters to the right of the entrance doors on the south wall. The text reads “Hopewell Culture National Historical Park, Mound City Group, Visitor Center.” There is also a National Park Service arrowhead to the left of the text. The roof is made of red, smooth, flat steel slats with small raised ridges between them. Two cement walkways, surrounded by green lawn, lead from the asphalt parking lot to the main entrance on the south side of the building. Two 6-foot-tall waysides are placed to the right edge of the walkway, 50 feet before the entrance doors, where the two concrete walkways converge into one walkway. 15 feet before the entrance doors, there is a small plaza area with an L-shaped bench 5 feet to the right of the entrance doors. Stone pavers, each approximately 8 inches by 8 inches, fill the small plaza ground. There is an automatic open button for the entrance doors to the right of the entrance doors. 5 feet inside of the main entrance double doors, there is another set of double doors. There is an automatic open button for the second set of doors on the wall, to the right. The second set of doors leads to the lobby and a curved information desk which is 8 feet straight ahead after entering. The bookstore begins to the right of the information desk. The restrooms are to the right of the entrance doors. The women’s restroom entrance is 8 feet to the right of the entrance doors and the men’s restroom entrance is 20 feet to the right of the entrance doors. There is a water fountain that sticks out about 18 inches from the wall, between the women’s and men’s restrooms entrances. There is a museum (temporarily unavailable) and theater inside of the visitor center. The museum entrance is 15 feet past the information desk. The theater entrance is 20 feet past the information desk. The park brochure is available in braille. Text guides for the museum are available in large print. End of description.

name: Mount Locust Information Center Milepost 15.5
description: Located at milepost 15.5, the Mount Locust Information Center is at the site of the only remaining inn, or "stand" on the Parkway. During open hours, rangers are available to hand out maps, brochures, and answer questions about the historic house, just a short walk up he hill from the information center. Videos are available at https://www.nps.gov/natr/learn/photosmultimedia/videos.htm. Please visit the America's National Parks online store at https://shop.americasnationalparks.org/store/
audioDescription: The Mount Locust Information Center is a long single-story stone and wooden building that is parallel to the parking lot. The restrooms are on right side of the building with a locked door in between. The door on the left between the signs that say information and open/closed leads to a Park Ranger who is available to answer your questions and provide information. To the left of the door is a bench to rest on and a metal bicycle rack. The open breezeway in the middle leads you to the Mount Locust historic house.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available inside the visitor center during normal business hours.

name: Mount Washington Tavern
description: The Mount Washington Tavern is a museum that focuses on travel and life along the National Road in the early 1800s, when it was a stagecoach stop along the nation's first federally funded highway.
directionsInfo: The Mount Washington Tavern is located in the main unit of Fort Necessity National Battlefield on a hill overlooking Fort Necessity. Please stop at the Fort Necessity Visitor Center prior to visiting the tavern.

name: Muir Woods Visitor Center
description: Visitors are required to check-in at the Visitor Center upon arriving at Muir Woods. Purchase entrance tickets or use your annual pass here for entrance fees, as well as receive a free map of the main trail of the park. You can also purchase annual passes, a detailed trail map of the surrounding area, and a variety of books and souvenirs. You can also pick up a free Junior Ranger booklet here, leave a comment card, or connect with ranger staff.

name: Munising Falls Visitor Center
description: Munising Falls is located near the western gateway to Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore and at the beginning of the park's segment of the North Country National Scenic Trail. The visitor center is currently closed due to needed structural maintenance work. Information about the park is available on large bulletin boards in the parking lot. Also, see park website for more detailed information. Flush restrooms are available year-round. The paved trail to Munising Falls begins at the visitor center.
audioDescription: A concrete pathway from the parking lot winds its way to the visitor center and restroom buildings. The pathway goes between the two buildings on the way to the viewing platforms for Munising Falls. Trash and recycling receptacles and an informational bulletin board are located to your right as you approach the two buildings. The restrooms are in the building to your right. The entrances to each restroom are in a small alcove. The women’s restroom is to your left and the men’s restrooms are on your right. There is a center door for park storage. Inside each restroom, there are accessible stalls and sinks for handwashing. Munising Falls Visitor Center is directly across from the restrooms, or the building to the left as you come from the parking lot. The visitor center door opens outwards. Straight ahead when you enter, and along the left and far side of the building, is the cooperating association retail sales area. To the immediate right of the front door, are exhibits. They run along the right-hand side of the interior. The main exhibit describes the blast furnace mining industry in Munising. Continuing right and going past the exhibit and the retail areas, you will find the information desk. A large map of the park is located to your left when you face the information desk. The front door is the only entrance to the visitor center. As you head back towards the parking lot, the concrete pathway skirts along the left side of the parking lot passing by trash and recycling receptacles on your left and ending at a larger lot. Across the lot is a grassy picnic area under trees.
passportStampLocationDescription: Munising Falls Visitor Center has one passport stamp available. When the VC is closed, take a photo of the stamp that is posted on the outside information board. You can resize and print it on paper later, fill in the date, and then cut and paste it into your NPS passport book.

name: Munising Falls Visitor Contact Station
description: Munising Falls is located near the western gateway to Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore and at the beginning of the park's segment of the North Country National Scenic Trail. The visitor center is currently closed due to needed structural maintenance work. The temporary contact station closed for the season October 22 and will reopen mid-May 2023. Information about the park is available outside on large bulletin boards in the parking lot. Also, see the park website for more detailed information.
audioDescription: A concrete pathway from the parking lot winds its way to the visitor center and restroom buildings. The pathway goes between the two buildings on the way to the viewing platforms for Munising Falls. On the path there is a temporary visitor contact station set up in a trailer. There is a wooden deck with a short staircase and railings in front, and an accessible ramp with railings on the right side of the trailer. Once on the deck, staff is available to provide maps and information, as well as passes, through a service window. Back on the concrete path, trash and recycling receptacles and an informational bulletin board are located to your right as you approach the two buildings. The restrooms are in the building to your right. The entrances to each restroom are in a small alcove. The women’s restroom is to your left and the men’s restroom is on your right. There is a center door for park storage. Inside each restroom, there are accessible stalls and sinks for handwashing. Munising Falls Visitor Center is directly across from the restrooms, or the building to the left as you come from the parking lot. The visitor center is temporarily closed. As you head back towards the parking lot, the concrete pathway skirts along the left side of the parking lot passing by trash and recycling receptacles on your left and ending at a larger lot. Across the lot is a grassy picnic area under trees.
passportStampLocationDescription: Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore passport stamp is available at the temporary visitor contact station during summer operating hours. Stamp reads "Pictured Rocks National Lakeshore, Munising - Grand Marais, MI" in orange text.

name: Murie Science and Learning Center
description: The Murie Science and Learning Center (MSLC) is located at Mile 1.3 of the Denali Park Road at the entrance of Denali National Park and Preserve. The Murie Science and Learning Center is closed to the public in summer. It serves as an operations base for registration-based educational programs. In winter, the MSLC serves as Denali’s Winter Visitor Center. A 24-hour Automated Fee Machine is located outside the building. You can purchase the park entrance fee and Denali Annual Pass here by credit card only.

name: Museum Information Desk
description: Visitors to the museum at Belmont-Paul Women's Equality National Monument are greeted by a friendly member of our staff of rangers and volunteers. At the desk, you can stamp your National Park Service Passport book, pick up a Junior Suffragist booklet, and chat about the ongoing struggle for women's equality.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport cancellation stamps are available at the information desk for Belmont-Paul Women's Equality National Monument, When the museum is closed to visitors, you can find the Belmont-Paul Women's Equality NM stamp at the Dwight D. Eisenhower Memorial on Independence Ave SW between 4th & 6th Streets.

directionsInfo: Belmont-Paul Women's Equality NM is located on Capitol Hill at the corner of Constitution Avenue and 2nd Street, NE, next to the Hart Senate Office Building. It is a free-standing, federal style brick house surrounded by a black cast-iron fence. The entrance for museum tours and the museum shop is located on 2nd Street. Follow the entrance signs to the brick stairway. The exterior lift is temporarily out of order. We apologize for the inconvenience. The doors facing Constitution Avenue are not entrances.

name: Museum and Visitor Center
description: Gettysburg National Military Park Museum and Visitor Center is the place to begin your visit to the battlefield. Here you will learn how to visit the park and what to see around Gettysburg. Backpacks are not permitted in the Museum and Visitor Center. (Exceptions are backpacks that are medical and/or first-aid packs, camera bags, or baby essential bags.) The Museum and Visitor Center is privately owned and operated by the Gettysburg Foundation, in partnership with the National Park Service.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Gettysburg National Military Park and Eisenhower National Historic Site passport stamps are available at the Gettysburg National Military Park Museum and Visitor Center information desk.

name: Museum of North Carolina Minerals
description: The Museum of North Carolina Minerals highlights the rich mineral resources & the mining heritage of this portion of the Blue Ridge. The museum is open year-round with interactive & experiential exhibits for children & adults. This area, called Gillespie Gap, was also significant in the American Revolution, where frontiersmen from the mountains known as the "Overmountain Men" crossed the Blue Ridge on their way to battle at Kings Mountain. The Mitchell County Chamber of Commerce has an information desk.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps are located in the America's National Parks store in the visitor center.

name: Museum of North Carolina Minerals, Blue Ridge Parkway Visitor Center
description: Blue Ridge Parkway Visitor Center and Museum of North Carolina Minerals, located along the Overmountain Victory National Historic Trail at Gillespie Gap. Featuring displays about the history and geology of western North Carolina and the Blue Ridge Mountains, and hiking trail along the Overmountain Victory NHT. On September 29, 1780, the Overmountain Men descended the east face of the Blue Ridge Mountains through Gillespie and Hefner Gaps using separate trails before reuniting at the Catawba River.

name: Museum of the National Park Ranger
description: Once a US Army outpost built in 1908, this visitor center houses exhibits that celebrate the history of the park ranger profession. To enhance the story of the park ranger experience, this visitor center is staffed by volunteer retired rangers. The current structure replaced previous structures dating back to 1884.

name: Museum of the Sea
description: About 50 miles south of the seashore's north entrance is the Hatteras Island Visitor Center and Museum of the Sea in Buxton, NC. The Museum of the Sea is within the historic Cape Hatteras Lighthouse Double Keepers' Quarters. The two-floor museum contains exhibits on Outer Banks history and natural history. A small audiovisual room provides video presentations, available upon request. Between the Park Store and the Museum of the Sea stands the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse.
audioDescription: From the main parking area at the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, follow the walkway past the visitor center and continue down the sidewalk to the lighthouse. Continue past the lighthouse along the brick walkway and the Museum of the Sea will be at the end of the path. Enter the museum using the left door. Inside, the movie room on your left shows the park film. Exhibits on the first floor explore maritime history and the move of the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse. The upstairs of the museum can be accessed by staircases on both ends of the building. Exhibits upstairs explore additional natural and cultural resources found here at Cape Hatteras.

name: NPS Visitor Center
description: Start your visit at the National Park Service's Visitor Center in Middletown, Virginia. Pick up maps and a Junior Ranger activity book. Plan your visit with a park ranger or volunteer. See exhibits to learn about the settlement and agricultural history of the Shenandoah Valley as well as its role as an important theater of war during the Civil War.

name: Namekagon River Visitor Center
description: The Namekagon River Visitor Center is closed for the season and may reopen Memorial Day weekend in 2024. When open, visitors can view exhibits, pick up park publications, Junior Ranger booklets, and maps, and watch the park movie. Park rangers staff an information counter and offer trip planning assistance for the Namekagon and upper St. Croix rivers. The visitor center is located near the Namekagon River off Highway 63 in Trego, Wisconsin.
audioDescription: A single story green and brown building with a cross-gable roof. A main entrance door and two employee service doors face the front of the building. Concrete walkways surround the building's front with a concrete walkway leading to the entrance door. Between the building and the walkways is landscaped with wildflowers and low-growing native plants.

name: Natchez Trace Parkway Visitor Center
description: The National Park Service administers the national battlefield site through the Natchez Trace Parkway. Since there are no visitor facilities at the battlefield site, visitors are welcome to learn more about the battlefield at the Parkway Visitor Center, located 15 miles south of Brices Cross Roads in Tupelo, at Milepost 266 of the Natchez Trace Parkway. The Parkway Visitor Center is open every day of the year except Thanksgiving. December 25, and January 1 from 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. (Central Time).
audioDescription: The Parkway Visitor Center is a single story red brick building that is parallel to the parking lot. The words Visitor Center Natchez Trace Parkway on the left hand side of the building front. The restroom entrance is around the right side corner. A water fountain and water bottle filling station is near the entrance of the restrooms. You can enter the visitor center in the center of the building through the glass door which is located under an covered awning. You walk through two sets of glass doors before entering the visitor center. The Park Information desk is on your right hand side after you enter through the second door. A park ranger or volunteer will be happy to assist you at the information desk.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Brices Cross Roads National Battlefield passport stamp can be found at the Parkway Visitor Center during normal business hours. The visitor center is closed on Thanksgiving, December 25th and January 1st.

name: Natchez Trace Parkway Visitor Center

Visitors are welcome to ask questions and learn more about the battlefield at the Parkway Visitor Center (Milepost 266) located about six miles north of the monument. The Visitor Center is open every day of the year except Thanksgiving, December 25, and January 1 from 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. (Central Time). The Natchez Trace Parkway can be reached at 800-305-7417.

You can enter the visitor center in the center of the building through the glass door which is located under a covered awning. You walk through two sets of glass doors before entering the visitor center. The Park Information desk is on your right-hand side after you enter through the second door. name: Natchez Visitor Center
description: The Natchez Visitor Reception Center is owned, operated and maintained by the National Park Service. The building also serves as the official southern terminus and welcome center for the Natchez Trace Parkway. The Natchez Visitor Center is home to Natchez National Historical Park Headquarters, the Mississippi Welcome Center, and the City of Natchez Visitor Information Services. Currently, the Natchez Visitor Center is closed due to construction surrounding the installation of a new HVAC system.
audioDescription: The Natchez Visitor Center is located in a large, modern building at the busy corner of Canal Street and John R. Junkin Drive, near the Mississippi River bridge connecting Natchez with Vidalia, Louisiana. The entrance to the building is adjacent to a large parking lot. Restrooms are accessible from the exterior of the building and are located immediately to the left of the main entrance. The visitor center also serves as a Mississippi State Welcome Center. Visitors will find themselves in a large lobby with expansive views of the Mississippi River. The lobby contains racks with cards and brochures for attractions throughout the Natchez and Miss-Lou areas as well as the state of Mississippi. Park personnel are stationed at counters along the right side of the lobby and are there to answer any questions. Exhibits detailing the history of Natchez are located along the right side of the lobby just passed the information counters. At the end of the lobby is the Natchez Shop, our primary bookstore which contains books, souvenirs and collectibles. Immediately to the left of the bookstore entrance, a glassed-in walkway takes visitors to a platform where they can enjoy a view of the river and Mississippi bridges. The walkway also leads guests to the mezzanine level where they can view an exhibit on the cartography associated with nearby Fort Rosalie, the 1716 French fort that established Natchez as one of the oldest settlements on the Mississippi.
passportStampLocationDescription: At the Natchez Visitor Center, one has access to six (6) passport stamps for the Natchez National Historical Park which include the following park sites: Melrose, Fort Rosalie, and the William Johnson House. Visitors may also receive a stamp for the Natchez Trace Parkway, the park's Junior Ranger stamp, and the National Park Service's centennial stamp.

name: Nathaniel P. Reed Visitor Center
description: Nathaniel P. Reed Visitor Center is a facility that was designed with energy conservation in mind, making maximum use of renewable resources. The visitor center offers indoor and outdoor exhibits related to the history of the Big Cypress Swamp, as well as printed materials and an introductory film to the Preserve, its resources and recreational opportunities. The auditorium is available to reserve.
audioDescription: Entering the parking area, the pastel green building is on the right. Breezeways at each end of the building provide access to the visitor center interior and lead to the boardwalk behind the building. The breezeway closest to the parking area also has public restrooms. The information desk is in the center of the room. Museum exhibits are found at both ends of the space. A park store sales area is found in the southeast corner of the visitor center. Beyond the eastern breezeway are doors that lead to the auditorium. A 28-minute Preserve orientation movie is shown on a continuous basis. Behind the visitor center is a 100 meter boardwalk that offers views and photo opportunities of the mangrove estuary. Manatees are often seen here in the winter months.

name: National Elk Refuge & Greater Yellowstone Visitor Center
description: The National Elk Refuge & Greater Yellowstone Visitor Center is an visitor center located in Jackson, WY. The visitor center is owned and operated by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service on the National Elk Refuge. The six agencies that operate from the visitor center are the Bridger-Teton National Forest, Grand Teton Association, Grand Teton National Park, National Elk Refuge, Jackson Hole Chamber of Commerce, and Wyoming Game & Fish.

name: National Prisoner of War Museum
description: At the National Prisoner of War Museum, the story of American prisoners of war (POWs) is powerfully presented through exhibits, audio-visual displays, and historic artifacts. The museum serves as the park's visitor center. You can find information, audio tours, and a gift shop with items about Andersonville, the Civil War, and POWs of other American wars. The museum has a theater where you can view two 30-minute films, including one about Andersonville and one about all American POWs.
audioDescription: As you approach the museum, two brick columns frame the walkway; each bears a plaque with the museum's logo: a star behind a single strand of barbed wire, conveying the hardships of confinement and a love of country shared by prisoners of war. Approaching the building, across a clean sweep of lawn, you see a long-low, solid dark-maroon brick building punctuated with three grey granite towers. The building form is reminiscent of prisons and uses the thematic elements common to all POW stories: towers, gates, confinement, water, and light. Walking toward the building from the parking lot, visitors are forced to approach in pairs or single file up a narrow straight walk leading between two small, square brick buildings. These buildings and the black entry gate serve to constrict the approach to quiet groups and create a feeling of tension prior to entering the lobby. The brick, slate, and granite materials of the museum were chosen to immortalize the losses suffered by American soldiers over the last two centuries. The use of these materials links the visitor to the physical reality of imprisonment, a reality defined by solid forms which keep the captive from family, freedom, and country.
passportStampLocationDescription: The park has 2 passport stamps. One is a circle with the date in the center, and with Andersonville NHS along the top and Andersonville, GA along the bottom. The other is a circle with the date in the center, and with Andersonville NHS along the top and Andersonville National Cemetery along the bottom.

name: Nature Center
description: The Nature Center is home to our Planetarium and nature exhibit area which features displays of plants and animals that can be found in the park. Most of Rock Creek park's public and educational programs begin at the Nature Center.
audioDescription: The Nature Center is a long, low building at the end of a long parking area. It is surrounded by deciduous trees and nestled against a hill side. From the front, the structure appears to be a single story, but from the rear it is a two story building. A small ramp leads up to the front glass doors for accessibility in addition to two small steps going directly to a covered front porch area. The building has an addition to the north where the planetarium was built and this structure sits slightly below that of the main section of the nature center. Paved pathways and a wooden boardwalk lead to the rear of the building where there is an elevated porch that exits off the exhibit area and a wheel chair accessible entrance to the lower section of the building which enters into the 150 seat auditorium. Many trails, both paved and dirt converge at or near the building.

name: Navajo Bridge Interpretive Center
description: Bookstore, outdoor exhibits, and self guided walks across the historic Navajo Bridge. This is a popular spot to look for California Condors.
audioDescription: Small rectangular building made from local rocks and set into the canyon at Navajo Bridge on U.S. Highway 89A. Parking lot is also small. There is an area in front to drop off passengers. Entry is accessible. There are no stairs. A few exhibits inside about the bridges and surrounding areas. Outdoor shade structure requires some steps up and down. The walking bridge across the Colorado River is flat and wheelchair accessible. Restrooms are outside of the visitor center and only available when the visitor center is open. The restrooms have vault toilets and no running water. The parking lot is closed when the building is closed.
passportStampLocationDescription: Navajo Bridge Interpretive Center holds the stamps for Glen Canyon National Recreation Area (Navajo Bridge, Marble Canyon, AZ), and Vermilion Cliffs National Monument (Marble Canyon, AZ). These stamps are not available when the visitor center is closed.

name: New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park
description: The park is devoted to sharing the origins of jazz and its development through today via performances, ranger talks, and other programs. French Quarter Visitor Center for New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park visitor center is at 419 Decatur St, New Orleans, LA 70130. Open Tuesday-Saturday, 9:30 am - 4:30 pm. The secondary site for New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park, at 916 N Peters St. New Orleans, LA 70116, is open only for special events. See our event calendar for more details.
audioDescription: French Quarter Visitor Center for New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park is at 419 Decatur St, New Orleans, LA 70130. Open Tuesday-Saturday, 9:30 am - 4:30 pm. This visitor center is on Decatur Street, between St. Louis and Conti Streets. It is near the statue of Bienville. The secondary site for New Orleans Jazz National Historical Park, at 916 N Peters St. New Orleans, LA 70116, is open only for special events. (See calendar for details.)

name: Nez Perce National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: Contains a museum, park film, junior ranger program, and various maps and brochures.
audioDescription: As you enter the visitor center, you see a large ranger-staffed information desk and a mural showing historic Nez Perce people carving canoes, drying salmon, and playing near the banks of a river. In front of that mural is a real Nez Perce canoe that is believed to be about 200 years old, protected behind waist-high plexiglass. There is a small gift store containing shirts, postcards, mugs, magnets, pins, and a few other items. There are two doors in the main visitor center room, one near the mural/canoe and one near the gift shop. The door near the canoe leads to the auditorium, where the park film is played. The door near the gift store leads to the museum, which contains a wealth of historic Nez Perce clothing, tools, and other artifacts.
passportStampLocationDescription: Contains stamps for: Nez Perce National Historical Park, Lewis and Clark National Historic Trail, Nez Perce National Historic Trail, and nine of our park sites (Canoe Camp, Bear Paw Battlefield, Weippe Prairie, Spalding, Old Joseph Gravesite, Buffalo Eddy, Heart of the Monster, Big Hole Battlefield, and White Bird Battlefield). We also have a Junior Ranger stamp.

name: Ninety Six National Historic Site
description: Open Wednesday-Sunday from 9:00 am to 4:30 pm, closed Monday and Tuesday. Museum contains a reproduction 3-pounder cannon, artifacts found on the battlefield, and other exhibits. "Ninety Six: Crossroads" is a 22-minute video shown on request. Sales Outlet operated by America's National Parks offers books, postcards, and theme-related souvenirs.
audioDescription: As visitors exit their cars, they will come to a brick patio with the shape of the Star Fort inlaid in it. Around this patio are interpretive signs to get them started on their exploration of the park. From the patio they can pick up the main loop trail around the battlefield. Entering the patio area from the parking lot a ramp on the left leads to the restrooms. To the right is the Logan Log House, a structure built in the Greenwood area around the 1780s or 1790s. Continuing straight they will find a board walk leading to the Visitor Center. Next to the board walk a swivel gun is on display. Across from the swivel gun is a bulletin board where visitor can learn more about park events safety regulations and reminders.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is available at visitor center when it is open. If you visit the park when the visitor center is closed, you can find it in a box connected to the bulletin board located between the restrooms and the visitor center.
