name: Niobrara National Scenic River Visitor Center
description: Begin your journey down the Niobrara at the visitor center, where you may discover what makes this river so special through exhibits and a twenty minute park film. Park rangers are on hand to answer questions, help you plan your trip, or give you a list of outfitters who will provide transportation and canoes, kayaks, or tubes.
audioDescription: Niobrara National Scenic River Visitor Center. 575 words. The visitor center is a brown tin-sided, one-story, “L” shaped structure with a white tin roof and white gutters. The length of the building that runs South to North is approximately 40 feet long with a manual door to a small vestibule 30 feet from the southern end. The building is located on a city street and is surrounded by various residential and commercial buildings. On the wall between the south end of the building and the door large text reads “Niobrara National Scenic River Visitor Center, National Park Service.” There is also a National Park Service arrowhead to the left of the text. Above the text on the wall there are three small narrow horizontal windows, approximately 4 feet across. Ten feet to the right of the door to the vestibule is the corner of the building, and the West to East wing extends approximately 50 feet from this corner. There are five large windows spaced evenly along this wall. Sidewalks run directly along the building’s walls, and a concrete parking lot fills the space in front of the building. There is a handicap parking space directly to the left of the manual door to the vestibule, and an up-sloped ramp leads from the parking lot to the manual vestibule entrance door. The entrance vestibule is approximately 5 feet across and 7 feet deep. Straight through the vestibule is a manual door to the visitor center. The floor is tile. Inside the manual door to the interior of the visitor center, the information desk is located immediately ahead. The floor is short carpet, and the walls are white. The ceiling is approximately 14 feet high. The information desk has two lengths, one that is four feet long faces the entrance door, and the other that is four feet long and faces the open room. Beyond the ranger desk along the North wall, there is a door for employees followed by approximately 10 feet of wall displays for the Park’s Bookstore. To the right, about four feet is a locked door. To the left, there is a donation box and a park bench and two displays against the wall that runs South to North. To the right of the bench and the left of the ranger desk, the space opens into a room approximately 30 feet, East to West, by 40 feet, North to South. There are two tables in the room, one is 12 feet long with tactile display objects on it. The touch table is 8 feet from the South wall and runs West to East. There is a 5-foot-wide, round table in the middle of the room with four, wheeled chairs around it. On the western wall (the back wall when facing the information desk from the front door) approximately 12 feet beyond the information desk, is a 4-foot-wide, 20-foot-long hallway that faces west. On the right-hand wall of the hallway, two feet from its entrance, is the door to the women’s restroom. 6 feet from the entrance of the hallway on the right-hand side, there are two drinking fountains set back into a four-foot-wide alcove, and two feet beyond the alcove is the door to the men’s restroom. After the door to the Men’s Restroom, there is a locked door. Along the left wall of the hallway, approximately 7 feet from the entrance, is a door to the theater. The hallway has an emergency exit at the end. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: There is a Passport Stamp located at the Niobrara National Scenic River Visitor Center. If we are closed, the Stamp is also located at the Fort Niobrara National Wildlife Refuge Visitor Center and Smith Falls State Park Visitor Center.

name: Norris Geyser Basin Museum and Information Station
description: Situated on the ridge overlooking the Norris Geyser Basin, this historic building is staffed during the summer with rangers who provide park information and facilitate ranger programs. Visitors have been seeking information here since 1930 when the museum was built as a "trailside museum" to serve people traveling in their own automobiles without a guide. Restrooms are located in the parking lot.
passportStampLocationDescription: Collect your passport stamp for the Norris Geyser Basin by stopping by the Yellowstone Forever bookstore, located near the Norris Geyser Basin Museum and Visitor Center.

name: North Bridge Visitor Center
description: The North Bridge visitor center is closed for winter. It will re-open in May 2024. It is located about 500 yards from the North Bridge battle site. Here you can see exhibits about the battle, watch a short film, get park information and shop in the park store.
audioDescription: From the parking area the visitor center is reached by a paved path that leads to the front entrance. The building is a large brick mansion house built in 1911. The door is located in the center of the building under a cement portico. Wheelchair accessible entrance is around the right side of the building. Continue to follow the paved path around the building to the ramp under another portico on the right side of the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport Stamps at North Bridge Visitor Center are only available during operating hours throughout the regular season. The North Bridge Visitor Center runs from the beginning of April- October 31. The stamps are located in the visitor center gift shop. Stamps include: North Bridge Visitor Center Stamp Underground Railroad Network to Freedom Stamp Junior Ranger Stamp

name: North Cascades Visitor Center
description: Location: Across the Skagit River from the North Cascades Highway (State Route 20) near milepost 120 and the town of Newhalem. Adjacent to Newhalem Creek Campground. Exhibits: Relief map of the park and surrounding area, exhibit room featuring multimedia exhibits on the park's natural and cultural history. Available Facilities: Theater featuring large format slide program and video presentation. Several short, accessible interpretive trails and restrooms. Information desk. Bookstore.
audioDescription: North Cascades Visitor Center is located in a forested area not far from the Skagit River. From the visitor center, one can see the charred trees and other evidence from a wildfire in 2015. Behind the visitor center, there is a short walk to a view of snowy, ragged peaks.

name: North Rim Visitor Center Park Store
description: The Visitor Center/Park Store will be open for the season between May 15, and October 15, 2024. Visitors have an opportunity to ask questions, plan trips, and learn about the day's activities and programs. The store offers a wide variety of books, maps, souvenirs, and gift items and is open from 9 am to 5 pm daily. Park rangers also staff an outdoor information desk between 10 am and 4 pm daily, at the Roaring Springs Overlook Kiosk, just north of the Visitor Center building, and along the canyon rim.
passportStampLocationDescription: The North Rim Visitor Center has its own unique, official, dated passport cancellation stamp which reads "North Rim" at the bottom. As this visitor center contains a park bookstore, it also features a special Grand Canyon Conservancy stamp featuring Brighty the Burro.

directionsInfo: Leaving U.S. 89A at the Jacob Lake junction, travel south on State Route 67 and drive 43 miles through forests and meadows to the North Rim of Grand Canyon. The North Rim Visitor Center is at the end of State Route 67, within the Grand Canyon Lodge complex, on the left, and adjacent to the main parking area for the lodge and Bright Angel Point. The North Rim of the park, as well as State Route 67 closes to all vehicle traffic from December 1, through May 14, due to snow.

name: Northwest Arctic Heritage Center
description: Large, half-dome shaped, blue and grey building with just over 11,000 square feet of space. The museum space is just over 1,800 square feet and contains animal displays, soundscapes, tactile exhibits and more. The Heritage Center also contains a bookstore, restroom, art gallery, and sitting area. The Northwest Arctic Heritage Center serves as the visitor centers for the Western Arctic National Parklands: Kobuk Valley National Park, Cape Krusenstern National Monument, and Noatak National Preserve.
audioDescription: An approximately 30 foot entrance ramp leads to main glass doorway. Upon entering the first door, you will be inside a small room with a glass wall and stuffed polar bear to your left and Alaskan map and mammoth tusk directly in front of you. Continue to your right approximately 14 feet to the next set of glass doors to enter the main visitor area of the building. A large map of the Western Arctic National Parklands is on your left and built in glass display case on your right displays cultural artifacts. Continue straight approximately 30 feet to reach a large regional map on your right, artist gallery and sitting area with couches and table and chairs directly in front of you, a large, wooden structure of a tradition umiaq (or boat) hanging from the vaulted ceiling 15 feet above you, and a Ranger desk and bookstore to your left. Continue past the Ranger desk to enter a short hallway. Approximately 9 feet to the left are the restrooms and water fountains; if you walk toward the restrooms, the women's are on the left, the men's on the right, with the water fountain in the middle against the wall. If you continue down the hallway next to the Ranger desk, the movie room will be on your right, approximately 6 feet passed the restrooms. This room is a large, mostly empty space with cultural posters and murals on the back walls and black chairs facing a large projector screen. Continuing down the hallway passed the movie room entrance approximately 15 feet, you will enter the museum. The museum is set up in a large oval shape approximately 55 feet long and 20 feet wide with display lining the outer walls and forming a small island in the middle . Continue around the room in a clockwise fashion by turning left upon entering. Throughout the room you will find displays of animals, plants, and cultural items as well as hands on activities and soundscapes.

directionsInfo: Noatak National Preserve is a very remote area. There are no roads that provide access. Commercial airlines provide service from Anchorage to Kotzebue or Fairbanks to Bettles. Once in Kotzebue or Bettles, you must fly to the preserve with various air taxi operators. There are scheduled flights to villages and chartered flights to remote park areas. Summer access may include motorized/non-motorized watercraft, aircraft, or by foot.

name: Oak Ridge Visitor Center
description: The Oak Ridge Visitor Center is located within the Children's Museum of Oak Ridge. Here you are able to speak with National Park Service rangers, watch a short film on the Manhattan Project, and get literature on Manhattan Project-related historic sites throughout Oak Ridge. Visitor Center services are limited on Sundays, but brochures, maps, and site films are available.
passportStampLocationDescription: Three passport stamps are available at the Oak Ridge visitor center.

name: Oakland Plantation Store
description: The park does not have a visitor center, though the historic Oakland Plantation Store is the park's main visitor contact station Wednesday through Sunday. Inside the store you'll find historic exhibits and a park store/gift shop. NPS passport stamps and Junior Ranger books are located inside the store. The park store/gift shop is closed on Monday and Tuesday.
audioDescription: From your vehicle you will walk south approximately 100-250 feet to the pavilion. The pavilion has a large opening located on the north side of the structure to walk through. Here you will find a water fountain and water filling station and restrooms as well as picnic tables. The center aisle is open with tables located on both sides. Under your feet you should feel a more solid surface- concrete. To locate the bathrooms, take 10 steps forward and turn left. Take five steps and turn right. Take seven steps and turn right. In front of you is a foyer where the bathrooms and water fountain are located. The water fountain is directly in front- 15 feet away. The men’s room is at a diagonal to your left, the women’s rest room is at a diagonal to your right. Both restroom doors are located on the same wall as the water fountain. Let’s get you up to the plantation store when you’re ready. There’s a second large opening like the one you entered the pavilion located on the east side of the structure. Where you initially turned to locate the bathrooms, you’ll want to walk forward a few feet until you feel a rubber matting under your shoes. You’ll be on this matting for a while and you find it throughout the park. Be careful, initially this trail has a few twists and turns within the first 200 feet. You also might feel the matting disappear and feel grass or even gravel under your feet- Don’t worry – you’re on the correct path. Keep walking forward and within about 75 yards you’ll be at the back of the plantation store. To your left is a fence line that separates the main house grounds from the path your walking. To your right is a large field. Once you feel more of the rubber matting in an open space you have arrived at the store. To your left is an accessible ramp that will take you to the back porch of the store and in front of you are two brick stairs that can also access the same location. Be careful, there are a bench and rocking chair on the back porch and space is limited. The door should be open. To the right of the door is a working doorbell- push it- it still works!
passportStampLocationDescription: The park has three passport stamps. Cane River Creole NHP, Cane River National Heritage Area , and El Camino Real De Los Tejas NHT.

directionsInfo: To reach Oakland Plantation, take I-49 to Exit 127, Flora/Cypress. Head east on LA Highway 120 toward Cypress. Cross over LA Highway 1 onto LA Highway 494. The parking lot and entrance pavilion for Oakland is 4.5 miles east of Highway 1 on the left. To reach the grounds of Magnolia Plantation, take I-49 to Exit 119, Derry. Head east on LA Highway 119. Cross over LA Highway 1 and proceed for 1.1 miles. The parking area of Magnolia Plantation is on the right just before the road closure.

name: Oasis Visitor Center
description: The Oasis Visitor Center contains exhibits related to the natural and cultural history of the preserve, educational materials, sales items, and an introductory film. Staff are available to assist visitors with information about available activities.
audioDescription: A large gray colored building with a short boardwalk out front overlooking a canal.

directionsInfo: If driving from Miami, visitors will find it fastest to find US-41 / Tamiami Trail northbound (called SW 8th Street in Miami itself) and proceed northbound (techinically, you are travelling west) all the way out. From the Keys or Homestead, Florida, we recommend taking 997 Krome Avenue, North to reach US-41. Once you leave the edge of Miami (at the intersection of US-41 / 997) you will drive about 40 miles. Oasis Visitor Center is located on the right, on the north side of US-41.

name: Obed Visitor Center
description: The visitor center has free WiFi, and offers exhibits on the river, its inhabitants, the cultural history of the area, and the recreational opportunities that the park provides. The visitor center also offers an award-winning orientation film. A small bookstore is also included in the visitor center, which is open daily from 9:00-5:00 pm (ET), daily. The visitor center is closed Thanksgiving, December 25, and January 1. Address: 208 North Maiden Street Wartburg, Tennessee, 37887
audioDescription: From the front visitor center parking lot, the main entrance is in the center of the building up a slight ramp. There are two doors that lead into a foyer and then another set of doors to go through. Once inside, there are offices on the right and left side of the large open room. Directly ahead of entering the front door is a water fountain with some wildlife exhibits. A back door exit is directly to the left of the fountain. Just to the right of the fountain is a bookstore with some souvenirs and books. This meets up with the far edge of the visitor center contact desk where a ranger greets people. The accessible restrooms are directly to the right and then into a hallway. Just inside the hallway and directly to the left is the first restroom. Another restroom is down the hall and to the left and then another left. Just outside this restroom door is the water fountain and water filling station. Back in the main room which lays center to the front entrance there is a set of benches that set in line on the left side of the room with a large TV display for a movie viewing. A ranger will start the movie whenever you request to view it. Captioning is available.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport cancellation stamp is located on the desk of the visitor center directly to the right of the front doors. The stamp is a hand-held type with blue ink.

name: Oconaluftee Visitor Center
description: Near Cherokee, North Carolina, the Oconaluftee Visitor Center is an ideal starting point as you enter the park's South District. Explore cultural history exhibits. Enjoy ranger-led programs conducted seasonally. Peruse the park bookstore and shop. Find public restrooms and drink vending machines. The adjacent Mountain Farm Museum contains a collection of log structures including a farmhouse, barn, smokehouse, applehouse, corn crib and others.
audioDescription: As you approach the visitor center, a large welcoming porch overlooks the Mountain Farm Museum and rocking chairs invite visitors to rest a while and enjoy the view. Once inside, you're met by a small exhibit area and fireplace with a monitor showcasing helpful information. To the left, there is a visitor center desk where you will find a knowledgeable group of volunteers and park rangers to assist with questions, directions and swearing in Jr. Rangers. Straight ahead there is an exhibit area that offers a glimpse of the park's establishment along a timeline from the Cherokee to early European settlement. To the right, there is a bookstore/souvenir shop. There's something for everyone!

name: Ocracoke Island Discovery Center
description: The Ocracoke Island Discovery Center is where you can go within the village of Ocracoke to get park information and start your exploration of Ocracoke Island.
audioDescription: From the discovery center parking lot, you will follow the sidewalk up to the boardwalk. Walk up the boardwalk and the discovery center will be the building on your left. Enter through the front door and inside you will find educational exhibits that explore the local ecosystem, sea turtles, shorebirds, science in the park, and Outer Banks history. Restrooms are located outside, in the building just to the right of the visitor center.

name: Ohanapecosh Visitor Center
description: This visitor center is located in the southeast corner of the park on State Route 123, 12 miles north of the town of Packwood. It is next to the Ohanapecosh Campground and near the trailhead for the Natural Hot Springs and Silver Falls. There are restrooms, exhibits, and a ranger or volunteer on duty to answer questions when it is open for the summer season.
audioDescription: The Ohanapecosh Visitor Center consists of bathrooms and information boards outside the building. Inside, the visitor center consists of one large room with exhibit panels educating visitors on the history and natural resources of the area. There is an information desk to the right upon entering and a small seating area to the left. There is a small book store behind the desk where visitors can purchase books and maps. The rest of the room has exhibits. The building itself is Mission 66 style, and surrounded by tall fir and cedar trees. There are also numerous types of smaller plants that can be found here, including alder and various wildflowers. There is parking in front of the building to the left. A path to the left of the building leads visitors to a large tree round with various world events marked on the tree like a timeline. There is a covered area with a few benches underneath. A path behind the building connects visitors to various hiking trails, including the Hot Springs Trail and the Silver Falls Trail.

name: Old Faithful Visitor Education Center
description: Located near Old Faithful Geyser, this visitor center offers views of the geyser's eruption from the tall, windowed front of the visitor center. Additionally, you can gather park information, talk with a park ranger at the front desk, shop for souvenirs in the park store, delve into the natural wonders of Yellowstone in the exhibit hall, join a ranger program, or use the restrooms.
audioDescription: Old Faithful Visitor Education Center 473 words You are standing in front of the Old Faithful Visitor Education Center. Exterior features of this wide structure include brown composite shingles, multiple roof lines, and a multi-story glass section in its center. The triangular gable roof shading this tall glass-front section is supported by steel beams; wood and glass double doors provide an entrance to the building at porch level. The sloping porch roof below, and on either side of, the central gable and entrance doors is supported by several large stone pillars. The cement porch spans left and right in front of the entrance. As you approach the building through the large circular cement plaza in front of the building, you will encounter a large sign standing beside a flagpole flying the United States flag. Text on the sign reads: “Old Faithful Visitor Education Center.” Attached on the sign’s left side is the arrowhead-shaped National Parks Service emblem featuring a single sequoia tree standing beside a snow-capped mountain and one lone bison. The stairs leading to the porch form a wide concave arc spanning nearly the entire width of the building. On the far left of this arc, one narrow section of stairs offers handrails on both sides. If you chose to enter somewhere along the wider stair section, please note that there are no handrails. You must also take care to avoid a pile of boulders located at the base of the stairs slightly left of the entrance doors. The boulders are surrounded by metal railings on three sides with the side facing the plaza left open. Another such boulder display is located in the plaza’s center. There is also a wheelchair ramp located to the right of the wall enclosing the right side of the wider stair section. This ramp curves upward from the plaza to the porch. A round metal button emblazoned with a drawing of a wheelchair and the words “Press to Open” is located on the outer frame of the right-hand entrance door. You will also encounter a large rubber mat in front of the doors. A small sign on each door gives the hours the visitor center is open. There are three benches on the porch--one to the left of the entrance and two to the right--positioned against the building’s front wall. More benches are placed in various spots behind the building, which overlooks Old Faithful geyser. If you prefer to view the geyser from indoors, there are several benches in front of the floor-to-ceiling glass window on the center’s rear wall. This viewing area is nearly a mirror image of the multi-story entrance area. Other indoor features include an information desk staffed by park rangers, interactive exhibits, an educational bookstore, and an auditorium. Public restrooms and drinking fountains are located to your right as you step inside the entrance. END OF MESSAGE

name: Old Slater Mill Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Contact Station at Old Slater Mill is operated seasonally. Please see active exceptions to ensure that the visitor contact station is open for your visit.
audioDescription: The Visitor Contact Station at Old Slater Mill is open April - November and is closed December - March. The grounds are open from dawn to dusk. Restrooms and drinking water are available only when facilities are open.

directionsInfo: From I-95 North, take Exit 28 - Route 114 / School Street. Take a left onto Route 114. Go under the highway, straight through the next light and bear left onto Broadway. Bear right onto Main Street and take a right at the light onto Roosevelt Avenue. The parking lot is 500' up on the right. From I-95 South, take Exit 29 - US-1 / Downtown Pawtucket. Turn right onto Fountain Street. Take your first right onto Exchange Street. Turn left onto Roosevelt Avenue. The parking lot is a 1/4 mile down on the left.

name: Old Stone House
description: Built circa 1766, Old Stone House is the oldest structure on its original foundation in Washington, DC. Old Stone House is open for visitors at the hours listed below. The grounds are open according to general park hours (sunrise to sunset).
audioDescription: The House is constructed of blue-gray rocks of varrying sizes stacked on top of one another and sealed with a mortar. On the first floor, there is a large door in the center of the wall facing the street with a large window to the right of it. To the left of the ground floor door is a set of stairs that leads up to a porch that allows entry to a door on the second floor. To the right of the second floor door is a window directly above the one on the ground floor and another window to the left of it above where the stairs angle across the front of the house. The roof is made of wooden shingles and two dormer windows poke up from the top of it directly above where the windows are on the second floor. To the right of the house is a white wooden fence and a gate. To the right of the gate is a gray and brown cut stone half wall topped by the same white wooden fence as is directly next to the house. The gate provides entry to the garden which extends beside and behind the house for a length of 270 feet. Terraces are accessible by stairs or a concrete ramp that leads to the grassy middle terrace area. The house is L shaped with the short leg of the L facing the street. The space in the bend of the L is a small square shaped courtyard paved with bricks. There is are windows on the side of the house (ground, second and third floors) that extend to the left of a prominent bulge in the side of the house that denotes a chimney. The Chimney is stone up to the second story and then the house and chimney are made of brick on the third floor. A large window overlooks the patio from the front room on the ground floor and another window sits about three feet above it. Two other windows on the wall perpendicular to the short leg of the house also look over the patio. Between these two windows is another door labeled "Emergency Exit Only." There are two windows on the second floor that overlook the patio area and two dormer windows in the roof.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport cancellations are a circle with the name of the site across the top of the circle, the date of visitation across the diameter and the city and state located at the bottom . Stamps in Washington, DC are red to indicate they are part of the National Capital Area. Stamps available at the Old Stone House are for the Old Stone House, Rock Creek Park, Rock Creek and Potomac Parkway, Francis Scott Key Memorial, Georgetown Waterfront Park, C&O Canal NHP-Georgetown, Dumbarton Oaks and Montrose Parks

name: Outdoors Santa Barbara Visitor Center
description: The small Outdoors Santa Barbara Visitor Center not only has one of the best views of Santa Barbara, but also offers visitors information about Channel Islands National Park, Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary, Santa Barbara Maritime Museum, and the City of Santa Barbara. Open 10:30 am until 4:30 pm daily. The visitor center is closed on Thanksgiving Day, December 25, January 1, and the first Friday in August for Fiesta.
audioDescription: Located in the bustling Waterfront of Santa Barbara's working harbor, the visitor center offers one of the best views of the city, beaches, harbor, mountains, wharf and islands. Stepping inside the visitor center there are interpretive displays about Chumash culture, Spanish explorers, Missionaries and American Ranchers. A spectacular mosaic tiled floor showing the Channel Islands and the Marine Sanctuary, the Rainbow Bridge legend and flowers native to the islands. An underwater kelp forest mural delights visitors who are curious about the marine life that inhabits our park and marine sanctuary. Garabaldi, tiger sharks, sea stars, lobster, abalone, and urchins are just a few of the species found in the kelp forest mural. Numerous free brochures and reference materials about the forest, park, sanctuary and the city of Santa Barbara are available for the visitor. A computer screen displays websites of all four agencies for ease in accessing updated information. Our outside deck has several interpretive displays about the park, the sanctuary and the forest. A telescope is setup for viewing wildlife and the visitor will find comfortable benches to sit and enjoy the spectacular views from the fourth floor deck.

name: Ozette Ranger Station
description: Ozette Ranger Station is open intermittently during the summer and closed during the winter. Informational brochures available.
audioDescription: Ozette Ranger Station. 2 minutes Along the road is a brown sign with white text and the National Park Service arrowhead logo that reads, Lake Ozette Ranger Station. Olympic National Park. A right pointing arrow indicates the direction of the parking area. The back of the ranger station faces the road. It is a rectangular, one-story, light gray building with a brown metal roof and four windows on the back side. Split rail fencing edges the perimeter of a backyard area and a path leading to the front of the station. From the parking lot, another trail leads to the front of the ranger station and two other buildings. On the right is a structure with interpretive panels. Straight ahead is a building with restrooms. The ranger station is on the left behind a split rail fence. An opening in the fence provides access across a grass yard. A brown and white sign attached to the building reads, Ozette Ranger Station. The National Park Service arrowhead logo is above the sign. There are four windows across the front of the station and two entrance doors each with steps and a landing. Attached to the building near the door on the right is a sign that reads, Permits and Information. Below the sign is a bulletin board with park information about tides, backcountry food storage, Leave No Trace ethics, and wildlife. To the left of the board is a brown lidded box with permit payment envelopes and to the left of this box is a tall metal cannister for depositing payment envelopes.
directionsInfo: Ozette Ranger Station is located near Lake Ozette along the Hoko-Ozette Road. The Hoko-Ozette Road is accessible from Highways 112 and 113, both of which connect to Highway 101.

name: Painted Desert Inn
description: In its almost 100 years overlooking the Painted Desert, the inn has undergone many changes. The original building from the early 1920s was made of petrified wood. Today's stucco façade dates to the 1930s renovation of the Painted Desert Inn. The national historic landmark functions only as a museum now, with no overnight accommodation and food service. Displays inside highlight the building's history, Route 66, and the Civilian Conservation Corps. There are also restored murals by Hopi artist Fred Kabotie.

name: Painted Desert Visitor Center
description: Painted Desert Visitor Center is located at exit #311 off of I-40. The center provides information, brochures, book sales, exhibits, and restrooms. A gift shop and convenience store are adjacent to the visitor center. It is part of the Painted Desert Community Complex which is on the National Register of Historic Places. This is the only place you can obtain a permit for Devil's Playground.
audioDescription: Painted Desert Visitor Center is located at exit #311 off of I-40. The center provides information, brochures, book sales, exhibits, and restrooms. A gift shop and convenience store are adjacent to the visitor center. It is part of the Painted Desert Community Complex which is on the National Register of Historic Places.

name: Palo Alto Visitor Center
description: The visitor center features an exhibit area features interactive exhibits, artifacts, and Mexican War era military uniforms. The center also offers a 15-minute video—"War on the Rio Grande.” The video gives an overview of the war and is available in English and Spanish. The visitor center includes a small book store with over 100 book titles and specialty items. Don’t forget to get your national parks passport book stamped!
audioDescription: A large, light brown stucco masonry building. A pergola covered faux stone cement walkway leads to the double wood and glass entry doors. Before you enter, restroom facilities are to your right-hand side. The inside of the visitor center features dark grey tile floors and a large freestanding interpretive exhibit in the center of the room directly below a skylights. More interpretive exhibits line the walls of the exhibit space. Glass double doors with glass side lights exit onto the back patio. To the right of the exhibit space, a door opens into a large 20 foot by 30 foot video room. There are no windows in this room. Rows of chairs face the wall on the west side of the room and a projector hangs overhead. To the left of the exhibit space is the front desk contact station. It is a curved desk with a faux marble counter top. Next to the front desk is the park store. This section features a wooden slat wall island with books and other sales items on shelves and pegs. More slat wall displays with books and other sales items on shelves and pegs line the north and west walls of the park store. Exiting the exhibit area through the back there is a covered faux stone cement patio. There is a painting on the floor in the center of the patio, directly below three sky lights. There is a tactile interpretive exhibit on the south wall of the patio.
passportStampLocationDescription: The park's cancellation stamp can be found inside the visitor center at the front desk.

name: Panther Junction Visitor Center
description: Panther Junction Visitor Center is the best place to begin your visit. Backcountry & river use permits are issued here. Entrance fees can be paid here. Exhibits provide an overview of geology & natural and cultural histories of the park. The visitor center also has a theater with a park orientation movie shown upon request.The visitor center complex includes a Big Bend Natural History Association bookstore, U.S. Post Office, and restrooms. A water faucet is available for filling personal water containers
audioDescription: Panther Junction Visitor Center is located at a major junction in Big Bend National Park. From here, roads continue in three directions: Rio Grande Village to the east, Persimmon Gap towards the north, and the Chisos Basin and Ross Maxwell Scenic Drive to the west. From the large parking lot, the center includes an outdoor native plant garden, a covered porch area, and main entrance. Inside, there are interesting exhibits that highlight the many activities visitors enjoy throughout the park, as well as a Big Bend Natural History Association Bookstore. A large relief map of the entire park is especially popular. A theater room provides regular viewings of the park film. Adjacent to the visitor center you will find a small US Post Office, and restrooms.

name: Paradise Wilderness Information Center
description: Open during the summer, the Paradise Wilderness Information Center (WIC) is located in the main room of the historic Guide House. The WIC has an information desk staffed by wilderness rangers. Rangers at the WIC assist with wilderness permits, trip planning, and providing maps and trail condition updates.
audioDescription: The Paradise Wilderness Information Center is obscured by vegetation from the parking lot. The sides of the exterior are wood painted a mottled gray and the building has a sharply-angled roof. The building has multiple floors with windows on the second and third level lined with green trim. To reach the Paradise Wilderness Information Center, approach from the parking area nearest the Paradise Inn. Following the cement path to a windowed door lined with green trim. As you enter you are in a hallway with art and photos along the wall. To the left is a self-register permit station. As you follow the hallway to enter the main room, the information desk is on the left and exhibits on the history of climbing line the walls of the rustic interior. A glass-fronted case holds historic climbing equipment in the corner to the right of the entrance. In the far left corner, past the information desk, is a small room with tin-lined walls. To the right of that room is an area with benches for viewing a short safety video for climbers.

name: Park Headquarters and Visitor Center
description: Park rangers and volunteers are available to answer questions and help plan your park visit. Maps of both the Johnson City district and LBJ Ranch district are available at the front desk. The visitor center also features exhibits on President Johnson's life and his legislative accomplishments as president. There are two 25-minute films in the visitor center that can be viewed upon request: "LBJ: The President" covers his presidential years and "Lady Bird" highlights her life and accomplishments.
audioDescription: Johnson City Visitor Center. 228 words The Visitor Center is a wide, one-story building made of light-colored stone with a gray metal roof. The sidewalk from the parking lot leads up from the left of the entrance to a concrete patio in front of the automatic sliding glass doors. The roof extends out to cover most of the patio in front. On either side of the covered patio are stone-paved areas with benches. Another stone-paved area extends out in front beyond the covered patio and contains a flag pole and two wayside signs. To the left of the entrance, at a point where the sidewalk splits to go to the parking lot and into the town of Johnson City, is a glass-fronted bulletin board about 3 feet wide and 6 feet tall which has changing information on the park including maps and visitor orientation. End of description.

name: Parkway Information Cabin Milepost 102.4
description: The Parkway Information Cabin is closed indefinitely. The Chisha Foka trail parking area is open.
audioDescription: As you turn into the parking lot, there is the Chisha Foka trail is in the back corner behind the shade structure and picnic table. There is limited parking at this small interpretative site. In the middle of the parking lot is a bulletin board and directly across the road from that is the short sidewalk that will take you to the front door of the visitor center. As you walk inside the visitor center, the information desk is directly to your left with the park stamps and cash register. Next to the information desk is a stone fire place and the Eastern National products available for purchase. On the right side of the visitor center is the interpretative exhibits with a map that wraps around three walls and highlights major stops along the Parkway. In the middle of the room is an island with additional information on Parkway animals and American Indian history. To use the restrooms, visitors will walk back outside of the visitor center and turn left (on the right side of the visitor center from the parking lot). The restrooms are located in the white trailer with a ramp leading up to it. There are two full bathroom stalls within the trailer, there is no gender assignment for either stall. No baby changing stations are available at this site.

name: Parkway Visitor Center Milepost 266
description: The Parkway Visitor Center is just north of Tupelo, Mississippi. A ranger is on duty to answer questions and provide information and brochures. Ask and we will be glad to show you our movie. Other videos are available at https://www.nps.gov/natr/learn/photosmultimedia/videos.htm. The bookstore is open from 9am-4:15pm. You can also visit the America's National Parks online store at https://shop.americasnationalparks.org/store/
audioDescription: The Parkway Visitor Center is a single-story red brick building that is parallel to the parking lot. The words Visitor Center Natchez Trace Parkway on the left-hand side of the building front. The restroom entrance is around the right-side corner. A water fountain and water bottle filling station are near the entrance of the restrooms. You can enter the visitor center in the center of the building through the glass door which is located under a covered awning. You walk through two sets of glass doors before entering the visitor center. The Park Information desk is on your right-hand side after you enter through the second door. A park ranger or volunteer will be happy to assist you at the information desk.

name: Paul H. Douglas Center for Environmental Education
description: The Paul H. Douglas Center for Environmental Education is your gateway to the stunning Paul H. Douglas Trail through Miller Woods. This facility connects you to the natural environment through educational hands-on exhibits, ranger-guided hikes, lectures, animals, crafts, and a Nature Play Zone. Summer hours are 9:00 am to 5:00 pm Central Time (Friday of Memorial Day weekend through Monday of Labor Day weekend). Winter hours are 9:00 am to 4:00 pm Central Time.
audioDescription: The Douglas Center is a wooden building built into several pod or round-shaped rooms. Crossing the pedestrian bridge is the main entrance. The trailhead for Miller Woods is down the set of stairs on the right. Entering the door is the main entry room. Rest rooms are on the left. Through the next set of doors is the welcome desk and a mural of Miller Woods. Down the hall on the right is a sloping hallway painted bright blue with a rainbow above. Two-(2) pods are located on either side of the bottom of the ramp. The left is the theater/auditorium room. The right is the craft room. Tables line the craft room with activity guides and supplies for children to make their own crafts. Continuing down the hall is the final pod on the right, the animal room. Bass, amphibians, snakes, and reptiles are on either side of the room in glass enclosures. The set of doors leads to the trail of Miller Woods. This trail is fully accessible and provides a short loop around the pond at the base of the dune the Paul H. Douglas center is built upon.
passportStampLocationDescription: The circular stamp is made with orange ink. On the top inside is written Indiana Dunes National Park. On the bottom inside is written Porter, IN. There so no date.

name: Pea Ridge National Military Park Visitor Center
description: There is construction work happening in and around the visitor center and park lot. Please follow all traffic signage in and around the visitor center’s parking lot. Everyone’s patience and understanding it's greatly appreciated while we continue to make improvements.
audioDescription: Visitor Center 337 words The apex of the wide A-frame-shaped building is 60 feet. The front of the structure has two smaller A-fame-shaped gables that overlap, with one forming a portico over the entrance doors. The wing to the left of the entrance is 100-foot-long with an upward slanted roof that is 20 feet tall. The façade is brown, light, and dark tan rocks with dark brown wooden slat siding. Large metal letters on the wall to the right of the entrance spell out Pea Ridge National Military Park. To the left of the entrance is a line of 6 windows. A four-foot-wide sand-colored sidewalk leads from the parking lot to the entrance. Thirty feet from the entrance the sidewalk widens to 12 feet with a tan flagstone inlay. At this point, there is a 30-foot-tall light gray metal flagpole. Eight feet from the flagpole in a 12-lb Napoleon cannon with 2 four-foot tall spoked wheels positioned in the middle of the flagstone inlay. The wood beam portico over the entrance is supported by two wooded columns on four-foot-tall natural stone pilings The heavy glass doors are manual pull and lead to an open large open lobby area. The entrance has vinyl wood flooring with a 6-foot by an 8-foot industrial area rug. To the left is the bookstore. The restrooms are approximately 25 feet from the entrance at the back of the bookstore on the right. A single low wall-mounted water fountain is just before the restroom entrances. The first restroom door is for the men’s, the large silver metal automatic door open button is on the left. The door opens outward. The second door is the women’s restroom. The large silver metal automatic door open button is on the right and this door opens outward. The information desk is 10 feet slightly to the left of the entrance. The park film is audio described. For more information see the park staff at the information desk. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Pea Ridge National Military Parks passport stamp can be found at the parks visitor center. This passport stamp is in black ink and goes in the southwest part of the passport book.

directionsInfo: When you drive into the park, on the entrance road off Highway 62, you will see trees on either side of the paved road. As you continue to drive slowly along this entrance road, on your left side the trees will open to a large grassy yard. Just beyond the yard is a large barn-like brown building. This building is the visitor center. You will slow down and turn to your left, between two large rock and cement signs that read Pea Ridge National Military Park.

name: Peaks of Otter Visitor Center
description: Visitors of the Peaks of Otter gain a sense of both the history of community and tourism in the Blue Ridge Mountains. The long history of visiting the mountains for health and relaxation is told in the visitor center. An extensive trail system is available with the hike to Sharp Top being a long-standing tradition. Dining and lodging is available, along with fishing in Abbot Lake, camping, and picnicking.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps are located in the America's National Parks store in the visitor center.

name: Pearl Harbor National Memorial Visitor Center
description: The Pearl Harbor Visitor Center is open seven days a week from 7:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. The visitor center, two museums, and USS Arizona Memorial program are free for all visitors. The visitor center is closed three days a year: Thanksgiving Day, December 25, and January 1. For every other day, including all other holidays, we are open from 7:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. with no shortened hours.

name: Peddocks Island Visitor Center
description: The former Guardhouse for Fort Andrews, the Peddocks Island Visitor Center is located near the dock. An information desk and seating are available with restrooms located on the lower level.
audioDescription: One story brick building. Eight stairs lead up to the main entrance of white doors. The entrance has a covered portico with brick columns connected by arches. Above the stairs are the words "Welcome Center" in black. There are four evenly-spaced windows across the front, with glass paned windows and white trim.

name: Peirce Mill
description: Peirce Mill, built in the 1820s, is the last operational grist mill on Rock Creek Park. The grounds are open according to general park hours. The mill is open for visitors at the hours listed below.
audioDescription: Peirce Mill is built into a naturally occuring set of hills next to Rock Creek. From the parking area or barn the building appears to rise two and a half stories from the ground level. There are two windows equidistant from the door which is in the center of the ground floor. Three windows on the second floor are above the two windows on the ground floor and the door. The roof is covered in dark shingles. A fence runs from the left corner of the building and continues in a Northerly direction. This encloses a stone lined trench called the headrace. From the side of the building, observers will see that the structure has a basement or second ground floor since the hill at the front obstructs it. There is a wooden wheel at the side of the building. Above it there are six windows, two on each floor. The top most floor is wood, painted white, instead of stone. The fence line continues past the wheel and extends to a small foot bridge that goes over the tailrace. A door in the middle of the ground floor at the rear of the mill allows visitors to enter the mill directly into the basement. Narrow wooden stairs inside allow visitors to move between floors.
passportStampLocationDescription: Rock Creek Park Stamp- The Rock Creek Park stamp consists of a circle with "Rock Creek Park" across the top arc of the circle, the date across the diameter of the circle and "Washington, DC" across the arc of the bottom of the circle. Perice Mill- The Peirce Mill stamp consists of a circle with "Rock Creek Park" across the top arc of the circle, the date across the diameter of the circle and "Peirce Mill" across the arc of the bottom of the circle.

name: Persimmon Gap Visitor Center
description: Located at the north entrance to the park, Persimmon Gap Visitor Center offers park orientation and information. The visitor center has exhibits, bookstore, mini-theater, and restrooms. River permits for the Lower Canyons are issued during normal business hours, and entrance fees can be paid at the Persimmon Gap Visitor Center.
audioDescription: The Persimmon Gap Visitor Center is located in a low pass between the Santiago Mountains at the northern end of the park. This pass has been a travel corridor for centuries for people entering and exiting the lower Big Bend country. The area around the visitor center includes the main building, a shaded picnic table with outdoor information exhibits, and a vault toilet. The visitor center is a one-story, white adobe structure with labeled desert plants growing in raised beds at the base. The inside of the visitor center contains a large open room with exhibits, a bookstore, and an information counter. To the right are indoor restrooms with flush toilets and sinks.
passportStampLocationDescription: At the Persimmon Gap Visitor Center, you can obtain the stamp for both Persimmon Gap and Rio Grande Wild & Scenic River.

name: Philip A. Hart Visitor Center
description: The Philip A. Hart Visitor Center is located on M-72 just east of the intersection with M-22 in Empire, MI. You will find a wealth of information about the park and the natural and human history of the area. Park passes, brochures, and maps are available at the Information Desk. If you have questions, rangers and volunteers are available to assist you.
audioDescription: A wide concrete walkway leads to the Philip A. Hart Visitor Center, located on M-72 just east of the intersection with M-22 in Empire, Michigan. This center serves as the park headquarters for the Sleeping Bear Dunes National Lakeshore. Here you can learn about the many features and facilities available at the park, as well as experience exhibits, an Eastern National bookstore, and a short multimedia presentation introducing visitors to the Sleeping Bear Dunes. The center is open year-round. The building housing the center is a one-story structure with 2 long wings stretching left and right from a square central tower rising about 50 feet—or approximately 5 stories—above the center’s entrance. The entire building is clad in weathered gray clapboard. A series of single white-trimmed windows line the façade of the wings, and there are two similar windows positioned one above the other on the front of the tower. Encircling the tower just below its roofline are several clerestory windows; these windows emit daylight into the upper part of the center’s high-ceilinged lobby. A large sign with the words “Philip A. Hart Visitor Center” stands in front of a flagpole located to the right of the walkway leading to the building. Also affixed to the sign is a smaller arrowhead-shaped sign with the words “National Park Service” appearing in white letters against the sign’s rust-colored background. To the left of the letters is the image of a single green sequoia tree; below the letters is a snow-covered mountaintop. Also appearing in white below the tree and mountaintop is the silhouette of a lone bison. This sign represents the National Park Service emblem. A shallow gable roof shades the double glass doors at the building’s entrance. These doors open outward and can be opened either manually or by pressing a gray metal wheelchair button—about 4 inches square—located near the top of an approximately 3-foot-tall metal pillar placed to the right of the right-side door. Also flanking the doors are metal safety railings of the same approximate height. The sidewalk leading to the entrance is flat, without steps.
passportStampLocationDescription: Don't forget to stamp your passport book while in the visitor center. And look for the special 50th anniversary stamp too.

name: Pinckney-Porter's Chapel Visitor Contact Station
description: Pinckney-Porters Chapel is a Reconstruction era Freedman's Chapel located in the Naval Heritage Park just outside the main gate to Naval Hospital Beaufort. The Town of Port Royal rebuilt the chapel in late 2020, and through an agreement, Reconstruction Era National Historical Park operates the site as a visitor contact station. Inside are temporary exhibits, and most Camp Saxton programs begin at this site. Pinckney-Porter's Chapel is open Fridays and Saturdays from 9am to 5pm.
audioDescription: Pinckney-Porters Chapel is a small wooden church painted white. There is a small steeple with a cross on top of it, with steps leading up to the front door. There are landscaped bushes around the building, and it is located within a large community park. Nearby are picnic areas, a skate park, and many live oak trees.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Port Royal, SC stamp is available at Porters Chapel

name: Plains High School Visitor Center and Museum
description: Plains High School is the main visitor center for the Jimmy Carter National Historical Park. The building has the parks orientation film, visitor services desk, exhibits, bookstore, and passport stamp location.
audioDescription: The Plains High School Museum and Visitor Center is housed in the old Plains High School. A red brick structure having large columns at the top of the stairs. The building is laid out in a H shape with the center section two stories tall. Plains High School serves as the park museum, visitor center, and administrative offices. Visitors find a historic classroom, principal's office and auditorium. Other rooms feature exhibits that explain the Carters' lives in Plains, including political and business careers, education, family, and post presidency. There is a 25-minute video that focuses on the life and accomplishments of Jimmy Carter told by those who know him best - his friends, neighbors and family.
passportStampLocationDescription: Eastern National Passport Cancellation stamp: circular stamp with Jimmy Carter National Historical Park in the upper half of the circle. The date: January 11, 2021 in the middle. Plains, Georgia in the lower half of the circle. State School of Georgia Stamp: a picture of Plains High School with State School of Georgia arched at the top of the stamp. Plains High School below that. Jimmy Carter National Historical Park at the bottom of the stamp.

name: Point Reyes Lighthouse Visitor Center
description: The Lighthouse Visitor Center (LHVC) offers exhibits on the Point Reyes Lighthouse, marine life, & maritime history, as well as a small bookstore. The stairs down to the lighthouse are only open when the LHVC is open and wind speeds remain below 40 mph (64km/h). The Observation Deck at the top of the stairs is open daily from 6 am to ~11:45 pm and offers a great view on a clear day.
audioDescription: The Lighthouse Visitor Center is a smallish white-sided, brown-shingled building with two wings near the western end of a narrow high rocky headland surrounded by the Pacific Ocean. A rocky knoll rises above the building to its west. A large concrete-covered watershed is to the south of the path that leads to and beyond the visitor center. Within the visitor center are exhibits about the historic Point Reyes Lighthouse, as well as on whales, seals and sea lions, wildflowers, birds and maritime history. A touch table allows visitors to feel baleen and to closely inspect the skulls of various marine mammals. The Fresnel lens from the San Francisco Lightship is also on display. Attached to the Lighthouse Visitor Center is the Ocean Exploration Center, which highlights the spectacularly rich and globally significant ocean environment of North-central California. The Ocean Exploration Center features 3-D models of a California sea lion, a Dall's porpoise, a sooty shearwater, and a white shark suspended from the ceiling, murals depicting life below the surface painted on the walls, and informative panels describing ocean wildlife and habitats off our coast. A large picture window offers visitors a stunning view of the Point Reyes Beach and the Pacific Ocean, while protecting them from the legendary winds of Point Reyes.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Point Reyes National Seashore passport stamp is available at the Lighthouse Visitor Center's information desk, if the visitor center is open. If the Lighthouse Visitor Center is closed, the passport stamp is also available at the Bear Valley Visitor Center. Please check the Bear Valley Visitor Center's operating hours to know when to arrive.

directionsInfo: From the Bear Valley Visitor Center (BVVC), head north 0.2 miles (0.3 km) to Bear Valley Rd. Turn left and follow Bear Valley Rd. 1.75 miles (2.8 km) northwest to Sir Francis Drake Blvd. Turn left and follow Sir Francis Drake Blvd. 18.7 miles (29.9 km) west to the Point Reyes Lighthouse visitor parking lot. name: Port Alsworth Visitor Center
description: Come and enjoy the visitor center and exhibits and get information from our rangers. Visitors can find a wealth of park information including local hiking trail details and check out a bear resistant container at the Port Alsworth Visitor Center. The Bristol Bay Double-Ender “boat barn” will be open daily. Visitors are free to explore the other outdoor exhibits including the Wassilie Trefon Dena’ina Fish Cache and Denison Sawmill Exhibit anytime.

name: Port Oneida Heritage Center
description: The Port Oneida Heritage Center, at the Olsen farmhouse is operated by Preserve Historic Sleeping Bear, a nonprofit partner of the national park. During seasonal open hours the Heritage Center offers exhibits and artifacts in the farmhouse that tell the story of the late 1800s agricultural community of Port Oneida. The large barn is open and people can enjoy the gardens and a small museum store.
audioDescription:
A short dirt driveway leads into the Charles and Hattie Olsen Farm, which is located on the M-22 Leelanau Scenic Heritage Route. This is the newest farm in Port Oneida with 2 buildings dating to 1918: a modified bungalow-style farmhouse and a large 2-story barn. These buildings are situated to the right and left of the driveway respectively. The farmhouse contains a history center offering several exhibits providing information about the Port Oneida area. The 2-story farmhouse is clad with white clapboard, and there is a single brick chimney jutting from the center of its black-shingled gable roof. Extending across the entire width of the structure's facade is an open concrete porch, its low-pitched shed roof supported by a white-painted beam and 4 block pillars, tapered at the top. The beam's curved bottom edge forms 5 arches: 3 separating the 4 pillars on the front of the porch, and 2 between each of the end pillars and the house facade itself. Positioned on the porch roof between the 2 central pillars framing the entrance is a gable pediment featuring on its face a red and white sunburst design. This design is repeated on both gable ends on the house's 2 sides and also on the sides of a dormer with shed roof that juts out from the main gable roof above the porch. There are 2 such sunburst designs on each gable end, framing a small diamond-shaped window located just below the gable's peak. There are 2 wide concrete steps in front of the porch at its center, flanked by a line of low manicured shrubs on either side. Take care as you take one additional step up to reach the porch itself, as you may encounter 2 potted plants, one each placed in the opening formed by the 2 central pillars. There are no railings on the front steps nor on the porch. Standing on the porch's left edge and reaching to the roof is a tall open-grid trellis. The porch's right side is open, overlooking a small garden and a white picket fence extending away from the building. You may encounter 2 benches, one each placed below the 2 windows flanking the entrance door, which will be located straight in front of you as you step onto the porch. There may also be a thin mat placed in front of the door. There is a wide wooden ramp without railings located on the back of the house. As you near the top of the ramp, a wooden entrance door will be on your right. Mounted to the building to the left of the door is a cast iron bell with an attached rope dangling to about 3 Â½ feet above the ramp. Grab the ball at the end of the rope to ring the bell, and someone will open the door for you. Otherwise, this door remains locked. Section 2 (161 words)The farmhouse interior boasts hardwood floors and dark wooden trim around the windows and doors. Here you will find a series of displays, maps, and videos offering an in-depth look at the Olsen family and others in the Port Oneida community, as well as information about the 366 historic structures and landscape features found in this area. Also included is information about the Port Oneida residents who rescued passengers and crew of the Rising Sun, which wrecked on the shore here in October, 1917. As you step inside the farmhouse, a small information desk with guestbook will be located immediately to your right. An arbor with arched top in the middle of the picket fence allows access to a single picnic table with benches located in the back yard. As you approach the table, take care to avoid a large propane tank and a wooden clothesline standing near the table. The farmhouse is open in the summer months through Labor Day. Section 3 (176 words) The three-bay barn is the only remaining gambrel-roofed barn-and also one of the largest barns-in the Port Oneida Rural Historic District. Its exterior is constructed of red-painted vertical wooden planks, and both its sloping gambrel roof and a shed roof sheltering a one-story section on the end closest to the driveway are constructed of gray metal sheeting. A silo located on the barn's back end is made of wood staves and is supported by steel rods which band the silo at every few feet up the silo's height. This barn is partially built into a hill on its right side.
Take care as you walk around the barn as there is a stone retaining wall extending out from the barn's right side. This wall is topped with a narrow walkway leading upward to a door on that same side of the building. It is not suggested that you climb this walkway as there are no railings on its front side, which is situated at least 4 feet above the ground at its highest point.

name: Portsmouth Visitor Center
description: Located in the historic Theodore & Annie Salter House (The first house on the right of the path from Haulover Dock) in Portsmouth Village on North Core Banks. Available Facilities: Restrooms, first aid, park passport stamp; Exhibits on maritime history and village life
audioDescription: In the historic village of Portsmouth, just a ferry ride across Ocracoke Inlet from the island and village of Ocracoke in Cape Hatteras National Seashore, sits the Portsmouth Visitor Center. It is found in the historic Theodore & Annie Salter House which is about 1/4 mile walk from the ferry dock through the marsh on the sand road. This historic house, built about 1900, has a wooden front porch reached by steep steps (the rise is taller than modern stairs). A screen door opens out to let you into the house. The visitor center has exhibits on the history of the village in 3 of the rooms of the main part of the house, there is a central hall, a staircase to the upper floors (closed to the public) and the last room on the right next to the stairs is a flush toilet facility. The toilet room is single gendered and is used by both -- There are two stalls with slide bar latches inside -- the outer door can be latched as well. At the end of the hall, is the entry into what had been the dining room with more exhibits, and finally at the end of that room, is the entry into the attached kitchen exhibit area. Another screen door, opening out, on the left leads to more steps leading back the ground level at the rear of the house. You can either retrace your steps through the house or descend these steps to the outside and walk back around through the yard. Once you leave the Visitor Center and return to the sand road, turn right to follow the road to rest of the village (next building is the General Store & Post Office on the right) or left to return to the ferry dock.

name: Poverty Point World Heritage Site
description: Located in northeastern Louisiana, Poverty Point National Monument can be visited in any season. This site, which contains some of the largest prehistoric earth works in North America, is managed by the state of Louisiana. These state park facilities are open to the public. Learn more on the Louisiana State Parks Poverty Point website. Please note that there are NO federal facilities!
audioDescription: This site features ancient Native American earthworks which date back to 12 centuries before the birth of Christ. A nearby museum surrounded by lush green trees and hearty fields includes an audio-visual presentation and numerous artifacts found on site. There is an archaeological laboratory, picnic areas, restrooms and self-guided hiking trails. Surrounding areas are flat with some gentle sloping hills.

name: Prairie Acadian Cultural Center
description: The Acadian exiles from Canada's Nova Scotia who settled Louisiana's prairies developed a distinctive cultural mix of Cajun, Creole, and cowboy. The Prairie Acadian Cultural Center tells this story through ranger programs, exhibits, and films. The center features cooking and crafts demonstrations, local musicians, and dancing for all. Center admission is free. This visitor center is currently closed. However, programming is offered off-site.
audioDescription: The visitor Center at the Prairie Acadian Cultural Center has many rooms to explore including a museum, a kitchen, a theater and a crafts room. The exterior is brick and there is a concrete area leading to the front door. Once you enter that door, you are in a vestibule; approximately 5 feet to the left is an interior door which leads to the main room of the visitor center. From that position, there are the following points of interest: In the 1:00 position, 20 feet away, are the restrooms. The women’s room in on the left, followed by a custodial closet, and then the men’s room straight ahead. From the interior door, you can turn right and proceed 30 feet. From this position, there are several things to explore: To your immediate right, there is a test kitchen; this room has seating for visitors where you can witness a cooking demonstration. (Check schedule for details.) To the right, past the kitchen is a crafts room where artisans sometimes create quilts and other pieces. Ahead, in 20 feet, is the museum. The museum exhibits are related to Prairie Acadian culture, displaying clothing, tools and musical instruments, among other items. To the left, in 20 feet, is the information desk, staffed by a park ranger. From that desk, turn right to enter the theater, where you can experience the park film or enjoy scheduled musical performances. As you navigate your surroundings, keep in mind that there are pillars, benches and other obstacles at irregular intervals around the space.

name: Prairie Creek Visitor Center
description: Located just off the Newton B. Drury Scenic Parkway - in the heart of Prairie Creek Redwoods State Park. Exhibits about the Civilian Conservation Corps and redwood ecology, park information, junior ranger program, bookstore and retail sales.
audioDescription: Historic 1930's building that looks like a cabin. It is single story and set in front of towering redwood trees. Porch and steps/ramp in front. RV and trailer parking is not available right at this visitor center, additional parking spots are 100-400 feet from the building. Picnic tables, interpretive panels, trail-head information, and water faucet.

name: President William Jefferson Clinton Birthplace Home National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The visitor center, set in a two-story former residence adjacent to the birthplace home, features exhibits on the childhood of William Jefferson Clinton plus a Jefferson National Parks Association (JNPA) bookstore. Visitors can park vehicles along Division Street; accessible and large-vehicle parking (RVs, buses) is available on 2nd Street.
audioDescription: A brown National Park Service sign welcomes you to the visitor center from the north entrance as you make your way across Division Street (vehicle parking is available on the north side of Division). Immediately past the NPS sign are three stairs that lead up the hill through an open black fence to one of the visitor center’s entrances. Note: an accessible entrance can be found on the south side of the building with adjacent parking available from W. 2nd Street. The visitor center is housed in a former residence adjacent to the Clinton Birthplace Home - a brown brick building with a white wooden door and a glass doorknob await you as you enter from Division Street. The accessible entrance features a ramp which leads you in through the back porch of the former home. Entering the visitor center from Division Street, you will pass alight brown information desk staffed by park rangers, an exhibit hall with displays to your left and a Jefferson National Parks Association bookstore/gift shop to your right. Two exhibit display panels ring the entrance to the exhibit hall with an additional two displays to the left of the fireplace. A white fireplace in the room features a large photograph of a young Bill Clinton and a bust of him seated atop the mantle.
passportStampLocationDescription: Available stamps include a passport stamp, Junior Ranger badge, campaign button and home visit. See below for images. Feel free to contact the Visitor Center at 870-777-4455 for actual prints with specific dates.

name: Prince William Forest Park Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is half a mile from the park entrance. The visitor center has seasonal hours: mid March - beginning of November, open every day from 9:00 am - 5:00 pm and beginning of November - mid March, 8:00 am - 4:00 pm with closures on Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday (dates follow daylight savings time). The visitor center is closed Thanksgiving, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a brown wooden cabin building located on a roundabout on the Park Entrance Road. There is a roughly paved stone pathway leading from the roundabout to a stairway up to a wooden porch and the building entrance. To the left of this stone pathway is a cement sidewalk leading to a dark brown building containing public restrooms as well as an optional ramp to the visitor center porch. A sign above the porch reads Visitor Center and Country Store. To the left of the entrance door on the outside porch is a sign with current hours and a box containing maps when the visitor center is closed. When entering the doors of the visitor center, immediately to your right is a large wooden desk where a ranger can sell visitor passes, bookstore items, or answer any questions about the park. Walking past the desk to the right leads to a small open museum display area and stone fireplace. The park film is shown on request on a TV above the fireplace. When entering the visitor center doors and turning to the left, a bookstore decorated with antiques to look like an old time country store is laid out before you. Books, souvenirs, and limited snacks can be found on bookshelves and counter of this store. Brochures about the natural and cultural resources of the park can also be found on a rack on the wall immediately to the left of the entry door. The entire visitor center walls are comprised of wood paneling with a flat wooden floor beneath your feet. Directly in front of the entrance to the visitor center is a door marked Employees only that leads to a stairway which divides the two sections of the visitor center (store to the left, museum displays to the right).
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp is located at the information desk.

name: Province Lands Visitor Center
description: Open May 1-October 31 annually. Let us help you plan a fabulous seashore visit! Exhibits, our award-winning orientation film, Standing Bold, and dramatic views of dunes and ocean await. Walking and biking trails are nearby, and whales may be observed swimming offshore. Ask about our Junior Ranger Program and ranger-guided activities. Want swag? The America's National Parks store is open during visitor center hours. The observation decks at the visitor center is open year-round.
audioDescription: The Province Lands Visitor Center is located atop a tall dune. Approach to the site is via a winding road through forested woodlands. The building sits in an open setting, providing extensive views in all directions of the Atlantic Ocean, the Gulf of Maine, Provincetown, dunes, and historic lighthouses, a former Coast Guard Station, and a former life-saving station. A restroom building is located slightly below the edge of an elongated parking lot which has ample parking, including spaces close to the entrance for vehicles with handicap placards. There are several picnic tables located in shady spots near the parking lot. The approach to the building from the parking area provides vast scenic views of ocean and dunes. To access the building there are stairs, plus an accessible path under construction. The visitor center is a two-story structure. It is angular, with a wood shingled roof, floor-to-to ceiling windows, a lower observation deck that looks out over ocean and dunes, and indoor and outdoor upper observation decks, accessed via stairs, with 360-degree views. Both observation decks have outdoor exhibits that explain the nature and history of the area and spotting scopes for spying whales and seabirds. Inside the building there is a staffed ranger desk with information for trip planning, and indoor exhibits on the area's history and nature, including tactile and audio visual elements. The exhibit gallery is audio-described. Ask the rangers for assistance. Included in the center is a well-stocked store with many national seashore-related items for sale. There is also a small theater with bench seating, where several short films play. All films have open captions and audio description. When the building is closed for the winter, the outdoor observation decks remain open. The Province Lands Bicycle Trail passes near this visitor center, and parking is available. Less than a mile away is the Beech Forest, which offers a picnic are and trails along ponds.

name: Pu'ukoholā Heiau National Historic Site
description: Our Visitor Center is ADA accessible and offers wall exhibits with both English and Hawaiian Language interpretive information in our open lanai area. We also offer a FREE Audio tour available for Smart Phones (Data/Service Provider fees may apply). Restrooms and drinking water fountains located outside of Visitor Center. Museum exhibits and Park Store are open daily from 7:30am-5:00pm located in the visitor center.
audioDescription: Driving through the parks entrance gate you will park in a designated parking stall to your left. Restrooms and drinking water fountains are located 15 yards heading north to the visitor center entrance. From the water fountain, there are several stairs to walk down to get to the visitor center glass door entrance. Once entered the door located to your right, The Hawaiian Political Pyramid chart is mounted on the wall. When continue to walk straight from the entrance, park brochures, donation box, collectible passport stamps, displays of Hawaiian history (Hawaiian and English) and structure designs by artist Dietrich Varez are located in the center of the outside open-air lanai. Continue to walk ahead, a topographic map is displayed of the parks boundaries from land to water. There is also an option to select between two 27-minute videos: 1-The story of two great epic chiefs, Kamehameha I and his cousin Keoua Ku'ahu'ula; 2- A strong connection between the people and a trail system, The Ala Kahakai. These videos are available for visitors to enjoy. There are images of Kamehameha I and battles between warriors on land and water, and stories of the Hawaiian history of how Kamehameha I had conquered and unify all the 8 major Hawaiian Islands under one ruler. The parks bookstore and museum are available daily (7:30am-5:00pm).

name: Public Lands Information Center
description: This federal interagency office is staffed by employees from the National Park Service, Bureau of Land Management, U.S National Forest Service, and by dedicated volunteers from the local community. The Public Lands Information Center provides recreational information and maps for federal lands managed in southwest Utah, northwest Arizona, and eastern Nevada.
passportStampLocationDescription: Are you a "Passport to Your National Parks" cancellation stamp collector? Grand Canyon-Parashant National Monument has a couple of stamps to commemorate your visit. Because of the unique administration of the monument, the cancellation stamp for Grand Canyon-Parashant may be included with the western region parks, the section of the Passport® books designated with green tabs. We provide a green ink pad for use with our cancellation and junior ranger stamp.

name: Pulltite Ranger Station
description: Pulltite Ranger Station is located next to Pulltite Campground. The facility offers a "Kids Center" with puppets, books, and other play materials. Adults can enjoy short park films and charging stations. Restrooms and showers are available at this location.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamp can be found in the pavilion of Pulltite Ranger Station. Look for a green canoe containing the stamp materials.

directionsInfo: Pulltite Ranger Station is found past the end of State Highway EE, north of Eminence, Missouri. To reach Pulltite from Eminence: Drive north for about 17 miles on Highway 19. There will be an intersection with Highway EE. Turn west onto EE and follow the road for about 4 miles. The station will be on your left, near the river.
