name: Quarai
description: The Quarai Visitor Center includes a museum, restrooms, and a bookstore. A small parking lot makes mid to large RV turnaround difficult. Please park in the gravel lot on hill above the parking lot. During the summer (May 1-October 31), the trails, restrooms, and visitor center are open daily from 9:00am-5:00pm. During the winter (November 1-April 30), trails and restrooms are open daily from 9:00am-4:00pm. The Quarai Visitor Center is open Thursday-Monday from 9:00am-4:00pm.
audioDescription: The Quarai Visitor Center is located at the end of Quarai Manzano Road. The paved parking lot with marked parking stalls is on your left as you drive in. When you exit your vehicle, continue straight a negligible distance to a covered walkway. The visitor center, which contains a model and a WNPA bookstore, will be on your right, and a museum is on the left. Restrooms are behind the visitor center; to access the restrooms, follow the cement trail that skirts the visitor center on the right.
passportStampLocationDescription: Each of our three sites and Headquarters have a stamp that will say Salinas Pueblo Missions NM, the date, and the name of the site. The Quarai Visitor Center has the Quarai stamp.

name: Quarry Exhibit Hall - Utah
description: The Quarry Exhibit Hall is where you can see a wall of approximately 1,500 dinosaur bones. This includes the remains of numerous species, such as Allosaurus, Apatosaurus, Camarasaurus, Diplodocus, and Stegosaurus. Exhibits, including an 80 foot (24 m) long mural, reveal the story of the many animals that lived in the Morrison environment during the Late Jurassic. This building is open year-round, except on certain holidays. Open hours change seasonally.

name: Quarry Visitor Center - Utah
description: Located 7 miles (11 km) north of Jensen, Utah, off Highway 149, the Quarry Visitor Center is the gateway to the Quarry Exhibit Hall and the wall of dinosaur bones. This facility features a staffed information desk, gift shop, and theater with a 12-minute park film. Exhibits introduce a variety of resources and places to explore within the monument. During summer, shuttle buses depart from here for the Quarry Exhibit Hall. This building is open year-round, except on certain holidays. Hours change seasonally.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a large building with an angular roof. A walkway over a bridge leads to the visitor center doors. Inside the visitor center entryway are restrooms and then doors that lead to the information desk, exhibit area and sales area.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamp is currently located at the information desk in the visitor center. The stamp is available during normal operating hours.

name: Quinault Rain Forest Ranger Station
description: Quinault Rain Forest Ranger Station is open intermittently during the summer and closed during the rest of the year. Educational exhibits and informational brochures available.
audioDescription: Quinault Ranger Station. 2 minutes A brown and white sign along the roadway reads, Quinault River Ranger Station. Olympic National Park. Visitor Center and Nature Trail. The National Park Service arrowhead logo is attached to the sign on the right. The entrance road loops around a central grassy area past the Ranger Station on the right to a parking area on the opposite side. Concrete parking bumpers edge the front of each parking spot. A concrete sidewalk rings the perimeter of the parking lot, then grass, then the forest. At the far left end of the parking lot is a bulletin board with posted park regulations, information about wildlife and safety, and trails in the area. To the right of the bulletin board is the Kestner Homestead Trailhead. At the far right of the parking lot near the top of the loop, a branch of the sidewalk turns left and heads up a slight rise to an accessible restroom building. The women’s room is on the left and the men’s room is on the right. A trash receptacle sits in front of the restroom. The sidewalk continues around the loop to the right toward the Ranger Station. The brown L-shaped building has a wooden shingled roof with an A-shaped peak covering the entranceway. The National Park Service arrowhead logo is on the front of the building. Information about the park is available on each side of the door. Inside the Ranger Station are exhibits about the people who once lived in the area and the natural world in the Quinault rainforest. To the right of the Ranger Station is a meadow surrounded by forest.
directionsInfo: Quinault Rain Forest Ranger Station is located along the North Shore Road in the Quinault Rain Forest. The North Shore Road is accessible via Highway 101.

description: Rainbow Forest Museum provides exhibits of petrified wood, fossils, and displays of prehistoric animals as well as information, book sales, and restrooms.
audioDescription: Rainbow Forest Museum provides exhibits of petrified wood, fossils, and displays of prehistoric animals as well as information, book sales, and restrooms.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are several dated cancellation stamps including the main one for the park, Route 66, Painted Desert, and the Painted Desert Inn. There is also a picture of a giant reptile and a junior ranger badge stamp.

name: Rainy Lake Visitor Center
description: Located on the shore of Black Bay with views across the water to the Kabetogama Peninsula. The Rainy Lake Visitor Center hours of operation vary with the season. Call ahead or stop by for the most current information and for help with trip planning (218) 286-5258. The visitor center offers an exhibit area, displays, a bookstore, a staffed information desk, a children's activity table, and a theater for viewing the park film.
audioDescription: The visitor center is located a short walk from the upper parking lot. To the left of the visitor center is a side walk ramp and stairs are located directly in front of the visitor center. A bulletin board is located on the right in front of the visitor center and has a large map of the park as well as brochures and a passport stamp. To enter the visitor center there are two sets of double doors. Once past those there is the front desk located to the right and to the left is a museum. The park bookstore is located on the right just past the front desk. After the bookstore is a hallway that leads to the restrooms.
passportStampLocationDescription: A passport stamp can be found inside the visitor center during business hours. There is also a passport stamp located on the bulletin board in front of the visitor center that can be accessed at all hours.

name: Ranger Station
description: Ranger Station near the campground is two miles from the park headquarters and park entrance. Ranger station is open seven days a week from 8:00 a.m. until 3:45 p.m.
audioDescription: The Ranger Station is a wooden structure located near the campground. The ranger station is surrounded with the forest of Greenbelt Park. The structure is located two miles from the park headquarters and park entrance.
passportStampLocationDescription: Ranger Station is the location for the Greenbelt Park, Baltimore Washington Parkway, and Junior ranger passport stamps.

name: Ranger Station
description: Located on the edge of the historic cabin district, the log cabin has basic exhibits and a sales area offering park-related clothing, gifts, books, and a few snacks and beverages. The building is NOT accessible and there are NO public restrooms in this building.
audioDescription: At a crossroads of dirt roads sits a large wooden building on a stone foundation. A covered front porch peers back out across the vast expanse of Valle Grande. Parking is along the dirt road leading up to the right side of the cabin. Stairs on the right side of the cabin ascend to the covered front porch. At the far end of the porch is the door into the ranger station.

directionsInfo: From Jemez Springs: Follow NM4 north for 22 miles. The entrance has a gate and signs on your left. Follow the dirt road 2 miles to the Entrance Station. Obtain a Backcountry Vehicle Permit and follow the dirt road another 2 miles. From Los Alamos: Follow NM4 west for 18 miles. The entrance has a gate and signs on your right. Follow the dirt road 2 miles to the Entrance Station. Obtain a Backcountry Vehicle Permit and follow the dirt road another 2 miles.

name: Reconstruction Era National Historical Park Visitor Center
description: The visitor center contains exhibits and information about the Reconstruction era in the low country, as well as information about visiting the various units of the park.
audioDescription: The park visitor center is a small, one story brick structure with wide archiving windows located in the downtown district of Beaufort, South Carolina. There is a sign that says "Reconstruction Era National Historical Park" and a small concrete courtyard with a few benches underneath the shade of several large oak trees. Inside the building is a simple one room exhibit space with a front desk and a few panel exhibits. Across the street from the visitor center is the Beaufort Arsenal, a castle-like structure painted a yellow color. Next door is the Beaufort Public Library. There is a lot of street parking available, and the occasional horse drawn carriage passes by carrying tourists. The neighborhoods surrounding the building are filled with large antebellum mansions and churches, most of which are well maintained and in use.

name: Red Hills Visitor Center (West)
description: The Red Hills Visitor Center is a great place to learn about the park and start your visit to Saguaro National Park's West District. Views from the patio are spectacular and overlook the Red Hills and majestic Saguaro cactus forest nearby. Learn more about the unique geology of the Tucson Mountains, get great recommendations on how to get the most out of your time in the park, or explore the park bookstore. General information, park maps, and hiking guides are available in front of the building 24-hrs a day

directionsInfo: Getting to the Tucson Mountain District from the City of Tucson Travel west on Speedway Boulevard. At the junction of Camino de Oeste, Speedway Boulevard will change names to Gates Pass Road. From this junction, drive 4 miles (6.5 kilometers) west on Gates Pass Road until it ends at Kinney Road (turn right on Kinney Road). Drive 3 miles (5 kilometers) north on Kinney Road to the Park entrance (entrance is on the right side of the road). Vehicles exceeding 12,000 pounds GVWR are prohibited on Gates Pass

name: Rim Visitor Center
description: Views of the lake are prominent and accessible from Rim Visitor Center. It is located at the historic Kiser Studio in Rim Village. Outdoor exhibits at the near-by Sinnott Memorial Overlook are open when the ice melts from the walkway in June until mid-October. Get your passport stamp when the visitor center is open. Rim Visitor Center is usually open seven days a week in summer.
audioDescription: Arrive at Rim Village, three miles north of the blinking stop sign at park headquarters or via a left turn from the stop sign on West Rim Drive. The road into Rim Village is narrow with two-way traffic, and a 15 mile-per-hour speed limit. Front-in parking aligns most of the right and left sides of the road until it ends in a loop in front of Crater Lake Lodge. RVs and other large vehicles are encouraged to park in the designated area as you enter Rim Village, or in a near-by pull-out along the roads that led you to the village. Accessible parking is available in several locations including in front of Rim Village Visitor Center. During hours of operation, the visitor center is easily located by looking for the American flag flying out front on a pole. Otherwise, no road sign is present indicating the visitor center location. Rim Village is an historic district listed in 1997 on the National Register of Historic Places. Rustic-style features were created with native stone and logs, including a stone parapet wall outlining the Rim Village Promenade. This is a pedestrian and pets only walkway at the caldera edge and serves as a guide through the village, passing behind the Rim Village Visitor Center. The visitor center is inside the Kiser Studio which Fred Kiser built in 1921 and expanded in 1926.It is a small building constructed with native stone and wood shingles. His studio offered visitors hand-colored post cards of photographs that he took of Crater Lake. Today, the Crater Lake Natural History Association operates the park store offering a variety of books, gifts, and educational items for children. In addition to the park store, a ranger is on duty to answer questions and assist with your itinerary. Junior ranger activities for children are offered throughout the day. Ranger talks are given at the Sinnott Memorial Overlook. Rangers will gladly move the talk to a more accessible location upon advance request.

name: Rincon Mountain Visitor Center (East)
description: At the visitor center, you will find the bookstore, information station, maps and restrooms. The visitor center is also the starting point for a scenic auto/bike tour around the Cactus Forest Loop Drive offering incredible views of the Rincon Mountains. There are several great hikes to do along the drive including the mile loop along the Freeman Homestead Trail to learn about homesteading in the desert.

name: Rio Grande Village Visitor Center
description: Rio Grande Village Visitor Center is located 0.25 miles north of the Rio Grande Village developed area and includes exhibits on Big Bend wildlife. River use permits are issued and entrance fees can be paid here. A small desert garden provides an overview of Chihuahuan Desert plants. Rio Grande Village Visitor Center includes a small theater, a Big Bend Natural History Association bookstore, and restrooms. A water faucet is available for filling personal water containers.

name: Rio Grande Village Visitor Center
description: The Rio Grande Village Visitor Center is located 0.25 miles north of the Rio Grande Village developed area. New exhibits focus on the Rio Grande (how it has changed over time, how the NPS works with our Mexican counterparts to protect and care for it, and the rich assemblage of species that it supports). An outdoor ramada showcases a large raised-relief map of the area, and life-sized bronze sculptures showcase some of the area's special wildlife. River use permits are issued during normal business hours.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is located a short distance from the campground and the Rio Grande. It is situated in a flat area, surrounded by mesquite trees, cacti, shrubs, and other desert plants. A number of plants growing in front of the visitor center have been labeled with their names. Just outside the front door are restrooms, benches, and a water bottle filling station. A bookstore, exhibits, and an information table are located inside. An outdoor ramada showcases a large raised-relief map of the area, and life-sized bronze sculptures showcase some of the area's special wildlife.
passportStampLocationDescription: Both the Rio Grande Wild & Scenic River Stamp and Big Bend - Rio Grande Village Stamp are available here.

name: River Raisin National Battlefield Park Visitor / Education Center
description: The NEW Visitor Center is OPEN and offers a Diorama of the River Raisin Settlement, orientation maps, ranger programs, basic park orientation, gift shop, passport stamp and the NEW Theater. The NEW Education Center is still under development however. Please note that although you can get your passport book stamped, our unigrid (park) brochures are being updated and will be in production for some time. Thank you for your understanding.
audioDescription: The new Visitor / Education Center is a former multisports complex and is very large with plenty of room for parking in front of the building and a set of triple doors to the entrance. Once inside the area is expanse, with plenty of room to move about all on the first floor. The eating area, comfort areas, and gift shop are in the main lobby. The new theater has a handicap elevator and handicap seating. The new exhibit areas are all main level with plenty of access, but not open yet.

description: The Robert F. Griggs Visitor Center overlooks the famous Valley of Ten Thousand Smokes and is the starting point of the Ukak Falls Trail. The posted hours are estimated because the visitor center is only open during ranger-led Valley of Ten Thousand Smokes tours.

name: Robert Limbert Visitor Center
description: When open, stop by the visitor center for maps and the Craters of the Moon Natural History Association bookstore, and of course: your passport stamp!
audioDescription: A single-story brown brick building built in the mid century-modern style, lined with large windows. An open concrete walkway connects the front doors to the parking area. Near the entrance to the parking area is a classic brown sign that reads, “Visitor Center, Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve.” On the visitor center itself are the symbols of the National Park Service and the Bureau of Land Management. The Visitor Center is surrounded by native vegetation such as limber pines and sagebrush scrub.
passportStampLocationDescription: Stop by the visitor center to stamp your passport book. Choose from three different stamps, or collect them all!

name: Rock Harbor Visitor Center
description: The Rock Harbor Visitor Center is located in Rock Harbor on the northeast end of Isle Royale National Park. It is only accessible by boat or seaplane. Permitting and fee payment, trip planning assistance, and a park store area available.
audioDescription: As you arrive at the Rock Harbor Dock, the Rock Harbor Visitor Center is located at the end of the dock, beneath the breezeway, on the right hand side. It is a small building with limited occupancy. Obtain passes, permits, and information from park rangers. Shop the Isle Royale & Keweenaw Parks Association Store. The Rock Harbor Trading Post, which sells basic food and camping supplies, is located opposite the Visitor Center beneath the breezeway.

directionsInfo: Rock Harbor is accessible by ferry, private boat, or seaplane. The Ranger III (Houghton, MI), Isle Royale Queen IV (Copper Harbor, MI), and Voyageur II (Grand Portage, MN) boat ferries have service to Rock Harbor. Isle Royale Seaplanes (Houghton, MI and Grand Marais, MN) also has service to Rock Harbor. The Rock Harbor Visitor Center is located at the end of the main passenger ferry dock beneath the breezeway.

description: The Rosie the Riveter Visitor Education Center is the first place to visit when coming to our park. You will be able to see films, interactive exhibits, programs and find out additional information about the Richmond WWII Home Front historic sites.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Visitor Education Center at the Rosie the Riveter/WWII Home Front National Historical Park has a passport stamp for those who visit the site.

name: Rugby Visitor Contact Station
description: Facilities & Activities Ask a ranger what to do in the park; free public WiFi, restrooms; park permits.
audioDescription: From the parking lot to the front door of the visitor center are a set of steps or a ramp to access the porch. The visitor information desk is located straight ahead of the entrance doorway. The restrooms are back outside the visitor center in the parking lot and to the right. The women's room is the first door on the right and the men's room is the on the left. Both restrooms are accessible with several toilet stalls and a sink.

name: Russian Bishop's House
description: One of only four Russian period buildings left in North America. Explore exhibits about Russian America and the role of the Russian Orthodox Church. Free tours are offered May to September. Hours of operation vary depending on staff availability.
audioDescription: One of only four Russian period buildings left in North America. A two story rectangular shaped building. The exterior is painted in Russian America Company signature colors of yellow ochre and iron oxide red. Windows line each story in a uniform fashion. The panes form the shape of the cross.

name: Ryan Visitor Center
description: The Visitors Center, once New York City's first airport terminal, now houses a ranger desk, a bookstore, bathrooms, and many exhibits on the history of aviation, particularly here at Floyd Bennett Field, as well as exhibits about the ecosystems and flora and fauna of the New York Harbor area.
audioDescription: Floyd Bennett Field Ryan Visitor Center Exterior1 of 2 Descriptions of this area597 words; Length: 2:24The Ryan Visitor Center at Floyd Bennett Field is a red brick Georgian style building with white concrete trim. A set of concrete stairs, twenty-five feet wide, lead up to a portico with three sets of glass-paned double doors. The overhanging roof of the portico is supported by two thirty-foot-tall white columns, about two feet in diameter at the base, narrowing slightly at the top. There are ten tall windows on the first floor, five on either side of the steps, and thirteen windows across the second floor. The face of the building at the top of the stairs is white. To the right of the steps as you face the building, there is a trash can and two recycling cans, one for mixed paper in the center and on the right, a can for metal, glass, and plastic. The Visitors Center, once New York's first airport terminal, now houses a ranger desk, a bookstore, bathrooms, and many exhibits on the history of aviation, particularly here at Floyd Bennett Field, as well as exhibits about the eco-systems and flora and fauna of the New York Harbor area. The front doors have glass-paned, rectangular transoms with the panes arranged in an arched design, reflecting the decorative architectural arch above each door and above each of the first floor windows. Above the center door, there is a classic circular clock, about three feet in diameter, with a black frame. A four-foot wide band of white stone trims the top of the second floor all the way around the building. On the left wing of the building, bronze letters with a deep green patina attached to the white stone spell out "Naval Air Station". In the center of the building, it reads "Floyd Bennett Field". On the right wing, it reads "New York". Above this stone band, there is another three feet of brick before reaching the flat roofline of the building. An art-deco-style ornamentation trims the center of the roofline above the door. Two bronze wings with a dark green patina flank a white, raised relief globe that protrudes from the center. The continents of North and South America are featured front and center on the globe.To the right of the steps in the grass between the sidewalk and the building, there is a three-foot by six-foot sign with a stylized wing logo centered with a stylized airplane propeller. Above the logo it reads: "William Fitts Ryan Visitor Center."End of TextAt the rear of the Visitor Center, a trapezoidal-shaped control tower rises four stories high in the center of the building. The top of the control tower is green with a green balustrade and windows on all sides. Twelve-foot wide steps flank each side of the control tower, leading up to a narrow veranda with a white balustrade. There are nine steps up from the ground to the veranda. Double doors at the top of each set of stairs open into the interior of the building. In the stone panel above the second floor, to the left of the control tower, it reads "Naval Air Station". To the right, it reads "Floyd Bennett Field". Standing on the concrete runways behind the Visitors Center and facing the building, there are airplane hangars on the right that have been restored to their original look and feel. To the left, there are unrestored hangars. The runway area is vast. Some of the runways are as long as a mile. There are trees in the distance but other than the tree line, this is wide, open area.End of MessageFloyd Bennett Field Visitor Center Interior2 of 2 Descriptions in this area505 words; Length: 2:13The spacious front hall of the Floyd Bennett Field Visitor Center is about forty feet wide and forty feet deep. The room has been restored to its original art deco look. The floors are a green and white checkerboard pattern. There are three foot by three foot square columns at the corners of the room supporting the second floor balcony, which surrounds the left, rear and right sides of the room. The columns and the walls are painted in a peach toned trompe-l'oeil pattern to resemble horizontal stone blocks. The Visitors Center, once New York's first airport terminal, now houses a ranger desk, a book store and gift shop, bathrooms, video exhibits with archival aviation footage and exhibits on the history of aviation, as well as exhibits about the eco-systems and flora and fauna of the New York Harbor area. About 30 feet from the entrance is a Park Ranger desk where you can obtain more information. There are six-foot tall grey upright signs on both sides of the room that give background on the Gateway National Recreation Area and Floyd Bennett Field.The store on the right sells a wide variety of merchandise, including books on aviation and other subjects, water bottles, t-shirts, snacks, small plush toys, and small camping items. name: Saddlehorn Visitor Center
description: For first hand information, maps, and brochures, the visitor center is a good place to start your adventure. It is located four miles from the Fruita Entrance and near Saddlehorn Campground. It is open every day except Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day and New Years Day. The visitor center includes educational exhibits, an information desk staffed with knowledgeable rangers and volunteers, an eighteen minute long movie, and a bookstore operated by Colorado National Monument Association.
audioDescription: For first hand information, maps, and brochures, the visitor center is a good place to start your adventure. It is located four miles from the Fruita Entrance and near Saddlehorn Campground. It is open every day except Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day and New Years Day. A wide ramp takes you past the restrooms on your right and a native plants garden on your left, from the parking area to the main double doors. The visitor center includes educational exhibits, just inside the main door to the right; an information desk staffed with knowledgeable rangers and volunteers, located inside on the left; an eighteen minute long movie that is played on-demand by a park ranger, located in the auditorium on the right past the exhibit hall; and a bookstore operated by Colorado National Monument Association, which fills the rest of the indoor space. You can pick up Junior Ranger books year round by asking a ranger at the desk. Ranger programs are offered from Memorial Day to Labor Day. A water fountain and water bottle filling station are available 24 hours a day, year round in front of the building. Restrooms are open from 9am to 5pm daily, located in the outdoor hallway to the right of the main entrance door.
passportStampLocationDescription: Collect your Colorado National Monument passport stamp at the visitor center desk.

name: Sailors Haven Visitor Center
description: In addition to a one and a half mile long boardwalk trail through the Sunken Forest, a globally rare maritime holly forest, Sailors Haven also offers a visitor center; snack bar/convenience store/gift shop; picnic tables and grills; lifeguarded beach (summer only); a 45-slip public marina with electricity, water and a free boat pump-out station; restrooms and showers.

name: Saint Croix Island Ranger Station
description: The ranger station provides information for the area and the history of Saint Croix Island and marks the start of the interpretive trail leading out to the viewpoint overlooking the island. During winter, typically the end of October to the week before Memorial Day, services are limited. The displays and bronze statutes along the interpretive trail are covered to prevent damage from inclement weather, and the visitor center is closed.
audioDescription: The ranger station provides information for the area and the history of Saint Croix Island, and marks the start of the interpretive trail leading out to the viewpoint overlooking the island.

The site is located 8 miles (13 km) south of Calais, Maine, on US Route 1, and can be reached either by Route 9 from Bangor or US Route 1, the coastal route from Portland and points south. From US Route 1, turn onto St. Croix Drive. The entrance gate is on the right. The visitor center is inside the ranger station.

name: Salem Armory
description: In the Salem Armory Visitor Center, National Park Service staff and volunteers provide information on historic sites and other places of interest throughout the Essex National Heritage Area. Visitors can learn more about the history of Essex County from the exhibits and free orientation film available inside. Books and gifts are available for purchase in the Salem Maritime National Historic Site Park Store.
audioDescription: Salem Armory Visitor Center. 316 words. The visitor center is a several story red brick building that is approximately 15,000 square feet. The exterior is historic in its character, with red brick columns in the south facing patio of the building. On all sides the building are different aspects of downtown Salem industry and social life: roads, parking lots, and museums. The building has two entrances: one on the southeast corner, and the other on the southwest corner. These are both large glass double-doors that are push/pull only and are accessible via a flat walkway. The interior of the building has three sections open to the public: the large main exhibit space, the giftshop space, then a long hallway leading to a theater. The main exhibit space is approximately 7,000 square feet with the ceiling approximately 50 feet high. On the south wall, there is a large replica of a tall ship, approximately 15 feet across and 30 feet tall, and a red historic coat on the wall. There is a large diorama in the middle of the room and a large flat-screen television with two rows of benches against the east wall. Near there, a replica of the building as it was is under a plastic case. The giftshop space includes multiple rows of shelves and aisles, each adorned with merchandise relating to the national park service or to Salem in particular. On the west side, a long desk used by park and store staff has two cash registers and two large flat-screen television screens on the wall. The long hallway begins north of the giftshop. The hallway is approximately 100 feet long and 25 feet wide. On either sides of the walls are drape exhibits with information relating to the site. Bathrooms are on the east side of this hallway. At the end of the wall way, wooden double-doors on the east side lead to a theater accommodating approximately 200 people. End of Description.

name: Salt Pond Visitor Center
description: Open year-round. Let us help you plan the perfect seashore day! Visit the park museum to learn about the many layers of human history here, watch our award-winning orientation film, Standing Bold, and take in the expansive view of Salt Pond, Nauset Marsh, and the Atlantic. Walking and biking trails start nearby. Ask about the Junior Ranger Program and ranger-guided activities. Want swag? The America's National Parks store operated by Eastern National is open daily.
audioDescription: Salt Pond Visitor Center is a large brick and wood-shingled building with a central lobby area, a hipped cupola-style roof with skylights, and two wings that house a museum and an auditorium. Access to the building is via a state highway. Upon arrival, the building sits on an elevated grassy knoll above a large parking area with hundreds of parking places, including several near the building entrance that are available for vehicles with handicap placards. A restroom building with a bottle filling station is located at the parking lot level. Nearby is a paved accessible path that leads to the building entrance. Upon reaching the entrance, there is an automatic door opener that opens two sets of doors into the lobby. The lobby is a large open area with a high ceiling and a slate(stone) floor. Within the lobby is a staffed ranger information desk, wall exhibits that convey things to do at the seashore, two interior restrooms and a bottle filling station, and a large accessible exhibit at the center of the lobby that includes a tactile element. The lobby includes benches for seating, and floor-to-ceiling windows with a view out to the Salt Pond, a tidal river, a marsh, and the Atlantic beyond. Extending from the lobby are two wings. The wing to the right provides access to a museum with a vast collection of artifacts representing the national seashore's human history, as well as a well-stocked store with seashore-related items for sale. The other wing leads to a classroom, which often hosts art exhibits, and a large auditorium, where several short films are shown. All films have open captions and audio description. Three doors provide access to an outdoor terrace on the pond side of the building. There is an outdoor exhibit describing the creation of the Salt Pond, as well as a large, open-air wooden shed containing a wooden boat and an exhibit explaining its history. Adjacent to the visitor center is a large outdoor amphitheater with bench seating, the Nauset Marsh Trail, which meanders along the pond to the ocean, and the Buttonbush Trail, which has Braille signage and exploration activities for young children. The Nauset Bicycle Trail is located at the end of the parking area.

name: Salt River Bay NHP & EP
description: Salt River Bay Visitor Contact Station: Due to damage from Hurricane Maria the Salt River Bay Visitor Contact Station is closed. Please visit the Visitor Center at Fort Christiansvaern in Christiansted for park information. Fort Christiansvaern at Christiansted National Historic Site serves as the point of information for all three national park units on St. Croix, including Salt River Bay National Historical Park and Ecological Preserve. Visit the fee booth for brochures, pamphlets, and guides.
audioDescription: You will drive through the gates at the bottom of the hill and continue up the steep driveway until you reach the building at the top of the hill. You may drop off passengers at the open gate that takes you to a courtyard. When you enter the courtyard, turn left and walk to the main room of the Visitor Contact Station, where a park volunteer can answer your questions.
passportStampLocationDescription: Come get all three of our St. Croix parks' passport stamps in the fee booth at Christiansted National Historic Site. They may be just simple circles that say the park name and the date of your visit, but you will be the envy of everyone with proof that you were in the Virgin Islands!

name: San Juan NHS Visitor Center
description: Located at Castillo San Cristobal right before entrance to Old San Juan Visitor Center is closed during the pandemic.
audioDescription: Visitors can access San Juan National Historic Site Visitor Center from Muñoz Rivera Avenue. Using a pedestrian gate, they will walk approximately 160 feet to a set of 10 steps or use a ramp of approximately 45 feet in order to enter through two glass doors with the NPS Arrowhead. The visitor center is located at a World War II Bunker built by the US Army in 1942 when the fortifications were part of Fort Brooke. As you enter the visitor center to your left you’ll find a visitor comment form as well as maps of Old San Juan next there is a recycling trash can as well as a donation box in the shape of a Spanish century box called Garita and right after the fee desk where admission fee is paid. Once the visitors pay their admission fee, they will find an exhibit area to their right. They will see a miniature model of Castillo San Cristóbal from the 1700’s. In the model, visitors will be able to see other structures and parts of the park that no longer exists. On top of that model there’s an interpretive panel that with the title: “How to Read a Fortification”. To the left of the miniature the visitors will see other interpretive panels with the following titles: “The Changing Defenses”, “Live in San Juan”, “Standing Guard”, “Key to the Caribbean” and “History and Heritage”. In front of these interpretive panels, visitors will see two wooden benches where they can rest. About 10 feet to the left of these benches there is an exhibit showcasing an original 8 pounder Spanish bronze cannon with an interpretive panel. Behind the cannon, visitors will see another interpretive panel with more information about artillery with the title “Artillery: The King of Battle”. Visitors can see replica tools and instruments used to clean the cannons after each shot was fired. As visitors keep moving to their left, they will find two water fountains as well as both male and female restrooms which are wheelchair accessible. To the left of the restrooms, visitors will find a complete exhibit on the materials and instruments used to build and maintain a fortifications. In this area visitors will see interpretive panels with the titles “It takes Teamwork” “Beyond Trowels and Plaster”, “Getting it Right”. To the left of this exhibit there is a hallway that provides visitors access to the entrance of the Visitor Center’s Theater. Currently the park is showing a documentary about the chronological history of the park that last approximately 17 minutes. To the left of the theater there is a World War II decontamination chamber that has an interpretive panel with the title “Decontamination Room” if the visitor keeps walking to the left they will find the exit which leads them back to the steps in front of the Visitor Center. To the right of the theater there is a monitor with two phones where visitors can select items from the collection that they want to know more about visitors will find an exhibit case that has inside a 16 century armor, the Spanish flag of the 1900s, three models of the Spanish vessels of La Niña La Pinta and La Santa Maria and finally reproductions of 1898 Spanish-American war telegrams. In front of the exhibit case there are four interpretive panels with the titles “Within These Walls”, “Clothes Make the Soldier”, “Documenting the Past”, “The Things They Left Behind”. To the left of these interpretive panels, visitors will find America’s National Parks Stores. Here visitors can find water as well as books and souvenirs about the park, including the NPS passport stamp. To the left of the store the visitors will find a set of 5 steps that lead to a tunnel and to the left of the steps there is an elevator that takes visitors one flight up to an open area, where visitors can start exploring the Spanish fortification.
passportStampLocationDescription: Please visit our America's National Park Stores throughout the park to get your passport stamped.

name: San Miguel Island Ranger and Visitor Contact Station
description: The visitor contact and ranger station is only open when staff is present.
audioDescription:
In an open field, next to the airplane landing strip, sits the ranger station. It is an L-shaped wooden building. The building has brown, planked wood siding. If facing the front of the building, four upper, clerestory windows are visible near the peak of the roof. A lower roof overhangs the front of the building, supported by beams and posts, creating a covered walkway. Along that walkway, at ground level, five windows alternate with five doors. Two wooden benches along the exterior wall provide seating. At the bend of the L-shape is a 10-foot by 10-foot structure that sticks up about 10 feet taller than the roof. Sticking up from it are several tall rods and a shallow, concave-shaped satellite dish. An outdoor lamp attached to the side.

In front of the station is a picnic table and a flagpole, flying the United States flag. On the left side of the walkway is a low wire frame platform. Mounted on top of this is a large brush, made of stiff blue plastic spikes, used to clean off the bottoms of boots. Further to the left is a small, single-seater wood plank outhouse, with symbols on the door representing both a man and a woman. Several other small storage sheds are nearby.The ranger station information center is through the second door from the right. The room is a large and open space, with high ceilings. It has light wood paneling. Windows line the back wall behind a partially-partitioned area with desks and a table with two chairs. Colorful pictures on the walls display island views. On the left side of the room are two doors leading to equipment and supply closets. To the right is a television, set on the top of a corner cabinet, with a shelf of videos below it.

name: Santa Barbara Island Visitor Center
description: A small visitor center is located on the island. Features include displays on the natural and cultural resources of the island.
audioDescription:
If you are standing at the flagpole, facing the Santa Barbara Island Visitor Center, you are on a high bluff, and the ocean is far below, on your left. You are in the middle of a coreopsis forest. Depending on the season, the coreopsis, with a thick, bare trunk, topped by a shaggy mop of yellow flowers and feathery green leaves, shaped like fluffy ostrich feathers. In late summer, fall or winter, the coreopsis will turn into waist-high brown stalks that look dead.

The single-story beige building, has a roof made of overlapping curved red tiles. On the wall, facing you, are two wooden signs with white lettering. The one on the ocean side reads, "Visitor Center." The one on the land side reads, "Private Residence." Between the signs are two narrow vertical windows. Below the windows, running the length of the building are several dense shrubs. An open patio extends out on the ocean side of the building, but watch your step, as it is about ten inches above ground. Just off this patio is the door to the visitor center and a tall window with a view into the exhibit. The patio has a picnic table and an outdoor panel about sea bird habitat, described separately. Beyond this first patio is another, gated, patio, blocked by a brick wall. On the opposite side of building-the "Private Residence" side- is a walkway running the length of the building.

name: Santa Rosa Island Visitor Contact Station
description: The historic schoolhouse is now home to this small visitor contact station with exhibits on the ranching history of Santa Rosa Island.
audioDescription: Standing in the doorway of the school house facing inward, the interior is about 16 feet long and 8 feet wide. The walls and ceiling are finished with narrow vertical wooden slat paneling, painted white. The ceiling has a framed inset panel, to access the attic, and a white ceramic ceiling lamp, with a brass mount. The wooden plank floor has a glossy polish. Moving into the room, along the left wall, you will find a framed window with thin wooden mullions containing 12 glass panes; a mounted metal box; a clear plastic pamphlet holder; an information panel; two larger exhibit panels with a low wooden green bench below them; six exhibits with large photographs; and a wall plaque that reads,AcknowledgementsImages of Santa Cruz Island, Santa Rosa Island and Nuestra Senora del RefugioCommemorating Early Land Grants on Both Sides of the ChannelAn exhibition organized by the Santa Barbara Trust for Historic PreservationExhibition Sponsors: The Henry W. Bull FoundationCurators: Carol Storke, Anne Petersen, Curator. SBTHPCuratorial Assistant: Amanda WillifordPhotography and Printing: William B. DeweyGraphic Design: Mary KirkPatrick, Clearview StudioPrint Mounting: Ken KirkPatrick, Anacapa SignsSpecial Thanks:Chris Chapman, Manager, Arroyo Hondo Preserve; Peggy Dahl, Santa Cruz Island Foundation; Marla Daily, President, Santa Cruz Island Foundation; Neal Graffy, Elizabeth Hvolboll, Michael Redmon, Archivist, Santa Barbara Historical Society; Terri Sheridan, Archivist, Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History; Nita Vail, Executive Director, California Rangeland Trust; Kim Walters, Archivist, Southwest Museum; Lynn Weber, Curatorial Volunteer, SBTHP. Will Woolley and the staff, board and many volunteers at the Santa Barbara Trust for Historic Preservation. On the lower right corner of the plaque is the Seal of the Santa Barbara Trust Historic Preservation, a round logo, with a center illustration of an early adobe brick Spanish mission building, with a bell tower with a cross on top.Along the back wall is wooden door, and also two tall closet doors.Along the right wall, from back to front, are two windows; four exhibits with large photos; and another window with a green wooden bench below it.On the floor near the back of the room, are four wooden chairs, arranged in two rows, both facing the front door. Each has a single arm rest that extends and curves out to become a wide flat panel, parallel to the floor. The two chairs have this arm rest panel on the right "arm," and the other two have it on the left "arm."An information panel, titled "Santa Rosa Island Interpretive Guide," is posted on the wall inside the School House.The panel background is a black and white photo showing twelve people on horseback, in front of a wooden fence. Behind it is a thick section of trees. In the distance, to the left, is a large hill.The text reads,Learn more about ranch history, including a complete map and guide to the ranch area, in the Santa Rosa Island Interpretive Guide.The guide also provides detailed information on island Chumash history, military history, and natural history. In addition, it serves as a trail guide for the 1.75 mile hike from the pier to Water Canyon Beach via Cherry Canyon.Borrow the guide and return it or take it home and donate at ciparkfoundation.org/join-support/.Below and to the left of this panel is a small metal box with a locked panel in front, and a slanted top with a slit in the center, about three inches wide. To the right of this box is a wall mounted plastic holder that contains the guides. This exhibit panel, titled "Channel Island Ranchos," provides cultural history about Santa Cruz Island and Santa Rosa Island.The panel background is a faded sepia photo, in shades of brown. It shows a steep, rocky shoreline, with a wooden staircase rising from the beach to the rocky plateau above. On the plateau are a large, long building, two smaller buildings, and canvas tents. The text reads:Santa Cruz Island covers almost 61,000 acres, its fertile central valley girded by rugged mountains, reaching 2,434 feet.Santa Rosa Island encompasses over 54,000 acres, of strikingly different topography - rolling grassy hills, mesas with deep-cut arroyos, and dunes that shift in the almost continuous winds.The Early Years.Humans inhabited the Channel Islands as early as 12,000 years ago. In 1542, Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo found populous Chumash villages on Santa Cruz, Santa Rosa, and San Miguel islands. The waters of the Santa Barbara Channel teemed with marine life, and the Channel Islands were regular ports of call for fur traders, hunters, and fishermen in the late eighteenth century, although most trade was illegal under both Spanish (1769 to 1821) and Mexican (1821 to 1848) rule. The sea otter population experienced a serious decline by 1820 and the seals by 1830. By 1810 the islanders, victimized by European disease and their economy disrupted, began to migrate to the mainland at the urging of Franciscan padres.

name: Satwiwa Native American Indian Culture Center
description: Located at the southern end of the community of Newbury Park, this site reflects the heritage of both Native Americans and local ranching. The Satwiwa Native American Indian Culture Center is open on weekends from 9am to 5pm. Native American workshops and programs occur throughout the year.

description: The Schoodic Institute Welcome Center at Rockefeller Hall is located on Schoodic Peninsula off the one-way loop road. Exhibits about the old Navy base and park information can be found here.
audioDescription: A large two-story brick and slate building with blue detailing and a front walkway from a parking area. A walkway leads to a main entrance from the parking area. Inside, visitors can see exhibits about the old Navy base, find park information, or browse the gift shop.

A pattern of outwardly radiating lines borders the stamp's graphics and text.

name: Scorpion Ranch Visitor Center on Santa Cruz Island
description: The small visitor center resides in the historic Scorpion Ranch house which was constructed in 1886-1887.
audioDescription: On the valley floor, within the protection of a wide canyon is the Scorpion Ranch housing complex that consists of a two-story ranch house with a kitchen, bakery with a built-in masonry oven, dining area and two rooms upstairs for housing ranch staff. A bunkhouse and a storage shed, about the size of a garage, are also within the 5-foot-high wooden split rail fence that surrounds the compound. Gardens, shrubs and fig trees edge the buildings. The two-story, adobe Scorpion Ranch house, now the visitor center with exhibits, is tucked in close to the canyon walls and faces the open valley to the south. The ranch house was built in 1886 of rubble-wall masonry and rests on a stone and mortar foundation. The building has a rectangular plan that measures 51 feet by 18 feet. It has a shed roof and walls that are 20 inches thick and composed of local stone, adobe bricks, mortar covered with white stucco, and limestone. Windows across the face of the building provide natural light. The first floor has two main rooms, both are open to the public with exhibits and audio visual components that describe the natural and cultural history of the area. The bakery is at the west end of the building and also contains exhibits. The bunkhouse is located immediately south of the adobe ranch house. Built in 1914, this one-and-a-half story wood frame structure has a simple, gable-roof and white board-and-batten siding.

name: Scotts Bluff National Monument Visitor Center
description: Located just steps away from the route of the Oregon, California, and Pony Express Trails; the Scotts Bluff National Monument Visitor Center features exhibits, a theater, and restroom facilities. The visitor center is located in the Mountain Time Zone.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 578 words. A brick and adobe building, painted tan, approximately 130 feet wide on its south side and topped with a pitched cedar shake roof. One-eighth of a mile behind the building, the sandstone bluff known as Scotts Bluff rises 435 feet above the elevation of the building. The bluff is covered with scattered trees, shrubs and grasses. West of the building is the start of a road that leads up to the summit of the bluff. To the east of the building is a parking area for oversized vehicles and a small picnic area with three covered picnic tables. Most of the building is one story high and 15 feet tall, but on the southwest corner of the building is a second story tower that measures 15 feet by 15 feet and is about 15 feet taller than the rest of the building. Below the second story tower, on the first flor of the building, is a large 8 foot wide by 5 foot tall picture window. Just to the east of the picture window is a triangular-shaped archway portico entrance and a 40 inch wide by 80 inch tall wooden door. East of the triangular entrance archway are 7 windows. Each is 8 feet above ground level and measures 5 feet wide by 2 feet tall. Each of these windows is separated by about 36 inches and covered with a decorative brick lattice work. In front of the building is a grassy lawn. A sidewalk leads on an east/west axis about 4 feet in front of the south side of the building. In between the sidewalk and the building, the ground is landscaped with smooth river rocks, with native plants scattered throughout. A 36 foot long and 15 foot wide concrete sidewalk leads from the parking lot to the entrance portico which is enclosed in brick and located on the east end of the south side of the building. The portico is about 15 feet wide and 6 feet deep, and terminates at a set of brown steel double doors, each with 42 inch tall by 23 inch wide windows, that leads into the building. On each side of the doors is an additional 15 inch wide by 44 inch tall window. Inside the entrance doors, an information desk that is 12 feet wide and 2 feet deep, is 9 feet straight ahead in a lobby area. Just west of the lobby is the cooperating association bookstore; a sales area filled with apparel, books, and souvenirs. Twenty feet southwest of the entrance doors is a short hallway that is 20 feet long and 5 feet wide. At the northern terminus of this hallway is another hallway. Fifteen feet due east is a wooden door that leads into the men's room. The ladies room is accessed by a wooden door 15 feet north of the men's room door. From the restroom area, a hallway heads west for 96 feet. Forty feet west of the restroom area, there is a door on the north side of the hallway that leads into a 30 foot by 25 foot multi-purpose room and theater. Continuing down this hallway will lead to two exhibit rooms. From the entrance portico, a sidewalk leads east 10 feet, then turns to the north where it travels 60 feet to the entrance to a unisex bathroom accessed by a steel door, painted brown on the east side of the building. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: Scotts Bluff National Monument features five different "Passport to Your National Parks" cancellation stamps: Scotts Bluff National Monument, Oregon National Historic Trail, California National Historic Trail, Mormon Pioneer National Historic Trail, and Pony Express National Historic Trail.

name: Sea Camp Ranger Station
description: Located at the Sea Camp dock on Cumberland Island. Visitors camping on the island must visit Sea Camp for a quick orientation and to receive their camping permits. Volunteers and rangers staff the station when available throughout the day. Here visitors can get information, see exhibits, attend interpretive programs, and rent bicycles when the ferry arrives.
audioDescription: When arriving on the island at the Sea Camp from the Cumberland Island Ferry, the ranger station will be on the left after exiting the dock pier. The building is tucked under a canopy of live oak trees. A small clearing in the front of the building allows visitors to get their bearings as they arrive. Picnic tables are scattered throughout the clearing. The ranger station is a single story wooden building with a large front porch with no railing. The siding is natural and has darkened over time. A short set of stairs leads up to the porch. The the main entrance is straight ahead, to the left is the presentation room, and to the right the porch continues and there is a water filling station and bathrooms. The main visitor area of the ranger station has a screen door that opens outward and a wooden door with paned windows that opens inward and leads inside. Large picture windows frame the visitor area on three sides. Once inside, the information desk is diagonal ahead to the right. It is staffed periodically throughout the day depending on the duties the ranger has to attend. Straight ahead upon entering is a small touch table containing objects found on the island. A few shadow box frames hung on the wall highlight some of the fossils, shark teeth and shells found on the island. There is a weather board with current weather conditions on the wall and to the left of the touch table. Back on the porch, to the left at the top of the stairs, the porch wraps around and leads to a presentation room, which is open daily at 4:00 for a dockside talk. There is short entrance area that leads into the room. Chairs are set up in two sets of rows on the left side of the room and the right side of the room contains the TV and other props for the ranger to use for their presentation. Back on the porch, turning to the right at the top of the stairs leads to an uncovered portion of the porch. There is a bottle filling station to the left, located next to the main room of the ranger station. Benches line the porch along the building. There is no railing on the edge of the porch. At the far end of the porch, to the right when facing the ranger station, there is an ADA ramp that leads up to the porch. Bathrooms are located a the far right side of the porch and around the corner to the left. Women’s on the left and men’s on the right. Near the bathrooms are several beach wheelchairs available for those with mobility issues.
passportStampLocationDescription: Three stamps are available at the Sea Camp Ranger Station. Cumberland Island Stamp – The official stamp with the words “Cumberland Island National Seashore, St. Marys, GA,” and the date. Gullah-Geechee stamp – A stamp commemorating Cumberland Island’s role in the Gullah-Geechee Heritage Corridor. Reads “Gullah-Geechee Historic Corridor, Cumberland Island,” and the date. Cumberland Island outline stamp – This stamp is an outline of Cumberland Island with the words “Cumberland Island.”

name: Selma Interpretive Center
description: This center is currently closed.
audioDescription: This visitor center is at the corner of Broad Street and Water Street in Selma, and is located mere steps from the Edmund Pettus Bridge. Diagonal street parking on the sides of the building face a 3-story tan structure connected to the rest of the buildings on the block. A National Park Service arrowhead can be seen on the corner of the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Selma Interpretive Center has four stamps: our traditional NPS stamp, our park emblem stamp, the U.S. Civil Rights Trail stamp and a new Selma Interpretive Center stamp.

name: Shark Valley Visitor Center
description: Shark Valley Visitor Center provides the gateway to a panoramic 15-mile loop trail and observation tower. Open year-round, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. the visitor center also hosts exhibits, park film, and association bookstore, alongside the Shark Valley Tram Tour concessionaire. The GPS address for the visitor center is; 36000 SW 8th Street, Miami, FL 33194.
audioDescription: As you cross the parking lot of five rows, you may notice the clumps of large mahogany and gumbo limbo trees with their peeling red bark. A small quiet picnic table sits amongst the trees. Before entering the building, there are signs detailing the variety of experiences that visitors can create. Information on tram and bicycle prices, tour length, and expectations of your experience are posted outside the building. There are a couple of large satellite images, to the left of the door, showing the fifteen-mile long path and the habitats that it traverses through. The large, white building holds both a visitor center and a concessionaire for bicycle and tram tour sales. Alongside the main entrance doors is a blue accessibility symbol on the right-hand side. The right-hand door will open automatically into a foyer where an extremely large black and white mural by Clyde Butcher is displayed. The mural depicts a sawgrass prairie in wet season, with the classic Shark Valley Lookout Tower in the background. The quote by Gifford Pinchot (Pin – Shoh), “It is a region so different that it hardly seems to belong to the United States. It is full of the most vivid and interesting life on land, in the air, and in the water,” is placed in the middle of the mural. If you would like to talk to the concessionaire, turn right, otherwise head left into the well-lit, Shark Valley Visitor Center. As you turn left into the visitor center, immediately upon the left wall is the floor plan with a tactile braille display. An emergency exit plan is displayed as well. As you walk further into the visitor center, to your left, a four-foot-tall wooden board rests against the wall and details the height of several Florida birds. This is fascinating for our younger visitors. Next to the bird display is our stamp table, a very popular item. To the right of the stamps is the ranger station, where numerous pamphlets and informational brochures are available. Behind the ranger station, upon the wall is an enormous map of Everglades National Park, detailing all the visitor centers, trails and ecosystems. To the left of the park map is a blowup map of the 15-mile paved Shark Valley Loop Trail. Two TV screens to the left and right of the park map show a continual slideshow of information on weather, ranger programs and frequently asked questions. Two wheelchairs are available and placed behind the ranger desk. Various Everglades educational props can be found on display behind the ranger desk. To the right of the ranger desk, is an additional surface filled with brochures on Everglades National Park, invasive species and junior ranger books. If you turn around, the opposite side of the room contains more exhibits for hands-on learning. Along the far wall is an exhibit detailing the differences between Florida’s wet and dry seasons. The display shows a month by month basis, detailing the temperature, humidity and hydroperiod (amount of time that water is present) within Everglades National Park. Furthermore, there is a touch table display detailing how water flows during wet season, the importance of periphyton (puh-rif-i-ton), how the land topography affects the water flow and why this area is called the River of Grass. Additional mini displays explain common Florida animals and how their lifecycles are tied to the seasonal changes in Everglades National Park. A detailed photo of an alligator mentions how they are ecosystem engineers. A large three-dimensional wood stork stalks and hunts for fish across a display that mentions their role in the Everglades as well. In the center of the room is a teardrop shaped, standalone exhibit. It is covered with photos of Everglades ecosystems. If you open the doors on the display, additional information on the Everglades equation can be found. A door on the limestone bedrock, hardwood hammocks, willow heads and sawgrass marsh open under your hands and provide additional details on their roles. This display tells the story of swamp manipulation that began in the 1880s, and how important the protected area of Shark Valley is today. To your right after leaving the exhibit area is a set of glass doors that lead you out of the visitor center, and under a canopy, where you can wait for your designated tram tour to begin. As you wait, you can sit upon several benches, and enjoy a park film which will prepare you for your exploration of Shark Valley.

name: Shiloh Battlefield Visitor Center
description: Shiloh Battlefield Visitor Center is open from 8:00 am to 5:00 pm every day except Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Year's Day. View the award winning orientation film, "Shiloh: Fiery Trial," shown every hour. Shiloh Battlefield Visitor Center is located at 1055 Pittsburg Landing Road in Shiloh, TN.
audioDescription: Upon arriving in the visitor center parking lot at 1055 Pittsburg Landing Road, walk west towards the large brick building with four tall, yellow columns on the front porch. Once your enter the building, the restrooms and water fountain will be located on your left, and an information desk will be located to your right, staffed by NPS rangers. Park maps for the driving tour can be acquired from the rangers at the information desk. As you walk to the rear of the visitor center there are three witness cannon on the wall ahead of you. To the left of the cannons are artifacts from the battle and exhibits, both on the walls and in exhibit cases. To the right of the the three cannons you will walk down a short hallway to the double doors of the auditorium. The park film, "Shiloh: Fiery Trial" is shown in the auditorium every hour on the hour.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available in the park's bookstore located across the parking lot from the visitor center.

name: South Unit Visitor Center
description: Rangers staff the desk, assist visitors with trip planning, and issue backcountry permits. Theodore Roosevelt's Maltese Cross Cabin, located just outside, is open for self-guided tours year-round. Ranger-led cabin tours are offered in the summer. The park film, Refuge of the American Spirit, shows in the theater. A bookstore sells books, postcards, and more. A museum houses artifacts from Theodore Roosevelt's presidency and time in the badlands.

name: Spectacle Island Visitor Center
description: The Spectacle Island Visitor Center has a staffed information desk, a small island exhibit and informative island movie, and restrooms.
audioDescription: Two-story rectangular building with tan-colored siding. The first floor is surrounded on three sides with a covered porch, which has dark-colored tiled roofing. The porch has several rocking chairs interspersed. Large glass doors and wall-length windows are line most of the three sides that are accessible to the public. The second floor has a series of large square windows with black trim. When facing the only long side of the building accessible to visitors, there are two pediments with gabled roofs that cut into the main roof.

name: Springfield Armory National Historic Site Visitor Center and Museum
description: The park visitor center offers a large museum dedicated to the American Industrial Revolution and the weapons made at Springfield Armory. There is a Junior Ranger program available.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is located inside of the Main Arsenal. The Main Arsenal is a three story brick building, with a central clock tower and an American Flag erected on top. The Visitor Center Desk is located inside the building at the back. On either side of the Visitor Center Desk is the Springfield Armory Museum, with one side focusing on technological innovations and industry, and the other side looks at firearms.

name: St. Croix River Visitor Center
description: The St. Croix River Visitor Center is CLOSED for the winter season and will reopen April 12, 2024. Hours of operation are 10:00 am to 5:00 pm daily including all federal holidays. When open, visitors can view exhibits, pick up park publications, Junior Ranger booklets, and maps, and view the park film. Park rangers offer trip planning assistance for the St. Croix and Namekagon rivers. The park headquarters offices are also located in this building along the St. Croix River.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 521 words. The Saint Croix River Visitor Center is a two story dark brown and tan wood and concrete building measuring 125 feet wide. It faces east at Hamilton Street. The building consists of two sections. Seen from the front, the lower section is a one-story curved wall of glass windows. The roof of that section is flat with native low-grow plants. The second section is a two-story rectangle building with a line of individual windows on the second floor facing south. Another set of windows on the same floor faces south. It's flat roof is not visible at ground level. A prominent tan concrete wall jets out from the middle of the building measuring 20 feet tall and extends 20 feet from the main entrance doors. Two sets of concrete walkways lead down from Hamilton Street to a set of two metal-glass entrance doors. One walkway has two sets of 6 steps measuring 10 feet wide by 75 feet long down to the entrance doors. Another concrete wheelchair accessible path leads down from Hamilton Street 275 feet to the entrance doors. There is an automatic open button for the entrance doors to the right of the entrance doors. An information map panel is located on the same wall as the button to the right. The information map panel shows the St Croix and Namekagon Rivers. Below the panel is a long, clear plastic brochure box with a lid containing 10 different river maps for the park. A small, brown metal box located to the right of the plastic brochure box contain park brochures. A 35-foot tall silver aluminum flag pole with an American flag waves in the breeze located 50 feet to the east of the building with three short lamp posts that canvas the concrete walkway leading into the building. Between the building and the walkways is landscaped with wildflowers and low-growing native plants with larger and taller trees in the back and north sides of the building. Five feet inside the main entrance double doors, there is another set of double doors. There is an automatic button for the second set of doors on the wall, to the right. The second set of doors leads to a hallway. Immediately after entering the building using the second set of double doors to the right is the entrance for the bathrooms. To the left is the entrance door for the men's bathroom. To the right is the entrance for the women's bathroom. There is a water fountain that sticks out 18 inches from the wall, between the men's and women's restroom entrances. The hallway leading from the second set of main entrance double doors leads to an information desk which is 15 feet straight ahead after entering. A plastic brochure rack is on the left contains various information brochures. The bookstore begins about 20 feet to the left after the information desk. There is a museum space of exhibits and theater inside the visitor center. The museum is 40 feet past the information desk to the left. The theater entrance is 10 feet directly opposite of the information desk. End of description.
passportStampLocationDescription: If the St. Croix River Visitor Center is closed upon your visit, please call 715-483-2274 or email sacn_info@nps.gov to request the stamp to be mailed. The Riverway stamps are also available at the Polk County Information Center located at 710 Highway 35 S in St. Croix Falls. Phone 1-800-222-POLK for business hours.

name: Stearns Visitor Contact Station
description: Facilities Ask a ranger what to do in the park; restrooms; park permits.
audioDescription: From the parking lot to the front door of the visitor center are a set of steps or a ramp to access the porch. The visitor information desk is located straight ahead of the entrance doorway. The desk sits in a room with a couch and chair on one side and a conference table and chair on the other. The restrooms are back outside the visitor center in the parking lot and to the right. The women's room is the first door on the right and the men's room is the next door to the right. Both restrooms are accessible with a toilet stall and sink.

name: Steel Creek Ranger Station
description: Steel Creek Ranger Station is open in the summer on an intermittent basis as rangers are available. The Steel Creek Ranger Station is located in the Valley Y Ranch Historic Area of Steel Creek Campground. Please call before you visit to ensure that staff will be available to assist you: 870-861-2570.
audioDescription: Steel Creek Ranger Station is located in a former outbuilding of the Valley Y Ranch. The entrance to Steel Creek is a 2 1/2 mile curving paved road off Highway 74. At the valley floor the road becomes gravel and divides - left to the campground and right to the horse campground, ranger station and river access area. Straight ahead is a long tall cliff of gray rock with mineral stains of multiple colors streaking from top to bottom. Right on the gravel road past the horse campground is a small parking area at a brown wooden building. The ranger station entrance is to the right, up a short grassy incline. The entrance door is on your left.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamp is a black circle. Buffalo National River curves along the top. The current date is straight across the center. First National River curves along the bottom.

directionsInfo: From Ponca, AR take Hwy. 74 E. for approximately 1.5 miles OR from Jasper, AR take Hwy. 74 W. approximately 12.6 miles until you see the entrance sign for Steel Creek Area. Turn onto the Steel Creek Road and follow it for approximately 1 mile into the valley. When the paved entrance road turns to gravel, take the first right and follow the road past the horse camping area until you reach the ranger station on the right side of the corner.

name: Steel Visitor Center
description: Steel Visitor Center is closed until late Winter 2024 due to major structural renovation to stabilize the building against seismic and excessive snow load forces. The historic integrity of this former ranger dormitory, now known as the Steel Visitor Center, will remain while accessibility and safety will be increased for all visitors and staff. The building will get new electric wiring, IT cabling, plumbing, heating, and an updated interior building layout.
audioDescription: Steel Visitor Center is in the historic, park headquarters area. A blinking stop sign, the only one in the park, signals where to turn off the main drive and into the oval parking lot with an oval center of native plants (currently more dirt than plants). The American flag flies on a pole in front of the 2-story, native stone building with wood roof shingles. If the flag is not erected, it is a signal that the visitor center and all amenities are closed. The Sager Administration Building is also in the oval with additional parking behind it. There are two accessible parking spaces in front of the flagpole, and drop-off space next to the winter-access snow tunnel. Entry into the building is across a native stone walkway in the front during summer but through a year-round snow tunnel on the right side of the building during winter and early spring. The stones on the front walkway create an unlevel surface which presents navigation challenges for some. At the building entrance are trash and recycling containers. A native stone patio, and stone corners with low wood railings surrounds a bank of windows, and provides a place for visitors to gather. The front entry door is a large, wood, rustic-style door. Once inside, immediately to the right is a window opening to the Crater Lake Post Office, (check for current hours) a mail drop-slot, and a few framed posters sold in the park store. Approximately five to six steps forward from the front door is a hallway to the right. In nine steps up a slightly-sloped ramp, and to the right are the men’s restroom, a combination drinking fountain and water bottle filling station, and the women’s restroom. An outward swinging door to each restoom provides access to an accessible stall, toilets, and urinals respectively. A baby diaper changing station is found in the women’s restroom. To the left of the front door is the visitor center, auditorium, and the park store operated by the Crater Lake Natural History Association. Rangers and park store personnel are available to answer your questions about the park and assist with travel plans. The space is small so there are no exhibits except for a relief model of the lake and caldera rim. You will find a variety of books, gifts, Junior Ranger and educational items for sale. A few comfy chairs are in front of an historic native stone, non-functional, fireplace. During summer the room is too crowded to linger but during winter the chairs offer a nice reprieve from the cold. A door next to the visitor center information desk leads into the auditorium which seats 37 people. Within three feet of entering the auditorium, there are two steps up, marked with yellow tape. Staff is available to safely assist everyone in finding an available seat. A park video plays every hour and half hour. An audio described version is shown upon request.
passportStampLocationDescription: Crater Lake's stamp is generally available during business hours at any open visitor center. If you arrive after hours or forget to bring your Passport book, you can print a stamp from home or contact us to request a stamped piece of paper through the mail. https://www.nps.gov/crla/planyourvisit/stamp-your-passport-book.htm

name: Stockton Island Visitor Center
description: Stockton Island Visitor Center is open seasonally during the summer months. The building is open during the day, and rangers are on site or around the greater Presque Isle area. Rangers are available to answer questions or assist in emergencies. General information and small exhibits are available inside. This area provides trail access to the Tombolo, Julian Bay, and Anderson Bay Trails. The Presque Isle camping area and marina provide 17 campsites and overnight docking locations.

name: Sugarlands Visitor Center
description: Near Gatlinburg, TN, Sugarlands Visitor Center is an excellent starting point as you enter the park's North District. Learn about the park's plants and animals with natural history exhibits. Enjoy ranger-led programs conducted seasonally. Peruse the park bookstore and shop. Access public restrooms and drink vending machines. The Backcountry Permit Office is here, too.
audioDescription: Once in the visitor center, you're met at the door by a black bear exhibit. Next, there is a large relief map of the entire Smoky Mountains and it's trails. At the front desk you will find a knowledgeable group of employees to assist with questions, directions and swearing in Jr. Rangers. There's a monitor on the wall showcasing the webcams throughout the park, with helpful information such as temperature, elevation, and more. Then you walk into the exhibit area. It displays some of the animals and plants that live or once lived in the Smokies. Head into the bookstore/souvenir shop. There's something for everyone in there. No cash? No worries, there's an ATM just outside of the store.
