name: Sunrise Visitor Center
description: Located on the northeast flank of Mount Rainier, this visitor center is at the end of the Sunrise Road, 15 miles after the turn off from State Route 410. Only open and accessible in summer, the Sunrise Visitor Center has exhibits, books and maps for sale, and rangers and volunteers on duty to answer questions. Restrooms, gift shop, and food services are located nearby during the summer season.
audioDescription: The Sunrise Visitor Center is a long, rectangular building of log construction, standing on a slight rise at the far end of the parking lot. In front of it on either side are two smaller, square, two-story buildings, forming a "U." These blockhouses are ranger residences and are not open to the public. All three buildings are of log construction with white caulking and cedar shake roofing. Each has a stone chimney extending above the roof. The visitor center has large, multi-paned windows just under the two-story roofline. To reach the visitor center, there are two sidewalks, one on either side, which curve up between the other buildings to the entrance. There are two steps up to the windowed, double doors. Above them a sign, white lettering on a wooden background says "Sunrise Visitor Center."This is a large, airy rectangular room, approximately 80 feet by 45 feet. The walls, floor and ceiling are all made of wood, either unfinished or with a natural finish, giving the room a warm, rustic feel. The walls are made of logs over a foot in diameter and rise up about 15 feet to the open rafters. Log truss-work supports the plank roofing. The smooth, polished flooring is made of wide planks. There are windows high up on the long, east and west walls, just under the roofline. The wall on the south (on your left when entering) has large, plate glass windows where the mountain may be viewed on clear days. The north wall to the right has a massive stone fireplace in its center. Benches grouped around a low table sit in front of the fireplace. On the far side of the fireplace, in the northeast corner of the room, is a short hallway that leads to another exit, leading to the picnic area. The main entrance is through doors halfway along the east wall. Immediately to the right is an information desk. Beyond the desk is the bookstore, with shelving along the wall and two bookcases, one on the far side of the fireplace grouping, and one near the front of the counter. A variety of items are available for purchase, including books, posters, tee shirts, postcards and other items. The exhibits in the room consist of graphic panels, glass cases, and some touchable items, located along most of the walls and in five groupings in the middle of the floor. Audio description of the exhibits is available at the desk.

name: Sunset Crater Volcano Visitor Center
description: The Sunset Crater Volcano Visitor Center includes a museum, WNPA park store, park film, and restroom facilities. The building features architecture from the Mission 66 era. Park rangers are present, passes are available for purchase, and Junior Ranger activities are available.

name: Sycamore Shoals State Historic Park Visitor Center
description: Visitor Center for Sycamore Shoals State Historic Park, part of the Tennessee State Parks system. Featuring a museum and lecture hall, gift store, recreation of a 1776 log fort, and hiking trail along the Watauga River.

name: Taft Education Center
description: The Taft Education Center is the park's main visitor center. It is the first building visitors should enter upon arriving to the park. Restrooms are located inside the building along with a water fountain. Visitors will be able to view the park film, arrange for a tour of the Taft home and purchase small items in the park's bookstore. Additionally, special exhibits are available for viewing during various times of the year. Please check the Operations Hours section for building hours.

name: Tallgrass Prairie National Preserve Visitor Center
description: Begin your preserve visit with the visitor center, complete with 10-minute orientation video, exhibits, indoor and outdoor restrooms, and water fountains. The visitor center is located on the left side of the breezeway. Rangers attend the visitor center during regular business hours. Summer hours run from May through October. Shorter winter hours run from November through April.
audioDescription: Begin your preserve visit with the visitor center, complete with ten minute orientation video, exhibits, indoor and outdoor restrooms, and water fountains. The visitor center is located on the left side of the breezeway. Rangers attend the visitor center during regular business hours. Summer hours run from May through October. Shorter winter hours run from November through April.
passportStampLocationDescription: Tallgrass Prairie National Preserve offers 4 stamps. The standard passport cancellation stamp depicts the park name, city, and current date. The National Parks 2016 Centennial stamp has the static date 1916-2016. The larger stamp has the name with cowboy riding a horse. The large Tallgrass Prairie 20th Anniversary stamp depicts the ranch house with current date.

name: The Chilkoot Trail Center
description: Open daily Memorial Day to Labor Day, this is the registration and information center for the Chilkoot Trail. Stop by to pick up your Chilkoot Trail permit, see the bear awareness video, and get your trail orientation. During permit season, regularly scheduled orientations are at 8am, 10am, noon, 2pm, and 4pm daily.

name: The Needles Visitor Center
description: The Needles Visitor Center normally offers exhibits, book & map sales, backcountry permits, information, picnic area, and park rangers on duty. The park orientation movie (15 minutes) is not currently showing. Water is available year-round. When the visitor center is closed in winter, you must self-register for backcountry permits outside the visitor center entrance.
audioDescription: The Needles Visitor Center is located off Highway 211, a less-trafficked road that winds westward from busy Highway 191, south of Moab, Utah. A right turn into the parking lot reveals the visitor center building, which faces east, across from the parking lot. The area is surrounded by vast desert; in the distance, a U-shaped mesa is visible. This is Grand View Point Overlook, located in the Island in the Sky district, the northern portion of Canyonlands. The visitor center is a low, one-story building with pueblo style architecture. The walls of the visitor center itself are sandy-tan in color, with multicolored orange, maroon, and tan sandstone bricks stacked ¾ of the way up each wall. Sections of ramada roofing jut from the front of the visitor center, supported by wooden logs set in sandstone brick. These sections provide shade for the main entrance, as well as a foyer with a water filling station, payphone, and access to gendered and accessible bathrooms. Between the entryway and parking lot sits an expansive plaza, with a flagpole and several cement walkways separated by sections of landscaping with native desert plants and shrubs. To the left, a shaded porch area jutting out from the visitor center provides both places to sit and access WIFI. A low profile cement wall provides seating for approximately 15 people. On the wall that connects this area with the visitor center, three large informational bulletin boards provide information on the park and two free publications. The information on these boards is rotated seasonally, and the publications include a souvenir map of Canyonlands, as well as a newspaper guide with hiking recommendations and information on the park. The parking lot is east of the visitor center and features accessible parking. A sidewalk separates the parking lot and visitor center plaza. Along this sidewalk are bear safe trash and recycling bins, as well as three shaded picnic tables located on the dirt beyond the sidewalk. The picnic table closest to the visitor center has an extended table for additional seating. Continuing along the sidewalk, there is a short dirt path located at 3 o’clock. This is a nature walk with identifications of common plants in the area. The path curves to the left connecting back with the sidewalk closer to the VC entrance. While on this short path there is only one section that narrows. Various desert plants like Narrow Leaf Yucca and two needle pinyon are visible on either side. To the right, a plaque about Bates E. Wilson, an early advocate and superintendent of Arches and Canyonlands rests on the ground. The path rejoins the sidewalk along the ramp where the plaza meets the parking lot. Left of this point, an additional plaque is visible among a section of plants that reads acknowledging Stephen T. Mather as an early leader of the National Park Service. Inside, the visitor center has a desk for information and purchases from the bookstore. The bookstore is to your right. To the left is a museum area with exhibits about the geological and cultural history of the park. The visitor center auditorium holds showings of two different informational videos on the park. Towards the back of the visitor center, there is a 3-dimensional map of Canyonlands nestled between two glass walls that look out onto the plains and mesa tops outside. Bench seating surrounds the map. To the right of the map and seating area is another room; The Needles Backcountry office, where one can obtain permits and information abut the backcountry. The backcountry office features large L-shaped counters with maps and rules and regulations about the Needles.

name: The Wing Luke Museum of the Asian Pacific American Experience
description: The Wing Luke Museum of the Asian Pacific American Experience is located in a 1910 historic building, situated in Seattle’s Chinatown-International District. Tours are available of the surrounding neighborhood and several nearby preserved historic spaces.

name: Thomas Condon Visitor Center
description: Located in the Sheep Rock Unit, the Thomas Condon Visitor Center is a National Park Service research facility containing an outstanding paleontology lab dedicated to the John Day Fossil Beds. Picture windows let you view the working laboratory and collections room with over 60,000 specimens. In the fossil museum gallery, you can walk through nearly 50 million years of the Age of Mammals. Hundreds of fossil specimens are displayed, along with eight large murals depicting plants and animals of the time.

name: Thomas H. Kuchel Visitor Center
description: Southern-most visitor center in the park and located right on the beach. Exhibits about Yurok culture, art and history, redwood ecology, park information, junior ranger program, bookstore and retail sales. Park film available.
audioDescription: Located off HWY 101 in the southern part of the parks. It is 1/4 mile to the west (ocean-side) of the HWY and there are signs showing where the turn off it. There is a 1/4-mile drive to a large parking area in front of the brown and grey facility, plenty of RV and trailer parking available. Information kiosks are frosting of steps and up to the entry doors. ADA accessible ramps is to the right and left side of the building. These facilities are not visible from the road.

name: Thompson Island Information Center
description: Thompson Island Information Center is located off Route 3 on a small island between the mainland and Mount Desert Island. It is a small, seasonal facility usually staffed by a park ranger and local chamber of commerce representative. Park passes are available for purchase here.
audioDescription: A small brown building with a wooden deck and ramp providing access. Informational bulletin boards are located outside along the edge of the parking area.

name: Thousand Springs Visitor Center
description: The new Thousand Springs Visitor Center, operated jointly with Idaho Department of Parks and Recreation, is located about one mile north of Hagerman on Highway 30. Visitors will find maps and information for both Hagerman Fossil Beds National Monument and the six units of Thousand Springs State Park. This is the only place at the monument to see Pliocene fossils on display. The visitor center also offers restrooms, drinking water, passport stamps, junior ranger programs, ranger talks, and a small giftshop.
audioDescription: The Thousand Springs Visitor Center is a boxy, flat-roofed structure paneled with cedar planks, on a grassy, landscaped lawn. It sits in the midst of farmland, with scenic views of basalt cliffs to the east and the fossil beds along the river to the west. A paved sidewalk leads from the parking area to the glass front doors. On the front of the building are logos for the National Park Service and Idaho State Parks, with the words "Visitor Center", "Thousand Springs State Park", and "Hagerman Fossil Beds National Monument.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps are available at the Thousand Springs Visitor Center during regular operating hours.

name: Timpanogos Cave Visitor Center
description: The Timpanogos Cave Visitor Center is located in American Fork Canyon on UT-92. It sits at the base of the cave trail that leads to Timpanogos Cave. The visitor center is generally closed when the cave tours are closed. See https://www.nps.gov/tica for the most up-to-date information.
audioDescription: The Timpanogos Cave Visitor Center is located in American Fork Canyon on UT-92. It sits at the base of the cave trail that leads to Timpanogos Cave, and is closed during the winter season.
passportStampLocationDescription: The stamp can be located at the visitor center during the summer season and at the administration building during the winter.

directionsInfo: From I-15: take Exit 284 (Alpine-Highland exit), turn east on UT-92, drive 10 miles (16km) to the monument. From UT 40: from Heber or Provo Canyon travel on UT40 through Provo Canyon, turning west onto Orem 800 North (UT 52), then after 2.4 miles turn right onto State Street (Hwy 89). After 3.8 miles, turn onto Pleasant Grove 100 East (UT 146). Stay on this road for five miles, as it turns into Canyon Rd and takes you to the mouth of American Fork Canyon. When Canyon Rd ends, turn right into the canyon.

name: Timucuan Preserve Visitor Center at Fort Caroline
description: Located at Fort Caroline National Memorial, the Timucuan Preserve Visitor Center hosts the exhibit "Where the Waters Meet." This exhibit showcases the richness of the environment in northeast Florida and how humans have interacted with this environment for thousands of years. The Visitor Center hosts a bookstore and information desk, and activities are available to do while exploring the exhibits.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a simple mission 66 style architecture building atop a small hill with a central staircase leading to the glass doors. As you walk in you face a large under the river view mural to your right museum exhibits line both walls, to the left is a bookstore area and a large desk where rangers or volunteers sit.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are several cancellation stamps at this location including Fort Caroline National Memorial, Gullah-Geechee Heritage Corridor and Timucuan Preserve.

directionsInfo: Fort Caroline is located in Jacksonville, Florida, about 14 miles northeast of downtown. From I-95 north of Jacksonville: Traveling from the north via Interstate 95 exit at the I-295 East Beltway. I-295 crosses the St. Johns River. Exit at Monument Road, follow the brown signs to the left, and travel to Fort Caroline Road. Turn right, and follow Fort Caroline Road as it curves to the left. The entrance to the Fort Caroline is on your left.

name: Toms Cove Visitor Center
description: The Toms Cove Visitor Center is located in the Virginia District within the Chincoteague National Wildlife Refuge.
audioDescription: The Toms Cove Visitor Center is located at the east end and south side of Beach Road. The GPS location is 8586 Beach Road, Chincoteague, VA 23336. There is a winding brown ramp that leads you up a gradual slope to the visitor center that is sitting on 10 foot tall pilings. The Toms Cove Visitor Center is a square, one story gray building with white trim and windows. The main door entrance faces east towards Beach Road and may be automatically opened using the switch that is located to the right side of the door. Attached to the west side of the visitor center is a deck with a bench, chairs, and viewing scopes overlooking the water and marshes of Toms Cove. The side door entrance is located on the southwestern deck portion of the visitor center and does not have an automatic door option. Inside the visitor center is an information desk staffed with a park ranger or volunteer, hand-painted panels featuring local plants and animals, a touch table exhibit, an aquarium and a touch tank. Various bulletin boards with current news and events, and informational brochures are also available. There is also a bookstore located in the visitor center that features items for sale that relate to Assateague Island.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Passport stamp is located inside the Toms Cove Visitor Center at the entrance to the America's National Parks book store, near the front information desk.

name: Travertine Nature Center
description: A good starting place for visitors. It has brochures, exhibits, maps and helpful Rangers. Get information about lakes, camping, hiking trails, and special events.
audioDescription: The Travertine Nature Center is in the northeast section of the recreation area, and is the eastern most point of the loop road, Perimeter Drive. It is also the trailhead for the Antelope Springs and Buffalo Springs area, which has a number of small loop trails spurring off of a stem trail. It is located very near Little Niagara Falls. It has restroom facilities on the exterior of the building that are open the same hours as the Nature Center. It contains a number of exhibits about the history and nature of the area, as well as a small store with books and some souvenir items.

name: Tri-Cities Visitor Center
description: Visit Tri-Cities is the tourism information center for the local area. This is a great place to stop by for helpful trip-planning advice for visiting the park and numerous other attractions in the Tri-Cities. The helpful staff can provide you with itineraries for visits to the Tri-Cities region and suggest entertainment, lodging, and dining options. You may also purchase souvenir items and stamp your national parks passport here. Visit Tri-Cities may be reached at 509-735-8486.

name: Tule Lake Visitor Center
description: Tule Lake National Monument visitor center is open for the summer. The Visitor Center hours are Thursday through Monday from 9:00am - 4:30pm. The visitor center is located 8 miles south of Tulelake CA along Hwy 139 at 44340 Hwy 139. Tulelake, CA 96134. We are the only driveway off the hwy between County Rd 113 & 176.
passportStampLocationDescription: Two passport stamps are available. One is the traditional passport stamp with just the date and Tule Lake National Monument. The second stamp has the image of a guard tower top, with the date in the center of that and name above and below the image. Both stamps are available when the visitor center is open. During the winter the traditional stamp is available at the Lava Beds visitor center, or you can request to have them mailed to you.

name: Tumacácori Visitor Center and Museum
description: The historic 1937 visitor center building is the main entry point for those visiting the Tumacácori mission grounds. It is also an interpretive exhibit in and of itself. Its design uses architectural details from other Sonoran missions contemporary to Tumacácori.

name: Tuolumne Meadows Visitor Center
description: The Tuolumne Meadows Visitor Center has an information desk, Yosemite Conservancy Bookstore, and an exhibit area detailing the area's geology, plant and animal life, and history. A designated accessible parking space and entrance are available. From the main parking lot, drive up the service road to the visitor center. Park in the designated accessible parking space, and follow the paved path in front of the visitor center to the rear entrance. Accessible restrooms are adjacent to the main parking lot.
audioDescription: The Tuolumne Meadows Visitor Center is located on a small hill overlooking its parking lot. A narrow service road leads up to the Visitor Center building, however, a posted sign reads, road closed! Service vehicles and vehicles with accessibility placards only. The building is a brown building with wood paneling and has a shingled roof and stone chimney. It has a stone foundation and long stone steps that extend across the length of the front porch, giving access to the wooden, double-door entrance. In front of the building is a wood sign that reads, Civilian Conservation Corps. The CCC began work in Yosemite in May 1933. During the ensuing years, significant projects included the Half Dome cable system, Badger Pass Ski Complex, Henness Ridge lookout tower, numerous park structures and many miles of hiking and riding trails. World War II ended CCC work in July 1942. More than 6,000 young men of the peacetime army passed through the park's 10 CCC camps. They did much to help make the park accessible and enjoyable. Their contributions will be forever remembered. Dedicated on CCC Recognition Day, October 22, 1988. The United States Civilian Conservation Corps logo and National Park Service logo are in the upper left and right corner of the sign. To the right side of the building is one designated accessible parking spot, and in front of the building, across a service road that leads to residential housing, is a brown trash bin, a green recycle bin, and a flag pole waving the American flag. Down in the parking area, on the east side, is a long brown building with a covered porch and wood railings, which houses the men's and women's restroom. Along the paved pathway that leads from the restrooms, up the hill, to the visitor center are some trash and recycle bins, and four exhibit panels. Three of the panels are joined together. Of the three panels, the left panel is titled, Exploring Yosemite, and has an illustration of two people hiking on a trail below steep mountains. Caption: Yosemite is famous for its sheer cliffs, towering waterfalls, and huge trees. Surrounded by this grandeur, take time to shift your focus from large to small. Discover a more intimate wilderness - a Giant Sequoia seedling, tiny meadow wildflowers, or the changing light on a cliff face. North Country - The Tioga Road (usually open from late May until early November) traverses a setting of high country lakes, meadows, and mountain peaks. At 8600 feet in elevation, Tuolumne Meadows is a wilderness threshold. The Visitor Center, open and staffed during summer, houses exhibits and offers park information and publications. South Country - Walk among ancient Giant Sequoias in the Mariposa Grove. (The Tuolumne and Merced Groves are located near Crane Flat northwest of Yosemite Valley.) Experience part of Yosemite's past among the historic buildings of the Pioneer Yosemite History Center at Wawona. Glacier Point (accessible by car in summer and early fall) offers spectacular views of Yosemite Valley, Half Dome, and Vernal and Nevada Falls as well as a panorama of the High Sierra. In winter, Summit Meadow and Badger Pass are popular sites for cross-country and downhill skiing. Yosemite Valley - The waterfalls and monoliths of Yosemite Valley have inspired poets, painters, photographers, and millions of visitors for more than 100 years. The Valley Visitor Center offeres current park information, an orientation slide program, exhibits, book and map sales, and wilderness permits. A model Indian village and the Indian Cultural Museum adjoin the Visitor Center. Yosemite Valley is open year-round. Map: A small map outline of the entire park shows the main roads and areas. On the far left side of the park is a road that runs north to south. At the top point is Hetch Hetchy, coming down to Big Oak Flat, which has a campground and information station, then down to Crane Flat, which has a campground and a gas station with limited groceries. The road continues through a portion of Yosemite Valley, then onward past an intersection for Glacier Point Road, to Wawona and the Mariposa Grove of Giant Sequioas, which are at the bottom tip of the park. Gas, dining, groceries, and accomodations are available in the Wawona area. Just above Yosemite Valley is a road that extends from the left to the right of the park, which is the Tioga Road. Several campgrounds, White Wolf, Tenaya Lake, Tuolumne Meadows, and Tioga Pass are all labeled along Tioga Road. For information regarding park maps, call our park accessibility coordinator at (209) 379-1035. The middle panel is enclosed in glass and has a black and white photo of an elder man with wire rimmed glasses, wearing the National Park Service winter uniform. He has a collared shirt with a tie, and a dress jacket with chest pockets that are buttoned. A badge is above his left pocket and his name tag is above his right pocket. He is wearing a felt NPS hat with a leather band.

name: Tuskegee Airmen NHS Visitor Center
description: The Hangar #1 Museum houses the Visitor Center and is open Monday-Saturday. Step inside the Orientation Room and be taken back to the 1940s through a re-creation of some of the sights and sounds of Moton Field. A 4-minute video that introduces the visitor to the Tuskegee Airmen. Here visitors can pick up a copy of the Park brochure and other printed materials including a JR. Ranger booklet.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center has multiple exhibits lining the walls. At one end of the room is a set of photos documenting the chain of command from the 1940s. Directly below is a ranger station housing the printed materials.

name: Tuskegee Institute National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: The visitor center for is located inside the George Washington Carver Museum. The Visitor Center is open Monday-Friday from 9am CST to 4:30pm CST. There is no physical address for the museum because it sits inside the campus gates of Tuskegee University. Inside of the Visitor Center is the location of the restrooms,stamps, brochures, rack cards, and training cards the site offers visitors . The visitor center is also the pickup location for the site’s Junior Ranger Program.
audioDescription: From The Oaks Parking lot walking Turn 180 and face the building across from The Oaks, Carnegie Hall. Use the crosswalk between Carnegie Hall and the building to its right, the Old Administration building, to enter onto the campus. Walk towards the right of the statue between Carnegie Hall and The Old Administration building. Follow the path and veer right to go down the slight hill. Please do not use any of the stairs that are painted as those are owned by various fraternities and sororities . Cross the street facing Tompkins Hall and walk towards your left. Continue walking straight until you reach the Carver Museum. Take the stairs down and walk towards your left to reach the door. Once inside you will be greeted by a ranger or volunteer. From The Oaks Parking lot Driving If you are parked inside the Oaks parking lot drive out towards your left. At the 1st streetlight turn right into the main gate of the university. Let the guard at the gate know you are visiting the Carver Museum. Continue straight passing the statue of Booker T. Washington on your left and The Kellogg’s center and Hotel on your right. Immediately after passing the Kellogg’s Center and Hotel turn right to enter into the Kellogg’s parking lot. Drive to the second level and park. Take the breezeway ramp out. Walk straight, pass by the stairs and door to your left. Turn left and walk passing the flag pole take the next left to enter into the door for the Carver Museum. Once inside a ranger or a volunteer will greet you.

name: Tyler Bend Visitor Center
description: The Tyler Bend Visitor Center is located about 2 1/2 miles off of Highway 65 between St. Joe and Marshall, Arkansas. Here visitors can get park orientation information, see the park film, and shop at the park bookstore.
audioDescription: The approach to the visitor center circles around a large grassy area to drive directly in front of the building. The building has a rock base with redwood horizontal siding above. There are wooden posts at the junction of the sidewalk and drive, spaced for easy access for wheelchairs. the sidewalk is concrete aggregate. A native wildflower garden lines the right side of the walk and a native shrub garden is at the left front of the building. A wooden portico shelters the double glass doors and sidelights of the entrance. An automatic door opener button is on the wooden post at mid-level where the wood meets the rock base. This opener opens both the outer doors into the foyer and the doors into the exhibit/desk area at the same time. The foyer has a tile floor. The restrooms are down a hallway to the right with the women's room the 1st door on the right and the men's room the second door on the right. A second set of double glass doors and sidelights is the entrance to the visitor center exhibit/desk area. A second opener button is at the middle of the rock wall at left. The visitor center is carpeted. A touch table is about 20 feet straight ahead with a fireplace behind it and large picture windows and exit doors behind the fireplace. The desk and sales area are to the right and the exhibit area is to the left.

name: Ulysses S. Grant National Historic Site Visitor Center
description: This is the first stop for your visit. You can watch an introductory film, get information on historic house tours, explore the museum in the historic stable, and shop in the bookstore.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 346 words. A two-story visitor center painted a two-toned color scheme of red and white measuring 250 feet square. Its orange metal roof is topped with a large solar panel and a window filed cupola. Several small windows wrap around the first floor of the building, while several larger windows wrap around the second floor. An up-sloped access ramp from the parking lot leads via a large concrete patio toward the building entrance. Directly in front of the visitor center door is a covered patio, which includes two benches to the right and left. An automatic door button is mounted to a post on the left side of the covered patio, roughly five feet from the door. In the interior of the building, a small vestibule with a red tile floor leads to a large lobby space with blue carpeted floors, and beige painted walls. Paintings of Ulysses and Julia Grant hang on the wall to the right, and a quote by President Grant hangs on the wall to the left. Immediately inside the lobby entrance on the right are entrances to the men's and women's public restrooms. The women’s restroom is on the left, and the men’s restroom is on the right. 15 feet from the lobby entrance is a wooden information desk and gift shop cash register. Immediately to the left of the information desk is a gift shop. 15 feet to the left of the information desk is a vestibule and exit leading to the historic stable and museum. 15 feet to the right of the information desk are a set of two stairs with a handrail leading into the visitor center theater. There is a second set of doors to access the theater via a ramp. This is located on the right near the end of a 30-foot-long hallway to the left of the stairs. A vestibule and exit located at the end of this hallway lead to a historic walking trace and President Grant’s home White Haven. The visitor center offers an audio described film and braille brochures. End of description.

name: Verkamp's Visitor Center (South Rim)
description: In the Village Historic District, near Hopi House and El Tovar Hotel, Verkamp's Visitor Center features exhibits that focus on the Grand Canyon Community; what it was like to live and work here on the brink of one of the seven natural wonders. A staffed information desk and a Grand Canyon Conservancy Museum Store are also located here. A water bottle filling station is just outside of the building near the canyon rim, and public restrooms are available in a separate building behind the Visitor Center.
audioDescription:
The easternmost building in the Village, a central eight-foot (2.4 m) wide concrete ramp with metal railings on either side leads up to an eight-foot (2.4 m) deep by 40-foot (12 m) wide covered porch area of the two-story, grey-shingled Verkamp's Visitor Center. Four evenly spaced eight-foot (2.4 m) wide arched openings extend to the left and right of the ramp, two on each side. An open deck area on the second floor spans the width of the building, with a central covered portico in front of a second-floor door. Inside, the facility features a Grand Canyon Conservancy Park Store. Several park ranger-conducted activities begin here, along with exhibits about the history of both the canyon and the Village. On the west side of the building sits a central information desk and check-out counter staffed by Grand Canyon Conservancy employees. A couple benches are placed just to the west of the center of the room, and there is a 12-foot (3.6 m) tall by six-foot (2 m) wide limestone brick fireplace at the back of the building. Also at this location, a set of restrooms is available in a separate building outside and behind the visitor center. Facing the store at the base of the entrance ramp, turn right and move about 20 feet (6 m) to the sidewalk bordering the parking lot, and turn left. Continue 40 feet (12 m) forward to the end of the asphalt path where it meets the paved road. Being mindful of car traffic, turn left 45-degrees and move another 40 feet (12 m) forward to the restroom outbuilding. The entrance is at the far left of the building with a concrete ramp and metal railings. About six feet to the right of the concrete entrance ramp to Verkamp's Visitor Center stands a three-foot (1 m) tall rectangular limestone-block pedestal with a roughly 10-inch (25 cm) square metal plaque embedded in the top. Note a two-foot (60 cm) tall pillar of petrified wood at the base of the ramp at the right in front of the plaque.
Text on the plaque reads: "Verkamp's Store has been placed on the National Register of Historic Places by the United States Department of the Interior, 1906."

directionsInfo: Verkamp's Visitor Center is a short walk just east of El Tovar Hotel and Hopi House. Parking in the nearby lot may be limited during busy periods, which include spring break, summer and fall months. If you are walking from the shuttle bus stop across from the Railroad Depot, climb the stairway to the top of the hill. Here you will find El Tovar Hotel, Hopi House, and Verkamp's Visitor Center. They are located on the east end of the Village Historic District.

directionsInfo: Fort Scott National Historic Site is located in downtown Fort Scott, Kansas. U.S. Highways 69 and 54 intersect here. Fort Scott is about 90 miles south of Kansas City and 60 miles northwest of Joplin, Missouri. Signs directing visitors to Fort Scott are posted on highway 69 for visitors coming from the north and the south and on highway 54 for visitors coming from the east and the west. The entrance to the site is one block west of the intersection of Highway 69 and Highway 54 east.

name: Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is open mid-May through mid-October. Enjoy a 15-minute film on the Battle of Lake Erie and Perry's Victory. Exhibits trace the events of the War of 1812, the armament of the time and more. A 2-story window offers a view of the 352-foot marble memorial. An interactive exhibit explores the memorial's construction and the peace that has endured since the War of 1812 between the United States, Great Britain, and Canada. Purchase tickets to the memorial observation deck.
audioDescription: Half-moon drive and sidewalk in front of a Tan building with white trim and green roof. Building sets 20 feet off of the drive. Building is 65 feet wide and the center section raise to two stories in height with three small square windows across the top five feet below the peak. Across the front of the building is 20-foot-deep porch supported by eight white 8-foot-tall columns. Two doors are located in the center section of the building. Here the porch roof curves in an upward arch. Allowing for transom windows and sidelights around the double doors. Trim for the doors and windows is dark green. To the right of the doors is a National Park Service Arrowhead. On the left side of the door is a vertical TV screen that rotates between hours of operations, special event announcements, and safety messages for those visiting the park. 12 six-foot backless gray benches line the edge of the walkway to the building and the porches. Upon entering the Visitor Center visitors will notice straight ahead the larger than life size marble statue carved by William Walcutt on top of a four and half tall black granite base. On the left is one twelve by eight-foot painting of the Battle of Lake Erie. To the right of that painting is a two foot by three-foot painting of Oliver Hazard Perry leaving the US Brig Lawrence during the Battle of Lake Erie. Above the front door is another twelve by eight painting of the final part of the battle of Lake Erie when the Niagara breaks the line. To the right as you enter is a tv that plays a few Great Lake Restoration Initiative videos on a loop and an invasive species exhibit. To the left of that screen is the information desk and beyond that is a bookstore and gift shop. The back right half of the building has exhibits about the Battle of Lake Erie, War of 1812, and the peace that came out of the war. The left half of the building contains an auditorium that plays a 15-minute movie about the Battle of Lake Erie and the women and men's restrooms with two drink fountains between. The back wall of the center section of the visitor center is large floor to ceiling windows with a view of large 352-foot stone memorial. Along the window is exhibit on the building of the memorial that runs the width of the building and windows. To the left and right are doors that exit onto two covered back porches of the visitor center. Sidewalk leads from porch to the memorial.

name: Visitor Center
description: Located just on the west end of the main parking lot, the visitor center can provide you with program information, park pamphlets, area information, and an overall introduction to Grant-Kohrs Ranch National Historic Site. There is also a bookstore located inside.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is located at the northwest end of the parking area. It is on a grassy bench with fenced pastures to the north and south. The Flint mountain range rises across the valley to the west. The Visitor Center building is a small, one story aged dark brown wooden building with a covered porch. The restrooms are in a separate single level building with brown siding and a rock façade up to about waist height. The restrooms are in a separate building, closest to the parking lot, north of the sidewalk. The building faces south, with two doors on the south wall. The doors are on the right and left sides of the wall, and there is a drinking fountain in the middle. The men’s restroom is on the left. Inside the men’s room, to the right of the door is a single sink and a urinal to the left of that. There is an accessible stall a stall straight back from the door. The ladies’ restroom is through the door on the right. Inside the ladies’ room, there is a single sink on the left closest to the door. There is one standard stall next on the left and an accessible stall straight back from the door. Visitor Center is 55 feet west of the restroom building, farther away from the parking lot. From the restrooms, the sidewalk travels about 10 feet south, then curves to the right and down a slight slope. About 45 feet down the slight slope, there is a Y in the sidewalk. Taking the sidewalk slightly to the right, it is about 37 feet to the porch of the Visitor Center. One short step up, then about 3 feet to the door, which is located adjacent to the back wall of the building. There is no doorknob, push to enter. If you continue slightly left at the Y, it is about 30 feet to the porch. Turn right 90 degrees and there is a slight ramp onto the porch. Continue straight across the porch for 28 feet and the door is 90 degrees to the left. Straight inside the door about 6 feet is a bar height visitor information desk. To the left is a display rack of bookstore sales items. This rack is perpendicular to the door wall and extends 4 feet 6 inches into the room. There are sales items displayed on the end, which is about 24 inches wide, and on the opposite side from the entrance. Another display rack of sales items is located on the on the wall to the left as you enter the door. Turn 90 degrees to the left at the end of the first display rack and it is about 6 feet to the wall mounted rack. The wall mounted display rack is 8 feet long, extends to the left back to the door wall, and right a few feet. There is a chair and a bench along the wall to the right of the wall mounted display rack, extending about 6 feet. There is a slight ramp transition up, about 3 feet past the visitor center. To the right is a counter with the passport cancelation station. There is a second door to the Visitor Center about 12 feet past the visitor information desk, on the left wall, perpendicular to the first door. If you exit this door, you cross about 3 feet of porch to 2 stairs down to the sidewalk. Here you can turn left to return to the parking lot or right to walk the trail to the main historic area. Another option is an accessible ramp that is a 90 degree right just outside the door. It follows the building for about 12 feet, then makes a 90-degreeF left for about 6 feet onto the sidewalk.

name: Visitor Center
description: The visitor center offers a museum, a movie about the battle, and a bookstore. From March 1st through October 31st, the Stones River National Battlefield visitor center is open from 9 AM to 5 PM daily. From November 1st through February 28th visitor center hours are 9 AM to 4 PM daily. The visitor center is closed on Thanksgiving and December 25th.
audioDescription: The entrance to the parking lot includes a circle drive with parking and two accessible spaces close to the Visitor Center. Approaching the building there is a bench, wayside exhibits, and bins for trash and recycling. The Visitor Center is a gray stone one-story building with a green metal roof and flagpole out front. There are two sets of double doors. The left set of doors lead to the restroom lobby. Upon entering the lobby, to the viewer’s left there is a women’s restroom, a drinking fountain, a family accessible restroom, and men’s restroom. There is braille on each of these signs. There is a wood bench on the viewer’s right, against the wall. Straight ahead, there is an exit. Outside, there is a second set of doors to the viewer’s right. These doors are the main entrance to the Visitor Center, and they are automatic. To the right of this is a wooden Stones River National Battlefield sign with the National Park Service arrowhead logo. The Visitor Center lobby is through two sets of automatic doors. Upon entering a large octagonal lobby, on the viewer’s left is an information desk. To the right is the gift shop. Straight ahead is the first gallery of the museum. Past the information desk to the far left is an emergency exit and temporary exhibit. The first gallery covers the time period before the Battle of Stones River. Walls are lined with exhibit text and graphics. To the viewer’s right is a three-dimensional exhibit with a Confederate soldier sitting outside of a tent, writing in a diary. He is wearing a butternut colored jacket, and blue pants with a tan colored hat. This exhibit has an audio component via a button to the right of the exhibit. To the left of the camp exhibit, is another describing Union and Confederate soldiers. On display are Union and Confederate uniforms and items. In the case to the viewer’s right is a navy blue Union coat with personal items a soldier once carried. To the viewer’s left is a gray Confederate coat with items carried by the common soldier. To the left of this is an exhibit describing military music with instruments on display. This exhibit plays Civil War music with the touch of a button. To the far left is an exhibit on new technology with a touchable telegraph and musket on display. Exiting gallery one, to viewers right a hallway leads to gallery two. Walls are lined with exhibit text and artifacts including munitions and personal items. This gallery covers the three-day Battle of Stones River. Gallery two is a circular room. To viewers right, there is a three-dimensional exhibit of two Union soldiers with a disabled cannon which was used during the battle. A few steps into the gallery there is a diorama on the left wall audio describing an event called Hell’s Half Acre. Visitors can operate this diorama via a button located below the diorama. When entering gallery three, to the viewer’s left there is an exhibit case with medical instruments. Gallery three covers the battle’s aftermath and Reconstruction. There is exhibit text on the left wall describing the wounded and the dead. To the right of this text are two exhibit cases with original soldier’s coats on display. These coats are from men who were killed at the battle. To the viewer’s right in the corner there are blown up newspaper articles mounted to the wall. To the left of the newspapers is an interactive display on Fortress Rosecrans. This display is a map on a slanted table and has an audio component describing some of its history. The buttons to operate the audio are located close to the edge of the table. Past the Fortress Rosecrans exhibit, to the viewers left on the far wall is a large exhibit case with a cannon inside also used during the Battle of Stones River. A medal of honor is displayed above the cannon. To the viewers left of the cannon is the Hazen Brigade monument exhibit with artifacts on display. The remaining walls in this gallery are lined with graphics and text describing this period. Exiting gallery three, you will find the gift shop. Shelves with items related to the park service and the battle line the walls. In this gift shop there are books related to the battle and the Civil War, souvenirs and clothing. There are additional items for purchase on display in the center of the room. There is an emergency exit in the back of the room. Exiting the gift shop into the lobby and past the information desk is a long hallway to the far left, which leads into the restroom lobby and building exit.

name: Visitor Center
description: This building has evolved over time. Beginning in 1846, it was the enlisted men's barracks and dining hall. In 1872, it was converted to a courthouse and jail. A second, more modern, jail was built in 1888. The last major change occurred between 1996-2000 when the buildings were renovated and exhibits added making the building more accessible to visitors. The visitor center helps tell the story of Fort Smith from 1817 to 1896.
audioDescription: Visitor Center – 330 words Three descriptions the building, entrance, and inside. Description 1 of 3. The visitor center is a red brick structure approximately 150 feet from end to end. It served as barracks, courthouse, and jail. It is actually two structures. At the north end is the former barracks and courthouse - a 2 1/2 story structure with covered wooden porches on the east and west sides of the building. Ten stone stairs lead up to the white porches. The south end of the visitor center is the former jail. On the east and west side of the darker red brick structure are 6 narrow windows with bars going the full length of the 20 ft tall windows. Rough-hewn white stones frame each window. The roof of the visitor center in covered in dark gray slate tiles. Description 2 of 3. Cement walkways from other areas of the park lead to an open entrance plaza at the south end of the building; 3 ft. high walls outlining the plaza outlining correspond to the outline of the fort walls. The larger flat stones indicate the locations of bastions or gun placements. The red brick portico is just before the double glass entrance doors. There is a park bench on the left side of the portico and there an automatic open button for the entrance doors on the right opposite the park bench. Description 3 of 3. A 20-foot-long vestibule has a men’s and unisex restrooms on the right and the women’s restroom and water fountains are right. The automatic open button for the lobby doors is on the right immediately past the women’s rest room entrance. Once in the lobby maps are on the left, a bookstore is on the right, and the information desk straight ahead. The park videos are open captioned, and audio described. The park brochure is audio described and available in braille. For more information see the staff at the information desk. End of description.

In the downtown area: On Rogers or Garrison Ave turn south at 4th St. Turn right onto Garland Ave. At the end of the next block is the entrance to the main parking lot. Parking is also available on Third Street.

name: Visitor Center
description: Housed in the Park's 1908 historic brick cannery warehouse, visitor center exhibits tell the stories of voyage, discovery and cultural diversity. A First Order Fresnel lighthouse lens, a magnificent brass structure encasing hundreds of precisely polished prisms, guides visitors through the door. Visit “The Waterfront” exhibit and take an interactive walk through six historical waterfront neighborhoods. Once inside, can get a heading from Park Rangers and volunteers staffing the information desk.

name: Visitor Center
description: Regular Hours (March through November): Open daily 8:30 - 4:30 central time. Admission is free and includes cultural demonstrations, exhibits, a film, and park store. The 3/4-mile paved trail is free to walk at all times. Winter Hours (December through February): Open Tuesday - Saturday 8:30 - 4:30 central time. No cultural demonstrations, but free snowshoe check-out is available in the visitor center to enjoy the trail from January until the snow melts (supplies are limited).
audioDescription: A one-story, Mission 66 building with a portico on the front at the east end of the teardrop-shaped parking lot. The structure is mostly red brick with the walls immediately surrounding the entrance doors and the portico pillars made of red Sioux Quartzite. Flag stones made of Sioux Quartzite also line the ground underneath the portico. Between the building and the sidewalk that borders it is tallgrass prairie and a couple of bur oak trees. Common milkweed is abundant. The north and south sides of the building have doors which open to a paved 3/4-mile Circle Trail which loops through the site and brings visitors back to the Visitor Center regardless of which side they begin from. The inside of the Visitor Center consists of two main exhibit and interpretive areas connected by a hallway. Entering the building via the front doors, there is a desk to your front-left. Here, park rangers distribute brochures and answer questions. It is also where you can get your passport stamp. Immediately to your right is a theater which plays a 22-minute film. Next to the theater is an exhibit area which explains the cultural and spiritual relevance of the site. As you move through the hallway, immediately to your right is a braille map of the building. Exhibits about petroglyphs, winter counts, and the prairie line the left side of the hall. Halfway down the hall there are doors on both sides leading to the Circle Trail. As you pass the doors, you will enter the second interpretive portion of the building. As you leave the hallway at the other end of the building, immediately to your right is the gift shop. To your front-right along the far wall next to the gift shop is a small gallery of pipestone art in a circular room. To the left of this gallery is a bookcase with items for sale, and to the left of that the culture demonstration area stretches along most of the far wall in front of you. This consists of three large, circular booths (each approximately 9 feet wide) with a circular railing around each one separating the pipestone carvers from the public. They are present April through October, but not all booths may be filled depending on staffing and the time of year. Between the center booth and the hallway, there is a large display case holding an eagle feather headdress and a stuffed eagle. The far left side of this section of the building houses the petroglyphs. The wall to your immediate left which connects the petroglyphs with the hallway is lined with historical panels.

directionsInfo: From I-90, take either US Hwy 75 or MN Hwy 23 north for ~30 miles to the town of Pipestone. The entrance road to the park is located off of Hiawatha Ave., which cuts through downtown. From I-29, take the exit for SD Hwy 34. This turns into MN Hwy 30 and brings you directly to Pipestone. Take a left of Hiawatha Ave., which brings you to the entrance road of the park.

name: Visitor Center
description: Start your visit at the Visitor Center, where park rangers are available to answer questions and help you get oriented. Allow yourself about 30 minutes in the Visitor Center, which is open from 9:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. daily.
audioDescription: Visitor Center. 1 ¾ minutes. The Visitor Center for the Herbert Hoover National Historic Site is located at the northeast corner of the historic site, near the intersection of Parkside Drive and Main Street. There is a parking area on the south side of the visitor center, and the building’s entrance faces the parking lot. From the parking lot, the building presents a façade of glass and multi-hued red bricks. It’s one story high and the design is modern and angular. There is a pitched roof, but the angle of the roof is greater on the left side than the right, so the two halves do not meet at a point; instead the peak of the left-hand portion sticks up about six feet higher in the center. The left-hand side is brick and windowless. In grey raised metal the words “Herbert Hoover National Historic Site” and the National Park Service arrowhead logo are affixed to the brick. The entrance is on the right-hand side—through double glass doors set into a larger tinted-glass vestibule. A ramp provides access to the doors from the left side of the parking lot, rising up along the front of the building. The front doors have an automatic open button on their left. Inside, you’ll find an introductory film, exhibits, a gift shop, and additional information about the park. A ranger is stationed at the main desk opposite the entrance. End of message.

name: Visitor Center
description: Begin your park visit at the visitor center. Here, you will find information on the park and the Battle of Guilford Courthouse through two interpretive movies and a museum. Rangers or volunteers at the information desk are glad to help you with answers and assistance. The Visitors Center is open 9:00AM - 5:00PM, Wednesday through Sunday except on Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Day, and New Years Day.
audioDescription: The Battlefield Visitor Center parking lot is a loop with an entrance on the left-hand side (closest to the visitor center) and exit on the right-hand side (near the gated entrance of the tour road). This parking lot is divided through the center by an uneven median covered with grass and stone pavers. The curb that surrounds the median requires visitors to step up onto the grass and pathway, but there is a graded, paved path with a ramp entrance at the front end of the median located closest to the Visitor Center. When you turn into the parking lot, two handicap parking spots are immediately located on the left. There is a small tree next to the first handicap parking spot. Both options have additional room for loading and unloading on the passenger side of the vehicle. The first row of car parking offers a paved path that visitors must step up onto from a curb, but there is a graded ramp entrance at the rear of the first handicap parking spot closest to the visitor center. Please note that the ramp has a narrow entrance and may be slightly difficult to use due to the slight elevation of the ramp’s edges. This ramp will connect to the paved path leading to the Visitor Center. To access the Visitor Center, continue to the left along the paved path located next to the handicap parking, then walk straight ahead. Please note that seasonally, acorns and leaves fall on the path which could pose a small slip risk. Wheelchair accessibility is only available in the front of the building. You will pass by a low-lying split rail fence on your right and then pass between two mature trees. Next, a stone water fountain and bench will be on your right. Curve to the right towards the front door and be aware there is a low-level brick garden wall. The two-story modern style brick building is a light tan with a dark brown high sloping metal roof. The front door is under a flat awning that juts out from the front wall of the building. The entrance has two doors that swing outward towards guests. An automatic button to open the door for accessibility is available on the wall to the left of the door. A bulletin board of two panels describing features of the park is to the left of the button against the wall. Once you enter the front door, the information desk is on the right side of the lobby. The bathrooms are to the far left of the front door down a hallway that runs against the left wall of the building. A replica of a British three-pounder cannon is located in center of the lobby. The museum exhibit entrance is to the left of the cannon in the center of the lobby, and it features an enlarged image of re-enactors wearing Continental drum and fife corps uniforms. The museum has a winding corridor with exhibit panels that are predominantly blue. The exhibit cases describe the Southern Theater of the American Revolution and hold artifacts such as muskets, powder horns, swords, pistols, cannonballs, musketballs, grapeshot, camping artifacts, and colonial era artifacts. A second cannon and a long facade of the Guilford Courthouse are in the rear of the exhibit along with large windows that look out into the woods of the park. The museum corridor is a one-way hallway that loops back to the lobby. Guests will exit behind the cannon in the main lobby area. Immediately next to the museum’s exit door, there is a small hallway that contains the entrance to the visitor center’s main theater and a painting gallery filled with Don Troiani’s Revolutionary War watercolor works. A water fountain with upper and lower water spouts is near the back of the building on the left wall, and another exit door is straight across from the front door at the rear of the Visitor Center. A gift shop and second, smaller theater room are located on the right side of the visitor center behind the front desk. The gift shop is a narrow space lined with tall bookshelves. There is a door exiting the gift shop.
passportStampLocationDescription: Standard 1.25" circular cancellation stamp. Purple ink for the southeast region. Date is centered with text along the diameter of the stamp reading "Guilford Courthouse NMP Virtual Visit 2020". Ask a Ranger at the Visitor Center front desk for assistance. If you cannot physically obtain a stamp at the Visitor Center, you can download the "Virtual Visit 2020" passport stamp.

To reach the Visitor Center, drive East on New Garden Road and turn right into the parking lot when you see the stone sign “Guilford Courthouse National Military Park.” If you drive down Old Battleground Road, do not drive through the Forest Lawn cemetery, this is a dead end and is not connected to the National Park. name: Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center at Kenilworth Park and Aquatic Gardens is an ideal place to begin your visit. Restrooms are located here as well as orientation brochures. A small room of exhibit panels provides a brief overview of the history of the gardens and its key plants. Those with children should ask about the Junior Ranger program. The gift shop offers a variety of items for the nature enthusiast. Stamps for all sites in National Captial Parks East can be found at this Visitor Center.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Kenilworth Visitors Center hosts all of the stamps for National Capital Parks-East. The Visitor Center is open daily from 9am to 3pm. The stamps are located just inside the door to your left when you visit.

name: Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center offers an introduction on the people who built the dwellings 700 years ago. Artifacts and replicas of pottery and textiles are on display in the museum while the park store, operated by Western National Parks Association, sells educational items. The 20-minute park movie, located on the upstairs viewing platform, shows on demand throughout the day. Ask park staff for accessible movie options.

name: Visitor Center
description: Welcome to Fort Matanzas National Monument. Our site is located at 8635 A1A South, St. Augustine, FL 32080. Upon arrival at the park, you will circle the picnic area and see our visitor center. The parking spaces will lead you to the public restrooms and a sidewalk that directs you to our visitor center. There is limited parking and the parking lot often fills up fast. Ferry Boarding Passes are available at this location. Behind the Visitor Center is the dock where the ferry departs.
audioDescription: From the drop off point, The Fort Matanzas Visitor Center entrance is directly ahead, about 50 feet away. There is a welcome interpretive panel and a bulletin board immediately to your left, to the left of the sidewalk. The visitor center is a two story building with a shingled peaked roof. The first story is built of tan stone blocks. The second level has gray, planked wood siding. Cutting through the first level is an arched breezeway. The breezeway, is described from left to right. There are staff only areas at 9 o’clock. On the wall, at 10 o’clock, are two interpretive panels. A panel titled: Matanzas 1565. The text explains the story of the French and Spanish conflict here, and the fate of the French after their defeat. A map of the Florida Coast shows illustrations of Spanish soldiers marching north through a swamp toward Fort Caroline, and a large French sailing ship sinking into the ocean off of St. Augustine, after fleeing from Fort Caroline. A panel titled: Way of the Treasure Fleets. The text and an illustrated map of the Atlantic Ocean show the routes that the King of Spain’s merchant fleets took over the ocean. They sailed from Europe to South and Central America, and then back again, aided by the Gulf Stream, off the Florida coast. At 12 o’clock is the exit to the back of the building and the ferry. At 1’oclock is an interpretive panel titled, Historic Matanzas. It shows a timeline from 1565 to present, with six illustrated events and a map of the Florida Coast. Topics include the strategic importance of this location, coastal defense, pirates, how the fort changed hands between various nations over the years, and the history of the fort’s preservation. To the right of this panel, at a 4 foot height, is a button that opens the door to the visitor center, located to the right, at 3 o’clock. Open the door to the visitor center/bookstore, and the theater is straight ahead. The theater has three wooden benches on each side, with a 3 foot wide aisle down the middle. The visitor center door opens outward, toward you. Once inside, the information desk is ahead and slightly to the left. A monitor behind the desk displays historic pictures of the fort, ferry tour times, and special event information. Staff can assist you with information. Gift shop merchandise is in tall bookcases along the wall to your left. There are two models of the fort in Plexiglas cases: a during-construction model directly to the right of the front door, and a completed fort model on the left-hand side of the desk.

directionsInfo: Fort Matanzas National Monument is located about 14 miles south of the historic district of St. Augustine, Florida. St. Augustine is located on Florida's Northeastern Atlantic coast about midway between Jacksonville and Daytona Beach. From I-95: Take exit 305 (Route 206). Follow Route 206 east about 6 miles to Highway A1A. Turn right and follow A1A south for 4 miles to the park entrance on the right side of the road.
operatingHours: [{'exceptions': [], 'description': 'Upon your arrival at the park, you will circle the picnic area and see our visitor’s recreation area. directionsInfo: GPS units and cell phone services are unreliable throughout the Navajo Nation. The recommended route to the park is from Highway 191 in Chinle then turning east on Route 7. name: Visitor Center
description: The visitor center hosts exhibits and a 5-minute film about Roger Williams and early Providence. Outside, the landscaped park includes the site of the spring which provided fresh water to Providence's inhabitants. Restrooms and drinking water are available only when facilities are open.
audioDescription: The visitor center is located at the northeast corner of the park and next to the sidewalks on the corner of North Main and Smith Streets. The early 18th century two-story structure is constructed of wood painted dark teal with a white trim around windows and doors. It has large storefront-type windows and two doors on the front entrance side of the building (facing North Main Street). On the second story, it has smaller windows with 24 panes of glass in each.

name: Visitor Center
description: Located next to the statue of Abraham Lincoln, the Visitor Center provides information and restrooms to all visitors. Here you can watch the orientation film, browse the gift store, and learn about available public programs.
audioDescription: One story building with brown wood siding. Informational material about Augustus Saint-Gaudens is mounted to the wall as you enter through the double doors. The women's restrooms are located to the left. At the end of the building turn right and immediately to the right again to enter the women's restrooms. The men's restrooms are located about 15 feet to the right after entering the building. Turn left and immediately to the left again to enter the men's restrooms. The gift store and information desk are at the end of the building to the right after entering. The auditorium is situated to the right of the gift store entrance.

name: Visitor Center
description: The visitor center hosts new exhibits, installed in spring 2019. Learn about the history of Catoctin Mountain and the national park that was created here. American Indians, farmers, iron makers, the WPA, CCC, Jobs Corps and so many others played a role in making Catoctin Mountain Park the special place it is today. Discover how even your visit plays a part in the making of this park. Eastern National provides a small sales area with items to help you remember your visit.

name: Visitor Center
description: Open 7 days a week from 8:00 a.m. - 4:30 p.m. Closed on Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's Day.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a red and yellow two-story building with a green roof built into the side of a small hill. The walls are either red stone with wavy yellow lines or solid yellow, adorned with sets of red stone buttresses. In front of the building is the parking lot which makes a loop around a grassy area with some trees and benches. Behind the visitor center is the valley that the Washita River runs through with the red Horseshoe Hills making up the horizon on the far side of the valley. The visitor center for Washita Battlefield is on the upper floor with a paved, curving path leading up to an automatic glass door which is surrounded by windows, while the downstairs is where Black Kettle National Grassland is located. Once inside, you enter a large gallery area with a high cathedral style wood ceiling, red stone walls, a grey tile floor, and large floor to ceiling sets of windows on either end. The walls are adorned with art depicting the Battle of the Washita and there is a large red granite counter on the left side with a park ranger to speak with visitors. Hanging from a set of four large green metal rafters near the ceiling there are eight flags representing that nations that had members at the Washita and the National Park Service. Around the visitor center there are patterns of four and diamonds representing the four sacred directions. In the back-left corner of the visitor center is the bookstore with books, art, clothes, toys, and souvenirs and the back-right corner has the entrance to the museum. The museum makes a loop through three rooms back to the main gallery. As you first enter the museum there is a large map showing how tribes from around the country were pushed to Indian territory, present day Oklahoma, and a display describing the broken treaty system and the treaties signed by the Cheyenne and Arapaho tribes. Next, there is a tipi containing typical Cheyenne belongings and display containing a Seventh Cavalry blue coat with yellow stripes and a rifle. In the back room are quotes from tribal members and military officials showing different perspectives on the attack as well as a large wall sized mural showing an artist’s rendition of the 7th Cavalry’s attack on Black Kettle’s village. As you enter the last room there is a large, red sand stone marker that was placed at the Washita by a Seventh Cavalry soldier in the winter of 1890 to 1891 and a reproduction of an officer’s desk inviting visitors to write their opinions of the battle and place it on a bulletin board for all to read. The last displays contain panels showing the Cheyenne and Arapaho tribes today as well as changing temporary exhibits. Back in the gallery by the main entrance there is a doorway that leads to the bathrooms, movie theater, and stairs and an elevator leading downstairs to Black Kettle National Grassland’s information and offices.

name: Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is open Tuesday - Saturday, 9:00 am to 5:00 pm. This includes access to exhibits, the park's 10-minute film, "In the Most Furious Manner", the gift shop, and America the Beautiful Military and Access Passes. We do not sell the Annual or Senior Passes. Although the Visitor Center is closed on Sunday and Monday, the trailhead kiosk remains open for visitors to procure basic information and stamp their National Park Service Passport. The Visitor Center phone number is 910-283-5591 ex. 2223
audioDescription: When walking towards the front door of the Visitor Center our comfort station/ restrooms are located to the right of the building. At the restrooms is a water fountain located just to the left of the men's room. When entering the Visitor Center to the right of the door you will encounter a rain garden filled with native plants that can be found in southeastern North Carolina. Once entering the visitor center, you will then enter the main doors of the Visitor Center, and the front desk will be located immediately to your right. Visitors can obtain information for the park as well as additional information for local and state parks in the area. To the left is the start of our exhibits. Visitors will first encounter a timeline of the American Revolution beginning with the Stamp act in 1765, ending with George Washington returns home to Mount Vernon in 1783. The timeline is dived into two areas, on the top of the timeline is events specific to the colonies in general, and on the bottom are vents specific to the Carolina's. This exhibit stretches all the way around the outside wall inside the Visitor Center. Our exhibits located on the partisan begin with four maps of Southeastern North Carolina during the time of the American Revolution. From right to left, each map gives detailed information of the Moores Creek Campaign as it unfolded in February of 1776. Visitors will gain an understanding of troop movements, and how both armies choose Moores Creek Bridge as the decided place to do battle. As you finish the campaign maps immediately to your left on the outer wall, around the corner from the first half of the timeline, leading up to the Battle of Moores Creek Bridge in 1776, is our next exhibit. The exhibit is of a soldier from North Carolina in 1776. A mannequin adorns colonial civilian attire, worn by both sides during the battle. A simple question is posed to visitors, Loyalist or Patriot? This exhibit points out the fact that this battle is was fought among the colonists of North Carolina, making the American Revolution truly a civil war. Following along the outer wall visitors will encounter the entrance to our auditorium, where the park plays our film "In the Most Furious Manner." This ten-minute film explores the actions of both the Loyalists and Patriots the afternoon before the Battle of Moores Creek Bridge, though that long night, leading to the battle itself, and ultimately the aftermath. The film is a good place to obtain the park significance. When visitors leave the door of the auditorium they continue to the opposite side of the partition. On the outside wall visitors can continue the timeline of events from 1776 to the end of the war in 1783. Looking across the aisle on partition is an exhibit of weapons, supplies, and money captured from the Loyalists after the battle. At the end of this exhibit is a small timeline of the park beginning with the earliest vision of the park in 1856 to the current layout of Moores Creek National Battlefield. At the end of the exhibits, visitors can enter our America's National Park's bookstore/gift shop to the right with a variety of park specific related items, as well as various books related to the battle and the American Revolution. If visitors opt to take a left at this point, they will leave the Visitor Center enter the History Trail that further explains the events leading up to the Battle of Moores creek Bridge.

directionsInfo: Moores Creek National Battlefield is located 20 miles NW of Wilmington, North Carolina. · From Highway 17, follow US 421 to NC 210, then West on NC 210 · From Interstate 40 west, take exit 408 (NC 210) West at Rocky Point. · From Interstate 95 North, take exit 13-A for NC 74 East towards Wilmington. · From Interstate 95 South: take exit 81-B for I-40 East towards Wilmington. · From Fayetteville, North Carolina, take Interstate 95 South to Exit 13-A

name: Visitor Center
description: Explore exhibits about traditional Tlingít life and see drums, robes, and other ceremonial objects. A 12-minute film, "The Voices of Sitka," weaves together the stories of Sitkans, past and present. The nearby Totem Trail displays Northwest Coast totem poles and leads to the site of the Battle of 1804.
audioDescription: Explore exhibits about traditional Tlingít life and see drums, robes, and other ceremonial objects. A 12-minute film, "The Voices of Sitka," weaves together the stories of Sitkans, past and present. The nearby Totem Trail displays Northwest Coast totem poles and leads to the site of the Battle of 1804.

name: Visitor Center
description: The Hampton Visitor Center, historic buildings, and interpretive operations are open Thursdays - Sundays from 9:00 am to 4:00 pm. Tickets for mansion tours, park brochures, and passport stamps are available in the Visitor Center. Amenities include restrooms, gift shop, and a water bottle refill station.
audioDescription: From the Baltimore Beltway (I 695) eastbound or westbound: Take Exit 27B, Dulaney Valley Road northbound. Take the first right turn onto Hampton Lane. The park will be on your right, about one mile from the intersection. PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION: Bus #11 stops at Goucher College, less than one mile from Hampton. The Light Rail stop at Lutherville is approximately three miles from Hampton NHS. Once inside the park gates on the mansion side, continue up the road to the main parking lot. The visitor contact station is the building on the right before reaching the parking lot.
passportStampLocationDescription: Hampton NHS's Visitor Contact Station features four NPS Passport Stamps. These are the Hampton NHS stamp, the Network To Freedom stamp, the 19th Amendment Centennial stamp, and the Hampton Junior Ranger stamp.

name: Visitor Center (Secure Truman Home Tickets Here)
description: The park visitor center is located at 223 North Main Street, in the historic 1928 Independence Fire Station, which is in the Harry S Truman Historic District National Historic Landmark and one block north of the historic Independence Town Square. (816) 254-2720. An audio version of the park's main brochure is here: https://unidescription.org/account/project/export/123
audioDescription: An audio version of the park's main brochure (sometimes called the "unigrid") is available here: https://unidescription.org/account/project/export/123
passportStampLocationDescription: Effective June, 2021, and until the Visitor Center opens, Passport stamps are available at the Noland Home, 216 North Delaware Street (across the street from the Truman Home). Please note park is open Wednesdays to Sundays, and CLOSED ON MONDAYS AND TUESDAYS.

directionsInfo: The Visitor Center is located at 223 North Main Street, in Historic Fire Station No.1. From the north or south, take I-435 to Truman Road (State Hwy 12), exit 60. Travel east on Truman Road three miles; you'll pass the Truman Home at Delaware Street. From the east or west, take I-70 to the Noland Road exit (12). Travel north on Noland Road four miles to Truman Road. Turn west on Truman Road and travel two blocks.

name: Visitor Center Anacapa Island
description: Once the historic Coast Guard general services building (workshop and garage), this Mission Revival style building now serves as a small visitor center that features include displays on the natural and cultural resources of the island and the original lead-crystal Fresnel lens from the Anacapa Lighthouse.
audioDescription: Across the trail from the power house is the visitor center. Once the historic workshop, also designed in Mission Revival style white stucco, this long rectangular building has a gable roof with terra cotta shingles. Two perpendicular gable roof sections that look like garage fronts frame the east and west ends. Four windows and three doors all with green trim and panes alternate across the front face of the building while benches line the walkway. A picnic area is directly in front of the building.<The entrance to the visitor center is on the west end and has interior exhibits, a passport station and houses the original Fresnel lens. The east end of the building is now a bunkhouse and storage area for staff.<Outside on the east corner is a welcome kiosk and the main trailhead. Take a short path behind the west end of the building to access the pit toilets.
