name: Visitor Center and View Building
description: The Visitor Center at Cabrillo National Monument is the perfect place to get oriented to the park. Rangers and volunteers are always available to answer questions and provide suggestions on what to do. Here you can: • Find the day’s schedule of auditorium programs and ranger talks • Get your National Parks Passport book stamped • Chat with a ranger • Pick up a Junior Ranger activity for kids • Find out when low tide is • Visit the park store • Many other things!
audioDescription: The Visitor Center complex consists of the View Building, a theater, a museum, an administrative building, and a covered breezeway that connects several of the buildings. A wide, rocky-textured sidewalk leads off a traffic circle and heads directly east from the curb to the View Building. Most of this sidewalk section is covered by a breezeway that is shared between several of the other buildings of the complex. The breezeway is held up by white posts. The buildings connecting the breezeway all have white-painted walls and dark brown roofs. The theater and Cabrillo Museum share the same structure on the north side of the sidewalk. The structure on the south side of the sidewalk houses park administrative offices. The View Building at the end of the breezeway is a large, white-framed building with a pointed, dark-brown roof. It is walled with glass windows on all sides and has glass doors, offering maximum visibility to the surrounding area. The interior finish is a natural light-brown wood. The park store, information kiosk, and some exhibits are located inside the building. A large open patio surrounds the building. It has several interpretive exhibit panels and offers sweeping views of San Diego Bay, the City of San Diego, and the hillsides of Point Loma. Restroom facilities and a water bottle-filling station are available on the eastern side of the theater/museum building.

name: Visitor Center at Abraham Lincoln Birthplace
description: The Visitor Center at the Birthplace Unit is open 9:00 am - 5:00 pm eastern time. Inside there are exhibits, including the Lincoln family bible, a 15 minute long movie, Abraham Lincoln: The Kentucky Years, and the park store. Phone number: 270-358-3137
audioDescription: Upon arrival at the parking lot at 2995 Lincoln Farm Road exit your car and follow the sidewalk to the Visitor Center. The entrance to the Visitor Center is underneath the front porch midway of the Visitor Center. Inside the Visitor Center you can pick up park brochures and maps, watch the park’s 15-minute orientation movie, shop in the park store and learn more about the park. The Visitor Center bookstore has books, magnets, hiking sticks, coffee mugs and other memorabilia for purchase. Here you can also learn more about other things to do and places to see at the park. Once you have completed the viewing of the movie and examining the exhibits, exit the Visitor Center and follow the sidewalk to the left. At the end of the porch of the Visitor Center there are accessible restrooms, a water fountain and water bottle filling station, and the trailhead for the 800 feet Pathway of a President accessible boardwalk that takes you through the woods behind the Visitor Center to the Memorial Building at the top of the hill. You may also take the sidewalk to the right once you exit the Visitor Center and follow the sidewalk to the basin area at the flagpole and then ascend the 56 pink granite steps (one step for each year of Abraham Lincoln’s life) in front of you leading up to the Memorial Building. Or you may take the sidewalk to your left for about 20 feet to the head of the steps leading down to the Sinking Spring, the water source for the Lincoln family at the Sinking Spring Farm. The sidewalks in this area are level to a slight incline of less than five percent and are accessible. If you visit the Sinking Spring, you will descend 25 steps to view the spring and when you ascend the steps back up to the sidewalk, take the sidewalk to the right for about 80 feet to reach the site of the Boundary Oak tree. The Boundary Oak tree was the starting point for surveys of the farm beginning in 1805. From the Boundary Oak tree location, follow the sidewalk back toward the Sinking Spring. After approximately 40 feet, take the sidewalk to the left to ascend the hill to the Memorial Building. This sidewalk has a grade of approximately ten percent with 25 steps with handrails. Or you can continue for another 30 feet on the sidewalk passing by the head of the steps descending into the Sinking Spring to reach the 56 granite steps on the left leading up to the Memorial Building. Once you have reached the top of the hill, you can go to the left or right to go around behind the Memorial Building to enter the building. Once inside the Memorial Building you will be facing a mid-19th century Kentucky frontier log cabin. The Memorial Building and “symbolic birth cabin” sit on the site where the Lincoln family cabin was located when the family resided on the Sinking Spring Farm. You may go either left or right to view the cabin. Once you have viewed the cabin exit through the rear doors of the Memorial Building to return to the sidewalk, going to the right to follow the sidewalk and the 800 feet Pathway of a President accessible boardwalk or to descend the 56 pink granite steps to return to the Visitor Center.

name: Visitor Center at Mission San José
description: Park Store in the Visitor Center is open 9 am to 5pm, 7 days/week. Visitor Center is often closed for the lunch hour. Closed Thanksgiving Day, December 25, and January 1. Park Store operated by Western National Parks Association. Just outside of the Visitor Center, you will find a plaque recognizing the park's World Heritage designation. La tienda en el Centro de Visitantes está abierta de 9 am a 5 pm todos los días. El Centro de Visitantes está cerrado durante la hora del almuerzo.
audioDescription: Visitor Center is a large rectangular structure with exterior stones meant to replicate the appearance of the limestone at the missions. The trim is royal blue. Restrooms are located on the left as you approach the Visitor Center, before entering the lobby doors. The building is surrounded by large mesquite trees. Inside, you will find a large lobby area with a gift shop straight ahead, museum to the right, and information desk to the left. The museum contains original and replica artifacts representing mission life in the 18th century.
passportStampLocationDescription: San Antonio Missions National Historical Park offers six passport stamps at the Visitor Center at at each ranger contact station. This includes cancellation stamps for San Antonio Missions National Historical Park and El Camino Real de los Tejas. It also includes four decorative stamps, one for each of the four mission church facades.

name: Visitor Center at Valley Forge
description: The Visitor Center at Valley Forge is open daily, 9 AM to 5 PM. Closed on Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's days. First opened in 1978, the Visitor Center at Valley Forge is a multi-use building designed by Walter Ogg of the Philadelphia firm of Eshbach, Glass, Kale, and Associates, and includes visitor information services, The Encampment Store, and a museum exhibit that tells the story of the Valley Forge encampment of the Continental Army.
passportStampLocationDescription: Standard circular passport stamp for Valley Forge National Historical Park includes the month, day, and year.

From Interstate I-76, take Route 422 West to Route 23 West/Valley Forge. From State Route 252, take State Route 23 East.

name: Visitor Center at the Big Hole National Battlefield
description: The park's visitor center offers museum exhibits, a film, and a book sales area. The award-winning film Weet'uciklitukt: There's No Turning Back, Battle at Big Hole provides an introduction to the Nez Perce Flight of 1877 and the battle that took place at this site. The film is shown throughout the day and is close-captioned. Audio and braille guides are available upon request. Park grounds are open sunrise to sunset daily.

name: Visitor Center/Park Store and Information
description: The Sandburg Home Visitor Center/Park Store and Tours are open Thursday to Sunday (4 days per week) from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Hours vary by season; the Holiday closures below will change by season. The visitor center/park store and information area is a great place to start your visit! You can find information to plan your visit, get a passport stamp, participate in the Jr Ranger or BARK Ranger programs, and get a schedule of upcoming events.
audioDescription: Upon arriving at the main parking lot at 1800 Carl Sandburg Lane exit your car and follow the sidewalk path as it leads down to the front lake. At the lake visitors have a view of the Sandburg Home at the top of a hill and a choice of taking a wooded path to the left that will lead them around the lake, or continue on the sidewalk to the right. Following the sidewalk to the right, there is a building with accessible restrooms, a water fountain and water bottle filling station, and wall mounted exhibit panels with text and photos featuring images of the Sandburg family at Connemara, and information about Carl Sandburg's life and his contributions to American literature and poetry. There are four picnic tables behind the building for visitor use. Just past this building is a small white bridge. Proceed across the white wooden bridge with the lake to the left and a spillover dam on the right. Follow the gravel trail straight ahead. This portion of the trail is rocky and moderately sloped. It ascends 100 feet over 1/3 mile to the Sandburg Home at the top. As you walk up the rock trail there are fenced pastures, and tall Hemlock trees lining both sides with a historic rock wall between the trail and a road. This trail continues up the hill and at the top of the hill the trail splits into left and right lanes. Visitor restrooms and access to the barn follow the path to the right. The left fork in the lane delivers you to the Sandburg Home where visitor information and park store services are available on the ground floor of the three story historic white home. The entrance to the Visitor Center is underneath the front porch. Inside you can pick up park brochures and maps, purchase house tour tickets, watch a video, shop in the park store and learn more about the park. The Visitor Center bookstore has books, magnets, hiking sticks, cards, and other memorabilia for purchase. Here you can also learn more about other things to do and places to see at the park. If you arrived at the Hikers lot at 81 Carl Sandburg Lane, follow the signs from to the trail from the parking lot to the gravel road. Park Headquarters and the maintenance compound are on the left. You will use a pedestrian path to walk around a closed vehicle gate and back onto the road. Proceed down this gravel road for approximately 1/3 mile keeping in mind occasional park vehicles may use this road. You may stop to visit the goats at the barn area. To continue to the Sandburg Home and visitor center, continue walking on the gravel road for 100 yards. There is a fork in the road. To the left is an accessible public restroom and water fountain, to the right is a paved road leading to the Sandburg Home. Visitors enter the home underneath the porch. Inside you can find park brochures and maps, sign up and pay for house tours, and watch a short documentary. The park store also has books, magnets, hiking sticks, cards, and other memorabilia for purchase. Here you can learn about other things to do and places to see at the park.

name: Visitor Contact Station
description: The Contact Station is located at the historic site, which is eight miles north of the town of Chivington. It provides education and orientation materials and has a sales outlet for educational merchandise. The Contact Station maintains the same hours as the park. NOTE: Bookstore sales end at 3:30 pm.
audioDescription: The Sand Creek Massacre contact station is located approximately 100 feet from the main parking area. The surrounding area is mostly open prairie, with a few cottonwood trees close to the building. The Contact Station is inside a modular building with an open deck in the front. A ramp provides access to the deck and building entrance. A concrete sidewalk runs from the end of the ramp to a vault toilet restroom about 50 feet away from the contact station. Inside the contact station is a small bookstore where visitors can buy books, magnets, postcards, and other similar items. There is a water fountain / bottle filling station along the wall to the right of the entrance door. Park rangers are usually available inside to answer questions.

name: Visitor and Education Center
description: The Sand Creek Massacre Visitor and Education Center is located in downtown Eads, Colorado. It provides education and orientation materials and has a sales outlet for educational merchandise. On the second floor there is an exhibit space featuring images of people connected to the Sand Creek Massacre.
audioDescription: The Sand Creek Massacre Visitor and Education Center is located on the main street of Eads, Colorado. Within a block of the same street are several local businesses, a grocery store, pharmacy, post office, bank, and small theatre. The Visitor and Education Center is housed in a restored brick building on the corner of Maine Street and 13th Street, with the main entrance facing Maine Street. There is a small space between the outer and inner doors, about 4 feet long. The inner door opens onto the bookstore and front desk on the left and a staircase against the right-hand wall, leading upward. Beyond the front desk is a hallway where restrooms, an elevator, and a water fountain can be found. Going up the staircase to the second floor, the steps go straight for two thirds of its length, then turn left for the remainder. At the top of the stairs, on the right are stanchions with rope between then marking the staff only area. To the left is the elevator. Beyond the elevator is another room which serves as an exhibit space.

name: W. Kerr Scott Dam & Reservoir Visitor Center
description: Visitor Center for W. Kerr Scott Dam & Reservoir, featuring information about the Army Corps of Engineers, the wildlife of the Yadkin River Valley, and the Overmountain Victory National Historic Trail. On September 28, 1780, hundreds of Patriot militia traveled down the Yadkin River on their way to the Battle of Kings Mountain. Their original route is now underneath the reservoir, and hiking and biking trails along the shoreline closely follow their route.

name: WNPA Trailhead Bookstore
description: At the Trailhead Bookstore, you will find our park store operated by the Western National Parks Association. Many items related to the park, the Gila Wilderness, and to the Continental Divide Trail are available, as well as souvenirs and American Indian crafts. Park staff are available to answer questions and help plan visits. Come discover your heritage and your public lands.

name: Waite & Peirce
description: Waite & Peirce offers a curated selection of quality products that will help extend your park experience with maritime themed goods that hearken back to Salem's place in the history of global trade. Explore the exclusive line of Waite & Peirce apparel, jewelry, home goods, historical reproductions, collectibles, toys and gifts.
audioDescription: Waite and Peirce. 175 words. A two-story dark brown wood building rests on the east side of a busy city street. On the east side of the building is the harbor where the wharf and the derby lighthouse can be seen. The north side of the building is a field with grass and a large monument with an anchor and accompanying text which reads: “Salem Maritime National Historic Site.” The west and south side of the building is the town of Salem with red brick buildings, cobblestone walkways, and busy roads. The visitor center has two ways of entry: On the west side, the door is accessible via a flat walkway from the sidewalk. On the north side, a small staircase and ramp, both with handrails, lead into the building. The interior of the building has one backroom on the south side. The rest of the building is one large room, with racks and shelves of merchandise. The cashier desk is in the northwest corner. A wooden door behind the desk leads to a staircase that ascends to employee offices. End of Description.

name: Walnut Canyon Visitor Center
description: The Walnut Canyon Visitor Center includes a museum, film, WNPA park store, canyon viewpoint, and restroom facilities. The building features architecture from both the Civilian Conservation Corps and Mission 66 era. Park rangers are present, and Junior Ranger activities are available.

name: Walter Harper Talkeetna Ranger Station
description: Located in the town of Talkeetna, about 100 miles south of the entrance to Denali National Park and Preserve, this ranger station serves as the center of mountaineering operations. Climbers wishing to attempt Denali or other peaks in the Alaska Range stop here first, for an orientation to the mountain and to acquire their climbing permit. This ranger station also offers some visitor services, particularly in summer. It is open year-round.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Walter Harper Talkeetna Ranger Station is located in Talkeetna, Alaska, about 2.5 hours drive south of the main entrance to Denali National Park. Visitors must travel on Highway 3 to the Talkeetna Spur Road, and then drive 15 miles into town to find the ranger station in "downtown" Talkeetna. This is the starting point for most mountaineering expeditions to climb Denali, Mount Foraker, and other noteworthy peaks in the Alaska Range.

name: Washington's Headquarters Museum
description: Built by the National Park Service in the 1930s, the Washington's Headquarters Museum contains numerous artifacts about the American Revolution. There are three galleries, an auditorium, a theater, and the Discover History Center. The museum often hosts special exhibits and programs. Situated just behind the historic Ford Mansion that served as Washington's headquarters for six months, guided tours of the home begin in the museum as well.
audioDescription: The Washington Headquarters museum building is a three story structure modeled after Mount Vernon, with two wings flanking a central Georgian style entryway. A cupola adorns the building, with large windows arranged in symmetrical fashion. Above the main entryway facing the Ford Mansion are these words etched in marble, "HISTORICAL MUSEUM / Morristown National Historical Park / A.D. 1935 / National Park Service / Department of the Interior". Low hedges and trimmed bushes line the walkway and the perimeter of the building, as well as seasonal flowers in large pots.

description: The Watch Hill area offers a visitor center, family campground, ranger-led interpretive programs (including guided kayak trips), a 175-slip transient marina with water, electric, and pump-out station; a small convenience store, snack bar, self-guiding nature trail, restrooms, and lifeguarded beach (summer only).

name: Waterrock Knob Visitor Center
description: Waterrock Knob is our highest elevation visitor center on the Parkway. Known for its beautiful long-range views of several major mountain chains in the Appalachians, Waterrock Knob is uniquely suited for viewing sunrises and sunsets. The small visitor center introduces visitors to the area's rugged terrain and tremendous scenic resources, including the Great Smoky Mountains that are visible from here.
passportStampLocationDescription: The passport stamps are located in the America's National Parks store in the visitor center.

name: Wawona Visitor Center at Hill's Studio
description: The Wawona Visitor Center has an information desk, Wilderness permit desk, and Yosemite Conservancy bookstore. In winter, self-registration wilderness permits for the Wawona trailheads are available on the porch. You must bring your own bear canister when the information station is closed. Wilderness permits are required for overnight stays in Yosemite's Wilderness. Accessible parking is available, and a lift for wheelchair access is available at the rear of the building (use intercom for assistance).
audioDescription: The Hill's Studio is a boxy brown building with a long porch along the front. There are five steps that lead up to the entrance. A sign above the porch reads Hill's Studio. There are remnants of an old round fountain, no longer in use, in the front of the studio. Smooth, round palm sized rocks fill the center of the fountain a quarter way up.

name: Welcome Center
description: Guided tours of the Dig Shelter begin here. Tours are conducted every 30 minutes, no reservation needed. Tours last from 45 minutes to one hour. Tour guides will lead you from the Welcome Center, down a 300 yard paved path to the Dig Shelter where mammoth fossils are in situ (still in their original position within the bone bed).

name: West Thumb Information Station
description: A small facility at the start of the West Thumb Geyser Basin boardwalks, where you can visit with a park ranger and gather park information, shop for souvenirs in the park store, or join a ranger program. The structure was built in 1925 and is an example of historic ranger-station architecture in Yellowstone.

name: West Yellowstone Visitor Information Center (Chamber of Commerce Desk)
description: Located in the town of West Yellowstone, Montana, there is a desk staffed by National Park Service rangers (summer and winters only). The building is open year-round and a second desk is staffed by the West Yellowstone Chamber of Commerce. Stop by to obtain backcountry and fishing permits, get park information or to use the restrooms.
audioDescription: West Yellowstone Visitor Information Center 238 words A large concrete plaza fills the area in front of this L-shaped one-story building with brown clapboard siding and multiple gable roofs. The glass double doors at the building’s entrance lie beyond a covered breezeway with its two partial side walls supported by concrete and wood pillars on each end. The exterior breezeway wall to the right of the entrance is edged in pale wood which also frames a large map labeled “West Yellowstone Historic Walking Tour.” Painted on the concrete plaza and leading toward the entrance from the right is a single line of green bear tracks; each large footprint has five toes. Hanging on the building façade between two sets of double windows located to the right of the entrance doors are two long horizontal signs that read: “Visitor Information: West Yellowstone Montana.” Affixed to the wall below these signs are three smaller emblem signs representing the “National Park Service,” “Forest Service Department of Agriculture,” and “Montana Big Sky Country.” Public restrooms are located in a separate entrance in front of and slightly to the right of the center. The restroom entrances are located on the side facing away from the center, with the women’s room on the far left and the men’s room on the far right. Wheelchair logos indicate that both restrooms are wheelchair-accessible. A small sign on each door warns us: “Caution! Watch your step. Inside floor may be slippery.” END OF MESSAGE

name: West Yellowstone Visitor Information Center (NPS Desk)
description: Located in the town of West Yellowstone, Montana, there is a desk and backcountry office staffed by National Park Service rangers (summer and winters only). The building is open year-round and a second desk is staffed by the West Yellowstone Chamber of Commerce. Stop by to obtain backcountry and fishing permits (fees are payable by debit or credit card), to get park information, or to use the restrooms. Call 307-344-2876 for additional information.
audioDescription: West Yellowstone Visitor Information Center 238 words A large concrete plaza fills the area in front of this L-shaped one-story building with brown clapboard siding and multiple gable roofs. The glass double doors at the building’s entrance lie beyond a covered breezeway with its two partial side walls supported by concrete and wood pillars on each end. The exterior breezeway wall to the right of the entrance is edged in pale wood which also frames a large map labeled “West Yellowstone Historic Walking Tour.” Painted on the concrete plaza and leading toward the entrance from the right is a single line of green bear tracks; each large footprint has five toes. Hanging on the building façade between two sets of double windows located to the right of the entrance doors are two long horizontal signs that read: “Visitor Information: West Yellowstone Montana.” Affixed to the wall below these signs are three smaller emblem signs representing the “National Park Service,” “Forest Service Department of Agriculture,” and “Montana Big Sky Country.” Public restrooms are located in a separate entrance in front of and slightly to the right of the center. The restroom entrances are located on the side facing away from the center, with the women’s room on the far left and the men’s room on the far right. Wheelchair logos indicate that both restrooms are wheelchair-accessible. A small sign on each door warns us: “Caution! Watch your step. Inside floor may be slippery.” END OF MESSAGE

name: Wetlands Acadian Cultural Center
description: The Acadian exiles who settled along Louisiana's bayous created a distinctive Cajun culture based on life in a watery realm. The center shares their way of life through a film, special and permanent exhibits, musical performances, and boat tours of Bayou Lafourche. Admission to the center and to most programs is free; boat tours are by ticket and reservation.
audioDescription: The Wetlands Acadian Cultural Center is housed in the historic Percy-Lobdell building constructed in the early 1900s as a grocer warehouse. The building itself is a 2-story brick building on the banks of Bayou Lafourche which served as the route for the groceries to be delivered. The parking lot is an elongated U from Saint Mary Street/LA 1 towards Bayou Lafourche. The grounds are sparsely planted with Live Oaks and some Cypress Trees. There is a sidewalk and concrete patio leading to a deck area and dock area on Bayou Lafourche. There is also a connecting sidewalk along Bayou Lafourche leading to historic downtown Thibodaux, approximately 2 blocks away. The Visitor Center Desk is located just inside the front entrance to the right, there is also a Craft Room all the way to the right towards Bayou Lafourche, leading out to the patio and deck area, where special events are hosted including Monday Night Music, and Tuesday French Cere Francophone, the Theater receptions, etc. The opposite side towards Saint Mary Street/LA 1 is the museum and small theater for video viewing. Across from the Visitor Center Desk is the Gumbo Room with interactive exhibits on sugarcane and music as well as a playroom for younger visitors with a kitchen and stage area. Just beyond the Visitor Center Desk is the Gallery for local artists to display their works, and the entrance to the large stage theater and restrooms. After you enter the front doors of the Visitor Center, to reach the visitor desk you continue straight approximately 20 feet, turn to the right approximately 10 feet and you will arrive at the Visitor Center Desk. The Visitor Center Desk shaped like an L with 1 side running along the hallway to the Craft Room, and the other side running towards the Gallery, Large Theater, and Restroom areas. There will be a ranger there to greet you. To reach the restrooms, after you enter the front doors of the Visitor Center continue straight approximately 50 feet to the doors of the Gallery. Open one of the doors and enter the gallery. Once inside the gallery walk 7 feet to the right (to avoid the posts) then turn left and head straight approximately 25 feet, then turn right, you will move from carpet to tile, this is the tile hallway for the restrooms, the door to the Women’s Restroom is on your right approximately 5 feet, the door to the men’s restroom is approximately 12 feet to the left next to the bank of water fountains. In the Women’s restroom there is a tile alcove approximately 10 feet long, turn to the left and you will enter a central area with wash basins to the left of you, and a small paper hand towel dispenser with a trash receptacle below, on the right side, if you continue straight there is a bank of 4 stalls varying from 2-4 feed in width. The wash basin area has 2 sinks on counter with a soap dispenser in the middle on the mirrored wall in front of the basins, approximately 1.5 feet above the counter with the sink basins. In the Men’s restroom there is a small tile alcove with a wall divider approximately 5 feet in front of the door, enter approximately 3 feet turn to the left (to avoid the wall) on the other side of this wall to the right there is a small paper hand towel dispenser with a trash receptacle below, then another 3 feet begins the counter with 2 sink basins. The wash basin area has 2 sinks on counter with a soap dispenser in the middle on the mirrored wall in front of the basins, approximately 1.5 feet above the counter with the sink basins. To reach the restrooms after you have entered and gotten around the wall, go straight approximately 8 feet to a bank of 3 stalls directly in front of you. There are urinals all the way to right against the back wall and you may reach them by going approximately 10-12 feet to the right turning left and go another 3 feet until you reach the two urinals against the back wall.

name: Whalebone Junction Information Center
description: The Whalebone Junction Information Center is located on Highway 12 in Nags Head, NC at the entrance to Cape Hatteras National Seashore. Park maps, newspapers, and current beach conditions are available inside. The building is staffed by the Outer Banks Visitors Bureau. The Dyke Trail can be accessed from the Information Center parking lot.
audioDescription: The entrance area to the Whalebone Junction Information Center is divided by a small parking area. On the left side is a small building staffed by the Outer Banks Visitors Bureau. The building contains brochures, maps, and other traveler information. Restrooms are located outside the information center, directly across the parking area.

name: Whiskeytown Visitor Center
description: The Visitor Center is a great place to start when you arrive in the park. Knowledgeable staff can help you maximize your visit. The Visitor Center is located at the intersection of Kennedy Memorial Drive and Highway 299. You can purchase a variety of Interagency and park-specific entrance passes as well as books, maps, and souvenir items. Exhibits outside the building introduce you to the natural and cultural history of the park. A small native plant garden is located behind the Visitor Center.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is located at the north end of a plaza that overlooks Whiskeytown Lake from about 200 feet above the water. Trees frame the view and a trail (Shasta Divide Trail) leads down to the lakeshore from the south end of the parking lot. Benches and information kiosks in the plaza are covered to provide protection from the rain and sun. Native plants are featured in the plaza behind low rock walls and along a short path that loops behind the visitor center. Entrance passes may be purchased inside the Visitor Center and staff are available to answer questions about the park. Inquire about discounts available to seniors, military personnel, fourth grade students, and visitors with permanent disabilities.
passportStampLocationDescription: We have the standard passport stamp and a Junior Ranger stamp at the Visitor Center.

name: White River Visitor Center
description: The visitor center is located on the Pine Ridge Reservation and offers a staffed information desk, exhibits, restrooms, picnic tables, and water. Impromptu talks are available by request. This visitor center is only open during the summer season.
audioDescription: White River Visitor Center. 288 words. The grey double-wide trailer has a wooden deck with stairs and a parallel gently sloping wood path leading to the to the main entrance of the building. The building is surrounded on its south and east side by large parking lots accommodating dozens of vehicles. The building is surrounded by prairie grasses extending for miles towards layered, jagged badlands formations hundreds of feet high. On the southwest side of the building down a grassy knoll, there are five picnic tables with shade structures. In the main area of the front, south-facing, wall of the building there is a picnic table beneath a large cottonwood tree. Southeast of the building, approximately 30 feet across the street, is there is a tan concrete welcome sign with the National Park Service logo and the text "Welcome to Badlands National Park" with a smaller sign beneath it reading “Managed in cooperation with the Oglala Sioux Tribe.” The main entrance is on the south side of the building, with an emergency exist on the north side. Beside the main entrance, a sign affixed to the building read in English and Lakota: Makȟa Makȟošiča Oínažiŋ Badlands National Park Makhízíta Wakpá Thiléaŋg Ománi Hí Chokáta Thípi White River Visitor Center In cooperation with the Oglala Sioux Tribe. The interior of the building is an open space with a large, multicolored and perpendicular circular exhibit in the middle in the style of a medicine wheel design. The east side of the building has two unisex bathrooms and a water fountain. The west side of the building has a small office, and a square room with multiple wall exhibits and a small TV that functions as a theater. A wayside exhibit outside the building has the following text and images: The Badlands Gunnery Range: More than a third of a million acres of the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, including much of what is now the South Unit of Badlands National Park, was set aside for gunnery and bombing practice by the U.S. Army Air Corps at the start of World War II. Residents had to move on short notice. Some never returned. With sound an fury, mock battles raged throughout the war. Bombs burst among fossil bones. In the sky young pilots improved their aim by shooting at wide ribbons of nylon net strung behind tow planes. Occasionally a bullet clipped a tow cable, and a net fluttered to earth. By war's end, many nearby ranchers had screened their windows with salvaged netting. Some told tales of stray bombs and bullets. While Granny Saunders fried eggs on morning, an errant shell crashed through her roof, her bed, and the bedroom floor. (black and white photos of large bomber planes with approximately 30' wing spans accompanied by text: "The workhorse bombers of World War II, a pair of B-17s makes a run over the Badlands Gunnery Range" and "Tow planes with target nets.") End of Description.

name: White River Wilderness Information Center
description: Open during the summer, the White River Wilderness Information Center (WIC) located at the Winter River Entrance. The WIC has an information desk staffed by wilderness rangers. Rangers at the WIC assist with wilderness permits, trip planning, and providing maps and trail condition updates.
audioDescription: The White River Wilderness Information Center (WIC) is located in a small rustic ranger station just on the right side of the road after passing into the park through the Winter River Entrance Station in the bottom of a canyon. The building is currently undergoing renovation and will be described once the project is complete. To the left of the WIC is a parking area with paths leading through the trees to restrooms. The path to the women's restroom is located at the far end of the parking area from the WIC with the path to the men's restroom closer to the WIC. An information board is between the two paths.

name: White Sands Visitor Center
description: The visitor center was built in 1936 and is part of the historic district at White Sands. Inside you will find the park store as well as the museum for the park.
audioDescription: The Visitor Center is constructed of adobe in a common southwest style, with smooth walls, a rounded top edge and flat roof. Seen from the front, which faces the highway, the central part of the building is two stories, flanked on each side by a single-story wing. Along the front, between the two wings is a deep, covered verandah with benches placed along the wall. The entrance consisting of two, multi-glass-paned doors, is located at the left end of the verandah. Both the roof over the central section and the verandah in the front is supported by large logs which extend out several feet beneath the top of the wall. The walls are a pinkish-tan color with the wood trim being painted a dark brown. At the right end of the front of the building is a historic sign of white-painted adobe which reads, “White Sands National Monument Visitor Center. Information, Scenic Drive, Museum.” To the left of the visitor center is a similar adobe building which houses the restrooms, women to the far left and men to the right. A sidewalk between the two buildings leads to a separate parking lot at the rear, past a water fountain and two shaded picnic tables. The area around the building is landscaped with desert plants. The interior of the Visitor Center has red-tiled floors and white painted walls. Upon entering the building, you find yourself in a rectangular foyer. An opening on the right leads to a large room with informational displays, books and other educational items for sale and the information desk. On the wall at the left side of the foyer is a tactile map of the building. A star indicates your current location and there are also room labels are also in Braille. At the far end of the foyer, another set of double doors leads into an enclosed courtyard. A verandah with benches is located on two sides, straight ahead and to the right. The verandah straight ahead leads to the entrance of the Gift Shop, which may also be entered from the rear parking lot.

name: Wilderness Information Center
description: The Wilderness Information Center is the main backcountry permit office for North Cascades National Park and the adjacent Ross Lake and Lake Chelan National Recreation Areas. Backcountry permits are required for overnights in the park year-round and are available at an outdoor self-issue station when the center is closed during the winter season. Information desk. Sales area with books, maps, videos, and other items related to the national park and adjacent national forests.

name: Wilderness Visitor Center
description: The Fire Island Wilderness Visitor Center includes a ranger contact station, 360-degree view of barrier island, Eastern National sales outlet, and exhibit space. Permits for recreational driving and waterfowl hunting are issued in season and park ranger-led programs are offered year-round. Hiking trails into the Otis Pike High Dune Wilderness are also accessible from here.

name: William Floyd Estate
description: The William Floyd Estate, which was authorized as an addition to Fire Island National Seashore in 1965, is located on the mainland of Long Island in Mastic Beach. Visitors can explore the Estate grounds, trails, twelve outbuildings, family cemetery, and enslaved crosses, no fee required. Currently, the Old Mastic House is closed to the public for renovations. Visitors are welcome to explore the Estate grounds.

name: William Johnson House Visitor Center
description: This visitor contact station at the William Johnson House site is located in the two-and-a-half story brick building known as the McCallum House which is adjacent to the Johnson home. The McCallum House serves as the site's visitor contact station and provides restroom facilities, a small bookstore/giftshop, and exhibits.
audioDescription: This visitor contact station at the William Johnson House site is located in the two-and-a-half story brick building known as the McCallum House which is adjacent to the Johnson home. The McCallum House serves as the site's visitor contact station and provides restroom facilities, a small bookstore/giftshop, and exhibits. The restored historic facade of the McCallum House reflects its time as a commercial space on the first floor with five doors and a living space above. Today, the upstairs of the McCallum house serves as offices for the curatorial staff of the park. An elevator located on the rear gallery of this building provides access to the upper floors of the historic site. The center doorway of the McCallum House is an accessible entrance. Upon entering, visitors find themselves in a large lobby/bookstore/gift shop with some exhibits about early Natchez history. These exhibits are accompanied by listening devices for the visually impaired. A large opening provides access to the first floor of the adjacent William Johnson House which contains exhibits on the first floor and period museum rooms on the second floor.
passportStampLocationDescription: At the William Johnson House Visitor Center, one has access to six (6) passport stamps for the Natchez National Historical Park which include the following park sites: Melrose, Fort Rosalie, and the William Johnson House. Visitors may also receive a stamp for the Natchez Trace Parkway, the park's Junior Ranger stamp, and the National Park Service's centennial stamp.

name: William M. Colmer Visitor Center
description: Located in the Davis Bayou area of Gulf Islands National Seashore this is the main visitor center for the park resources in Mississippi.
audioDescription: William M. Colmer Visitor Center. The conglomerate concrete sidewalk leads from the parking lot to the visitor center. The single-story white building is made of two hexagonal units joined in the middle by a small rectangular section where the main entrance is located. This section has glass walls both front and back and has a skylight. The rest of the building has a green metal roof. Grassy lawns lie in front of the building which is surrounded by woods on the other three sides. Each of the side units have the National Park Service arrowhead-shaped logo mounted on the wall. A flagpole in front of the building at the left side of the walk flies the American flag. Near the flagpole another sidewalk extends to the right, circling the building and leading to outdoor exhibits, overlooks and seating areas. End of Description.

name: Williamsport Visitor Center
description: The Williamsport Visitor Center is located at mile 99.8 along the C&O Canal towpath in Washington County, MD. Situated at the confluence of the Conococheague Creek and the Potomac River, Williamsport was first settled in 1740. A half-mile rewatered section of canal leads through the turning basin, under the only Railroad Lift Bridge on the canal, and continues to Lock House 44 and the adjacent lock. The Conocheague Aqueduct is located across from the turning basin.
audioDescription: [180 words] The visitor’s center is old warehouse building with dimensions in feet of about 80 by 25 and 20 high. The longer walls face North and South. The exterior wall is made of brick painted maroon and a metal roof with darken edges of rust. Thirty-five openings/windows, most are covered with grayish-blue shutters, embed the building. Large 2 to 4-foot painted white words decorate the walls. East wall words read Cushwa, Brick, Coal, Fuel Oil. South wall reads Coal, Building and Supplies, Office, this word is located beside a door. West wall reads, Cushwa, Coal, Brick these words have a large black background with a white outline. A gravel road splits to the north and south on the East wall leading to separate parking lots. On the west wall begins a body of water about three times the size of the warehouse named a basin. It is shaped like a semi-square which connects to the canal. It is outlined in a 2-foot stone wall which is flush with the ground. The distance from ground level to water level is about 4 feet.

name: Wilson's Creek Visitor Center & Museum
description: Newly renovated visitor center and museum is now open to the public. The renovation added 1,800 square feet of new museum exhibit space, an additional restroom, new HVAC system to protect the artifacts. See the original "Lyon bed," a rare Model 1860 Henry repeating rifle, several interactive and accessible audio-visual displays and virtual displays. Watch the orientation film, visit the newly renovated book and gift store, Visit the John k. and Ruth Hulston Civil War Research Library.
audioDescription: The modern one-story building sits on a slight hill. Taller trees, two cannons, and some large limestone rocks are in an open area to the right as you face the long, low building. An information bulletin board with park brochures faces the parking lot and is set up under oak trees along the main sidewalk along the west edge of the parking lot. From the main sidewalk, two paved walkways run toward the main entrance and merge at the main door. One of the walkways also leads to two secondary entrances to the left of the main entrance. Along both walkways are engraved stone "timeline" panels set flat along the edges with information about significant Civil War dates and events. The front of the building is formed primarily of large windows. A fully glassed-in space extends out at an angle near the main entrance. An exhibit with full-sized uniformed figures standing around a cannon is seen through the windows and inside the angled space. Another exhibit with cannon and limber (ammunition wagon) is seen running inside the large windows to the right of the main entrance. A paved area with a semi-circle of benches, the flag pole, and water fountain sits in front of the building and slightly to the left of the main entrance as you face the building.
passportStampLocationDescription: Passport stamps will be available inside the brochure rack located at the edge of the parking lot, just below the Visitor Center building. Visitors seeking a passport stamp also may contact the park's main number, under contact information, and a park ranger will assist you.

name: Windigo Visitor Center
description: The Windigo Visitor Center is located in Windigo on the southwest end of Isle Royale National Park. It is only accessible by boat or seaplane. Permitting and fee payment, trip planning assistance, a park store, and exhibits are available.
audioDescription: As you arrive at the Windigo Dock, the Windigo Visitor Center is located to the left of the picnic pavilion, up the hill, following the signed path. It is a large wooden building with an outdoor porch providing seating. Obtain passes, permits, and information from park rangers. Explore exhibits and shop the Isle Royale & Keweenaw Parks Association Store. Restrooms are not located in the visitor center; restrooms are located at the bottom of the hill, north of the Windigo Dock, heading down the trail towards the Washington Creek Campground.

name: Winter Information: Bar Harbor Chamber of Commerce
description: During winter and spring, the park shares winter visitor operations with the Bar Harbor Chamber of Commerce, 2 Cottage Street, at the corner of Cottage and Main streets (GPS coordinates = 44.398633, -68.204933). Hours are 8 am to 4 pm weekdays. There will be early closure at 3 pm the day before Thanksgiving Nov 22 and noon on Dec. 31, and full-day holiday closures on Nov 23, Dec 24, Dec 25, Dec 26, and Jan 1. Telephone operations continue at (207) 288-3338 during regular hours, except holidays.

name: Wright Brothers Visitor Center and Museum
description: The visitor center at Wright Brothers National Memorial is the best place to start your visit to the national park. The visitor center offers trip planning information, a park store, and detailed hands-on exhibits that bring the invention of the Wright Brothers to life. Not to miss, is the reproduction 1903 flyer in the Flight Room. Here, you can see up-close what the flyer looked like, and explore the workings of powered flight.
audioDescription: The Wright Brothers National Memorial visitor center can be found just beyond the parking lot on the right hand side. Climb the three steps onto the patio and enter through the glass doors. Once inside, straight ahead a few feet will be the tactile map of the park. To the left of the map, about 10 feet is the information desk. Turning right at the map, you will be facing the beginning of the exhibit hall. About 20 feet and to the right are the interactive exhibits exploring the story of the Wright brothers from their childhood through their history-making flight in the Outer Banks. Directly to the right of the beginning of the exhibits is the Museum store. About 20 feet from the map, to the left, is the flight room, a large open room that features a replica of the 1903 Flyer as well as additional exhibits which explore the challenges of flight. Restrooms are located outside the visitor center. If you exit through main entrance door, follow the wall and turn left once you reach the corner, the women's restroom will be first on the left and the men's room is a few feet past that also on the left.
passportStampLocationDescription: WRBR's passport stamp is the NPS Classic Passport Cancellation Stamp consisting of a circle containing the park name and date. Find the stamp in the Park Store.

name: Wupatki Visitor Center
description: The Wupatki Visitor Center includes a museum, WNPA park store, park film, and restroom facilities. The building features architecture from the Mission 66 era. Park rangers are present, passes are available for purchase, and Junior Ranger activities are available.
audioDescription: The visitor center is a one story red sandstone building with a light tan metal roof that slants down from the center with wooden eves. There is a long overhang in front of the main doors and a row of ten windows along the front wall to the right. On the left side of the doors there is a large wooden painted NPS arrowhead and six inch brass letters that read Visitor Center mounted on a slatted wooden wall. There are two concrete sidewalks that lead up to the building from the parking lot. The sidewalk on the left goes around a landscaped island and up to the front doors and the restrooms down a hallway to the left. The landscaped island is filled with native plants such as Sand Sage, Apache Plume, and yucca in a black volcanic cinder soil. The sidewalk on the right goes up three steps with handrails on both sides then to the front doors. Trash and recycle cans are located to the right of these steps. There is a flagpole in front of the building on the right side. The sidewalk on the right splits at the flagpole and also leads to the trailhead for the Wupatki Pueblo trail. The trail is paved and rated accessible for about 200 ft. up to the overlook. There is a green water fountain on the left side of the building about thirty feet before the hallway to the bathroom. This water fountain has a water bottle filling feature on top with a button on the front, a water spout for drinking in the back with button on the side, and a dog fountain at the bottom with a button in the back. There is also a motion sensor water bottle fill station inside the visitor center on the wall left of the front desk. The interior of the building has red flagstone floors and white painted walls. As you enter the building there is a front desk with the park store and fee registers to the right and museum exhibits to the left. The shape of the interior is a hexagon. The exhibits are located on the walls and the park store is located in the center of the room. End of description.

name: Xunaa Shuká Hít (Huna Tribal House)
description: Xunaa Shuká Hít (Huna Tribal House) is open on a limited basis during the summer season (Memorial Day to Labor Day) for scheduled ranger programs. In 2016, after almost 20 years of planning, NPS and the Hoonah Indian Association dedicated Xunaa Shuká Hít (Huna Tribal House), a traditional Tlingit structure designed to symbolically anchor the Huna Tlingit in Glacier Bay, their ancestral homeland.

name: Yakutat
description: Yakutat is located in the southern portion of the park along the coastline in Yakutat Bay at the base of the St. Elias Mountains. Accessible only by plane or boat, this area encompasses the park's coastal region, with 155 miles of little-known coastline, where giant mountains, enormous glaciers, and temperate rainforest meet the ocean. For information, please call Park Headquarters in Copper Center at (907) 822-5234.
audioDescription: Yakutat is located in the southern portion of the park along the coastline in Yakutat Bay at the base of the St. Elias Mountains. Accessible only by plane or boat, this area encompasses the park's coastal region, with 155 miles of little-known coastline, where giant mountains, enormous glaciers, and temperate rainforest meet the ocean. For information, please call Park Headquarters in Copper Center at (907) 822-5234.

directionsInfo: Yakutat is a remote community and, like many cities in Southeast Alaska, can only be accessed by air or water. Alaska Airlines offers daily jet passenger and freight service to and from both Juneau and Anchorage. Flight times vary depending on the season. The local airport is 4 miles southeast of the city of Yakutat. The Alaska State Ferry System offers a stop in Yakutat, but does not service the community year-round.

name: Yellowtail Dam Visitor Center (Fort Smith, Montana. North District)
description: The Yellowtail Dam Visitor Center is on the Fort Smith, MT District and is only open between Memorial Day and Labor Day. Construction of the Yellowtail Dam was completed by by the Bureau of Reclamation. This dam, named after the famous Crow chairman Robert Yellowtail, harnesses the waters of the Bighorn River and turns this variable stream into a magnificent lake. This visitor center offers a variety of displays focused on the building of the dam and the functions of the dam.
passportStampLocationDescription: The Yellowtail Dam Passport Stamp is available at the front of the Visitor Center during normal operations from Memorial Day through Labor Day only.

name: Yorktown Battlefield Visitor Center
description: The Yorktown Visitor Center is the orientation point for your visit to Yorktown and Yorktown Battlefield. At the visitor center information desk, you can obtain a park brochure with maps and information, an orientation to the park, and an opportunity to schedule your visit around the various interpretive programs going on throughout the day.
audioDescription: The Yorktown Visitor Center is a large red brick building with entrance doors to the right and exit doors to the left. It has a large National Park Service Arrowhead next to the entrance doors and a six pounder cannon on a carriage. There are 6 flag poles in front of the visitor center that have flags of different regiments that were here during the siege.
passportStampLocationDescription: There are three stamps available for your National Park Passport book at Yorktown Battlefield: The Colonial National Historical Park: Yorktown Battlefield stamp, The Washington-Rochambeau National Historical Trail stamp, and the Cape Henry Memorial stamp.

name: Yosemite Valley Welcome Center
description: The Yosemite Valley Welcome Center is the NEW destination for visitor information in the Valley. Stop here before you begin your Yosemite adventure! The welcome center is located next to the Yosemite Village Parking and the Village Store in Yosemite Valley (Shuttle Stops 1 & 2.) Get help planning your visit and pick up free trail maps, junior ranger booklets, and more.
audioDescription: Concrete steps lead up to the front of the Welcome Center, a renovated midcentury modern building from the 1950s. Its face angles outward and upward, with large windows from floor to ceiling. To the right of the main entrance is the National Park Service arrowhead symbol and a large sign that reads "Welcome Center".

name: Youngsholm - Closed for Renovations
description: The Young family home, Youngsholm, is currently closed for renovation. In-Person visitor services at the Payne Theological Seminary Library will end on Thursday, October 26th, 2023 and will remain in effect until renovations on the Young family home are complete. Contact the park by email at chyo_info@nps.gov if you have questions or concerns. You can view the searchable park Calendar to see what events are planned or visit our social media pages to stay up-to-date on current park happenings.

It is situated less than one mile west of the Wilberforce University and Central State University campuses on U.S. Route 42 at 1120 US Route 42 E. Visit the park's website for additional directions and maps of the area.

name: Zimmerman Center for Heritage
description: The Zimmerman Center for Heritage sits on the banks of the Susquehanna River and is part of the Susquehanna National Heritage Area. The Susquehanna River has long been a gateway to exploration and a corridor of culture and commerce. As rich in history as it is in breathtaking scenery, spectacular wildlife and soul restoring recreation, the river is a place for experiencing the stories of America.

name: Zion Canyon Visitor Center
description: Located near the South Entrance of the park, the Zion Canyon Visitor Center is an excellent place to begin your exploration of Zion Canyon. Park rangers and outdoor exhibits will help you plan your visit and make the most of your time. Inquire at the Zion Canyon Wilderness Desk about permits for backpacking, canyoneering, and other trips into the wilderness. Visit the bookstore for maps, books, and gifts.
audioDescription: Located 0.2 miles from the South Entrance. Reserved parking spaces are available with accessible walkways leading to the building. Accessible unisex restroom, sales displays, water fountain, and information desk.
passportStampLocationDescription: Located in the Zion Forever Project Bookstore at the Zion Canyon Visitor Center.
